INSERT INTO verses (book_id, chapter, verse, text, version) VALUES
(3, 11, 3, 'include those that have completely divided hooves and chew the cud.', 'NLT'),
(3, 11, 4, 'You may not, however, eat the animals named here because they either have split hooves or chew the cud, but not both. The camel may not be eaten, for though it chews the cud, it does not have split hooves.', 'NLT'),
(3, 11, 5, 'The same is true of the rock badger', 'NLT'),
(3, 11, 6, 'and the hare, so they also may never be eaten.', 'NLT'),
(3, 11, 7, 'And the pig may not be eaten, for though it has split hooves, it does not chew the cud.', 'NLT'),
(3, 11, 8, 'You may not eat the meat of these animals or touch their dead bodies. They are ceremonially unclean for you.', 'NLT'),
(3, 11, 9, '"As for marine animals, you may eat whatever has both fins and scales, whether taken from fresh water or salt water.', 'NLT'),
(3, 11, 10, 'You may not, however, eat marine animals that do not have both fins and scales. You are to detest them,', 'NLT'),
(3, 11, 11, 'and they will always be forbidden to you. You must never eat their meat or even touch their dead bodies.', 'NLT'),
(3, 11, 12, 'I repeat, any marine animal that does not have both fins and scales is strictly forbidden to you.', 'NLT'),
(3, 11, 13, '"These are the birds you must never eat because they are detestable for you: the eagle, the vulture, the osprey,', 'NLT'),
(3, 11, 14, 'the buzzard, kites of all kinds,', 'NLT'),
(3, 11, 15, 'ravens of all kinds,', 'NLT'),
(3, 11, 16, 'the ostrich, the nighthawk, the seagull, hawks of all kinds,', 'NLT'),
(3, 11, 17, 'the little owl, the cormorant, the great owl,', 'NLT'),
(3, 11, 18, 'the white owl, the pelican, the carrion vulture,', 'NLT'),
(3, 11, 19, 'the stork, herons of all kinds, the hoopoe, and the bat.', 'NLT'),
(3, 11, 20, '"You are to consider detestable all swarming insects that walk along the ground.', 'NLT'),
(3, 11, 21, 'However, there are some exceptions that you may eat. These include insects that jump with their hind legs:', 'NLT'),
(3, 11, 22, 'locusts of all varieties, crickets, bald locusts, and grasshoppers. All these may be eaten.', 'NLT'),
(3, 11, 23, 'But you are to consider detestable all other swarming insects that walk or crawl.', 'NLT'),
(3, 11, 24, '"The following creatures make you ceremonially unclean. If you touch any of their dead bodies, you will be defiled until evening.', 'NLT'),
(3, 11, 25, 'If you move the dead body of an unclean animal, you must immediately wash your clothes, and you will remain defiled until evening.', 'NLT'),
(3, 11, 26, '"Any animal that has divided but unsplit hooves or that does not chew the cud is unclean for you. If you touch the dead body of such an animal, you will be defiled until evening.', 'NLT'),
(3, 11, 27, 'Of the animals that walk on all fours, those that have paws are unclean for you. If you touch the dead body of such an animal, you will be defiled until evening.', 'NLT'),
(3, 11, 28, 'If you pick up and move its carcass, you must immediately wash your clothes, and you will remain defiled until evening.', 'NLT'),
(3, 11, 29, '"Of the small animals that scurry or creep on the ground, these are unclean for you: the mole, the mouse, the great lizard of all varieties,', 'NLT'),
(3, 11, 30, 'the gecko, the monitor lizard, the common lizard, the sand lizard, and the chameleon.', 'NLT'),
(3, 11, 31, 'All these small animals are unclean for you. If you touch the dead body of such an animal, you will be defiled until evening.', 'NLT'),
(3, 11, 32, 'If such an animal dies and falls on something, that object, whatever its use, will be unclean. This is true whether the object is made of wood, cloth, leather, or sackcloth. It must be put into water, and it will remain defiled until evening. After that, it will be ceremonially clean and may be used again.', 'NLT'),
(3, 11, 33, '"If such an animal dies and falls into a clay pot, everything in the pot will be defiled, and the pot must be smashed.', 'NLT'),
(3, 11, 34, 'If the water used to cleanse an unclean object touches any food, all of that food will be defiled. And any beverage that is in such an unclean container will be defiled.', 'NLT'),
(3, 11, 35, 'Any object on which the dead body of such an animal falls will be defiled. If it is a clay oven or cooking pot, it must be smashed to pieces. It has become defiled, and it will remain that way.', 'NLT'),
(3, 11, 36, '"However, if the dead body of such an animal falls into a spring or a cistern, the water will still be clean. But anyone who removes the dead body will be defiled.', 'NLT'),
(3, 11, 37, 'If the dead body falls on seed grain to be planted in the field, the seed will still be considered clean.', 'NLT'),
(3, 11, 38, 'But if the seed is wet when the dead body falls on it, the seed will be defiled.', 'NLT'),
(3, 11, 39, '"If an animal that is permitted for eating dies and you touch its carcass, you will be defiled until evening.', 'NLT'),
(3, 11, 40, 'If you eat any of its meat or carry away its carcass, you must wash your clothes. Then you will remain defiled until evening.', 'NLT'),
(3, 11, 41, '"Consider detestable any animal that scurries along the ground; such animals may never be eaten.', 'NLT'),
(3, 11, 42, 'This includes all animals that slither along on their bellies, as well as those with four legs and those with many feet. All such animals are to be considered detestable.', 'NLT'),
(3, 11, 43, 'Never defile yourselves by touching such animals.', 'NLT'),
(3, 11, 44, 'After all, I, the LORD, am your God. You must be holy because I am holy. So do not defile yourselves by touching any of these animals that scurry along the ground.', 'NLT'),
(3, 11, 45, 'I, the LORD, am the one who brought you up from the land of Egypt to be your God. You must therefore be holy because I am holy.', 'NLT'),
(3, 11, 46, '"These are the instructions regarding the land animals, the birds, and all the living things that move through the water or swarm over the earth,', 'NLT'),
(3, 11, 47, 'so you can distinguish between what is unclean and may not be eaten and what is clean and may be eaten."', 'NLT'),
(3, 12, 1, 'The LORD said to Moses, "Give these instructions to the Israelites:', 'NLT'),
(3, 12, 2, 'When a woman becomes pregnant and gives birth to a son, she will be ceremonially unclean for seven days, just as she is defiled during her menstrual period.', 'NLT'),
(3, 12, 3, 'On the eighth day, the boy must be circumcised.', 'NLT'),
(3, 12, 4, 'Then the woman must wait for thirty-three days until the time of her purification from the blood of childbirth is completed. During this time of purification, she must not touch anything that is holy. And she must not go to the sanctuary until her time of purification is over.', 'NLT'),
(3, 12, 5, 'If a woman gives birth to a daughter, she will be ceremonially defiled for two weeks, just as she is defiled during her menstrual period. She must then wait another sixty-six days to be purified from the blood of childbirth.', 'NLT'),
(3, 12, 6, '"When the time of purification is completed for either a son or a daughter, the woman must bring a year-old lamb for a whole burnt offering and a young pigeon or turtledove for a purification offering. She must take her offerings to the priest at the entrance of the Tabernacle.', 'NLT'),
(3, 12, 7, 'The priest will then present them to the LORD and make atonement for her. Then she will be ceremonially clean again after her bleeding at childbirth. These are the instructions to be followed after the birth of a son or a daughter.', 'NLT'),
(3, 12, 8, '"If a woman cannot afford to bring a sheep, she must bring two turtledoves or two young pigeons. One will be for the whole burnt offering and the other for the purification offering. The priest will sacrifice them, thus making atonement for her, and she will be ceremonially clean."', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 1, 'The LORD said to Moses and Aaron,', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 2, '"If some of the people notice a swelling or a rash or a shiny patch on their skin that develops into a contagious skin disease, they must be brought to Aaron the priest or to one of his sons.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 3, 'The priest will then examine the affected area of a person''s skin. If the hair in the affected area has turned white and appears to be more than skin-deep, then it is a contagious skin disease, and the priest must pronounce the person ceremonially unclean.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 4, '"But if the affected area of the skin is white but does not appear to be more than skin-deep, and if the hair in the spot has not turned white, the priest will put the infected person in quarantine for seven days.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 5, 'On the seventh day the priest will make another examination. If the affected area has not changed or spread on the skin, then the priest will put the person in quarantine for seven more days.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 6, 'The priest will examine the skin again on the seventh day. If the affected area has faded and not spread, the priest will pronounce the person ceremonially clean. It was only a temporary rash. So after washing the clothes, the person will be considered free of disease.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 7, 'But if the rash continues to spread after this examination and pronouncement by the priest, the infected person must return to be examined again.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 8, 'If the priest notices that the rash has spread, then he must pronounce this person ceremonially unclean, for it is a contagious skin disease.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 9, '"Anyone who develops a contagious skin disease must go to the priest for an examination.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 10, 'If the priest sees that some hair has turned white and an open sore appears in the affected area,', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 11, 'it is clearly a contagious skin disease, and the priest must pronounce that person ceremonially unclean. In such cases, the person need not be quarantined for further observation because it is clear that the skin is defiled by the disease.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 12, '"Now suppose the priest discovers after his examination that a rash has broken out all over someone''s skin, covering the body from head to foot.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 13, 'In such cases, the priest must examine the infected person to see if the disease covers the entire body. If it does, he will pronounce the person ceremonially clean because the skin has turned completely white.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 14, 'But if any open sores appear, the infected person will be pronounced ceremonially unclean.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 15, 'The priest must make this pronouncement as soon as he sees an open sore because open sores indicate the presence of a contagious skin disease.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 16, 'However, if the open sores heal and turn white like the rest of the skin, the person must return to the priest.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 17, 'If, after another examination, the affected areas have indeed turned completely white, then the priest will pronounce the person ceremonially clean.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 18, '"If anyone has had a boil on the skin that has started to heal,', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 19, 'but a white swelling or a reddish white spot remains in its place, that person must go to the priest to be examined.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 20, 'If the priest finds the disease to be more than skin-deep, and if the hair in the affected area has turned white, then the priest must pronounce that person ceremonially unclean. It is a contagious skin disease that has broken out in the boil.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 21, 'But if the priest sees that there is no white hair in the affected area, and if it doesn''t appear to be more than skin-deep and has faded, then the priest is to put the person in quarantine for seven days.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 22, 'If during that time the affected area spreads on the skin, the priest must pronounce the person ceremonially unclean, because it is a contagious skin disease.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 23, 'But if the area grows no larger and does not spread, it is merely the scar from the boil, and the priest will pronounce that person ceremonially clean.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 24, '"If anyone has suffered a burn on the skin and the burned area changes color, becoming either a shiny reddish white or white,', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 25, 'then the priest must examine it. If the hair in the affected area turns white and the problem appears to be more than skin-deep, a contagious skin disease has broken out in the burn. The priest must then pronounce that person ceremonially unclean, for it is clearly a contagious skin disease.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 26, 'But if the priest discovers that there is no white hair in the affected area and the problem appears to be no more than skin-deep and has faded, then the priest is to put the infected person in quarantine for seven days.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 27, 'If at the end of that time the affected area has spread on the skin, the priest must pronounce that person ceremonially unclean, for it is clearly a contagious skin disease.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 28, 'But if the affected area has not moved or spread on the skin and has faded, it is simply a scar from the burn. The priest must then pronounce the person ceremonially clean.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 29, '"If anyone, whether a man or woman, has an open sore on the head or chin,', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 30, 'the priest must examine the infection. If it appears to be more than skin-deep and fine yellow hair is found in the affected area, the priest must pronounce the infected person ceremonially unclean. The infection is a contagious skin disease of the head or chin.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 31, 'However, if the priest''s examination reveals that the infection is only skin-deep and there is no black hair in the affected area, then he must put the person in quarantine for seven days.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 32, 'If at the end of that time the affected area has not spread and no yellow hair has appeared, and if the infection does not appear to be more than skin-deep,', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 33, 'the infected person must shave off all hair except the hair on the affected area. Then the priest must put the person in quarantine for another seven days,', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 34, 'and he will examine the infection again on the seventh day. If it has not spread and appears to be no more than skin-deep, the priest must pronounce that person ceremonially clean. After washing clothes, that person will be clean.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 35, 'But if the infection begins to spread after the person is pronounced clean,', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 36, 'the priest must do another examination. If the infection has spread, he must pronounce the infected person ceremonially unclean, even without checking for yellow hair.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 37, 'But if it appears that the infection has stopped spreading and black hair has grown in the affected area, then the infection has healed. The priest will then pronounce the infected person ceremonially clean.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 38, '"If anyone, whether a man or woman, has shiny white patches on the skin,', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 39, 'the priest must examine the affected area. If the patch is only a pale white, this is a harmless skin rash, and the person is ceremonially clean.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 40, '"If a man loses his hair and his head becomes bald, he is still ceremonially clean.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 41, 'And if he loses hair on his forehead, he simply has a bald forehead; he is still clean.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 42, 'However, if a reddish white infection appears on the front or the back of his head, this is a contagious skin disease.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 43, 'The priest must examine him, and if he finds swelling around the reddish white sore,', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 44, 'the man is infected with a contagious skin disease and is unclean. The priest must pronounce him ceremonially unclean because of the infection.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 45, '"Those who suffer from any contagious skin disease must tear their clothing and allow their hair to hang loose. Then, as they go from place to place, they must cover their mouth and call out, `Unclean! Unclean!''', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 46, 'As long as the disease lasts, they will be ceremonially unclean and must live in isolation outside the camp.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 47, '"Now suppose an infectious mildew contaminates some woolen or linen clothing,', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 48, 'some woolen or linen fabric, the hide of an animal, or anything made of leather.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 49, 'If the affected area in the clothing, the animal hide, the fabric, or the leather has turned bright green or a reddish color, it is contaminated with an infectious mildew and must be taken to the priest to be examined.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 50, 'After examining the affected spot, the priest will put it away for seven days.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 51, 'On the seventh day the priest must inspect it again. If the affected area has spread, the material is clearly contaminated by an infectious mildew and is unclean.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 52, 'The priest must burn the linen or wool clothing or the piece of leather because it has been contaminated by an infectious mildew. It must be completely destroyed by fire.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 53, '"But if the priest examines it again and the affected spot has not spread in the clothing, the fabric, or the leather,', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 54, 'the priest will order the contaminated object to be washed and then isolated for seven more days.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 55, 'Then the priest must inspect the object again. If he sees that the affected area has not changed appearance after being washed, even if it did not spread, the object is defiled. It must be completely burned up, whether it is contaminated on the inside or outside.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 56, 'But if the priest sees that the affected area has faded after being washed, he is to cut the spot from the clothing, the fabric, or the leather.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 57, 'If the spot reappears at a later time, however, the mildew is clearly spreading, and the contaminated object must be burned up.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 58, 'But if the spot disappears after the object is washed, it must be washed again; then it will be ceremonially clean.', 'NLT'),
(3, 13, 59, '"These are the instructions for dealing with infectious mildew in woolen or linen clothing or fabric, or in anything made of leather. This is how the priest will determine whether these things are ceremonially clean or unclean."', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 1, 'And the LORD said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 2, '"The following instructions must be followed by those seeking purification from a contagious skin disease. Those who have been healed must be brought to the priest,', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 3, 'who will examine them at a place outside the camp. If the priest finds that someone has been healed of the skin disease,', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 4, 'he will perform a purification ceremony, using two wild birds of a kind permitted for food, along with some cedarwood, a scarlet cloth, and a hyssop branch.', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 5, 'The priest will order one of the birds to be slaughtered over a clay pot that is filled with fresh springwater.', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 6, 'He will then dip the living bird, along with the cedarwood, the scarlet cloth, and the hyssop branch, into the blood of the slaughtered bird.', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 7, 'The priest will also sprinkle the dead bird''s blood seven times over the person being purified, and the priest will pronounce that person to be ceremonially clean. At the end of the ceremony, the priest will set the living bird free so it can fly away into the open fields.', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 8, '"The people being purified must complete the cleansing ceremony by washing their clothes, shaving off all their hair, and bathing themselves in water. Then they will be ceremonially clean and may return to live inside the camp. However, they must still remain outside their tents for seven days.', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 9, 'On the seventh day, they must again shave off all their hair, including the hair of the beard and eyebrows, and wash their clothes and bathe themselves in water. Then they will be pronounced ceremonially clean.', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 10, '"On the next day, the eighth day, each person cured of the skin disease must bring two male lambs and one female year-old lamb with no physical defects, along with five quarts of choice flour mixed with olive oil and three-fifths of a pint of olive oil.', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 11, 'Then the officiating priest will present that person for cleansing, along with the offerings, before the LORD at the entrance of the Tabernacle.', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 12, 'The priest will take one of the lambs and the olive oil and offer them as a guilt offering by lifting them up before the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 13, 'He will then slaughter the lamb there in the sacred area at the place where sin offerings and burnt offerings are slaughtered. As with the sin offering, the guilt offering will be given to the priest. It is a most holy offering.', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 14, 'The priest will then take some of the blood from the guilt offering and put it on the tip of the healed person''s right ear, on the thumb of the right hand, and on the big toe of the right foot.', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 15, '"Then the priest will pour some of the olive oil into the palm of his own left hand.', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 16, 'He will dip his right finger into the oil and sprinkle it seven times before the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 17, 'The priest will then put some of the oil remaining in his left hand on the tip of the healed person''s right ear, on the thumb of the right hand, and on the big toe of the right foot, in addition to the blood of the guilt offering.', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 18, 'The oil remaining in the priest''s hand will then be poured over the healed person''s head. In this way, the priest will make atonement before the LORD for the person being cleansed.', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 19, '"Then the priest must offer the sin offering and again perform the atonement ceremony for the person cured of the skin disease. After that, the priest will slaughter the whole burnt offering', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 20, 'and offer it on the altar along with the grain offering. In this way, the priest will make atonement for the person being cleansed, and the healed person will be ceremonially clean.', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 21, '"But anyone who cannot afford two lambs must bring one male lamb for a guilt offering, along with two quarts of choice flour mixed with olive oil as a grain offering and three-fifths of a pint of olive oil. The guilt offering will be presented by lifting it up, thus making atonement for the person being cleansed.', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 22, 'The person being cleansed must also bring two turtledoves or two young pigeons, whichever the person can afford. One of the pair must be used for a sin offering and the other for a whole burnt offering.', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 23, 'On the eighth day, the person being cleansed must bring the offerings to the priest for the cleansing ceremony to be performed in the LORD''s presence at the Tabernacle entrance.', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 24, 'The priest will take the lamb for the guilt offering, along with the olive oil, and lift them up before the LORD as an offering to him.', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 25, 'Then the priest will slaughter the lamb for the guilt offering and put some of its blood on the tip of the person''s right ear, on the thumb of the right hand, and on the big toe of the right foot.', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 26, '"The priest will also pour some of the olive oil into the palm of his own left hand.', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 27, 'He will dip his right finger into the oil and sprinkle some of it seven times before the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 28, 'The priest will then put some of the olive oil from his hand on the lobe of the person''s right ear, on the thumb of the right hand, and on the big toe of the right foot, in addition to the blood of the guilt offering.', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 29, 'The oil that is still in the priest''s hand will then be poured over the person''s head. In this way, the priest will make atonement for the person being cleansed.', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 30, '"Then the priest will offer the two turtledoves or the two young pigeons, whichever the person was able to afford.', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 31, 'One of them is for a sin offering and the other for a whole burnt offering, to be presented along with the grain offering. In this way, the priest will make atonement before the LORD for the person being cleansed.', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 32, 'These are the instructions for cleansing those who have recovered from a contagious skin disease but who cannot afford to bring the sacrifices normally required for the ceremony of cleansing."', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 33, 'Then the LORD said to Moses and Aaron,', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 34, '"When you arrive in Canaan, the land I am giving you as an inheritance, I may contaminate some of your houses with an infectious mildew.', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 35, 'The owner of such a house must then go to the priest and say, `It looks like my house has some kind of disease.''', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 36, 'Before the priest examines the house, he must have the house emptied so everything inside will not be pronounced unclean. Then the priest will go in and inspect the house.', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 37, 'If he finds bright green or reddish streaks on the walls of the house and the contamination appears to go deeper than the wall''s surface,', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 38, 'he will leave the house and lock it up for seven days.', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 39, 'On the seventh day the priest must return for another inspection. If the mildew on the walls of the house has spread,', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 40, 'the priest must order that the stones from those areas be removed. The contaminated material will then be thrown into an area outside the town designated as ceremonially unclean.', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 41, 'Next the inside walls of the entire house must be scraped thoroughly and the scrapings dumped in the unclean place outside the town.', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 42, 'Other stones will be brought in to replace the ones that were removed, and the walls will be replastered.', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 43, '"But if the mildew reappears after all these things have been done,', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 44, 'the priest must return and inspect the house again. If he sees that the affected areas have spread, the walls are clearly contaminated with an infectious mildew, and the house is defiled.', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 45, 'It must be torn down, and all its stones, timbers, and plaster must be carried out of town to the place designated as ceremonially unclean.', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 46, 'Anyone who enters the house while it is closed will be considered ceremonially unclean until evening.', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 47, 'All who sleep or eat in the house must wash their clothing.', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 48, '"But if the priest returns for his inspection and finds that the affected areas have not reappeared after the fresh plastering, then he will pronounce the house clean because the infectious mildew is clearly gone.', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 49, 'To purify the house the priest will need two birds, some cedarwood, a scarlet cloth, and a hyssop branch.', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 50, 'He will slaughter one of the birds over a clay pot that is filled with fresh springwater.', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 51, 'Then he will dip the cedarwood, the hyssop branch, the scarlet cloth, and the living bird into the blood of the slaughtered bird, and he will sprinkle the house seven times.', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 52, 'After he has purified the house in this way,', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 53, 'he will release the living bird in the open fields outside the town. In this way, the priest will make atonement for the house, and it will be ceremonially clean.', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 54, '"These are the instructions for dealing with the various kinds of contagious skin disease and infectious mildew,', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 55, 'whether in clothing, in a house,', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 56, 'in a swollen area of skin, in a skin rash, or in a shiny patch of skin.', 'NLT'),
(3, 14, 57, 'These instructions must be followed when dealing with any contagious skin disease or infectious mildew, to determine when something is ceremonially clean or unclean."', 'NLT'),
(3, 15, 1, 'The LORD said to Moses and Aaron,', 'NLT'),
(3, 15, 2, '"Give these further instructions to the Israelites: Any man who has a genital discharge is ceremonially unclean because of it.', 'NLT'),
(3, 15, 3, 'This defilement applies whether the discharge continues or is stopped up. In either case the man is unclean.', 'NLT'),
(3, 15, 4, 'Any bedding on which he lies and anything on which he sits will be defiled.', 'NLT'),
(3, 15, 5, '"So if you touch the man''s bedding, you will be required to wash your clothes and bathe in water, and you will remain ceremonially defiled until evening.', 'NLT'),
(3, 15, 6, 'If you sit where the man with the discharge has sat, you will be required to wash your clothes and bathe in water. You will then remain defiled until evening.', 'NLT'),
(3, 15, 7, 'The same instructions apply if you touch the man who has the unclean discharge.', 'NLT'),
(3, 15, 8, 'And if he spits on you, you must undergo the same procedure.', 'NLT'),
(3, 15, 9, 'Any blanket on which the man rides will be defiled.', 'NLT'),
(3, 15, 10, 'If you touch or carry anything that was under him, you will be required to wash your clothes and bathe in water, and you will remain defiled until evening.', 'NLT'),
(3, 15, 11, 'If the man touches you without first rinsing his hands, then you will be required to wash your clothes and bathe in water, and you will remain defiled until evening.', 'NLT'),
(3, 15, 12, 'Any clay pot touched by the man with the discharge must be broken, and every wooden utensil he touches must be rinsed with water.', 'NLT'),
(3, 15, 13, '"When the man''s discharge heals, he must count off a period of seven days. During that time, he must wash his clothes and bathe in fresh springwater. Then he will be ceremonially clean.', 'NLT'),
(3, 15, 14, 'On the eighth day he must bring two turtledoves or two young pigeons and present himself to the LORD at the entrance of the Tabernacle and give his offerings to the priest.', 'NLT'),
(3, 15, 15, 'The priest will present the offerings there, one for a sin offering and the other for a whole burnt offering. In this way, the priest will make atonement for the man before the LORD for his discharge.', 'NLT'),
(3, 15, 16, '"Whenever a man has an emission of semen, he must wash his entire body, and he will remain ceremonially defiled until evening.', 'NLT'),
(3, 15, 17, 'Any clothing or leather that comes in contact with the semen must be washed, and it will remain defiled until evening.', 'NLT'),
(3, 15, 18, 'After having sexual intercourse, both the man and the woman must bathe, and they will remain defiled until evening.', 'NLT'),
(3, 15, 19, '"Whenever a woman has her menstrual period, she will be ceremonially unclean for seven days. If you touch her during that time, you will be defiled until evening.', 'NLT'),
(3, 15, 20, 'Anything on which she lies or sits during that time will be defiled.', 'NLT'),
(3, 15, 21, 'If you touch her bed, you must wash your clothes and bathe in water, and you will remain defiled until evening.', 'NLT'),
(3, 15, 22, 'The same applies if you touch an object on which she sits,', 'NLT'),
(3, 15, 23, 'whether it is her bedding or any piece of furniture.', 'NLT'),
(3, 15, 24, 'If a man has sexual intercourse with her during this time, her menstrual impurity will be transmitted to him. He will remain defiled for seven days, and any bed on which he lies will be defiled.', 'NLT'),
(3, 15, 25, '"If the menstrual flow of blood continues for many days beyond the normal period, or if she discharges blood unrelated to her menstruation, the woman will be ceremonially unclean as long as the discharge continues.', 'NLT'),
(3, 15, 26, 'Anything on which she lies or sits during that time will be defiled, just as it would be during her normal menstrual period.', 'NLT'),
(3, 15, 27, 'If you touch her bed or anything on which she sits, you will be defiled. You will be required to wash your clothes and bathe in water, and you will remain defiled until evening.', 'NLT'),
(3, 15, 28, '"When the woman''s menstrual discharge stops, she must count off a period of seven days. After that, she will be ceremonially clean.', 'NLT'),
(3, 15, 29, 'On the eighth day, she must bring two turtledoves or two young pigeons and present them to the priest at the entrance of the Tabernacle.', 'NLT'),
(3, 15, 30, 'The priest will offer one for a sin offering and the other for a whole burnt offering. In this way, the priest will make atonement for her before the LORD for her menstrual discharge.', 'NLT'),
(3, 15, 31, '"In this way, you will keep the people of Israel separate from things that will defile them, so they will not die as a result of defiling my Tabernacle that is right there among them.', 'NLT'),
(3, 15, 32, 'These are the instructions for dealing with a man who has been defiled by a genital discharge or an emission of semen;', 'NLT'),
(3, 15, 33, 'for dealing with a woman during her monthly menstrual period; for dealing with anyone, man or woman, who has had a bodily discharge of any kind; and for dealing with a man who has had intercourse with a woman during her period."', 'NLT'),
(3, 16, 1, 'The LORD spoke to Moses after the death of Aaron''s two sons, who died when they burned a different kind of fire than the LORD had commanded.', 'NLT'),
(3, 16, 2, 'The LORD said to Moses, "Warn your brother Aaron not to enter the Most Holy Place behind the inner curtain whenever he chooses; the penalty for intrusion is death. For the Ark''s cover--the place of atonement--is there, and I myself am present in the cloud over the atonement cover.', 'NLT'),
(3, 16, 3, '"When Aaron enters the sanctuary area, he must follow these instructions fully. He must first bring a young bull for a sin offering and a ram for a whole burnt offering.', 'NLT'),
(3, 16, 4, 'Then he must wash his entire body and put on his linen tunic and the undergarments worn next to his body. He must tie the linen sash around his waist and put the linen turban on his head. These are his sacred garments.', 'NLT'),
(3, 16, 5, 'The people of Israel must then bring him two male goats for a sin offering and a ram for a whole burnt offering.', 'NLT'),
(3, 16, 6, '"Aaron will present the bull as a sin offering, to make atonement for himself and his family.', 'NLT'),
(3, 16, 7, 'Then he must bring the two male goats and present them to the LORD at the entrance of the Tabernacle.', 'NLT'),
(3, 16, 8, 'He is to cast sacred lots to determine which goat will be sacrificed to the LORD and which one will be the scapegoat.', 'NLT'),
(3, 16, 9, 'The goat chosen to be sacrificed to the LORD will be presented by Aaron as a sin offering.', 'NLT'),
(3, 16, 10, 'The goat chosen to be the scapegoat will be presented to the LORD alive. When it is sent away into the wilderness, it will make atonement for the people.', 'NLT'),
(3, 16, 11, '"Then Aaron will present the young bull as a sin offering for himself and his family. After he has slaughtered this bull for the sin offering,', 'NLT'),
(3, 16, 12, 'he will fill an incense burner with burning coals from the altar that stands before the LORD. Then, after filling both his hands with fragrant incense, he will carry the burner and incense behind the inner curtain.', 'NLT'),
(3, 16, 13, 'There in the LORD''s presence, he will put the incense on the burning coals so that a cloud of incense will rise over the Ark''s cover--the place of atonement--that rests on the Ark of the Covenant. If he follows these instructions, he will not die.', 'NLT'),
(3, 16, 14, 'Then he must dip his finger into the blood of the bull and sprinkle it on the front of the atonement cover and then seven times against the front of the Ark.', 'NLT'),
(3, 16, 15, '"Then Aaron must slaughter the goat as a sin offering for the people and bring its blood behind the inner curtain. There he will sprinkle the blood on the atonement cover and against the front of the Ark, just as he did with the bull''s blood.', 'NLT'),
(3, 16, 16, 'In this way, he will make atonement for the Most Holy Place, and he will do the same for the entire Tabernacle, because of the defiling sin and rebellion of the Israelites.', 'NLT'),
(3, 16, 17, 'No one else is allowed inside the Tabernacle while Aaron goes in to make atonement for the Most Holy Place. No one may enter until he comes out again after making atonement for himself, his family, and all the Israelites.', 'NLT'),
(3, 16, 18, '"Then Aaron will go out to make atonement for the altar that stands before the LORD by smearing some of the blood from the bull and the goat on each of the altar''s horns.', 'NLT'),
(3, 16, 19, 'Then he must dip his finger into the blood and sprinkle it seven times over the altar. In this way, he will cleanse it from Israel''s defilement and return it to its former holiness.', 'NLT'),
(3, 16, 20, '"When Aaron has finished making atonement for the Most Holy Place, the Tabernacle, and the altar, he must bring the living goat forward.', 'NLT'),
(3, 16, 21, 'He is to lay both of his hands on the goat''s head and confess over it all the sins and rebellion of the Israelites. In this way, he will lay the people''s sins on the head of the goat; then he will send it out into the wilderness, led by a man chosen for this task.', 'NLT'),
(3, 16, 22, 'After the man sets it free in the wilderness, the goat will carry all the people''s sins upon itself into a desolate land.', 'NLT'),
(3, 16, 23, '"As Aaron enters the Tabernacle, he must take off the linen garments he wore when he entered the Most Holy Place, and he must leave the garments there.', 'NLT'),
(3, 16, 24, 'Then he must bathe his entire body with water in a sacred place, put on his garments, and go out to sacrifice his own whole burnt offering and the whole burnt offering for the people. In this way, he will make atonement for himself and for the people.', 'NLT'),
(3, 16, 25, 'He must also burn all the fat of the sin offering on the altar.', 'NLT'),
(3, 16, 26, '"The man chosen to send the goat out into the wilderness as a scapegoat must wash his clothes and bathe in water. Then he may return to the camp.', 'NLT'),
(3, 16, 27, '"The bull and goat given as sin offerings, whose blood Aaron brought into the Most Holy Place to make atonement for Israel, will be carried outside the camp to be burned. This includes the animals'' hides, the internal organs, and the dung.', 'NLT'),
(3, 16, 28, 'The man who does the burning must wash his clothes and bathe himself in water before returning to the camp.', 'NLT'),
(3, 16, 29, '"On the appointed day in early autumn, you must spend the day fasting and not do any work. This is a permanent law for you, and it applies to those who are Israelites by birth, as well as to the foreigners living among you.', 'NLT'),
(3, 16, 30, 'On this day, atonement will be made for you, and you will be cleansed from all your sins in the LORD''s presence.', 'NLT'),
(3, 16, 31, 'It will be a Sabbath day of total rest, and you will spend the day in fasting. This is a permanent law for you.', 'NLT'),
(3, 16, 32, 'In future generations, the atonement ceremony will be performed by the anointed high priest who serves in place of his ancestor Aaron. He will put on the holy linen garments', 'NLT'),
(3, 16, 33, 'and make atonement for the Most Holy Place, the Tabernacle, the altar, the priests, and the entire community.', 'NLT'),
(3, 16, 34, 'This is a permanent law for you, to make atonement for the Israelites once each year." Moses followed all these instructions that the LORD had given to him.', 'NLT'),
(3, 17, 1, 'Then the LORD said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(3, 17, 2, '"Give Aaron and his sons and all the Israelites these commands from the LORD:', 'NLT'),
(3, 17, 3, 'If any Israelite sacrifices a bull or a lamb or a goat anywhere inside or outside the camp', 'NLT'),
(3, 17, 4, 'and does not bring it to the entrance of the Tabernacle to present it as an offering to the LORD, that person will be guilty of a capital offense. Such a person has shed blood and must be cut off from the community.', 'NLT'),
(3, 17, 5, 'This rule will stop the Israelites from sacrificing animals in the open fields. It will cause them to bring their sacrifices to the priest at the entrance of the Tabernacle, so he can present them to the LORD as peace offerings.', 'NLT'),
(3, 17, 6, 'That way the priest will be able to sprinkle the blood and burn the fat on the LORD''s altar at the entrance of the Tabernacle, and it will be very pleasing to the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(3, 17, 7, 'The people must no longer be unfaithful to the LORD by offering sacrifices to evil spirits out in the fields. This is a permanent law for them, to be kept generation after generation.', 'NLT'),
(3, 17, 8, '"Give them this command as well, which applies both to Israelites and to the foreigners living among you. If you offer a whole burnt offering or a sacrifice', 'NLT'),
(3, 17, 9, 'and do not bring it to the entrance of the Tabernacle to offer it to the LORD, you will be cut off from the community.', 'NLT'),
(3, 17, 10, '"And I will turn against anyone, whether an Israelite or a foreigner living among you, who eats or drinks blood in any form. I will cut off such a person from the community,', 'NLT'),
(3, 17, 11, 'for the life of any creature is in its blood. I have given you the blood so you can make atonement for your sins. It is the blood, representing life, that brings you atonement.', 'NLT'),
(3, 17, 12, 'That is why I said to the Israelites: `You and the foreigners who live among you must never eat or drink blood.''', 'NLT'),
(3, 17, 13, '"And this command applies both to Israelites and to the foreigners living among you. If you go hunting and kill an animal or bird that is approved for eating, you must drain out the blood and cover it with earth.', 'NLT'),
(3, 17, 14, 'The life of every creature is in the blood. That is why I have told the people of Israel never to eat or drink it, for the life of any bird or animal is in the blood. So whoever eats or drinks blood must be cut off.', 'NLT'),
(3, 17, 15, '"And this command also applies both to Israelites and the foreigners living among you. If you eat from the carcass of an animal that died a natural death or was killed by a wild animal, you must wash your clothes and bathe yourselves in water. Then you will remain ceremonially unclean until evening; after that, you will be considered clean.', 'NLT'),
(3, 17, 16, 'But if you do not wash your clothes and bathe, you will be held responsible."', 'NLT'),
(3, 18, 1, 'Then the LORD said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(3, 18, 2, '"Say this to your people, the Israelites: I, the LORD, am your God.', 'NLT'),
(3, 18, 3, 'So do not act like the people in Egypt, where you used to live, or like the people of Canaan, where I am taking you. You must not imitate their way of life.', 'NLT'),
(3, 18, 4, 'You must obey all my regulations and be careful to keep my laws, for I, the LORD, am your God.', 'NLT'),
(3, 18, 5, 'If you obey my laws and regulations, you will find life through them. I am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(3, 18, 6, '"You must never have sexual intercourse with a close relative, for I am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(3, 18, 7, 'Do not violate your father by having sexual intercourse with your mother. She is your mother; you must never have intercourse with her.', 'NLT'),
(3, 18, 8, 'Do not have sexual intercourse with any of your father''s wives, for this would violate your father.', 'NLT'),
(3, 18, 9, '"Do not have sexual intercourse with your sister or half sister, whether she is your father''s daughter or your mother''s daughter, whether she was brought up in the same family or somewhere else.', 'NLT'),
(3, 18, 10, '"Do not have sexual intercourse with your granddaughter, whether your son''s daughter or your daughter''s daughter; that would violate you.', 'NLT'),
(3, 18, 11, 'Do not have sexual intercourse with the daughter of any of your father''s wives; she is your half sister.', 'NLT'),
(3, 18, 12, 'Do not have intercourse with your aunt, your father''s sister, because she is your father''s close relative.', 'NLT'),
(3, 18, 13, 'Do not have sexual intercourse with your aunt, your mother''s sister, because she is your mother''s close relative.', 'NLT'),
(3, 18, 14, 'And do not violate your uncle, your father''s brother, by having sexual intercourse with his wife; she also is your aunt.', 'NLT'),
(3, 18, 15, 'Do not have sexual intercourse with your daughter-in-law; she is your son''s wife.', 'NLT'),
(3, 18, 16, 'Do not have intercourse with your brother''s wife; this would violate your brother.', 'NLT'),
(3, 18, 17, '"Do not have sexual intercourse with both a woman and her daughter or marry both a woman and her granddaughter, whether her son''s daughter or her daughter''s daughter. They are close relatives, and to do this would be a horrible wickedness.', 'NLT'),
(3, 18, 18, '"Do not marry a woman and her sister because they will be rivals. But if your wife dies, then it is all right to marry her sister.', 'NLT'),
(3, 18, 19, '"Do not violate a woman by having sexual intercourse with her during her period of menstrual impurity.', 'NLT'),
(3, 18, 20, '"Do not defile yourself by having sexual intercourse with your neighbor''s wife.', 'NLT'),
(3, 18, 21, '"Do not give any of your children as a sacrifice to Molech, for you must not profane the name of your God. I am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(3, 18, 22, '"Do not practice homosexuality; it is a detestable sin.', 'NLT'),
(3, 18, 23, '"A man must never defile himself by having sexual intercourse with an animal, and a woman must never present herself to a male animal in order to have intercourse with it; this is a terrible perversion.', 'NLT'),
(3, 18, 24, '"Do not defile yourselves in any of these ways, because this is how the people I am expelling from the Promised Land have defiled themselves.', 'NLT'),
(3, 18, 25, 'As a result, the entire land has become defiled. That is why I am punishing the people who live there, and the land will soon vomit them out.', 'NLT'),
(3, 18, 26, 'You must strictly obey all of my laws and regulations, and you must not do any of these detestable things. This applies both to you who are Israelites by birth and to the foreigners living among you.', 'NLT'),
(3, 18, 27, '"All these detestable activities are practiced by the people of the land where I am taking you, and the land has become defiled.', 'NLT'),
(3, 18, 28, 'Do not give the land a reason to vomit you out for defiling it, as it will vomit out the people who live there now.', 'NLT'),
(3, 18, 29, 'Whoever does any of these detestable things will be cut off from the community of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(3, 18, 30, 'So be careful to obey my laws, and do not practice any of these detestable activities. Do not defile yourselves by doing any of them, for I, the LORD, am your God."', 'NLT'),
(3, 19, 1, 'The LORD also said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(3, 19, 2, '"Say this to the entire community of Israel: You must be holy because I, the LORD your God, am holy.', 'NLT'),
(3, 19, 3, 'Each of you must show respect for your mother and father, and you must always observe my Sabbath days of rest, for I, the LORD, am your God.', 'NLT'),
(3, 19, 4, 'Do not put your trust in idols or make gods of metal for yourselves. I, the LORD, am your God.', 'NLT'),
(3, 19, 5, '"When you sacrifice a peace offering to the LORD, offer it properly so it will be accepted on your behalf.', 'NLT'),
(3, 19, 6, 'You must eat it on the same day you offer it or on the next day at the latest. Any leftovers that remain until the third day must be burned.', 'NLT'),
(3, 19, 7, 'If any of the offering is eaten on the third day, it will be contaminated, and I will not accept it.', 'NLT'),
(3, 19, 8, 'If you eat it on the third day, you will answer for the sin of profaning what is holy to the LORD and must be cut off from the community.', 'NLT'),
(3, 19, 9, '"When you harvest your crops, do not harvest the grain along the edges of your fields, and do not pick up what the harvesters drop.', 'NLT'),
(3, 19, 10, 'It is the same with your grape crop--do not strip every last bunch of grapes from the vines, and do not pick up the grapes that fall to the ground. Leave them for the poor and the foreigners who live among you, for I, the LORD, am your God.', 'NLT'),
(3, 19, 11, '"Do not steal. "Do not cheat one another. "Do not lie.', 'NLT'),
(3, 19, 12, '"Do not use my name to swear a falsehood and so profane the name of your God. I am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(3, 19, 13, '"Do not cheat or rob anyone. "Always pay your hired workers promptly.', 'NLT'),
(3, 19, 14, '"Show your fear of God by treating the deaf with respect and by not taking advantage of the blind. I am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(3, 19, 15, '"Always judge your neighbors fairly, neither favoring the poor nor showing deference to the rich.', 'NLT'),
(3, 19, 16, '"Do not spread slanderous gossip among your people. "Do not try to get ahead at the cost of your neighbor''s life, for I am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(3, 19, 17, '"Do not nurse hatred in your heart for any of your relatives. "Confront your neighbors directly so you will not be held guilty for their crimes.', 'NLT'),
(3, 19, 18, '"Never seek revenge or bear a grudge against anyone, but love your neighbor as yourself. I am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(3, 19, 19, '"You must obey all my laws. "Do not breed your cattle with other kinds of animals. Do not plant your field with two kinds of seed. Do not wear clothing woven from two different kinds of fabric.', 'NLT'),
(3, 19, 20, '"If a man has sexual intercourse with a slave girl who is committed to become someone else''s wife, compensation must be paid. But since she had not been freed at the time, the couple will not be put to death.', 'NLT'),
(3, 19, 21, 'The man, however, must bring a ram as a guilt offering and present it to the LORD at the entrance of the Tabernacle.', 'NLT'),
(3, 19, 22, 'The priest will then make atonement for him before the LORD with the sacrificial ram of the guilt offering, and the man will be forgiven.', 'NLT'),
(3, 19, 23, '"When you enter the land and plant fruit trees, leave the fruit unharvested for the first three years and consider it forbidden.', 'NLT'),
(3, 19, 24, 'In the fourth year the entire crop will be devoted to the LORD as an outburst of praise.', 'NLT'),
(3, 19, 25, 'Finally, in the fifth year you may eat the fruit. In this way, its yield will be increased. I, the LORD, am your God.', 'NLT'),
(3, 19, 26, '"Never eat meat that has not been drained of its blood. "Do not practice fortune-telling or witchcraft.', 'NLT'),
(3, 19, 27, '"Do not trim off the hair on your temples or clip the edges of your beards.', 'NLT'),
(3, 19, 28, '"Never cut your bodies in mourning for the dead or mark your skin with tattoos, for I am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(3, 19, 29, '"Do not defile your daughter by making her a prostitute, or the land will be filled with promiscuity and detestable wickedness.', 'NLT'),
(3, 19, 30, '"Keep my Sabbath days of rest and show reverence toward my sanctuary, for I am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(3, 19, 31, '"Do not rely on mediums and psychics, for you will be defiled by them. I, the LORD, am your God.', 'NLT'),
(3, 19, 32, '"Show your fear of God by standing up in the presence of elderly people and showing respect for the aged. I am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(3, 19, 33, '"Do not exploit the foreigners who live in your land.', 'NLT'),
(3, 19, 34, 'They should be treated like everyone else, and you must love them as you love yourself. Remember that you were once foreigners in the land of Egypt. I, the LORD, am your God.', 'NLT'),
(3, 19, 35, '"Do not use dishonest standards when measuring length, weight, or volume.', 'NLT'),
(3, 19, 36, 'Your scales and weights must be accurate. Your containers for measuring dry goods or liquids must be accurate. I, the LORD, am your God, who brought you out of the land of Egypt.', 'NLT'),
(3, 19, 37, 'You must be careful to obey all of my laws and regulations, for I am the LORD."', 'NLT'),
(3, 20, 1, 'The LORD said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(3, 20, 2, '"Give the Israelites these instructions, which apply to those who are Israelites by birth as well as to the foreigners living among you. If any among them devote their children as burnt offerings to Molech, they must be stoned to death by people of the community.', 'NLT'),
(3, 20, 3, 'I myself will turn against them and cut them off from the community, because they have defiled my sanctuary and profaned my holy name by giving their children to Molech.', 'NLT'),
(3, 20, 4, 'And if the people of the community ignore this offering of children to Molech and refuse to execute the guilty parents,', 'NLT'),
(3, 20, 5, 'then I myself will turn against them and cut them off from the community, along with all those who commit prostitution by worshiping Molech.', 'NLT'),
(3, 20, 6, '"If any among the people are unfaithful by consulting and following mediums or psychics, I will turn against them and cut them off from the community.', 'NLT'),
(3, 20, 7, 'So set yourselves apart to be holy, for I, the LORD, am your God.', 'NLT'),
(3, 20, 8, 'Keep all my laws and obey them, for I am the LORD, who makes you holy.', 'NLT'),
(3, 20, 9, '"All who curse their father or mother must be put to death. They are guilty of a capital offense.', 'NLT'),
(3, 20, 10, '"If a man commits adultery with another man''s wife, both the man and the woman must be put to death.', 'NLT'),
(3, 20, 11, 'If a man has intercourse with his father''s wife, both the man and the woman must die, for they are guilty of a capital offense.', 'NLT'),
(3, 20, 12, 'If a man has intercourse with his daughter-in-law, both must be put to death. They have acted contrary to nature and are guilty of a capital offense.', 'NLT'),
(3, 20, 13, '"The penalty for homosexual acts is death to both parties. They have committed a detestable act and are guilty of a capital offense.', 'NLT'),
(3, 20, 14, 'If a man has intercourse with both a woman and her mother, such an act is terribly wicked. All three of them must be burned to death to wipe out such wickedness from among you.', 'NLT'),
(3, 20, 15, '"If a man has sexual intercourse with an animal, he must be put to death, and the animal must be killed.', 'NLT'),
(3, 20, 16, 'If a woman approaches a male animal to have intercourse with it, she and the animal must both be put to death. Both must die, for they are guilty of a capital offense.', 'NLT'),
(3, 20, 17, '"If a man has sexual intercourse with his sister, the daughter of either his father or his mother, it is a terrible disgrace. Both of them must be publicly cut off from the community. Since the man has had intercourse with his sister, he will suffer the consequences of his guilt.', 'NLT'),
(3, 20, 18, 'If a man has intercourse with a woman suffering from a hemorrhage, both of them must be cut off from the community, because he exposed the source of her flow, and she allowed him to do it.', 'NLT'),
(3, 20, 19, '"If a man has sexual intercourse with his aunt, whether his mother''s sister or his father''s sister, he has violated a close relative. Both parties are guilty of a capital offense.', 'NLT'),
(3, 20, 20, 'If a man has intercourse with his uncle''s wife, he has violated his uncle. Both the man and woman involved are guilty of a capital offense and will die childless.', 'NLT'),
(3, 20, 21, 'If a man marries his brother''s wife, it is an act of impurity. He has violated his brother, and the guilty couple will remain childless.', 'NLT'),
(3, 20, 22, '"You must carefully obey all my laws and regulations; otherwise the land to which I am bringing you will vomit you out.', 'NLT'),
(3, 20, 23, 'Do not live by the customs of the people whom I will expel before you. It is because they do these terrible things that I detest them so much.', 'NLT'),
(3, 20, 24, 'But I have promised that you will inherit their land, a land flowing with milk and honey. I, the LORD, am your God, who has set you apart from all other people.', 'NLT'),
(3, 20, 25, '"You must therefore make a distinction between ceremonially clean and unclean animals, and between clean and unclean birds. You must not defile yourselves by eating any animal or bird or creeping creature that I have forbidden.', 'NLT'),
(3, 20, 26, 'You must be holy because I, the LORD, am holy. I have set you apart from all other people to be my very own.', 'NLT'),
(3, 20, 27, '"Men and women among you who act as mediums or psychics must be put to death by stoning. They are guilty of a capital offense."', 'NLT'),
(3, 21, 1, 'The LORD said to Moses, "Tell the priests to avoid making themselves ceremonially unclean by touching a dead relative', 'NLT'),
(3, 21, 2, 'unless it is a close relative--mother or father, son or daughter, brother', 'NLT'),
(3, 21, 3, 'or virgin sister who was dependent because she had no husband.', 'NLT'),
(3, 21, 4, 'As a husband among his relatives, he must not defile himself.', 'NLT'),
(3, 21, 5, '"The priests must never shave their heads, trim the edges of their beards, or cut their bodies.', 'NLT'),
(3, 21, 6, 'They must be set apart to God as holy and must never dishonor his name. After all, they are the ones who present the offerings to the LORD by fire, providing God with his food, and they must remain holy.', 'NLT'),
(3, 21, 7, '"The priests must not marry women defiled by prostitution or women who have been divorced, for the priests must be set apart to God as holy.', 'NLT'),
(3, 21, 8, 'You must treat them as holy because they offer up food to your God. You must consider them holy because I, the LORD, am holy, and I make you holy.', 'NLT'),
(3, 21, 9, 'If a priest''s daughter becomes a prostitute, defiling her father''s holiness as well as herself, she must be burned to death.', 'NLT'),
(3, 21, 10, '"The high priest, who has had the anointing oil poured on his head and has been ordained to wear the special priestly garments, must never let his hair hang loose or tear his clothing.', 'NLT'),
(3, 21, 11, 'He must never defile himself by going near a dead person, even if it is his father or mother.', 'NLT'),
(3, 21, 12, 'He must not desecrate the sanctuary of his God by leaving it to attend his parents'' funeral, because he has been made holy by the anointing oil of his God. I am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(3, 21, 13, '"The high priest must marry a virgin.', 'NLT'),
(3, 21, 14, 'He must not marry a widow, a divorced woman, or a woman defiled by prostitution. She must be a virgin from his own clan,', 'NLT'),
(3, 21, 15, 'that he may not dishonor his descendants among the members of his clan, because I, the LORD, have made him holy."', 'NLT'),
(3, 21, 16, 'Then the LORD said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(3, 21, 17, '"Tell Aaron that in all future generations, his descendants who have physical defects will not qualify to offer food to their God.', 'NLT'),
(3, 21, 18, 'No one who has a defect may come near to me, whether he is blind or lame, stunted or deformed,', 'NLT'),
(3, 21, 19, 'or has a broken foot or hand,', 'NLT'),
(3, 21, 20, 'or has a humped back or is a dwarf, or has a defective eye, or has oozing sores or scabs on his skin, or has damaged testicles.', 'NLT'),
(3, 21, 21, 'Even though he is a descendant of Aaron, his physical defects disqualify him from presenting offerings to the LORD by fire. Since he has a blemish, he may not offer food to his God.', 'NLT'),
(3, 21, 22, 'However, he may eat from the food offered to God, including the holy offerings and the most holy offerings.', 'NLT'),
(3, 21, 23, 'Yet because of his physical defect, he must never go behind the inner curtain or come near the altar, for this would desecrate my holy places. I am the LORD who makes them holy."', 'NLT'),
(3, 21, 24, 'So Moses gave these instructions to Aaron and his sons and to all the Israelites.', 'NLT'),
(3, 22, 1, 'The LORD said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(3, 22, 2, '"Tell Aaron and his sons to treat the sacred gifts that the Israelites set apart for me with great care, so they do not profane my holy name. I am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(3, 22, 3, 'Remind them that if any of their descendants are ceremonially unclean when they approach the sacred food presented by the Israelites, they must be cut off from my presence. I am the LORD!', 'NLT'),
(3, 22, 4, '"If any of the priests have a contagious skin disease or any kind of discharge that makes them ceremonially unclean, they may not eat the sacred offerings until they have been pronounced clean. If any of the priests become unclean by touching a corpse, or are defiled by an emission of semen,', 'NLT'),
(3, 22, 5, 'or by touching a creeping creature that is unclean, or by touching someone who is ceremonially unclean for any reason,', 'NLT'),
(3, 22, 6, 'they will remain defiled until evening. They must not eat any of the sacred offerings until they have purified their bodies with water.', 'NLT'),
(3, 22, 7, 'When the sun goes down, they will be clean again and may eat the sacred offerings. After all, this food has been set aside for them.', 'NLT'),
(3, 22, 8, 'The priests may never eat an animal that has died a natural death or has been torn apart by wild animals, for this would defile them. I am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(3, 22, 9, 'Warn all the priests to follow these instructions carefully; otherwise they will be subject to punishment and die for violating them. I am the LORD who makes them holy.', 'NLT'),
(3, 22, 10, '"No one outside a priest''s family may ever eat the sacred offerings, even if the person lives in a priest''s home or is one of his hired servants.', 'NLT'),
(3, 22, 11, 'However, if the priest buys slaves with his own money, they may eat of his food. And if his slaves have children, they also may share his food.', 'NLT'),
(3, 22, 12, 'If a priest''s daughter marries someone outside the priestly family, she may no longer eat the sacred offerings.', 'NLT'),
(3, 22, 13, 'But if she becomes a widow or is divorced and has no children to support her, and she returns to live in her father''s home, she may eat her father''s food again. But other than these exceptions, only members of the priests'' families are allowed to eat the sacred offerings.', 'NLT'),
(3, 22, 14, '"Anyone who eats the sacred offerings without realizing it must pay the priest for the amount eaten, plus an added penalty of 20 percent.', 'NLT'),
(3, 22, 15, 'No one may defile the sacred offerings brought to the LORD by the Israelites', 'NLT'),
(3, 22, 16, 'by allowing unauthorized people to eat them. The negligent priest would bring guilt upon the people and require them to pay compensation. I am the LORD, who makes them holy."', 'NLT'),
(3, 22, 17, 'And the LORD said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(3, 22, 18, '"Give Aaron and his sons and all the Israelites these instructions, which apply to those who are Israelites by birth as well as to the foreigners living among you. If you offer a whole burnt offering to the LORD, whether to fulfill a vow or as a freewill offering,', 'NLT'),
(3, 22, 19, 'it will be accepted only if it is a male animal with no physical defects. It may be either a bull, a ram, or a male goat.', 'NLT'),
(3, 22, 20, 'Do not bring an animal with physical defects, because it won''t be accepted on your behalf.', 'NLT'),
(3, 22, 21, '"If you bring a peace offering to the LORD from the herd or flock, whether to fulfill a vow or as a freewill offering, you must offer an animal that has no physical defects of any kind.', 'NLT'),
(3, 22, 22, 'An animal that is blind, injured, mutilated, or that has a growth, an open sore, or a scab must never be offered to the LORD by fire on the altar.', 'NLT'),
(3, 22, 23, 'If the bull or lamb is deformed or stunted, it may still be offered as a freewill offering, but it may not be offered to fulfill a vow.', 'NLT'),
(3, 22, 24, 'If an animal has damaged testicles or is castrated, it may never be offered to the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(3, 22, 25, 'You must never accept mutilated or defective animals from foreigners to be offered as a sacrifice to your God. Such animals will not be accepted on your behalf because they are defective."', 'NLT'),
(3, 22, 26, 'And the LORD said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(3, 22, 27, '"When a bull or a ram or a male goat is born, it must be left with its mother for seven days. From the eighth day on, it will be acceptable as an offering given to the LORD by fire.', 'NLT'),
(3, 22, 28, 'But you must never slaughter a mother animal and her offspring on the same day, whether from the herd or the flock.', 'NLT'),
(3, 22, 29, 'When you bring a thanksgiving offering to the LORD, it must be sacrificed properly so it will be accepted on your behalf.', 'NLT'),
(3, 22, 30, 'Eat the entire sacrificial animal on the day it is presented. Don''t leave any of it until the second day. I am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(3, 22, 31, '"You must faithfully keep all my commands by obeying them, for I am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(3, 22, 32, 'Do not treat my holy name as common and ordinary. I must be treated as holy by the people of Israel. It is I, the LORD, who makes you holy.', 'NLT'),
(3, 22, 33, 'It was I who rescued you from Egypt, that I might be your very own God. I am the LORD."', 'NLT'),
(3, 23, 1, 'The LORD said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(3, 23, 2, '"Give the Israelites instructions regarding the LORD''s appointed festivals, the days when all of you will be summoned to worship me.', 'NLT'),
(3, 23, 3, 'You may work for six days each week, but on the seventh day all work must come to a complete stop. It is the LORD''s Sabbath day of complete rest, a holy day to assemble for worship. It must be observed wherever you live.', 'NLT'),
(3, 23, 4, 'In addition to the Sabbath, the LORD has established festivals, the holy occasions to be observed at the proper time each year.', 'NLT'),
(3, 23, 5, '"First comes the LORD''s Passover, which begins at twilight on its appointed day in early spring.', 'NLT'),
(3, 23, 6, 'Then the day after the Passover celebration, the Festival of Unleavened Bread begins. This festival to the LORD continues for seven days, and during that time all the bread you eat must be made without yeast.', 'NLT'),
(3, 23, 7, 'On the first day of the festival, all the people must stop their regular work and gather for a sacred assembly.', 'NLT'),
(3, 23, 8, 'On each of the next seven days, the people must present an offering to the LORD by fire. On the seventh day, the people must again stop all their regular work to hold a sacred assembly."', 'NLT'),
(3, 23, 9, 'Then the LORD told Moses', 'NLT'),
(3, 23, 10, 'to give these instructions to the Israelites: "When you arrive in the land I am giving you and you harvest your first crops, bring the priest some grain from the first portion of your grain harvest.', 'NLT'),
(3, 23, 11, 'On the day after the Sabbath, the priest will lift it up before the LORD so it may be accepted on your behalf.', 'NLT'),
(3, 23, 12, 'That same day you must sacrifice a year-old male lamb with no physical defects as a whole burnt offering to the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(3, 23, 13, 'A grain offering must accompany it consisting of three quarts of choice flour mixed with olive oil. It will be an offering given to the LORD by fire, and it will be very pleasing to him. Along with this sacrifice, you must also offer one quart of wine as a drink offering.', 'NLT'),
(3, 23, 14, 'Do not eat any bread or roasted grain or fresh kernels on that day until after you have brought this offering to your God. This is a permanent law for you, and it must be observed wherever you live.', 'NLT'),
(3, 23, 15, '"From the day after the Sabbath, the day the bundle of grain was lifted up as an offering, count off seven weeks.', 'NLT'),
(3, 23, 16, 'Keep counting until the day after the seventh Sabbath, fifty days later, and bring an offering of new grain to the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(3, 23, 17, 'From wherever you live, bring two loaves of bread to be lifted up before the LORD as an offering. These loaves must be baked from three quarts of choice flour that contains yeast. They will be an offering to the LORD from the first of your crops.', 'NLT'),
(3, 23, 18, 'Along with this bread, present seven one-year-old lambs with no physical defects, one bull, and two rams as burnt offerings to the LORD. These whole burnt offerings, together with the accompanying grain offerings and drink offerings, will be given to the LORD by fire and will be pleasing to him.', 'NLT'),
(3, 23, 19, 'Then you must offer one male goat as a sin offering and two one-year-old male lambs as a peace offering.', 'NLT'),
(3, 23, 20, '"The priest will lift up these offerings before the LORD, together with the loaves representing the first of your later crops. These offerings are holy to the LORD and will belong to the priests.', 'NLT'),
(3, 23, 21, 'That same day, you must stop all your regular work and gather for a sacred assembly. This is a permanent law for you, and it must be observed wherever you live.', 'NLT'),
(3, 23, 22, '"When you harvest the crops of your land, do not harvest the grain along the edges of your fields, and do not pick up what the harvesters drop. Leave it for the poor and the foreigners living among you. I, the LORD, am your God."', 'NLT'),
(3, 23, 23, 'The LORD told Moses', 'NLT'),
(3, 23, 24, 'to give these instructions to the Israelites: "On the appointed day in early autumn, you are to celebrate a day of complete rest. All your work must stop on that day. You will call the people to a sacred assembly--the Festival of Trumpets--with loud blasts from a trumpet.', 'NLT'),
(3, 23, 25, 'You must do no regular work on that day. Instead, you are to present offerings to the LORD by fire."', 'NLT'),
(3, 23, 26, 'Then the LORD said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(3, 23, 27, '"Remember that the Day of Atonement is to be celebrated on the ninth day after the Festival of Trumpets. On that day you must humble yourselves, gather for a sacred assembly, and present offerings to the LORD by fire.', 'NLT'),
(3, 23, 28, 'Do no work during that entire day because it is the Day of Atonement, when atonement will be made for you before the LORD your God, and payment will be made for your sins.', 'NLT'),
(3, 23, 29, 'Anyone who does not spend that day in humility will be cut off from the community.', 'NLT'),
(3, 23, 30, 'And I will destroy anyone among you who does any kind of work on that day.', 'NLT'),
(3, 23, 31, 'You must do no work at all! This is a permanent law for you, and it must be observed wherever you live.', 'NLT'),
(3, 23, 32, 'This will be a Sabbath day of total rest for you, and on that day you must humble yourselves. This time of rest and fasting will begin the evening before the Day of Atonement and extend until evening of that day."', 'NLT'),
(3, 23, 33, 'And the LORD said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(3, 23, 34, '"Tell the Israelites to begin the Festival of Shelters on the fifth day after the Day of Atonement. This festival to the LORD will last for seven days.', 'NLT'),
(3, 23, 35, 'It will begin with a sacred assembly on the first day, and all your regular work must stop.', 'NLT'),
(3, 23, 36, 'On each of the seven festival days, you must present offerings to the LORD by fire. On the eighth day, you must gather again for a sacred assembly and present another offering to the LORD by fire. This will be a solemn closing assembly, and no regular work may be done that day.', 'NLT'),
(3, 23, 37, '"These are the LORD''s appointed annual festivals. Celebrate them by gathering in sacred assemblies to present all the various offerings to the LORD by fire--whole burnt offerings and grain offerings, sacrificial meals and drink offerings--each on its proper day.', 'NLT'),
(3, 23, 38, 'These festivals must be observed in addition to the LORD''s regular Sabbath days. And these offerings must be given in addition to your personal gifts, the offerings you make to accompany your vows, and any freewill offerings that you present to the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(3, 23, 39, '"Now, on the first day of the Festival of Shelters, after you have harvested all the produce of the land, you will begin to celebrate this seven-day festival to the LORD. Remember that the first day and closing eighth day of the festival will be days of total rest.', 'NLT'),
(3, 23, 40, 'On the first day, gather fruit from citrus trees, and collect palm fronds and other leafy branches and willows that grow by the streams. Then rejoice before the LORD your God for seven days.', 'NLT'),
(3, 23, 41, 'You must observe this seven-day festival to the LORD every year. This is a permanent law for you, and it must be kept by all future generations.', 'NLT'),
(3, 23, 42, 'During the seven festival days, all of you who are Israelites by birth must live in shelters.', 'NLT'),
(3, 23, 43, 'This will remind each new generation of Israelites that their ancestors had to live in shelters when I rescued them from the land of Egypt. I, the LORD, am your God."', 'NLT'),
(3, 23, 44, 'So Moses gave these instructions regarding the annual festivals of the LORD to the Israelites.', 'NLT'),
(3, 24, 1, 'The LORD said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(3, 24, 2, '"Command the people of Israel to provide you with pure olive oil for the lampstand, so it can be kept burning continually.', 'NLT'),
(3, 24, 3, 'Aaron will set it up outside the inner curtain of the Most Holy Place in the Tabernacle and must arrange to have the lamps tended continually, from evening until morning, before the LORD. This is a permanent law for you, and it must be kept by all future generations.', 'NLT'),
(3, 24, 4, 'The lamps on the pure gold lampstand must be tended continually in the LORD''s presence.', 'NLT'),
(3, 24, 5, '"You must bake twelve loaves of bread from choice flour, using three quarts of flour for each loaf.', 'NLT'),
(3, 24, 6, 'Place the bread in the LORD''s presence on the pure gold table, and arrange the loaves in two rows, with six in each row.', 'NLT'),
(3, 24, 7, 'Sprinkle some pure frankincense near each row. It will serve as a token offering, to be burned in place of the bread as an offering given to the LORD by fire.', 'NLT'),
(3, 24, 8, 'Every Sabbath day this bread must be laid out before the LORD on behalf of the Israelites as a continual part of the covenant.', 'NLT'),
(3, 24, 9, 'The loaves of bread belong to Aaron and his male descendants, who must eat them in a sacred place, for they represent a most holy portion of the offerings given to the LORD by fire."', 'NLT'),
(3, 24, 10, 'One day a man who had an Israelite mother and an Egyptian father got into a fight with one of the Israelite men.', 'NLT'),
(3, 24, 11, 'During the fight, this son of an Israelite woman blasphemed the LORD''s name. So the man was brought to Moses for judgment. His mother''s name was Shelomith. She was the daughter of Dibri of the tribe of Dan.', 'NLT'),
(3, 24, 12, 'They put the man in custody until the LORD''s will in the matter should become clear.', 'NLT'),
(3, 24, 13, 'Then the LORD said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(3, 24, 14, '"Take the blasphemer outside the camp, and tell all those who heard him to lay their hands on his head. Then let the entire community stone him to death.', 'NLT'),
(3, 24, 15, 'Say to the people of Israel: Those who blaspheme God will suffer the consequences of their guilt and be punished.', 'NLT'),
(3, 24, 16, 'Anyone who blasphemes the LORD''s name must be stoned to death by the whole community of Israel. Any Israelite or foreigner among you who blasphemes the LORD''s name will surely die.', 'NLT'),
(3, 24, 17, '"Anyone who takes another person''s life must be put to death.', 'NLT'),
(3, 24, 18, '"Anyone who kills another person''s animal must pay it back in full--a live animal for the animal that was killed.', 'NLT'),
(3, 24, 19, '"Anyone who injures another person must be dealt with according to the injury inflicted--', 'NLT'),
(3, 24, 20, 'fracture for fracture, eye for eye, tooth for tooth. Whatever anyone does to hurt another person must be paid back in kind.', 'NLT'),
(3, 24, 21, '"Whoever kills an animal must make full restitution, but whoever kills another person must be put to death.', 'NLT'),
(3, 24, 22, '"These same regulations apply to Israelites by birth and foreigners who live among you. I, the LORD, am your God."', 'NLT'),
(3, 24, 23, 'After Moses gave all these instructions to the Israelites, they led the blasphemer outside the camp and stoned him to death, just as the LORD had commanded Moses.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 1, 'While Moses was on Mount Sinai, the LORD said to him,', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 2, '"Give these instructions to the Israelites: When you have entered the land I am giving you as an inheritance, the land itself must observe a Sabbath to the LORD every seventh year.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 3, 'For six years you may plant your fields and prune your vineyards and harvest your crops,', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 4, 'but during the seventh year the land will enjoy a Sabbath year of rest to the LORD. Do not plant your crops or prune your vineyards during that entire year.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 5, 'And don''t store away the crops that grow naturally or process the grapes that grow on your unpruned vines. The land is to have a year of total rest.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 6, 'But you, your male and female slaves, your hired servants, and any foreigners who live with you may eat the produce that grows naturally during the Sabbath year.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 7, 'And your livestock and the wild animals will also be allowed to eat of the land''s bounty.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 8, '"In addition, you must count off seven Sabbath years, seven years times seven, adding up to forty-nine years in all.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 9, 'Then on the Day of Atonement of the fiftieth year, blow the trumpets loud and long throughout the land.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 10, 'This year will be set apart as holy, a time to proclaim release for all who live there. It will be a jubilee year for you, when each of you returns to the lands that belonged to your ancestors and rejoins your clan.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 11, 'Yes, the fiftieth year will be a jubilee for you. During that year, do not plant any seeds or store away any of the crops that grow naturally, and do not process the grapes that grow on your unpruned vines.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 12, 'It will be a jubilee year for you, and you must observe it as a special and holy time. You may, however, eat the produce that grows naturally in the fields that year.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 13, 'In the Year of Jubilee each of you must return to the lands that belonged to your ancestors.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 14, '"When you make an agreement with a neighbor to buy or sell property, you must never take advantage of each other.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 15, 'When you buy land from your neighbor, the price of the land should be based on the number of years since the last jubilee. The seller will charge you only for the crop years left until the next Year of Jubilee.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 16, 'The more the years, the higher the price; the fewer the years, the lower the price. After all, the person selling the land is actually selling you a certain number of harvests.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 17, 'Show your fear of God by not taking advantage of each other. I, the LORD, am your God.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 18, '"If you want to live securely in the land, keep my laws and obey my regulations.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 19, 'Then the land will yield bumper crops, and you will eat your fill and live securely in it.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 20, 'But you might ask, `What will we eat during the seventh year, since we are not allowed to plant or harvest crops that year?''', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 21, 'The answer is, `I will order my blessing for you in the sixth year, so the land will produce a bumper crop, enough to support you for three years.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 22, 'As you plant the seed in the eighth year, you will still be eating the produce of the previous year. In fact, you will eat from the old crop until the new harvest comes in the ninth year.''', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 23, 'And remember, the land must never be sold on a permanent basis because it really belongs to me. You are only foreigners and tenants living with me.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 24, '"With every sale of land there must be a stipulation that the land can be redeemed at any time.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 25, 'If any of your Israelite relatives go bankrupt and are forced to sell some inherited land, then a close relative, a kinsman redeemer, may buy it back for them.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 26, 'If there is no one to redeem the land but the person who sold it manages to get enough money to buy it back,', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 27, 'then that person has the right to redeem it from the one who bought it. The price of the land will be based on the number of years until the next Year of Jubilee. After buying it back, the original owner may then return to the land.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 28, 'But if the original owner cannot afford to redeem it, then it will belong to the new owner until the next Year of Jubilee. In the jubilee year, the land will be returned to the original owner.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 29, '"Anyone who sells a house inside a walled city has the right to redeem it for a full year after its sale. During that time, the seller retains the right to buy it back.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 30, 'But if it is not redeemed within a year, then the house within the walled city will become the permanent property of the buyer. It will not be returned to the original owner in the Year of Jubilee.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 31, 'But a house in a village--a settlement without fortified walls--will be treated like property in the open fields. Such a house may be redeemed at any time and must be returned to the original owner in the Year of Jubilee.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 32, '"The Levites always have the right to redeem any house they have sold within the cities belonging to them.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 33, 'And any property that can be redeemed by the Levites--all houses within the Levitical cities--must be returned in the Year of Jubilee. After all, the cities reserved for the Levites are the only property they own in all Israel.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 34, 'The strip of pastureland around each of the Levitical cities may never be sold. It is their permanent ancestral property.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 35, '"If any of your Israelite relatives fall into poverty and cannot support themselves, support them as you would a resident foreigner and allow them to live with you.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 36, 'Do not demand an advance or charge interest on the money you lend them. Instead, show your fear of God by letting them live with you as your relatives.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 37, 'Remember, do not charge your relatives interest on anything you lend them, whether money or food.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 38, 'I, the LORD, am your God, who brought you out of Egypt to give you the land of Canaan and to be your God.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 39, '"If any of your Israelite relatives go bankrupt and sell themselves to you, do not treat them as slaves.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 40, 'Treat them instead as hired servants or as resident foreigners who live with you, and they will serve you only until the Year of Jubilee.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 41, 'At that time they and their children will no longer be obligated to you, and they will return to their clan and ancestral property.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 42, 'The people of Israel are my servants, whom I brought out of the land of Egypt, so they must never be sold as slaves.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 43, 'Show your fear of God by treating them well; never exercise your power over them in a ruthless way.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 44, '"However, you may purchase male or female slaves from among the foreigners who live among you.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 45, 'You may also purchase the children of such resident foreigners, including those who have been born in your land. You may treat them as your property,', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 46, 'passing them on to your children as a permanent inheritance. You may treat your slaves like this, but the people of Israel, your relatives, must never be treated this way.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 47, '"If a resident foreigner becomes rich, and if some of your Israelite relatives go bankrupt and sell themselves to such a foreigner,', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 48, 'they still retain the right of redemption. They may be bought back by a close relative--', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 49, 'an uncle, a nephew, or anyone else who is closely related. They may also redeem themselves if they can get the money.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 50, 'The price of their freedom will be based on the number of years left until the next Year of Jubilee--whatever it would cost to hire a servant for that number of years.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 51, 'If many years still remain, they will repay most of what they received when they sold themselves.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 52, 'If only a few years remain until the Year of Jubilee, then they will repay a relatively small amount for their redemption.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 53, 'The foreigner must treat them as servants hired on a yearly basis. You must not allow a resident foreigner to treat any of your Israelite relatives ruthlessly.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 54, 'If any Israelites have not been redeemed by the time the Year of Jubilee arrives, then they and their children must be set free at that time.', 'NLT'),
(3, 25, 55, 'For the people of Israel are my servants, whom I brought out of the land of Egypt. I, the LORD, am your God.', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 1, '"Do not make idols or set up carved images, sacred pillars, or shaped stones to be worshiped in your land. I, the LORD, am your God.', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 2, 'You must keep my Sabbath days of rest and show reverence for my sanctuary. I am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 3, '"If you keep my laws and are careful to obey my commands,', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 4, 'I will send the seasonal rains. The land will then yield its crops, and the trees will produce their fruit.', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 5, 'Your threshing season will extend until the grape harvest, and your grape harvest will extend until it is time to plant grain again. You will eat your fill and live securely in your land.', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 6, '"I will give you peace in the land, and you will be able to sleep without fear. I will remove the wild animals from your land and protect you from your enemies.', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 7, 'In fact, you will chase down all your enemies and slaughter them with your swords.', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 8, 'Five of you will chase a hundred, and a hundred of you will chase ten thousand! All your enemies will fall beneath the blows of your weapons.', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 9, '"I will look favorably upon you and multiply your people and fulfill my covenant with you.', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 10, 'You will have such a surplus of crops that you will need to get rid of the leftovers from the previous year to make room for each new harvest.', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 11, 'I will live among you, and I will not despise you.', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 12, 'I will walk among you; I will be your God, and you will be my people.', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 13, 'I, the LORD, am your God, who brought you from the land of Egypt so you would no longer be slaves. I have lifted the yoke of slavery from your neck so you can walk free with your heads held high.', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 14, '"However, if you do not listen to me or obey my commands,', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 15, 'and if you break my covenant by rejecting my laws and treating my regulations with contempt,', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 16, 'I will punish you. You will suffer from sudden terrors, with wasting diseases, and with burning fevers, causing your eyes to fail and your life to ebb away. You will plant your crops in vain because your enemies will eat them.', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 17, 'I will turn against you, and you will be defeated by all your enemies. They will rule over you, and you will run even when no one is chasing you!', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 18, '"And if, in spite of this, you still disobey me, I will punish you for your sins seven times over.', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 19, 'I will break down your arrogant spirit by making the skies above as unyielding as iron and the earth beneath as hard as bronze.', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 20, 'All your work will be for nothing, for your land will yield no crops, and your trees will bear no fruit.', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 21, '"If even then you remain hostile toward me and refuse to obey, I will inflict you with seven more disasters for your sins.', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 22, 'I will release wild animals that will kill your children and destroy your cattle, so your numbers will dwindle and your roads will be deserted.', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 23, '"And if you fail to learn a lesson from this and continue your hostility toward me,', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 24, 'then I myself will be hostile toward you, and I will personally strike you seven times over for your sins.', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 25, 'I will send armies against you to carry out these covenant threats. If you flee to your cities, I will send a plague to destroy you there, and you will be conquered by your enemies.', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 26, 'I will completely destroy your food supply, so the bread from one oven will have to be stretched to feed ten families. They will ration your food by weight, and even if you have food to eat, you will not be satisfied.', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 27, '"If after this you still refuse to listen and still remain hostile toward me,', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 28, 'then I will give full vent to my hostility. I will punish you seven times over for your sins.', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 29, 'You will eat the flesh of your own sons and daughters.', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 30, 'I will destroy your pagan shrines and cut down your incense altars. I will leave your corpses piled up beside your lifeless idols, and I will despise you.', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 31, 'I will make your cities desolate and destroy your places of worship, and I will take no pleasure in your offerings of incense.', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 32, 'Yes, I myself will devastate your land. Your enemies who come to occupy it will be utterly shocked at the destruction they see.', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 33, 'I will scatter you among the nations and attack you with my own weapons. Your land will become desolate, and your cities will lie in ruins.', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 34, 'Then at last the land will make up for its missed Sabbath years as it lies desolate during your years of exile in the land of your enemies. Then the land will finally rest and enjoy its Sabbaths.', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 35, 'As the land lies in ruins, it will take the rest you never allowed it to take every seventh year while you lived in it.', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 36, '"And for those of you who survive, I will demoralize you in the land of your enemies far away. You will live there in such constant fear that the sound of a leaf driven by the wind will send you fleeing. You will run as though chased by a warrior with a sword, and you will fall even when no one is pursuing you.', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 37, 'Yes, though no one is chasing you, you will stumble over each other in flight, as though fleeing in battle. You will have no power to stand before your enemies.', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 38, 'You will die among the foreign nations and be devoured in the land of your enemies.', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 39, 'Those still left alive will rot away in enemy lands because of their sins and the sins of their ancestors.', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 40, '"But at last my people will confess their sins and the sins of their ancestors for betraying me and being hostile toward me.', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 41, 'Finally, when I have given full expression to my hostility and have brought them to the land of their enemies, then at last their disobedient hearts will be humbled, and they will pay for their sins.', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 42, 'Then I will remember my covenant with Jacob, with Isaac, and with Abraham, and I will remember the land.', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 43, 'And the land will enjoy its years of Sabbath rest as it lies deserted. At last the people will receive the due punishment for their sins, for they rejected my regulations and despised my laws.', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 44, '"But despite all this, I will not utterly reject or despise them while they are in exile in the land of their enemies. I will not cancel my covenant with them by wiping them out. I, the LORD, am their God.', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 45, 'I will remember my ancient covenant with their ancestors, whom I brought out of Egypt while all the nations watched. I, the LORD, am their God."', 'NLT'),
(3, 26, 46, 'These are the laws, regulations, and instructions that the LORD gave to the Israelites through Moses on Mount Sinai.', 'NLT'),
(3, 27, 1, 'The LORD said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(3, 27, 2, '"Give the following instructions to the Israelites: If you make a special vow to dedicate someone to the LORD by paying the value of that person,', 'NLT'),
(3, 27, 3, 'here is the scale of values to be used. A man between the ages of twenty and sixty is valued at fifty pieces of silver;', 'NLT'),
(3, 27, 4, 'a woman of that age is valued at thirty pieces of silver.', 'NLT'),
(3, 27, 5, 'A boy between five and twenty is valued at twenty pieces of silver; a girl of that age is valued at ten pieces of silver.', 'NLT'),
(3, 27, 6, 'A boy between the ages of one month and five years is valued at five pieces of silver; a girl of that age is valued at three pieces of silver.', 'NLT'),
(3, 27, 7, 'A man older than sixty is valued at fifteen pieces of silver; a woman older than sixty is valued at ten pieces of silver.', 'NLT'),
(3, 27, 8, 'If you desire to make such a vow but cannot afford to pay the prescribed amount, go to the priest and he will evaluate your ability to pay. You will then pay the amount decided by the priest.', 'NLT'),
(3, 27, 9, '"If your vow involves giving a clean animal--one that is acceptable as an offering to the LORD--then your gift to the LORD will be considered holy.', 'NLT'),
(3, 27, 10, 'The animal should never be exchanged or substituted for another--neither a good animal for a bad one nor a bad animal for a good one. But if such an exchange is in fact made, then both the original animal and the substitute will be considered holy.', 'NLT'),
(3, 27, 11, 'But if your vow involves an unclean animal--one that is not acceptable as an offering to the LORD--then you must bring the animal to the priest.', 'NLT'),
(3, 27, 12, 'He will assess its value, and his assessment will be final.', 'NLT'),
(3, 27, 13, 'If you want to redeem the animal, you must pay the value set by the priest, plus 20 percent.', 'NLT'),
(3, 27, 14, '"If you dedicate a house to the LORD, the priest must come to assess its value. The priest''s assessment will be final.', 'NLT'),
(3, 27, 15, 'If you wish to redeem the house, you must pay the value set by the priest, plus 20 percent. Then the house will again belong to you.', 'NLT'),
(3, 27, 16, '"If you dedicate to the LORD a piece of your ancestral property, its value will be assessed by the amount of seed required to plant it--fifty pieces of silver for an area that produces five bushels of barley seed.', 'NLT'),
(3, 27, 17, 'If the field is dedicated to the LORD in the Year of Jubilee, then the entire assessment will apply.', 'NLT'),
(3, 27, 18, 'But if the field is dedicated after the Year of Jubilee, the priest must assess the land''s value in proportion to the years left until the next Year of Jubilee.', 'NLT'),
(3, 27, 19, 'If you decide to redeem the dedicated field, you must pay the land''s value as assessed by the priest, plus 20 percent. Then the field will again belong to you.', 'NLT'),
(3, 27, 20, 'But if you decide not to redeem the field, or if the field is sold to someone else by the priests, it can never be redeemed.', 'NLT'),
(3, 27, 21, 'When the field is released in the Year of Jubilee, it will be holy, a field specially set apart for the LORD. It will become the property of the priests.', 'NLT'),
(3, 27, 22, '"If you dedicate to the LORD a field that you have purchased but which is not part of your ancestral property,', 'NLT'),
(3, 27, 23, 'the priest must assess its value based on the years until the next Year of Jubilee. You must then give the assessed value of the land as a sacred donation to the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(3, 27, 24, 'In the Year of Jubilee the field will be released to the original owner from whom you purchased it.', 'NLT'),
(3, 27, 25, 'All the value assessments must be measured in terms of the standard sanctuary shekel.', 'NLT'),
(3, 27, 26, '"You may not dedicate to the LORD the firstborn of your cattle or sheep because the firstborn of these animals already belong to him.', 'NLT'),
(3, 27, 27, 'However, if it is the firstborn of a ceremonially unclean animal, you may redeem it by paying the priest''s assessment of its worth, plus 20 percent. If you do not redeem it, the priest may sell it to someone else for its assessed value.', 'NLT'),
(3, 27, 28, '"However, anything specially set apart by the LORD--whether a person, an animal, or an inherited field--must never be sold or redeemed. Anything devoted in this way has been set apart for the LORD as holy.', 'NLT'),
(3, 27, 29, 'A person specially set apart by the LORD for destruction cannot be redeemed. Such a person must be put to death.', 'NLT'),
(3, 27, 30, '"A tenth of the produce of the land, whether grain or fruit, belongs to the LORD and must be set apart to him as holy.', 'NLT'),
(3, 27, 31, 'If you want to redeem the LORD''s tenth of the fruit or grain, you must pay its value, plus 20 percent.', 'NLT'),
(3, 27, 32, 'The LORD also owns every tenth animal counted off from your herds and flocks. They are set apart to him as holy.', 'NLT'),
(3, 27, 33, 'The tenth animal must not be selected on the basis of whether it is good or bad, and no substitutions will be allowed. If any exchange is in fact made, then both the original animal and the substituted one will be considered holy and cannot be redeemed."', 'NLT'),
(3, 27, 34, 'These are the commands that the LORD gave to the Israelites through Moses on Mount Sinai.', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 1, 'One day in midspring, during the second year after Israel''s departure from Egypt, the LORD spoke to Moses in the Tabernacle in the wilderness of Sinai. He said,', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 2, '"Take a census of the whole community of Israel by their clans and families. List the names of all the men', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 3, 'twenty years old or older who are able to go to war. You and Aaron are to direct the project,', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 4, 'assisted by one family leader from each tribe."', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 5, 'These are the tribes and the names of the leaders chosen for the task: Reuben....................... Elizur son of Shedeur', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 6, 'Simeon................. Shelumiel son of Zurishaddai', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 7, 'Judah.................... Nahshon son of Amminadab', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 8, 'Issachar........................ Nethanel son of Zuar', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 9, 'Zebulun......................... Eliab son of Helon', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 10, 'Ephraim son of Joseph...... Elishama son of Ammihud Manasseh son of Joseph...... Gamaliel son of Pedahzur', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 11, 'Benjamin.................... Abidan son of Gideoni', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 12, 'Dan................... Ahiezer son of Ammishaddai', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 13, 'Asher......................... Pagiel son of Ocran', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 14, 'Gad......................... Eliasaph son of Deuel', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 15, 'Naphtali........................ Ahira son of Enan', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 16, 'These tribal leaders, heads of their own families, were chosen from among all the people.', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 17, 'Now Moses and Aaron and the chosen leaders', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 18, 'called together the whole community of Israel on that very day. All the people were registered according to their ancestry by their clans and families. The men of Israel twenty years old or older were registered, one by one,', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 19, 'just as the LORD had commanded Moses. So Moses counted the people there in the wilderness of Sinai.', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 20, 'This is the number of men twenty years old or older who were able to go to war, each listed according to his own clan and family: Reuben (Jacob''s oldest son)...... 46,500', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 21, '***', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 22, 'Simeon..................... 59,300', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 23, '***', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 24, 'Gad........................ 45,650', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 25, '***', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 26, 'Judah...................... 74,600', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 27, '***', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 28, 'Issachar.................... 54,400', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 29, '***', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 30, 'Zebulun.................... 57,400', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 31, '***', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 32, 'Ephraim son of Joseph........ 40,500', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 33, '***', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 34, 'Manasseh son of Joseph........ 32,200', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 35, '***', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 36, 'Benjamin................... 35,400', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 37, '***', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 38, 'Dan........................ 62,700', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 39, '***', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 40, 'Asher...................... 41,500', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 41, '***', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 42, 'Naphtali.................... 53,400', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 43, '***', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 44, 'These were the men counted by Moses and Aaron and the twelve leaders of Israel, all listed according to their ancestral descent.', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 45, 'They were counted by families--all the men of Israel who were twenty years old or older and able to go to war.', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 46, 'The total number was 603,550.', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 47, 'But this total did not include the Levites.', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 48, 'For the LORD had said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 49, '"Exempt the tribe of Levi from the census; do not include them when you count the rest of the Israelites.', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 50, 'You must put the Levites in charge of the Tabernacle of the Covenant, along with its furnishings and equipment. They must carry the Tabernacle and its equipment as you travel, and they must care for it and camp around it.', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 51, 'Whenever the Tabernacle is moved, the Levites will take it down and set it up again. Anyone else who goes too near the Tabernacle will be executed.', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 52, 'Each tribe of Israel will have a designated camping area with its own family banner.', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 53, 'But the Levites will camp around the Tabernacle of the Covenant to offer the people of Israel protection from the LORD''s fierce anger. The Levites are responsible to stand guard around the Tabernacle."', 'NLT'),
(4, 1, 54, 'So the Israelites did everything just as the LORD had commanded Moses.', 'NLT'),
(4, 2, 1, 'Then the LORD gave these instructions to Moses and Aaron:', 'NLT'),
(4, 2, 2, '"Each tribe will be assigned its own area in the camp, and the various groups will camp beneath their family banners. The Tabernacle will be located at the center of these tribal compounds.', 'NLT'),
(4, 2, 3, '"The divisions of Judah, Issachar, and Zebulun are to camp toward the sunrise on the east side of the Tabernacle, beneath their family banners. These are the names of the tribes, their leaders, and the number of their available troops: Judah....... Nahshon son of Amminadab.... 74,600', 'NLT'),
(4, 2, 4, '***', 'NLT'),
(4, 2, 5, 'Issachar.... Nethanel son of Zuar.......... 54,400', 'NLT'),
(4, 2, 6, '***', 'NLT'),
(4, 2, 7, 'Zebulun.... Eliab son of Helon............ 57,400', 'NLT'),
(4, 2, 8, '***', 'NLT'),
(4, 2, 9, 'So the total of all the troops on Judah''s side of the camp is 186,400. These three tribes are to lead the way whenever the Israelites travel to a new campsite.', 'NLT'),
(4, 2, 10, '"The divisions of Reuben, Simeon, and Gad are to camp on the south side of the Tabernacle, beneath their family banners. These are the names of the tribes, their leaders, and the number of their available troops: Reuben....... Elizur son of Shedeur.......... 46,500', 'NLT'),
(4, 2, 11, '***', 'NLT'),
(4, 2, 12, 'Simeon.... Shelumiel son of Zurishaddai.... 59,300', 'NLT'),
(4, 2, 13, '***', 'NLT'),
(4, 2, 14, 'Gad....... Eliasaph son of Deuel......... 45,650', 'NLT'),
(4, 2, 15, '***', 'NLT'),
(4, 2, 16, 'So the total of all the troops on Reuben''s side of the camp is 151,450. These three tribes will be second in line whenever the Israelites travel.', 'NLT'),
(4, 2, 17, '"Then the Levites will set out from the middle of the camp with the Tabernacle. All the tribes are to travel in the same order that they camp, each in position under the appropriate family banner.', 'NLT'),
(4, 2, 18, '"The divisions of Ephraim, Manasseh, and Benjamin are to camp on the west side of the Tabernacle, beneath their family banners. These are the names of the tribes, their leaders, and the number of their available troops: Ephraim....... Elishama son of Ammihud.... 40,500', 'NLT'),
(4, 2, 19, '***', 'NLT'),
(4, 2, 20, 'Manasseh.... Gamaliel son of Pedahzur..... 32,200', 'NLT'),
(4, 2, 21, '***', 'NLT'),
(4, 2, 22, 'Benjamin.... Abidan son of Gideoni....... 35,400', 'NLT'),
(4, 2, 23, '***', 'NLT'),
(4, 2, 24, 'So the total of all the troops on Ephraim''s side of the camp is 108,100, and they will follow the Levites in the line of march.', 'NLT'),
(4, 2, 25, '"The divisions of Dan, Asher, and Naphtali are to camp on the north side of the Tabernacle, beneath their family banners. These are the names of the tribes, their leaders, and the number of their available troops: Dan.......... Ahiezer son of Ammishaddai... 62,700', 'NLT'),
(4, 2, 26, '***', 'NLT'),
(4, 2, 27, 'Asher...... Pagiel son of Ocran........... 41,500', 'NLT'),
(4, 2, 28, '***', 'NLT'),
(4, 2, 29, 'Naphtali.... Ahira son of Enan............ 53,400', 'NLT'),
(4, 2, 30, '***', 'NLT'),
(4, 2, 31, 'So the total of all the troops on Dan''s side of the camp is 157,600. They are to bring up the rear whenever the Israelites move to a new campsite."', 'NLT'),
(4, 2, 32, 'In summary, the troops of Israel listed by their families totaled 603,550.', 'NLT'),
(4, 2, 33, 'The Levites were exempted from this census by the LORD''s command to Moses.', 'NLT'),
(4, 2, 34, 'So the people of Israel did everything just as the LORD had commanded Moses. Each clan and family set up camp and marched under their banners exactly as the LORD had instructed them.', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 1, 'This is the family line of Aaron and Moses as it was recorded when the LORD spoke to Moses on Mount Sinai:', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 2, 'Aaron''s sons were Nadab (the firstborn), Abihu, Eleazar, and Ithamar.', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 3, 'They were anointed and set apart to minister as priests.', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 4, 'But Nadab and Abihu died in the LORD''s presence in the wilderness of Sinai when they burned before the LORD a different kind of fire than he had commanded. Since they had no sons, this left only Eleazar and Ithamar to serve as priests with their father, Aaron.', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 5, 'Then the LORD said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 6, '"Call forward the tribe of Levi and present them to Aaron the priest as his assistants.', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 7, 'They will serve Aaron and the whole community, performing their sacred duties in and around the Tabernacle.', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 8, 'They will also maintain all the furnishings of the sacred tent, serving in the Tabernacle on behalf of all the Israelites.', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 9, 'Assign the Levites to Aaron and his sons as their assistants.', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 10, 'Appoint Aaron and his sons to carry out the duties of the priesthood. Anyone else who comes too near the sanctuary must be executed!"', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 11, 'And the LORD said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 12, '"I have chosen the Levites from among the Israelites as substitutes for all the firstborn sons of the people of Israel. The Levites are mine', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 13, 'because all the firstborn sons are mine. From the day I killed all the firstborn sons of the Egyptians, I set apart for myself all the firstborn in Israel of both men and animals. They are mine; I am the LORD."', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 14, 'The LORD spoke again to Moses, there in the wilderness of Sinai. He said,', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 15, '"Take a census of the tribe of Levi by its families and clans. Count every male who is one month old or older."', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 16, 'So Moses counted them, just as the LORD had commanded.', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 17, 'Levi had three sons, who were named Gershon, Kohath, and Merari.', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 18, 'The clans descended from Gershon were named for two of his descendants, Libni and Shimei.', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 19, 'The clans descended from Kohath were named for four of his descendants, Amram, Izhar, Hebron, and Uzziel.', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 20, 'The clans descended from Merari were named for two of his descendants, Mahli and Mushi. These were the Levite clans, listed according to their family groups.', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 21, 'The descendants of Gershon were composed of the clans descended from Libni and Shimei.', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 22, 'There were 7,500 males one month old or older among these Gershonite clans.', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 23, 'They were assigned the area to the west of the Tabernacle for their camp.', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 24, 'The leader of the Gershonite clans was Eliasaph son of Lael.', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 25, 'These two clans were responsible to care for the tent of the Tabernacle with its layers of coverings, its entry curtains,', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 26, 'the curtains of the courtyard that surrounded the Tabernacle and altar, the curtain at the courtyard entrance, the cords, and all the equipment related to their use.', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 27, 'The descendants of Kohath were composed of the clans descended from Amram, Izhar, Hebron, and Uzziel.', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 28, 'There were 8,600 males one month old or older among these Kohathite clans. They were responsible for the care of the sanctuary.', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 29, 'They were assigned the area south of the Tabernacle for their camp.', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 30, 'The leader of the Kohathite clans was Elizaphan son of Uzziel.', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 31, 'These four clans were responsible for the care of the Ark, the table, the lampstand, the altars, the various utensils used in the sanctuary, the inner curtain, and all the equipment related to their use.', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 32, 'Eleazar the priest, Aaron''s son, was the chief administrator over all the Levites, with special responsibility for the oversight of the sanctuary.', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 33, 'The descendants of Merari were composed of the clans descended from Mahli and Mushi.', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 34, 'There were 6,200 males one month old or older among these Merarite clans.', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 35, 'They were assigned the area north of the Tabernacle for their camp. The leader of the Merarite clans was Zuriel son of Abihail.', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 36, 'These two clans were responsible for the care of the frames supporting the Tabernacle, the crossbars, the pillars, the bases, and all the equipment related to their use.', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 37, 'They were also responsible for the posts of the courtyard and all their bases, pegs, and cords.', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 38, 'The area in front of the Tabernacle in the east toward the sunrise was reserved for the tents of Moses and of Aaron and his sons, who had the final responsibility for the sanctuary on behalf of the people of Israel. Anyone other than a priest or Levite who came too near the sanctuary was to be executed.', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 39, 'So among the Levite clans counted by Moses and Aaron at the LORD''s command, there were 22,000 males one month old or older.', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 40, 'Then the LORD said to Moses, "Now count all the firstborn sons in Israel who are one month old or older, and register each name.', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 41, 'The Levites will be reserved for me as substitutes for the firstborn sons of Israel; I am the LORD. And the Levites'' livestock are mine as substitutes for the firstborn livestock of the whole nation of Israel."', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 42, 'So Moses counted the firstborn sons of the people of Israel, just as the LORD had commanded.', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 43, 'The total number of firstborn sons who were one month old or older was 22,273.', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 44, 'Now the LORD said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 45, '"Take the Levites in place of the firstborn sons of the people of Israel. And take the livestock of the Levites as substitutes for the firstborn livestock of the people of Israel. The Levites will be mine; I am the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 46, 'To redeem the 273 firstborn sons of Israel who are in excess of the number of Levites,', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 47, 'collect five pieces of silver for each person, each piece weighing the same as the standard sanctuary shekel.', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 48, 'Give the silver to Aaron and his sons as the redemption price for the extra firstborn sons."', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 49, 'So Moses collected redemption money for the firstborn sons of Israel who exceeded the number of Levites.', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 50, 'The silver collected on behalf of these firstborn sons of Israel came to about thirty-four pounds in weight.', 'NLT'),
(4, 3, 51, 'And Moses gave the redemption money to Aaron and his sons as the LORD had commanded.', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 1, 'Then the LORD said to Moses and Aaron,', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 2, '"Take a census of the clans and families of the Kohathite division of the Levite tribe.', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 3, 'Count all the men between the ages of thirty and fifty who qualify to work in the Tabernacle.', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 4, '"The duties of the Kohathites at the Tabernacle will relate to the most sacred objects.', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 5, 'When the camp moves, Aaron and his sons must enter the Tabernacle first to take down the inner curtain and cover the Ark of the Covenant with it.', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 6, 'Then they must cover the inner curtain with fine goatskin leather, and the goatskin leather with a dark blue cloth. Finally, they must put the carrying poles of the Ark in place.', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 7, '"Next they must spread a blue cloth over the table, where the Bread of the Presence is displayed, and place the dishes, spoons, bowls, cups, and the special bread on the cloth.', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 8, 'They must spread a scarlet cloth over that, and finally a covering of fine goatskin leather on top of the scarlet cloth. Then they must insert the carrying poles into the table.', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 9, '"Next they must cover the lampstand with a dark blue cloth, along with its lamps, lamp snuffers, trays, and special jars of olive oil.', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 10, 'The lampstand with its utensils must then be covered with fine goatskin leather, and the bundle must be placed on a carrying frame.', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 11, '"Aaron and his sons must also spread a dark blue cloth over the gold altar and cover this cloth with a covering of fine goatskin leather. Then they are to attach the carrying poles to the altar.', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 12, 'All the remaining utensils of the sanctuary must be wrapped in a dark blue cloth, covered with fine goatskin leather, and placed on the carrying frame.', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 13, '"The ashes must be removed from the altar, and the altar must then be covered with a purple cloth.', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 14, 'All the altar utensils--the firepans, hooks, shovels, basins, and all the containers--are to be placed on the cloth, and a covering of fine goatskin leather must be spread over them. Finally, the carrying poles must be put in place.', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 15, 'When Aaron and his sons have finished covering the sanctuary and all the sacred utensils, the Kohathites will come and carry these things to the next destination. But they must not touch the sacred objects, or they will die. So these are the objects of the Tabernacle that the Kohathites must carry.', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 16, '"Eleazar son of Aaron the priest will be responsible for the oil of the lampstand, the fragrant incense, the daily grain offering, and the anointing oil. In fact, the supervision of the entire Tabernacle and everything in it will be Eleazar''s responsibility."', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 17, 'Then the LORD said to Moses and Aaron,', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 18, '"Don''t let the Kohathite clans be destroyed from among the Levites!', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 19, 'This is what you must do so they will live and not die when they approach the most sacred objects. Aaron and his sons must always go in with them and assign a specific duty or load to each person.', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 20, 'Otherwise they must not approach the sanctuary and look at the sacred objects for even a moment, or they will die."', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 21, 'And the LORD said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 22, '"Take a census of the clans and families of the Gershonite division of the tribe of Levi.', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 23, 'Count all the men between the ages of thirty and fifty who are eligible to serve in the Tabernacle.', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 24, '"The duties of the Gershonites will be in the areas of general service and carrying loads.', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 25, 'They must carry the curtains of the Tabernacle, the Tabernacle itself with its coverings, the outer covering of fine goatskin leather, and the curtain for the Tabernacle entrance.', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 26, 'They are also to carry the curtains for the courtyard walls that surround the Tabernacle and altar, the curtain across the courtyard entrance, the necessary cords, and all the altar''s accessories. The Gershonites are responsible for transporting all these items.', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 27, 'Aaron and his sons will direct the Gershonites regarding their duties, whether it involves moving or doing other work. They must assign the Gershonites the loads they are to carry.', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 28, 'So these are the duties assigned to the Gershonites at the Tabernacle. They will be directly responsible to Ithamar son of Aaron the priest.', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 29, '"Now take a census of the clans and families of the Merarite division of the Levite tribe.', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 30, 'Count all the men between the ages of thirty and fifty who are eligible to serve in the Tabernacle.', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 31, '"Their duties at the Tabernacle will consist of carrying loads. They will be required to carry the frames of the Tabernacle, the crossbars, the pillars with their bases,', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 32, 'the posts for the courtyard walls with their bases, pegs, cords, accessories, and everything else related to their use. You must assign the various loads to each man by name.', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 33, 'So these are the duties of the Merarites at the Tabernacle. They are directly responsible to Ithamar son of Aaron the priest."', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 34, 'So Moses, Aaron, and the other leaders of the community counted the Kohathite division by its clans and families.', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 35, 'The count included all the men between thirty and fifty years of age who were eligible for service in the Tabernacle,', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 36, 'and the total number came to 2,750.', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 37, 'So this was the total of all those from the Kohathite clans who were eligible to serve at the Tabernacle. Moses and Aaron counted them, just as the LORD had commanded through Moses.', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 38, 'The Gershonite division was also counted by its clans and families.', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 39, 'The count included all the men between thirty and fifty years of age who were eligible for service in the Tabernacle,', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 40, 'and the total number came to 2,630.', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 41, 'So this was the total of all those from the Gershonite clans who were eligible to serve at the Tabernacle. Moses and Aaron counted them, just as the LORD had commanded.', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 42, 'The Merarite division was also counted by its clans and families.', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 43, 'The count included all the men between thirty and fifty years of age who were eligible for service in the Tabernacle,', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 44, 'and the total number came to 3,200.', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 45, 'So this was the total of all those from the Merarite clans who were eligible for service. Moses and Aaron counted them, just as the LORD had commanded through Moses.', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 46, 'So Moses, Aaron, and the leaders of Israel counted all the Levites by their clans and families.', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 47, 'All the men between thirty and fifty years of age who were eligible for service in the Tabernacle and for its transportation', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 48, 'numbered 8,580.', 'NLT'),
(4, 4, 49, 'Each man was assigned his task and told what to carry, just as the LORD had commanded through Moses. And so the census was completed, just as the LORD had commanded Moses.', 'NLT'),
(4, 5, 1, 'The LORD gave these instructions to Moses:', 'NLT'),
(4, 5, 2, '"Command the people of Israel to remove anyone from the camp who has a contagious skin disease or a discharge, or who has been defiled by touching a dead person.', 'NLT'),
(4, 5, 3, 'This applies to men and women alike. Remove them so they will not defile the camp, where I live among you."', 'NLT'),
(4, 5, 4, 'So the Israelites did just as the LORD had commanded Moses and removed such people from the camp.', 'NLT'),
(4, 5, 5, 'Then the LORD said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(4, 5, 6, '"Give these instructions to the people of Israel: If any of the people--men or women--betray the LORD by doing wrong to another person, they are guilty.', 'NLT'),
(4, 5, 7, 'They must confess their sin and make full restitution for what they have done, adding a penalty of 20 percent and returning it to the person who was wronged.', 'NLT'),
(4, 5, 8, 'But if the person who was wronged is dead, and there are no near relatives to whom restitution can be made, it belongs to the LORD and must be given to the priest, along with a ram for atonement.', 'NLT'),
(4, 5, 9, 'All the sacred gifts that the Israelites bring to a priest will belong to him.', 'NLT'),
(4, 5, 10, 'Each priest may keep the sacred donations that he receives."', 'NLT'),
(4, 5, 11, 'And the LORD said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(4, 5, 12, '"Say to the people of Israel: `Suppose a man''s wife goes astray and is unfaithful to her husband.', 'NLT'),
(4, 5, 13, 'Suppose she sleeps with another man, but there is no witness since she was not caught in the act.', 'NLT'),
(4, 5, 14, 'If her husband becomes jealous and suspicious of his wife, even if she has not defiled herself,', 'NLT'),
(4, 5, 15, 'the husband must bring his wife to the priest with an offering of two quarts of barley flour to be presented on her behalf. Do not mix it with olive oil or frankincense, for it is a jealousy offering--an offering of inquiry to find out if she is guilty.', 'NLT'),
(4, 5, 16, '" `The priest must then present her before the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(4, 5, 17, 'He must take some holy water in a clay jar and mix it with dust from the Tabernacle floor.', 'NLT'),
(4, 5, 18, 'When he has presented her before the LORD, he must unbind her hair and place the offering of inquiry--the jealousy offering--in her hands to determine whether or not her husband''s suspicions are justified. The priest will stand before her, holding the jar of bitter water that brings a curse to those who are guilty.', 'NLT'),
(4, 5, 19, 'The priest will put the woman under oath and say to her, "If no other man has slept with you, and you have not defiled yourself by being unfaithful, may you be immune from the effects of this bitter water that causes the curse.', 'NLT'),
(4, 5, 20, 'But if you have gone astray while under your husband''s authority and defiled yourself by sleeping with another man"--', 'NLT'),
(4, 5, 21, 'at this point the priest must put the woman under this oath--"then may the people see that the LORD''s curse is upon you when he makes you infertile.', 'NLT'),
(4, 5, 22, 'Now may this water that brings the curse enter your body and make you infertile. "And the woman will be required to say, "Yes, let it be so."', 'NLT'),
(4, 5, 23, 'Then the priest will write these curses on a piece of leather and wash them off into the bitter water.', 'NLT'),
(4, 5, 24, 'He will then make the woman drink the bitter water, so it may bring on the curse and cause bitter suffering in cases of guilt.', 'NLT'),
(4, 5, 25, '" `Then the priest will take the jealousy offering from the woman''s hand, lift it up before the LORD, and carry it to the altar.', 'NLT'),
(4, 5, 26, 'He will take a handful as a token portion and burn it on the altar. Then he will require the woman to drink the water.', 'NLT'),
(4, 5, 27, 'If she has defiled herself by being unfaithful to her husband, the water that brings the curse will cause bitter suffering. She will become infertile, and her name will become a curse word among her people.', 'NLT'),
(4, 5, 28, 'But if she has not defiled herself and is pure, she will be unharmed and will still be able to have children.', 'NLT'),
(4, 5, 29, '" `This is the ritual law for dealing with jealousy. If a woman defiles herself by being unfaithful to her husband,', 'NLT'),
(4, 5, 30, 'or if a man is overcome with jealousy and suspicion that his wife has been unfaithful, the husband must present his wife before the LORD, and the priest will apply this entire ritual law to her.', 'NLT'),
(4, 5, 31, 'The husband will be innocent of any guilt in this matter, but his wife will be held accountable for her sin.''"', 'NLT'),
(4, 6, 1, 'Then the LORD said to Moses, "Speak to the people of Israel and give them these instructions:', 'NLT'),
(4, 6, 2, 'If some of the people, either men or women, take the special vow of a Nazirite, setting themselves apart to the LORD in a special way,', 'NLT'),
(4, 6, 3, 'they must give up wine and other alcoholic drinks. They must not use vinegar made from wine, they must not drink other fermented drinks or fresh grape juice, and they must not eat grapes or raisins.', 'NLT'),
(4, 6, 4, 'As long as they are bound by their Nazirite vow, they are not allowed to eat or drink anything that comes from a grapevine, not even the grape seeds or skins.', 'NLT'),
(4, 6, 5, '"They must never cut their hair throughout the time of their vow, for they are holy and set apart to the LORD. That is why they must let their hair grow long.', 'NLT'),
(4, 6, 6, 'And they may not go near a dead body during the entire period of their vow to the LORD,', 'NLT'),
(4, 6, 7, 'even if their own father, mother, brother, or sister has died. They must not defile the hair on their head, because it is the symbol of their separation to God.', 'NLT'),
(4, 6, 8, 'This applies as long as they are set apart to the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(4, 6, 9, '"If their hair is defiled because someone suddenly falls dead beside them, they must wait for seven days and then shave their heads. Then they will be cleansed from their defilement.', 'NLT'),
(4, 6, 10, 'On the eighth day they must bring two turtledoves or two young pigeons to the priest at the entrance of the Tabernacle.', 'NLT'),
(4, 6, 11, 'The priest will offer one of the birds for a sin offering and the other for a burnt offering. In this way, he will make atonement for the guilt they incurred from the dead body. Then they must renew their vow that day and let their hair begin to grow again.', 'NLT'),
(4, 6, 12, 'The days of their vow that were completed before their defilement no longer count. They must rededicate themselves to the LORD for the full term of their vow, and each must bring a one-year-old male lamb for a guilt offering.', 'NLT'),
(4, 6, 13, '"This is the ritual law of the Nazirites. At the conclusion of their time of separation as Nazirites, they must each go to the entrance of the Tabernacle', 'NLT'),
(4, 6, 14, 'and offer these sacrifices to the LORD: a one-year-old male lamb without defect for a burnt offering, a one-year-old female lamb without defect for a sin offering, a ram without defect for a peace offering,', 'NLT'),
(4, 6, 15, 'a basket of bread made without yeast--cakes of choice flour mixed with olive oil and wafers spread with olive oil--along with their prescribed grain offerings and drink offerings.', 'NLT'),
(4, 6, 16, 'The priest will present these offerings before the LORD: first the sin offering and the burnt offering;', 'NLT'),
(4, 6, 17, 'then the ram for a peace offering, along with the basket of bread made without yeast. The priest must also make the prescribed grain offering and drink offering.', 'NLT'),
(4, 6, 18, '"Then the Nazirites will shave their hair at the entrance of the Tabernacle and put it on the fire beneath the peace-offering sacrifice.', 'NLT'),
(4, 6, 19, 'After each Nazirite''s head has been shaved, the priest will take for each of them the boiled shoulder of the ram, one cake made without yeast, and one wafer made without yeast, and put them all into the Nazirite''s hands.', 'NLT'),
(4, 6, 20, 'The priest will then lift the gifts up before the LORD in a gesture of offering. These are holy portions for the priest, along with the breast and thigh pieces that were lifted up before the LORD. After this ceremony the Nazirites may again drink wine.', 'NLT'),
(4, 6, 21, '"This is the ritual law of the Nazirites. If any Nazirites have vowed to give the LORD anything else beyond what is required by their normal Nazirite vow, they must fulfill their special vow exactly as they have promised."', 'NLT'),
(4, 6, 22, 'Then the LORD said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(4, 6, 23, '"Instruct Aaron and his sons to bless the people of Israel with this special blessing:', 'NLT'),
(4, 6, 24, '`May the LORD bless you and protect you.', 'NLT'),
(4, 6, 25, 'May the LORD smile on you and be gracious to you.', 'NLT'),
(4, 6, 26, 'May the LORD show you his favor and give you his peace.''', 'NLT'),
(4, 6, 27, 'This is how Aaron and his sons will designate the Israelites as my people, and I myself will bless them."', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 1, 'On the day Moses set up the Tabernacle, he anointed it and set it apart as holy, along with all its furnishings and the altar with its utensils.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 2, 'Then the leaders of Israel--the tribal leaders who had organized the census--came and brought their offerings.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 3, 'Together they brought six carts and twelve oxen. There was a cart for every two leaders and an ox for each leader. They presented these to the LORD in front of the Tabernacle.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 4, 'Then the LORD said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 5, '"Receive their gifts and use these oxen and carts for the work of the Tabernacle. Distribute them among the Levites according to the work they have to do."', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 6, 'So Moses presented the carts and oxen to the Levites.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 7, 'He gave two carts and four oxen to the Gershonite division for their work,', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 8, 'and four carts and eight oxen to the Merarite division for their work. All their work was done under the leadership of Ithamar son of Aaron the priest.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 9, 'But he gave none of the carts or oxen to the Kohathite division, since they were required to carry the sacred objects of the Tabernacle on their shoulders.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 10, 'The leaders also presented dedication gifts for the altar at the time it was anointed. They each placed their gifts before the altar.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 11, 'The LORD said to Moses, "Let each leader bring his gift on a different day for the dedication of the altar."', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 12, 'On the first day Nahshon son of Amminadab, leader of the tribe of Judah, presented his offering.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 13, 'The offering consisted of a silver platter weighing about 3 1/4 pounds and a silver basin of about 1 3/4 pounds. These were both filled with grain offerings of choice flour mixed with olive oil.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 14, 'He also brought a gold container weighing about four ounces, which was filled with incense.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 15, 'He brought a young bull, a ram, and a one-year-old male lamb as a burnt offering;', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 16, 'a male goat for a sin offering;', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 17, 'and two oxen, five rams, five male goats, and five one-year-old male lambs for a peace offering. This was the offering brought by Nahshon son of Amminadab.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 18, 'On the second day Nethanel son of Zuar, leader of the tribe of Issachar, presented his offering.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 19, 'The offering consisted of a silver platter weighing about 3 1/4 pounds and a silver basin of about 1 3/4 pounds. These were both filled with grain offerings of choice flour mixed with olive oil.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 20, 'He also brought a gold container weighing about four ounces, which was filled with incense.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 21, 'He brought a young bull, a ram, and a one-year-old male lamb as a burnt offering;', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 22, 'a male goat for a sin offering;', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 23, 'and two oxen, five rams, five male goats, and five one-year-old male lambs for a peace offering. This was the offering brought by Nethanel son of Zuar.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 24, 'On the third day Eliab son of Helon, leader of the tribe of Zebulun, presented his offering.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 25, 'The offering consisted of a silver platter weighing about 3 1/4 pounds and a silver basin of about 1 3/4 pounds. These were both filled with grain offerings of choice flour mixed with olive oil.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 26, 'He also brought a gold container weighing about four ounces, which was filled with incense.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 27, 'He brought a young bull, a ram, and a one-year-old male lamb as a burnt offering;', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 28, 'a male goat for a sin offering;', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 29, 'and two oxen, five rams, five male goats, and five one-year-old male lambs for a peace offering. This was the offering brought by Eliab son of Helon.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 30, 'On the fourth day Elizur son of Shedeur, leader of the tribe of Reuben, presented his offering.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 31, 'The offering consisted of a silver platter weighing about 3 1/4 pounds and a silver basin of about 1 3/4 pounds. These were both filled with grain offerings of choice flour mixed with olive oil.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 32, 'He also brought a gold container weighing about four ounces, which was filled with incense.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 33, 'He brought a young bull, a ram, and a one-year-old male lamb as a burnt offering;', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 34, 'a male goat for a sin offering;', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 35, 'and two oxen, five rams, five male goats, and five one-year-old male lambs for a peace offering. This was the offering brought by Elizur son of Shedeur.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 36, 'On the fifth day Shelumiel son of Zurishaddai, leader of the tribe of Simeon, presented his offering.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 37, 'The offering consisted of a silver platter weighing about 3 1/4 pounds and a silver basin of about 1 3/4 pounds. These were both filled with grain offerings of choice flour mixed with olive oil.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 38, 'He also brought a gold container weighing about four ounces, which was filled with incense.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 39, 'He brought a young bull, a ram, and a one-year-old male lamb as a burnt offering;', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 40, 'a male goat for a sin offering;', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 41, 'and two oxen, five rams, five male goats, and five one-year-old male lambs for a peace offering. This was the offering brought by Shelumiel son of Zurishaddai.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 42, 'On the sixth day Eliasaph son of Deuel, leader of the tribe of Gad, presented his offering.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 43, 'The offering consisted of a silver platter weighing about 3 1/4 pounds and a silver basin of about 1 3/4 pounds. These were both filled with grain offerings of choice flour mixed with olive oil.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 44, 'He also brought a gold container weighing about four ounces, which was filled with incense.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 45, 'He brought a young bull, a ram, and a one-year-old male lamb as a burnt offering;', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 46, 'a male goat for a sin offering;', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 47, 'and two oxen, five rams, five male goats, and five one-year-old male lambs for a peace offering. This was the offering brought by Eliasaph son of Deuel.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 48, 'On the seventh day Elishama son of Ammihud, leader of the tribe of Ephraim, presented his offering.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 49, 'The offering consisted of a silver platter weighing about 3 1/4 pounds and a silver basin of about 1 3/4 pounds. These were both filled with grain offerings of choice flour mixed with olive oil.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 50, 'He also brought a gold container weighing about four ounces, which was filled with incense.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 51, 'He brought a young bull, a ram, and a one-year-old male lamb as a burnt offering;', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 52, 'a male goat for a sin offering;', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 53, 'and two oxen, five rams, five male goats, and five one-year-old male lambs for a peace offering. This was the offering brought by Elishama son of Ammihud.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 54, 'On the eighth day Gamaliel son of Pedahzur, leader of the tribe of Manasseh, presented his offering.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 55, 'The offering consisted of a silver platter weighing about 3 1/4 pounds and a silver basin of about 1 3/4 pounds. These were both filled with grain offerings of choice flour mixed with olive oil.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 56, 'He also brought a gold container weighing about four ounces, which was filled with incense.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 57, 'He brought a young bull, a ram, and a one-year-old male lamb as a burnt offering;', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 58, 'a male goat for a sin offering;', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 59, 'and two oxen, five rams, five male goats, and five one-year-old male lambs for a peace offering. This was the offering brought by Gamaliel son of Pedahzur.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 60, 'On the ninth day Abidan son of Gideoni, leader of the tribe of Benjamin, presented his offering.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 61, 'The offering consisted of a silver platter weighing about 3 1/4 pounds and a silver basin of about 1 3/4 pounds. These were both filled with grain offerings of choice flour mixed with olive oil.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 62, 'He also brought a gold container weighing about four ounces, which was filled with incense.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 63, 'He brought a young bull, a ram, and a one-year-old male lamb as a burnt offering;', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 64, 'a male goat for a sin offering;', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 65, 'and two oxen, five rams, five male goats, and five one-year-old male lambs for a peace offering. This was the offering brought by Abidan son of Gideoni.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 66, 'On the tenth day Ahiezer son of Ammishaddai, leader of the tribe of Dan, presented his offering.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 67, 'The offering consisted of a silver platter weighing about 3 1/4 pounds and a silver basin of about 1 3/4 pounds. These were both filled with grain offerings of choice flour mixed with olive oil.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 68, 'He also brought a gold container weighing about four ounces, which was filled with incense.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 69, 'He brought a young bull, a ram, and a one-year-old male lamb as a burnt offering;', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 70, 'a male goat for a sin offering;', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 71, 'and two oxen, five rams, five male goats, and five one-year-old male lambs for a peace offering. This was the offering brought by Ahiezer son of Ammishaddai.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 72, 'On the eleventh day Pagiel son of Ocran, leader of the tribe of Asher, presented his offering.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 73, 'The offering consisted of a silver platter weighing about 3 1/4 pounds and a silver basin of about 1 3/4 pounds. These were both filled with grain offerings of choice flour mixed with olive oil.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 74, 'He also brought a gold container weighing about four ounces, which was filled with incense.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 75, 'He brought a young bull, a ram, and a one-year-old male lamb as a burnt offering;', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 76, 'a male goat for a sin offering;', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 77, 'and two oxen, five rams, five male goats, and five one-year-old male lambs for a peace offering. This was the offering brought by Pagiel son of Ocran.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 78, 'On the twelfth day Ahira son of Enan, leader of the tribe of Naphtali, presented his offering.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 79, 'The offering consisted of a silver platter weighing about 3 1/4 pounds and a silver basin of about 1 3/4 pounds. These were both filled with grain offerings of choice flour mixed with olive oil.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 80, 'He also brought a gold container weighing about four ounces, which was filled with incense.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 81, 'He brought a young bull, a ram, and a one-year-old male lamb as a burnt offering;', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 82, 'a male goat for a sin offering;', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 83, 'and two oxen, five rams, five male goats, and five one-year-old male lambs for a peace offering. This was the offering brought by Ahira son of Enan.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 84, 'So this was the dedication offering for the altar, brought by the leaders of Israel at the time it was anointed: twelve silver platters, twelve silver basins, and twelve gold incense containers.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 85, 'In all, the silver objects weighed about 60 pounds, about 3 1/4 pounds for each platter and 1 3/4 pounds for each basin.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 86, 'The weight of the donated gold came to about three pounds, about four ounces for each of the gold containers that were filled with incense.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 87, 'Twelve bulls, twelve rams, and twelve one-year-old male lambs were donated for the burnt offerings, along with their prescribed grain offerings. Twelve male goats were brought for the sin offerings.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 88, 'Twenty-four young bulls, sixty rams, sixty male goats, and sixty one-year-old male lambs were donated for the peace offerings. This was the dedication offering for the altar after it was anointed.', 'NLT'),
(4, 7, 89, 'Whenever Moses went into the Tabernacle to speak with the LORD, he heard the voice speaking to him from between the two cherubim above the Ark''s cover--the place of atonement--that rests on the Ark of the Covenant. The LORD spoke to him from there.', 'NLT'),
(4, 8, 1, 'The LORD said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(4, 8, 2, '"Tell Aaron that when he sets up the seven lamps in the lampstand, he is to place them so their light shines forward."', 'NLT'),
(4, 8, 3, 'So Aaron did this. He set up the seven lamps so they reflected their light forward, just as the LORD had commanded Moses.', 'NLT'),
(4, 8, 4, 'The entire lampstand, from its base to its decorative blossoms, was made of beaten gold. It was built according to the exact design the LORD had shown Moses.', 'NLT'),
(4, 8, 5, 'Then the LORD said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(4, 8, 6, '"Now set the Levites apart from the rest of the people of Israel and make them ceremonially clean.', 'NLT'),
(4, 8, 7, 'Do this by sprinkling them with the water of purification. And have them shave their entire body and wash their clothing. Then they will be ceremonially clean.', 'NLT'),
(4, 8, 8, 'Have them bring a young bull and a grain offering of choice flour mixed with olive oil, along with a second young bull for a sin offering.', 'NLT'),
(4, 8, 9, 'Then assemble the whole community of Israel and present the Levites at the entrance of the Tabernacle.', 'NLT'),
(4, 8, 10, 'When you bring the Levites before the LORD, the people of Israel must lay their hands on them.', 'NLT'),
(4, 8, 11, 'Aaron must present the Levites to the LORD as a special offering from the people of Israel, thus dedicating them to the LORD''s service.', 'NLT'),
(4, 8, 12, '"Next the Levites will lay their hands on the heads of the young bulls and present them to the LORD. One will be for a sin offering and the other for a burnt offering, to make atonement for the Levites.', 'NLT'),
(4, 8, 13, 'Then have the Levites stand in front of Aaron and his sons, and present them as a special offering to the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(4, 8, 14, 'In this way, you will set the Levites apart from the rest of the people of Israel, and the Levites will belong to me.', 'NLT'),
(4, 8, 15, 'After this, they may go in and out of the Tabernacle to do their work, because you have purified them and presented them as a special offering.', 'NLT'),
(4, 8, 16, '"Of all the people of Israel, the Levites are reserved for me. I have claimed them for myself in place of all the firstborn sons of the Israelites; I have taken the Levites as their substitutes.', 'NLT'),
(4, 8, 17, 'For all the firstborn males among the people of Israel are mine, both people and animals. I set them apart for myself on the night I killed all the firstborn sons of the Egyptians.', 'NLT'),
(4, 8, 18, 'Yes, I claim the Levites in place of all the firstborn sons of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(4, 8, 19, 'And of all the Israelites, I have assigned the Levites to Aaron and his sons. They will serve in the Tabernacle on behalf of the Israelites and make atonement for them so no plague will strike them when they approach the sanctuary."', 'NLT'),
(4, 8, 20, 'So Moses, Aaron, and the whole community of Israel dedicated the Levites, carefully following all the LORD''s instructions to Moses.', 'NLT'),
(4, 8, 21, 'The Levites purified themselves and washed their clothes, and Aaron presented them to the LORD as a special offering. He then performed the rite of atonement over them to purify them.', 'NLT'),
(4, 8, 22, 'From then on the Levites went into the Tabernacle to perform their duties, helping Aaron and his sons. So they carried out all the commands that the LORD gave Moses concerning the Levites.', 'NLT'),
(4, 8, 23, 'The LORD also instructed Moses,', 'NLT'),
(4, 8, 24, '"This is the rule the Levites must follow: They must begin serving in the Tabernacle at the age of twenty-five,', 'NLT'),
(4, 8, 25, 'and they must retire at the age of fifty.', 'NLT'),
(4, 8, 26, 'After retirement they may assist their fellow Levites by performing guard duty at the Tabernacle, but they may not officiate in the service. This is how you will assign duties to the Levites."', 'NLT'),
(4, 9, 1, 'The LORD gave these instructions to Moses in early spring, during the second year after Israel''s departure from Egypt, while he and the rest of the Israelites were in the wilderness of Sinai:', 'NLT'),
(4, 9, 2, '"Tell the Israelites to celebrate the Passover at the proper time,', 'NLT'),
(4, 9, 3, 'at twilight on the appointed day in early spring. Be sure to follow all my laws and regulations concerning this celebration."', 'NLT'),
(4, 9, 4, 'So Moses told the people to celebrate the Passover', 'NLT'),
(4, 9, 5, 'in the wilderness of Sinai as twilight fell on the appointed day. And they celebrated the festival there, just as the LORD had commanded Moses.', 'NLT'),
(4, 9, 6, 'But some of the men had been ceremonially defiled by touching a dead person, so they could not offer their Passover lambs that day. So they came to Moses and Aaron that day', 'NLT'),
(4, 9, 7, 'and said, "We have become ceremonially unclean by touching a dead person. But why should we be excluded from presenting the LORD''s offering at the proper time with the rest of the Israelites?"', 'NLT'),
(4, 9, 8, 'Moses answered, "Wait here until I have received instructions for you from the LORD."', 'NLT'),
(4, 9, 9, 'This was the LORD''s reply:', 'NLT'),
(4, 9, 10, '"Say to the Israelites: `If any of the people now or in future generations are ceremonially unclean at Passover time because of touching a dead body, or if they are on a journey and cannot be present at the ceremony, they may still celebrate the LORD''s Passover.', 'NLT'),
(4, 9, 11, 'They must offer the Passover sacrifice one month later, at twilight on the appointed day. They must eat the lamb at that time with bitter herbs and bread made without yeast.', 'NLT'),
(4, 9, 12, 'They must not leave any of the lamb until the next morning, and they must not break any of its bones. They must follow all the normal regulations concerning the Passover.', 'NLT'),
(4, 9, 13, '" `But those who are ceremonially clean and not away on a trip, yet still refuse to celebrate the Passover at the regular time, will be cut off from the community of Israel for failing to present the LORD''s offering at the proper time. They will suffer the consequences of their guilt.', 'NLT'),
(4, 9, 14, 'And if foreigners living among you want to celebrate the Passover to the LORD, they must follow these same laws and regulations. The same laws apply both to you and to the foreigners living among you.''"', 'NLT'),
(4, 9, 15, 'The Tabernacle was set up, and on that day the cloud covered it. Then from evening until morning the cloud over the Tabernacle appeared to be a pillar of fire.', 'NLT'),
(4, 9, 16, 'This was the regular pattern--at night the cloud changed to the appearance of fire.', 'NLT'),
(4, 9, 17, 'When the cloud lifted from over the sacred tent, the people of Israel followed it. And wherever the cloud settled, the people of Israel camped.', 'NLT'),
(4, 9, 18, 'In this way, they traveled at the LORD''s command and stopped wherever he told them to. Then they remained where they were as long as the cloud stayed over the Tabernacle.', 'NLT'),
(4, 9, 19, 'If the cloud remained over the Tabernacle for a long time, the Israelites stayed for a long time, just as the LORD commanded.', 'NLT'),
(4, 9, 20, 'Sometimes the cloud would stay over the Tabernacle for only a few days, so the people would stay for only a few days. Then at the LORD''s command they would break camp.', 'NLT'),
(4, 9, 21, 'Sometimes the cloud stayed only overnight and moved on the next morning. But day or night, when the cloud lifted, the people broke camp and followed.', 'NLT'),
(4, 9, 22, 'Whether the cloud stayed above the Tabernacle for two days, a month, or a year, the people of Israel stayed in camp and did not move on. But as soon as it lifted, they broke camp and moved on.', 'NLT'),
(4, 9, 23, 'So they camped or traveled at the LORD''s command, and they did whatever the LORD told them through Moses.', 'NLT'),
(4, 10, 1, 'Now the LORD said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(4, 10, 2, '"Make two trumpets of beaten silver to be used for summoning the people to assemble and for signaling the breaking of camp.', 'NLT'),
(4, 10, 3, 'When both trumpets are blown, the people will know that they are to gather before you at the entrance of the Tabernacle.', 'NLT'),
(4, 10, 4, 'But if only one is blown, then only the leaders of the tribes of Israel will come to you.', 'NLT'),
(4, 10, 5, '"When you sound the signal to move on, the tribes on the east side of the Tabernacle will break camp and move forward.', 'NLT'),
(4, 10, 6, 'When you sound the signal a second time, the tribes on the south will follow. You must sound short blasts to signal moving on.', 'NLT'),
(4, 10, 7, 'But when you call the people to an assembly, blow the trumpets using a different signal.', 'NLT'),
(4, 10, 8, 'Only the priests, Aaron''s descendants, are allowed to blow the trumpets. This is a permanent law to be followed from generation to generation.', 'NLT'),
(4, 10, 9, '"When you arrive in your own land and go to war against your enemies, you must sound the alarm with these trumpets so the LORD your God will remember you and rescue you from your enemies.', 'NLT'),
(4, 10, 10, 'Blow the trumpets in times of gladness, too, sounding them at your annual festivals and at the beginning of each month to rejoice over your burnt offerings and peace offerings. The trumpets will remind the LORD your God of his covenant with you. I am the LORD your God."', 'NLT'),
(4, 10, 11, 'One day in midspring, during the second year after Israel''s departure from Egypt, the cloud lifted from the Tabernacle of the Covenant.', 'NLT'),
(4, 10, 12, 'So the Israelites set out from the wilderness of Sinai and traveled on in stages until the cloud stopped in the wilderness of Paran.', 'NLT'),
(4, 10, 13, 'When the time to move arrived, the LORD gave the order through Moses.', 'NLT'),
(4, 10, 14, 'The tribes that camped with Judah headed the march with their banner, under the leadership of Nahshon son of Amminadab.', 'NLT'),
(4, 10, 15, 'The tribe of Issachar was led by Nethanel son of Zuar.', 'NLT'),
(4, 10, 16, 'The tribe of Zebulun was led by Eliab son of Helon.', 'NLT'),
(4, 10, 17, 'Then the Tabernacle was taken down, and the Gershonite and Merarite divisions of the Levites were next in the line of march, carrying the Tabernacle with them.', 'NLT'),
(4, 10, 18, 'Then the tribes that camped with Reuben set out with their banner, under the leadership of Elizur son of Shedeur.', 'NLT'),
(4, 10, 19, 'The tribe of Simeon was led by Shelumiel son of Zurishaddai.', 'NLT'),
(4, 10, 20, 'The tribe of Gad was led by Eliasaph son of Deuel.', 'NLT'),
(4, 10, 21, 'Next came the Kohathite division of the Levites, carrying the sacred objects from the Tabernacle. When they arrived at the next camp, the Tabernacle would already be set up at its new location.', 'NLT'),
(4, 10, 22, 'Then the tribes that camped with Ephraim set out with their banner, under the leadership of Elishama son of Ammihud.', 'NLT'),
(4, 10, 23, 'The tribe of Manasseh was led by Gamaliel son of Pedahzur.', 'NLT'),
(4, 10, 24, 'The tribe of Benjamin was led by Abidan son of Gideoni.', 'NLT'),
(4, 10, 25, 'Last of all, the tribes that camped with Dan set out under their banner. They served as the rear guard for all the tribal camps. The tribe of Dan headed this group, under the leadership of Ahiezer son of Ammishaddai.', 'NLT'),
(4, 10, 26, 'The tribe of Asher was led by Pagiel son of Ocran.', 'NLT'),
(4, 10, 27, 'The tribe of Naphtali was led by Ahira son of Enan.', 'NLT'),
(4, 10, 28, 'This was the order in which the tribes marched, division by division.', 'NLT'),
(4, 10, 29, 'One day Moses said to his brother-in-law, Hobab son of Reuel the Midianite, "We are on our way to the Promised Land. Come with us and we will treat you well, for the LORD has given wonderful promises to Israel!"', 'NLT'),
(4, 10, 30, 'But Hobab replied, "No, I will not go. I must return to my own land and family."', 'NLT'),
(4, 10, 31, '"Please don''t leave us," Moses pleaded. "You know the places in the wilderness where we should camp.', 'NLT'),
(4, 10, 32, 'Come, be our guide and we will share with you all the good things that the LORD does for us."', 'NLT'),
(4, 10, 33, 'They marched for three days after leaving the mountain of the LORD, with the Ark of the LORD''s covenant moving ahead of them to show them where to stop and rest.', 'NLT'),
(4, 10, 34, 'As they moved on each day, the cloud of the LORD hovered over them.', 'NLT'),
(4, 10, 35, 'And whenever the Ark set out, Moses would cry, "Arise, O LORD, and let your enemies be scattered! Let them flee before you!"', 'NLT'),
(4, 10, 36, 'And when the Ark was set down, he would say, "Return, O LORD, to the countless thousands of Israel!"', 'NLT'),
(4, 11, 1, 'The people soon began to complain to the LORD about their hardships; and when the LORD heard them, his anger blazed against them. Fire from the LORD raged among them and destroyed the outskirts of the camp.', 'NLT'),
(4, 11, 2, 'The people screamed to Moses for help; and when he prayed to the LORD, the fire stopped.', 'NLT'),
(4, 11, 3, 'After that, the area was known as Taberah--"the place of burning"--because fire from the LORD had burned among them there.', 'NLT'),
(4, 11, 4, 'Then the foreign rabble who were traveling with the Israelites began to crave the good things of Egypt, and the people of Israel also began to complain. "Oh, for some meat!" they exclaimed.', 'NLT'),
(4, 11, 5, '"We remember all the fish we used to eat for free in Egypt. And we had all the cucumbers, melons, leeks, onions, and garlic that we wanted.', 'NLT'),
(4, 11, 6, 'But now our appetites are gone, and day after day we have nothing to eat but this manna!"', 'NLT'),
(4, 11, 7, 'The manna looked like small coriander seeds, pale yellow in color.', 'NLT'),
(4, 11, 8, 'The people gathered it from the ground and made flour by grinding it with hand mills or pounding it in mortars. Then they boiled it in a pot and made it into flat cakes. These cakes tasted like they had been cooked in olive oil.', 'NLT'),
(4, 11, 9, 'The manna came down on the camp with the dew during the night.', 'NLT'),
(4, 11, 10, 'Moses heard all the families standing in front of their tents weeping, and the LORD became extremely angry. Moses was also very aggravated.', 'NLT'),
(4, 11, 11, 'And Moses said to the LORD, "Why are you treating me, your servant, so miserably? What did I do to deserve the burden of a people like this?', 'NLT'),
(4, 11, 12, 'Are they my children? Am I their father? Is that why you have told me to carry them in my arms--like a nurse carries a baby--to the land you swore to give their ancestors?', 'NLT'),
(4, 11, 13, 'Where am I supposed to get meat for all these people? They keep complaining and saying, `Give us meat!''', 'NLT'),
(4, 11, 14, 'I can''t carry all these people by myself! The load is far too heavy!', 'NLT'),
(4, 11, 15, 'I''d rather you killed me than treat me like this. Please spare me this misery!"', 'NLT'),
(4, 11, 16, 'Then the LORD said to Moses, "Summon before me seventy of the leaders of Israel. Bring them to the Tabernacle to stand there with you.', 'NLT'),
(4, 11, 17, 'I will come down and talk to you there. I will take some of the Spirit that is upon you, and I will put the Spirit upon them also. They will bear the burden of the people along with you, so you will not have to carry it alone.', 'NLT'),
(4, 11, 18, '"And tell the people to purify themselves, for tomorrow they will have meat to eat. Tell them, `The LORD has heard your whining and complaints: "If only we had meat to eat! Surely we were better off in Egypt!" Now the LORD will give you meat, and you will have to eat it.', 'NLT'),
(4, 11, 19, 'And it won''t be for just a day or two, or for five or ten or even twenty.', 'NLT'),
(4, 11, 20, 'You will eat it for a whole month until you gag and are sick of it. For you have rejected the LORD, who is here among you, and you have complained to him, "Why did we ever leave Egypt?"''"', 'NLT'),
(4, 11, 21, 'But Moses said, "There are 600,000 foot soldiers here with me, and yet you promise them meat for a whole month!', 'NLT'),
(4, 11, 22, 'Even if we butchered all our flocks and herds, would that satisfy them? Even if we caught all the fish in the sea, would that be enough?"', 'NLT'),
(4, 11, 23, 'Then the LORD said to Moses, "Is there any limit to my power? Now you will see whether or not my word comes true!"', 'NLT'),
(4, 11, 24, 'So Moses went out and reported the LORD''s words to the people. Then he gathered the seventy leaders and stationed them around the Tabernacle.', 'NLT'),
(4, 11, 25, 'And the LORD came down in the cloud and spoke to Moses. He took some of the Spirit that was upon Moses and put it upon the seventy leaders. They prophesied as the Spirit rested upon them, but that was the only time this happened.', 'NLT'),
(4, 11, 26, 'Two men, Eldad and Medad, were still in the camp when the Spirit rested upon them. They were listed among the leaders but had not gone out to the Tabernacle, so they prophesied there in the camp.', 'NLT'),
(4, 11, 27, 'A young man ran and reported to Moses, "Eldad and Medad are prophesying in the camp!"', 'NLT'),
(4, 11, 28, 'Joshua son of Nun, who had been Moses'' personal assistant since his youth, protested, "Moses, my master, make them stop!"', 'NLT'),
(4, 11, 29, 'But Moses replied, "Are you jealous for my sake? I wish that all the LORD''s people were prophets, and that the LORD would put his Spirit upon them all!"', 'NLT'),
(4, 11, 30, 'Then Moses returned to the camp with the leaders of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(4, 11, 31, 'Now the LORD sent a wind that brought quail from the sea and let them fall into the camp and all around it! For many miles in every direction from the camp there were quail flying about three feet above the ground.', 'NLT'),
(4, 11, 32, 'So the people went out and caught quail all that day and throughout the night and all the next day, too. No one gathered less than fifty bushels! They spread the quail out all over the camp.', 'NLT'),
(4, 11, 33, 'But while they were still eating the meat, the anger of the LORD blazed against the people, and he caused a severe plague to break out among them.', 'NLT'),
(4, 11, 34, 'So that place was called Kibroth-hattaavah--"the graves of craving"--because they buried the people there who had craved meat from Egypt.', 'NLT'),
(4, 11, 35, 'From there the Israelites traveled to Hazeroth, where they stayed for some time.', 'NLT'),
(4, 12, 1, 'While they were at Hazeroth, Miriam and Aaron criticized Moses because he had married a Cushite woman.', 'NLT'),
(4, 12, 2, 'They said, "Has the LORD spoken only through Moses? Hasn''t he spoken through us, too?" But the LORD heard them.', 'NLT'),
(4, 12, 3, 'Now Moses was more humble than any other person on earth.', 'NLT'),
(4, 12, 4, 'So immediately the LORD called to Moses, Aaron, and Miriam and said, "Go out to the Tabernacle, all three of you!" And the three of them went out.', 'NLT'),
(4, 12, 5, 'Then the LORD descended in the pillar of cloud and stood at the entrance of the Tabernacle. "Aaron and Miriam!" he called, and they stepped forward.', 'NLT'),
(4, 12, 6, 'And the LORD said to them, "Now listen to me! Even with prophets, I the LORD communicate by visions and dreams.', 'NLT'),
(4, 12, 7, 'But that is not how I communicate with my servant Moses. He is entrusted with my entire house.', 'NLT'),
(4, 12, 8, 'I speak to him face to face, directly and not in riddles! He sees the LORD as he is. Should you not be afraid to criticize him?"', 'NLT'),
(4, 12, 9, 'The LORD was furious with them, and he departed.', 'NLT'),
(4, 12, 10, 'As the cloud moved from above the Tabernacle, Miriam suddenly became white as snow with leprosy. When Aaron saw what had happened,', 'NLT'),
(4, 12, 11, 'he cried out to Moses, "Oh, my lord! Please don''t punish us for this sin we have so foolishly committed.', 'NLT'),
(4, 12, 12, 'Don''t let her be like a stillborn baby, already decayed at birth."', 'NLT'),
(4, 12, 13, 'So Moses cried out to the LORD, "Heal her, O God, I beg you!"', 'NLT'),
(4, 12, 14, 'And the LORD said to Moses, "If her father had spit in her face, wouldn''t she have been defiled for seven days? Banish her from the camp for seven days, and after that she may return."', 'NLT'),
(4, 12, 15, 'So Miriam was excluded from the camp for seven days, and the people waited until she was brought back before they traveled again.', 'NLT'),
(4, 12, 16, 'Then they left Hazeroth and camped in the wilderness of Paran.', 'NLT'),
(4, 13, 1, 'The LORD now said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(4, 13, 2, '"Send men to explore the land of Canaan, the land I am giving to Israel. Send one leader from each of the twelve ancestral tribes."', 'NLT'),
(4, 13, 3, 'So Moses did as the LORD commanded him. He sent out twelve men, all tribal leaders of Israel, from their camp in the wilderness of Paran.', 'NLT'),
(4, 13, 4, 'These were the tribes and the names of the leaders: Reuben............. Shammua son of Zaccur', 'NLT'),
(4, 13, 5, 'Simeon................. Shaphat son of Hori', 'NLT'),
(4, 13, 6, 'Judah................ Caleb son of Jephunneh', 'NLT'),
(4, 13, 7, 'Issachar................... Igal son of Joseph', 'NLT'),
(4, 13, 8, 'Ephraim................. Hoshea son of Nun', 'NLT'),
(4, 13, 9, 'Benjamin................. Palti son of Raphu', 'NLT'),
(4, 13, 10, 'Zebulun................. Gaddiel son of Sodi', 'NLT'),
(4, 13, 11, 'Manasseh son of Joseph...... Gaddi son of Susi', 'NLT'),
(4, 13, 12, 'Dan................. Ammiel son of Gemalli', 'NLT'),
(4, 13, 13, 'Asher................. Sethur son of Michael', 'NLT'),
(4, 13, 14, 'Naphtali................ Nahbi son of Vophsi', 'NLT'),
(4, 13, 15, 'Gad..................... Geuel son of Maki', 'NLT'),
(4, 13, 16, 'These are the names of the men Moses sent to explore the land. By this time Moses had changed Hoshea''s name to Joshua.', 'NLT'),
(4, 13, 17, 'Moses gave the men these instructions as he sent them out to explore the land: "Go northward through the Negev into the hill country.', 'NLT'),
(4, 13, 18, 'See what the land is like and find out whether the people living there are strong or weak, few or many.', 'NLT'),
(4, 13, 19, 'What kind of land do they live in? Is it good or bad? Do their towns have walls or are they unprotected?', 'NLT'),
(4, 13, 20, 'How is the soil? Is it fertile or poor? Are there many trees? Enter the land boldly, and bring back samples of the crops you see." (It happened to be the season for harvesting the first ripe grapes.)', 'NLT'),
(4, 13, 21, 'So they went up and explored the land from the wilderness of Zin as far as Rehob, near Lebo-hamath.', 'NLT'),
(4, 13, 22, 'Going northward, they passed first through the Negev and arrived at Hebron, where Ahiman, Sheshai, and Talmai--all descendants of Anak--lived. (The ancient town of Hebron was founded seven years before the Egyptian city of Zoan.)', 'NLT'),
(4, 13, 23, 'When they came to what is now known as the valley of Eshcol, they cut down a cluster of grapes so large that it took two of them to carry it on a pole between them! They also took samples of the pomegranates and figs.', 'NLT'),
(4, 13, 24, 'At that time the Israelites renamed the valley Eshcol--"cluster"--because of the cluster of grapes they had cut there.', 'NLT'),
(4, 13, 25, 'After exploring the land for forty days, the men returned', 'NLT'),
(4, 13, 26, 'to Moses, Aaron, and the people of Israel at Kadesh in the wilderness of Paran. They reported to the whole community what they had seen and showed them the fruit they had taken from the land.', 'NLT'),
(4, 13, 27, 'This was their report to Moses: "We arrived in the land you sent us to see, and it is indeed a magnificent country--a land flowing with milk and honey. Here is some of its fruit as proof.', 'NLT'),
(4, 13, 28, 'But the people living there are powerful, and their cities and towns are fortified and very large. We also saw the descendants of Anak who are living there!', 'NLT'),
(4, 13, 29, 'The Amalekites live in the Negev, and the Hittites, Jebusites, and Amorites live in the hill country. The Canaanites live along the coast of the Mediterranean Sea and along the Jordan Valley."', 'NLT'),
(4, 13, 30, 'But Caleb tried to encourage the people as they stood before Moses. "Let''s go at once to take the land," he said. "We can certainly conquer it!"', 'NLT'),
(4, 13, 31, 'But the other men who had explored the land with him answered, "We can''t go up against them! They are stronger than we are!"', 'NLT'),
(4, 13, 32, 'So they spread discouraging reports about the land among the Israelites: "The land we explored will swallow up any who go to live there. All the people we saw were huge.', 'NLT'),
(4, 13, 33, 'We even saw giants there, the descendants of Anak. We felt like grasshoppers next to them, and that''s what we looked like to them!"', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 1, 'Then all the people began weeping aloud, and they cried all night.', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 2, 'Their voices rose in a great chorus of complaint against Moses and Aaron. "We wish we had died in Egypt, or even here in the wilderness!" they wailed.', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 3, '"Why is the LORD taking us to this country only to have us die in battle? Our wives and little ones will be carried off as slaves! Let''s get out of here and return to Egypt!"', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 4, 'Then they plotted among themselves, "Let''s choose a leader and go back to Egypt!"', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 5, 'Then Moses and Aaron fell face down on the ground before the people of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 6, 'Two of the men who had explored the land, Joshua son of Nun and Caleb son of Jephunneh, tore their clothing.', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 7, 'They said to the community of Israel, "The land we explored is a wonderful land!', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 8, 'And if the LORD is pleased with us, he will bring us safely into that land and give it to us. It is a rich land flowing with milk and honey, and he will give it to us!', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 9, 'Do not rebel against the LORD, and don''t be afraid of the people of the land. They are only helpless prey to us! They have no protection, but the LORD is with us! Don''t be afraid of them!"', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 10, 'But the whole community began to talk about stoning Joshua and Caleb. Then the glorious presence of the LORD appeared to all the Israelites from above the Tabernacle.', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 11, 'And the LORD said to Moses, "How long will these people reject me? Will they never believe me, even after all the miraculous signs I have done among them?', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 12, 'I will disown them and destroy them with a plague. Then I will make you into a nation far greater and mightier than they are!"', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 13, '"But what will the Egyptians think when they hear about it?" Moses pleaded with the LORD. "They know full well the power you displayed in rescuing these people from Egypt.', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 14, 'They will tell this to the inhabitants of this land, who are well aware that you are with this people. They know, LORD, that you have appeared in full view of your people in the pillar of cloud that hovers over them. They know that you go before them in the pillar of cloud by day and the pillar of fire by night.', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 15, 'Now if you slaughter all these people, the nations that have heard of your fame will say,', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 16, '`The LORD was not able to bring them into the land he swore to give them, so he killed them in the wilderness.''', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 17, '"Please, Lord, prove that your power is as great as you have claimed it to be. For you said,', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 18, '`The LORD is slow to anger and rich in unfailing love, forgiving every kind of sin and rebellion. Even so he does not leave sin unpunished, but he punishes the children for the sins of their parents to the third and fourth generations.''', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 19, 'Please pardon the sins of this people because of your magnificent, unfailing love, just as you have forgiven them ever since they left Egypt."', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 20, 'Then the LORD said, "I will pardon them as you have requested.', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 21, 'But as surely as I live, and as surely as the earth is filled with the LORD''s glory,', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 22, 'not one of these people will ever enter that land. They have seen my glorious presence and the miraculous signs I performed both in Egypt and in the wilderness, but again and again they tested me by refusing to listen.', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 23, 'They will never even see the land I swore to give their ancestors. None of those who have treated me with contempt will enter it.', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 24, 'But my servant Caleb is different from the others. He has remained loyal to me, and I will bring him into the land he explored. His descendants will receive their full share of that land.', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 25, 'Now turn around and don''t go on toward the land where the Amalekites and Canaanites live. Tomorrow you must set out for the wilderness in the direction of the Red Sea. "', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 26, 'Then the LORD said to Moses and Aaron,', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 27, '"How long will this wicked nation complain about me? I have heard everything the Israelites have been saying.', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 28, 'Now tell them this: `As surely as I live, I will do to you the very things I heard you say. I, the LORD, have spoken!', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 29, 'You will all die here in this wilderness! Because you complained against me, none of you who are twenty years old or older and were counted in the census', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 30, 'will enter the land I swore to give you. The only exceptions will be Caleb son of Jephunneh and Joshua son of Nun.', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 31, '" `You said your children would be taken captive. Well, I will bring them safely into the land, and they will enjoy what you have despised.', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 32, 'But as for you, your dead bodies will fall in this wilderness.', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 33, 'And your children will be like shepherds, wandering in the wilderness forty years. In this way, they will pay for your faithlessness, until the last of you lies dead in the wilderness.', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 34, '" `Because the men who explored the land were there for forty days, you must wander in the wilderness for forty years--a year for each day, suffering the consequences of your sins. You will discover what it is like to have me for an enemy.''', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 35, 'I, the LORD, have spoken! I will do these things to every member of the community who has conspired against me. They will all die here in this wilderness!"', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 36, 'Then the ten scouts who had incited the rebellion against the LORD by spreading discouraging reports about the land', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 37, 'were struck dead with a plague before the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 38, 'Of the twelve who had explored the land, only Joshua and Caleb remained alive.', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 39, 'When Moses reported the LORD''s words to the Israelites, there was much sorrow among the people.', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 40, 'So they got up early the next morning and set out for the hill country of Canaan. "Let''s go," they said. "We realize that we have sinned, but now we are ready to enter the land the LORD has promised us."', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 41, 'But Moses said, "Why are you now disobeying the LORD''s orders to return to the wilderness? It won''t work.', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 42, 'Do not go into the land now. You will only be crushed by your enemies because the LORD is not with you.', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 43, 'When you face the Amalekites and Canaanites in battle, you will be slaughtered. The LORD will abandon you because you have abandoned the LORD."', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 44, 'But the people pushed ahead toward the hill country of Canaan, despite the fact that neither Moses nor the Ark of the LORD''s covenant left the camp.', 'NLT'),
(4, 14, 45, 'Then the Amalekites and the Canaanites who lived in those hills came down and attacked them and chased them as far as Hormah.', 'NLT'),
(4, 15, 1, 'The LORD told Moses to give these instructions to the people of Israel:', 'NLT'),
(4, 15, 2, '"When you finally settle in the land I am going to give you,', 'NLT'),
(4, 15, 3, 'and you want to please the LORD with a burnt offering or any other offering given by fire, the sacrifice must be an animal from your flocks of sheep and goats or from your herds of cattle. When it is an ordinary burnt offering, a sacrifice to fulfill a vow, a freewill offering, or a special sacrifice at any of the annual festivals,', 'NLT'),
(4, 15, 4, 'whoever brings it must also give to the LORD a grain offering of two quarts of choice flour mixed with one quart of olive oil.', 'NLT'),
(4, 15, 5, 'For each lamb offered as a whole burnt offering, you must also present one quart of wine for a drink offering.', 'NLT'),
(4, 15, 6, '"If the sacrifice is a ram, give three quarts of choice flour mixed with two and a half pints of olive oil,', 'NLT'),
(4, 15, 7, 'and give two and a half pints of wine for a drink offering. This sacrifice will be very pleasing to the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(4, 15, 8, '"When you present a young bull as a burnt offering or a sacrifice in fulfillment of a special vow or as a peace offering to the LORD,', 'NLT'),
(4, 15, 9, 'then the grain offering accompanying it must include five quarts of choice flour mixed with two quarts of olive oil,', 'NLT'),
(4, 15, 10, 'plus two quarts of wine for the drink offering. This will be an offering made by fire, very pleasing to the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(4, 15, 11, '"These are the instructions for what is to accompany each sacrificial bull, ram, lamb, or young goat.', 'NLT'),
(4, 15, 12, 'Each of you must do this with each offering you present.', 'NLT'),
(4, 15, 13, 'If you native Israelites want to present an offering by fire that is pleasing to the LORD, you must follow all these instructions.', 'NLT'),
(4, 15, 14, 'And if any foreigners living among you want to present an offering by fire, pleasing to the LORD, they must follow the same procedures.', 'NLT'),
(4, 15, 15, 'Native Israelites and foreigners are the same before the LORD and are subject to the same laws. This is a permanent law for you.', 'NLT'),
(4, 15, 16, 'The same instructions and regulations will apply both to you and to the foreigners living among you."', 'NLT'),
(4, 15, 17, 'The LORD also said to Moses at this time,', 'NLT'),
(4, 15, 18, '"Give the people of Israel the following instructions: When you arrive in the land where I am taking you,', 'NLT'),
(4, 15, 19, 'you will eat from the crops that grow there. But you must set some aside as a gift to the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(4, 15, 20, 'Present a cake from the first of the flour you grind and set it aside as a gift, as you do with the first grain from the threshing floor.', 'NLT'),
(4, 15, 21, 'Throughout the generations to come, you are to present this offering to the LORD each year from the first of your ground flour.', 'NLT'),
(4, 15, 22, '"But suppose some of you unintentionally fail to carry out all these commands that the LORD has given you through Moses.', 'NLT'),
(4, 15, 23, 'And suppose some of your descendants in the future fail to do everything the LORD has commanded through Moses.', 'NLT'),
(4, 15, 24, 'If the mistake was done unintentionally, and the community was unaware of it, the whole community must present a young bull for a burnt offering. It will be pleasing to the LORD, and it must be offered along with the prescribed grain offering and drink offering and with one male goat for a sin offering.', 'NLT'),
(4, 15, 25, 'With it the priest will make atonement for the whole community of Israel, and they will be forgiven. For it was an unintentional sin, and they have corrected it with their offering given to the LORD by fire and by their sin offering.', 'NLT'),
(4, 15, 26, 'The whole community of Israel will be forgiven, including the foreigners living among you, for the entire population was involved in the sin.', 'NLT'),
(4, 15, 27, '"If the unintentional sin is committed by an individual, the guilty person must bring a one-year-old female goat for a sin offering.', 'NLT'),
(4, 15, 28, 'The priest will make atonement for the guilty person before the LORD, and that person will be forgiven.', 'NLT'),
(4, 15, 29, 'This same law applies both to native Israelites and the foreigners living among you.', 'NLT'),
(4, 15, 30, '"But those who brazenly violate the LORD''s will, whether native Israelites or foreigners, blaspheme the LORD, and they must be cut off from the community.', 'NLT'),
(4, 15, 31, 'Since they have treated the LORD''s word with contempt and deliberately disobeyed his commands, they must be completely cut off and suffer the consequences of their guilt."', 'NLT'),
(4, 15, 32, 'One day while the people of Israel were in the wilderness, they caught a man gathering wood on the Sabbath day.', 'NLT'),
(4, 15, 33, 'He was apprehended and taken before Moses, Aaron, and the rest of the community.', 'NLT'),
(4, 15, 34, 'They held him in custody because they did not know what to do with him.', 'NLT'),
(4, 15, 35, 'Then the LORD said to Moses, "The man must be put to death! The whole community must stone him outside the camp."', 'NLT'),
(4, 15, 36, 'So the whole community took the man outside the camp and stoned him to death, just as the LORD had commanded Moses.', 'NLT'),
(4, 15, 37, 'And the LORD said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(4, 15, 38, '"Say to the people of Israel: `Throughout the generations to come you must make tassels for the hems of your clothing and attach the tassels at each corner with a blue cord.', 'NLT'),
(4, 15, 39, 'The tassels will remind you of the commands of the LORD, and that you are to obey his commands instead of following your own desires and going your own ways, as you are prone to do.', 'NLT'),
(4, 15, 40, 'The tassels will help you remember that you must obey all my commands and be holy to your God.', 'NLT'),
(4, 15, 41, 'I am the LORD your God who brought you out of the land of Egypt that I might be your God. I am the LORD your God!''"', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 1, 'One day Korah son of Izhar, a descendant of Kohath son of Levi, conspired with Dathan and Abiram, the sons of Eliab, and On son of Peleth, from the tribe of Reuben.', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 2, 'They incited a rebellion against Moses, involving 250 other prominent leaders, all members of the assembly.', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 3, 'They went to Moses and Aaron and said, "You have gone too far! Everyone in Israel has been set apart by the LORD, and he is with all of us. What right do you have to act as though you are greater than anyone else among all these people of the LORD?"', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 4, 'When Moses heard what they were saying, he threw himself down with his face to the ground.', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 5, 'Then he said to Korah and his followers, "Tomorrow morning the LORD will show us who belongs to him and who is holy. The LORD will allow those who are chosen to enter his holy presence.', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 6, 'You, Korah, and all your followers must do this: Take incense burners,', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 7, 'and burn incense in them tomorrow before the LORD. Then we will see whom the LORD chooses as his holy one. You Levites are the ones who have gone too far!"', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 8, 'Then Moses spoke again to Korah: "Now listen, you Levites!', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 9, 'Does it seem a small thing to you that the God of Israel has chosen you from among all the people of Israel to be near him as you serve in the LORD''s Tabernacle and to stand before the people to minister to them?', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 10, 'He has given this special ministry only to you and your fellow Levites, but now you are demanding the priesthood as well!', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 11, 'The one you are really revolting against is the LORD! And who is Aaron that you are complaining about him?"', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 12, 'Then Moses summoned Dathan and Abiram, the sons of Eliab, but they replied, "We refuse to come!', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 13, 'Isn''t it enough that you brought us out of Egypt, a land flowing with milk and honey, to kill us here in this wilderness, and that you now treat us like your subjects?', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 14, 'What''s more, you haven''t brought us into the land flowing with milk and honey or given us an inheritance of fields and vineyards. Are you trying to fool us? We will not come."', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 15, 'Then Moses became very angry and said to the LORD, "Do not accept their offerings! I have not taken so much as a donkey from them, and I have never hurt a single one of them."', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 16, 'And Moses said to Korah, "Come here tomorrow and present yourself before the LORD with all your followers. Aaron will also be here.', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 17, 'Be sure that each of your 250 followers brings an incense burner with incense on it, so you can present them before the LORD. Aaron will also bring his incense burner."', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 18, 'So these men came with their incense burners, placed burning coals and incense on them, and stood at the entrance of the Tabernacle with Moses and Aaron.', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 19, 'Meanwhile, Korah had stirred up the entire community against Moses and Aaron, and they all assembled at the Tabernacle entrance. Then the glorious presence of the LORD appeared to the whole community,', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 20, 'and the LORD said to Moses and Aaron,', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 21, '"Get away from these people so that I may instantly destroy them!"', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 22, 'But Moses and Aaron fell face down on the ground. "O God, the God and source of all life," they pleaded. "Must you be angry with all the people when only one man sins?"', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 23, 'And the LORD said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 24, '"Then tell all the people to get away from the tents of Korah, Dathan, and Abiram."', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 25, 'So Moses got up and rushed over to the tents of Dathan and Abiram, followed closely by the Israelite leaders.', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 26, '"Quick!" he told the people. "Get away from the tents of these wicked men, and don''t touch anything that belongs to them. If you do, you will be destroyed for their sins."', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 27, 'So all the people stood back from the tents of Korah, Dathan, and Abiram. Then Dathan and Abiram came out and stood at the entrances of their tents with their wives and children and little ones.', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 28, 'And Moses said, "By this you will know that the LORD has sent me to do all these things that I have done--for I have not done them on my own.', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 29, 'If these men die a natural death, then the LORD has not sent me.', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 30, 'But if the LORD performs a miracle and the ground opens up and swallows them and all their belongings, and they go down alive into the grave, then you will know that these men have despised the LORD."', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 31, 'He had hardly finished speaking the words when the ground suddenly split open beneath them.', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 32, 'The earth opened up and swallowed the men, along with their households and the followers who were standing with them, and everything they owned.', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 33, 'So they went down alive into the grave, along with their belongings. The earth closed over them, and they all vanished.', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 34, 'All of the people of Israel fled as they heard their screams, fearing that the earth would swallow them, too.', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 35, 'Then fire blazed forth from the LORD and burned up the 250 men who were offering incense.', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 36, 'And the LORD said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 37, '"Tell Eleazar son of Aaron the priest to pull all the incense burners from the fire, for they are holy. Also tell him to scatter the burning incense', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 38, 'from the burners of these men who have sinned at the cost of their lives. He must then hammer the metal of the incense burners into a sheet as a covering for the altar, for these burners have become holy because they were used in the LORD''s presence. The altar covering will then serve as a warning to the people of Israel."', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 39, 'So Eleazar the priest collected the 250 bronze incense burners that had been used by the men who died in the fire, and they were hammered out into a sheet of metal to cover the altar.', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 40, 'This would warn the Israelites that no unauthorized man--no one who was not a descendant of Aaron--should ever enter the LORD''s presence to burn incense. If anyone did, the same thing would happen to him as happened to Korah and his followers. Thus, the LORD''s instructions to Moses were carried out.', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 41, 'But the very next morning the whole community began muttering again against Moses and Aaron, saying, "You two have killed the LORD''s people!"', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 42, 'As the people gathered to protest to Moses and Aaron, they turned toward the Tabernacle and saw that the cloud had covered it, and the glorious presence of the LORD appeared.', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 43, 'Moses and Aaron came and stood at the entrance of the Tabernacle,', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 44, 'and the LORD said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 45, '"Get away from these people so that I can instantly destroy them!" But Moses and Aaron fell face down on the ground.', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 46, 'And Moses said to Aaron, "Quick, take an incense burner and place burning coals on it from the altar. Lay incense on it and carry it quickly among the people to make atonement for them. The LORD''s anger is blazing among them--the plague has already begun."', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 47, 'Aaron did as Moses told him and ran out among the people. The plague indeed had already begun, but Aaron burned the incense and made atonement for them.', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 48, 'He stood between the living and the dead until the plague was stopped.', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 49, 'But 14,700 people died in that plague, in addition to those who had died in the incident involving Korah.', 'NLT'),
(4, 16, 50, 'Then because the plague had stopped, Aaron returned to Moses at the entrance of the Tabernacle.', 'NLT'),
(4, 17, 1, 'Then the LORD said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(4, 17, 2, '"Take twelve wooden staffs, one from each of Israel''s ancestral tribes, and inscribe each tribal leader''s name on his staff.', 'NLT'),
(4, 17, 3, 'Inscribe Aaron''s name on the staff of the tribe of Levi, for there must be one staff for the leader of each ancestral tribe.', 'NLT'),
(4, 17, 4, 'Put these staffs in the Tabernacle in front of the Ark of the Covenant, where I meet with you.', 'NLT'),
(4, 17, 5, 'Buds will sprout on the staff belonging to the man I choose. Then I will finally put an end to this murmuring and complaining against you."', 'NLT'),
(4, 17, 6, 'So Moses gave the instructions to the people of Israel, and each of the twelve tribal leaders, including Aaron, brought Moses a staff.', 'NLT'),
(4, 17, 7, 'Moses put the staffs in the LORD''s presence in the Tabernacle of the Covenant.', 'NLT'),
(4, 17, 8, 'When he went into the Tabernacle of the Covenant the next day, he found that Aaron''s staff, representing the tribe of Levi, had sprouted, blossomed, and produced almonds!', 'NLT'),
(4, 17, 9, 'When Moses brought all the staffs out from the LORD''s presence, he showed them to the people. Each man claimed his own staff.', 'NLT'),
(4, 17, 10, 'And the LORD said to Moses: "Place Aaron''s staff permanently before the Ark of the Covenant as a warning to rebels. This should put an end to their complaints against me and prevent any further deaths."', 'NLT'),
(4, 17, 11, 'So Moses did as the LORD commanded him.', 'NLT'),
(4, 17, 12, 'Then the people of Israel said to Moses, "We are as good as dead! We are ruined!', 'NLT'),
(4, 17, 13, 'Everyone who even comes close to the Tabernacle of the LORD dies. We are all doomed!"', 'NLT'),
(4, 18, 1, 'The LORD now said to Aaron: "You, your sons, and your relatives from the tribe of Levi will be held responsible for any offenses related to the sanctuary. But you and your sons alone will be held liable for violations connected with the priesthood.', 'NLT'),
(4, 18, 2, '"Bring your relatives of the tribe of Levi to assist you and your sons as you perform the sacred duties in front of the Tabernacle of the Covenant.', 'NLT'),
(4, 18, 3, 'But as the Levites go about their duties under your supervision, they must be careful not to touch any of the sacred objects or the altar. If they do, both you and they will die.', 'NLT'),
(4, 18, 4, 'The Levites must join with you to fulfill their responsibilities for the care and maintenance of the Tabernacle, but no one who is not a Levite may officiate with you.', 'NLT'),
(4, 18, 5, '"You yourselves must perform the sacred duties within the sanctuary and at the altar. If you follow these instructions, the LORD''s anger will never again blaze against the people of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(4, 18, 6, 'I myself have chosen your fellow Levites from among the Israelites to be your special assistants. They are dedicated to the LORD for service in the Tabernacle.', 'NLT'),
(4, 18, 7, 'But you and your sons, the priests, must personally handle all the sacred service associated with the altar and everything within the inner curtain. I am giving you the priesthood as your special gift of service. Any other person who comes too near the sanctuary will be put to death."', 'NLT'),
(4, 18, 8, 'The LORD gave these further instructions to Aaron: "I have put the priests in charge of all the holy gifts that are brought to me by the people of Israel. I have given these offerings to you and your sons as your regular share.', 'NLT'),
(4, 18, 9, 'You are allotted the portion of the most holy offerings that is kept from the fire. From all the most holy offerings--including the grain offerings, sin offerings, and guilt offerings--that portion belongs to you and your sons.', 'NLT'),
(4, 18, 10, 'You must eat it as a most holy offering. All the males may eat of it, and you must treat it as most holy.', 'NLT'),
(4, 18, 11, '"All the other offerings presented to me by the Israelites by lifting them up before the altar also belong to you as your regular share. Any member of your family who is ceremonially clean, male and female alike, may eat of these offerings.', 'NLT'),
(4, 18, 12, '"I also give you the harvest gifts brought by the people as offerings to the LORD--the best of the olive oil, wine, and grain.', 'NLT'),
(4, 18, 13, 'All the firstfruits of the land that the people present to the LORD belong to you. Any member of your family who is ceremonially clean may eat this food.', 'NLT'),
(4, 18, 14, '"Whatever is specially set apart for the LORD also belongs to you.', 'NLT'),
(4, 18, 15, '"The firstborn of every mother, whether human or animal, that is offered to the LORD will be yours. But you must always redeem your firstborn sons and the firstborn males of ritually unclean animals.', 'NLT'),
(4, 18, 16, 'Redeem them when they are one month old. The redemption price is five pieces of silver, each piece weighing the same as the standard sanctuary shekel.', 'NLT'),
(4, 18, 17, '"However, you may not redeem the firstborn of cattle, sheep, or goats. They are holy and have been set apart for the LORD. Sprinkle their blood on the altar, and burn their fat as an offering given by fire, very pleasing to the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(4, 18, 18, 'The meat of these animals will be yours, just like the breast and right thigh that are presented by lifting them up before the altar.', 'NLT'),
(4, 18, 19, 'Yes, I am giving you all these holy offerings that the people of Israel bring to the LORD. They are for you and your sons and daughters, to be eaten as your regular share. This is an unbreakable covenant between the LORD and you and your descendants."', 'NLT'),
(4, 18, 20, 'And the LORD said to Aaron, "You priests will receive no inheritance of land or share of property among the people of Israel. I am your inheritance and your share.', 'NLT'),
(4, 18, 21, 'As for the tribe of Levi, your relatives, I will pay them for their service in the Tabernacle with the tithes from the entire land of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(4, 18, 22, '"From now on, Israelites other than the priests and Levites are to stay away from the Tabernacle. If they come too near, they will be judged guilty and die.', 'NLT'),
(4, 18, 23, 'The Levites must serve at the Tabernacle, and they will be held responsible for any offenses against it. This is a permanent law among you. But the Levites will receive no inheritance of land among the Israelites,', 'NLT'),
(4, 18, 24, 'because I have given them the Israelites'' tithes, which have been set apart as offerings to the LORD. This will be the Levites'' share. That is why I said they would receive no inheritance of land among the Israelites."', 'NLT'),
(4, 18, 25, 'The LORD also told Moses,', 'NLT'),
(4, 18, 26, '"Say this to the Levites: `When you receive the tithes from the Israelites, give a tenth of the tithes you receive--a tithe of the tithe--to the LORD as a gift.', 'NLT'),
(4, 18, 27, 'The LORD will consider this to be your harvest offering, as though it were the first grain from your own threshing floor or wine from your own winepress.', 'NLT'),
(4, 18, 28, 'You must present one-tenth of the tithe received from the Israelites as a gift to the LORD. From this you must present the LORD''s portion to Aaron the priest.', 'NLT'),
(4, 18, 29, 'Be sure to set aside the best portions of the gifts given to you as your gifts to the LORD.''', 'NLT'),
(4, 18, 30, '"Also say to the Levites: `When you present the best part, it will be considered as though it came from your own threshing floor or winepress.', 'NLT'),
(4, 18, 31, 'You Levites and your families may eat this food anywhere you wish, for it is your compensation for serving in the Tabernacle.', 'NLT'),
(4, 18, 32, 'You will not be considered guilty for accepting the LORD''s tithes if you give the best portion to the priests. But be careful not to treat the holy gifts of the people of Israel as though they were common. If you do, you will die.''"', 'NLT'),
(4, 19, 1, 'The LORD said to Moses and Aaron,', 'NLT'),
(4, 19, 2, '"Here is another ritual law required by the LORD: Tell the people of Israel to bring you a red heifer that has no physical defects and has never been yoked to a plow.', 'NLT'),
(4, 19, 3, 'Give it to Eleazar the priest, and it will be taken outside the camp and slaughtered in his presence.', 'NLT'),
(4, 19, 4, 'Eleazar will take some of its blood on his finger and sprinkle it seven times toward the front of the Tabernacle.', 'NLT'),
(4, 19, 5, 'As Eleazar watches, the heifer must be burned--its hide, meat, blood, and dung.', 'NLT'),
(4, 19, 6, 'Eleazar the priest must then take cedarwood, a hyssop branch, and scarlet thread and throw them into the fire where the heifer is burning.', 'NLT'),
(4, 19, 7, '"Then the priest must wash his clothes and bathe himself in water. Afterward he may return to the camp, though he will remain ceremonially unclean until evening.', 'NLT'),
(4, 19, 8, 'The man who burns the animal must also wash his clothes and bathe in water, and he, too, will remain unclean until evening.', 'NLT'),
(4, 19, 9, 'Then someone who is ceremonially clean will gather up the ashes of the heifer and place them in a purified place outside the camp. They will be kept there for the people of Israel to use in the water for the purification ceremony. This ceremony is performed for the removal of sin.', 'NLT'),
(4, 19, 10, 'The man who gathers up the ashes of the heifer must also wash his clothes, and he will remain ceremonially unclean until evening. This is a permanent law for the people of Israel and any foreigners who live among them.', 'NLT'),
(4, 19, 11, '"All those who touch a dead human body will be ceremonially unclean for seven days.', 'NLT'),
(4, 19, 12, 'They must purify themselves on the third and seventh days with the water of purification; then they will be purified. But if they do not do this on the third and seventh days, they will continue to be unclean even after the seventh day.', 'NLT'),
(4, 19, 13, 'All those who touch a dead body and do not purify themselves in the proper way defile the LORD''s Tabernacle and will be cut off from the community of Israel. Since the water of purification was not sprinkled on them, their defilement continues.', 'NLT'),
(4, 19, 14, '"This is the ritual law that applies when someone dies in a tent: Those who enter that tent, and those who were inside when the death occurred, will be ceremonially unclean for seven days.', 'NLT'),
(4, 19, 15, 'Any container in the tent that was not covered with a lid is also defiled.', 'NLT'),
(4, 19, 16, 'And if someone outdoors touches the corpse of someone who was killed with a sword or who died a natural death, or if someone touches a human bone or a grave, that person will be unclean for seven days.', 'NLT'),
(4, 19, 17, '"To remove the defilement, put some of the ashes from the burnt purification offering in a jar and pour fresh water over them.', 'NLT'),
(4, 19, 18, 'Then someone who is ceremonially clean must take a hyssop branch and dip it into the water. That person must sprinkle the water on the tent, on all the furnishings in the tent, and on anyone who was in the tent, or anyone who has touched a human bone, or has touched a person who was killed or who died naturally, or has touched a grave.', 'NLT'),
(4, 19, 19, 'On the third and seventh days the ceremonially clean person must sprinkle the water on those who are unclean. Then on the seventh day the people being cleansed must wash their clothes and bathe themselves, and that evening they will be cleansed of their defilement.', 'NLT'),
(4, 19, 20, '"But those who become defiled and do not purify themselves will be cut off from the community, for they have defiled the sanctuary of the LORD. Since the water of purification has not been sprinkled on them, they remain defiled.', 'NLT'),
(4, 19, 21, 'This is a permanent law. Those who sprinkle the water of purification must afterward wash their clothes, and anyone who touches the water of purification will remain defiled until evening.', 'NLT'),
(4, 19, 22, 'Anything and anyone that a defiled person touches will be ceremonially defiled until evening."', 'NLT'),
(4, 20, 1, 'In early spring the people of Israel arrived in the wilderness of Zin and camped at Kadesh. While they were there, Miriam died and was buried.', 'NLT'),
(4, 20, 2, 'There was no water for the people to drink at that place, so they rebelled against Moses and Aaron.', 'NLT'),
(4, 20, 3, 'The people blamed Moses and said, "We wish we had died in the LORD''s presence with our brothers!', 'NLT'),
(4, 20, 4, 'Did you bring the LORD''s people into this wilderness to die, along with all our livestock?', 'NLT'),
(4, 20, 5, 'Why did you make us leave Egypt and bring us here to this terrible place? This land has no grain, figs, grapes, or pomegranates. And there is no water to drink!"', 'NLT'),
(4, 20, 6, 'Moses and Aaron turned away from the people and went to the entrance of the Tabernacle, where they fell face down on the ground. Then the glorious presence of the LORD appeared to them,', 'NLT'),
(4, 20, 7, 'and the LORD said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(4, 20, 8, '"You and Aaron must take the staff and assemble the entire community. As the people watch, command the rock over there to pour out its water. You will get enough water from the rock to satisfy all the people and their livestock."', 'NLT'),
(4, 20, 9, 'So Moses did as he was told. He took the staff from the place where it was kept before the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(4, 20, 10, 'Then he and Aaron summoned the people to come and gather at the rock. "Listen, you rebels!" he shouted. "Must we bring you water from this rock?"', 'NLT'),
(4, 20, 11, 'Then Moses raised his hand and struck the rock twice with the staff, and water gushed out. So all the people and their livestock drank their fill.', 'NLT'),
(4, 20, 12, 'But the LORD said to Moses and Aaron, "Because you did not trust me enough to demonstrate my holiness to the people of Israel, you will not lead them into the land I am giving them!"', 'NLT'),
(4, 20, 13, 'This place was known as the waters of Meribah, because it was where the people of Israel argued with the LORD, and where he demonstrated his holiness among them.', 'NLT'),
(4, 20, 14, 'While Moses was at Kadesh, he sent ambassadors to the king of Edom with this message: "This message is from your relatives, the people of Israel: You know all the hardships we have been through,', 'NLT'),
(4, 20, 15, 'and that our ancestors went down to Egypt. We lived there a long time and suffered as slaves to the Egyptians.', 'NLT'),
(4, 20, 16, 'But when we cried out to the LORD, he heard us and sent an angel who brought us out of Egypt. Now we are camped at Kadesh, a town on the border of your land.', 'NLT'),
(4, 20, 17, 'Please let us pass through your country. We will be careful not to go through your fields and vineyards. We won''t even drink water from your wells. We will stay on the king''s road and never leave it until we have crossed the opposite border."', 'NLT'),
(4, 20, 18, 'But the king of Edom said, "Stay out of my land or I will meet you with an army!"', 'NLT'),
(4, 20, 19, 'The Israelites answered, "We will stay on the main road. If any of our livestock drinks your water, we will pay for it. We only want to pass through your country and nothing else."', 'NLT'),
(4, 20, 20, 'But the king of Edom replied, "Stay out! You may not pass through our land." With that he mobilized his army and marched out to meet them with an imposing force.', 'NLT'),
(4, 20, 21, 'Because Edom refused to allow Israel to pass through their country, Israel was forced to turn around.', 'NLT'),
(4, 20, 22, 'The whole community of Israel left Kadesh as a group and arrived at Mount Hor.', 'NLT'),
(4, 20, 23, 'Then the LORD said to Moses and Aaron at Mount Hor on the border of the land of Edom,', 'NLT'),
(4, 20, 24, '"The time has come for Aaron to join his ancestors in death. He will not enter the land I am giving the people of Israel, because the two of you rebelled against my instructions concerning the waters of Meribah.', 'NLT'),
(4, 20, 25, 'Now take Aaron and his son Eleazar up Mount Hor.', 'NLT'),
(4, 20, 26, 'There you will remove Aaron''s priestly garments and put them on Eleazar, his son. Aaron will die there and join his ancestors."', 'NLT'),
(4, 20, 27, 'So Moses did as the LORD commanded. The three of them went up Mount Hor together as the whole community watched.', 'NLT'),
(4, 20, 28, 'At the summit, Moses removed the priestly garments from Aaron and put them on Eleazar, Aaron''s son. Then Aaron died there on top of the mountain, and Moses and Eleazar went back down.', 'NLT'),
(4, 20, 29, 'When the people realized that Aaron had died, all Israel mourned for him thirty days.', 'NLT'),
(4, 21, 1, 'The Canaanite king of Arad, who lived in the Negev, heard that the Israelites were approaching on the road to Atharim. So he attacked the Israelites and took some of them as prisoners.', 'NLT'),
(4, 21, 2, 'Then the people of Israel made this vow to the LORD: "If you will help us conquer these people, we will completely destroy all their towns."', 'NLT'),
(4, 21, 3, 'The LORD heard their request and gave them victory over the Canaanites. The Israelites completely destroyed them and their towns, and the place has been called Hormah ever since.', 'NLT'),
(4, 21, 4, 'Then the people of Israel set out from Mount Hor, taking the road to the Red Sea to go around the land of Edom. But the people grew impatient along the way,', 'NLT'),
(4, 21, 5, 'and they began to murmur against God and Moses. "Why have you brought us out of Egypt to die here in the wilderness?" they complained. "There is nothing to eat here and nothing to drink. And we hate this wretched manna!"', 'NLT'),
(4, 21, 6, 'So the LORD sent poisonous snakes among them, and many of them were bitten and died.', 'NLT'),
(4, 21, 7, 'Then the people came to Moses and cried out, "We have sinned by speaking against the LORD and against you. Pray that the LORD will take away the snakes." So Moses prayed for the people.', 'NLT'),
(4, 21, 8, 'Then the LORD told him, "Make a replica of a poisonous snake and attach it to the top of a pole. Those who are bitten will live if they simply look at it!"', 'NLT'),
(4, 21, 9, 'So Moses made a snake out of bronze and attached it to the top of a pole. Whenever those who were bitten looked at the bronze snake, they recovered!', 'NLT'),
(4, 21, 10, 'The Israelites traveled next to Oboth and camped there.', 'NLT'),
(4, 21, 11, 'Then they went on to Iye-abarim, in the wilderness on the eastern border of Moab.', 'NLT'),
(4, 21, 12, 'From there they traveled to the valley of Zered Brook and set up camp.', 'NLT'),
(4, 21, 13, 'Then they moved to the far side of the Arnon River, in the wilderness adjacent to the territory of the Amorites. The Arnon is the boundary line between the Moabites and the Amorites.', 'NLT'),
(4, 21, 14, 'For this reason The Book of the Wars of the LORD speaks of "the town of Waheb in the area of Suphah, and the ravines; and the Arnon River', 'NLT'),
(4, 21, 15, 'and its ravines, which extend as far as the settlement of Ar on the border of Moab."', 'NLT'),
(4, 21, 16, 'From there the Israelites traveled to Beer, which is the well where the LORD said to Moses, "Assemble the people, and I will give them water."', 'NLT'),
(4, 21, 17, 'There the Israelites sang this song: "Spring up, O well! Yes, sing about it!', 'NLT'),
(4, 21, 18, 'Sing of this well, which princes dug, which great leaders hollowed out with their scepters and staffs." Then the Israelites left the wilderness and proceeded on through Mattanah,', 'NLT'),
(4, 21, 19, 'Nahaliel, and Bamoth.', 'NLT'),
(4, 21, 20, 'Then they went to the valley in Moab where Pisgah Peak overlooks the wasteland.', 'NLT'),
(4, 21, 21, 'The Israelites now sent ambassadors to King Sihon of the Amorites with this message:', 'NLT'),
(4, 21, 22, '"Let us travel through your land. We will stay on the king''s road until we have crossed your territory. We will not trample your fields or touch your vineyards or drink your well water."', 'NLT'),
(4, 21, 23, 'But King Sihon refused to let them cross his land. Instead, he mobilized his entire army and attacked Israel in the wilderness, engaging them in battle at Jahaz.', 'NLT'),
(4, 21, 24, 'But the Israelites slaughtered them and occupied their land from the Arnon River to the Jabbok River. They went only as far as the Ammonite border because the boundary of the Ammonites was fortified.', 'NLT'),
(4, 21, 25, 'So Israel captured all the towns of the Amorites and settled in them, including the city of Heshbon and its surrounding villages.', 'NLT'),
(4, 21, 26, 'Heshbon had been the capital of King Sihon of the Amorites. He had conquered a former Moabite king and seized all his land as far as the Arnon River.', 'NLT'),
(4, 21, 27, 'For this reason the ancient poets wrote this about him: "Come to Heshbon, city of Sihon! May it be restored and rebuilt.', 'NLT'),
(4, 21, 28, 'A fire flamed forth from Heshbon, a blaze from the city of Sihon. It burned the city of Ar in Moab; it destroyed the rulers of the Arnon heights.', 'NLT'),
(4, 21, 29, 'Your destruction is certain, O people of Moab! You are finished, O worshipers of Chemosh! Chemosh has left his sons as refugees, and his daughters as captives of Sihon, the Amorite king.', 'NLT'),
(4, 21, 30, 'We have utterly destroyed them, all the way from Heshbon to Dibon. We have completely wiped them out as far away as Nophah and Medeba. "', 'NLT'),
(4, 21, 31, 'So the people of Israel occupied the territory of the Amorites.', 'NLT'),
(4, 21, 32, 'After Moses sent men to explore the Jazer area, they captured all the towns in the region and drove out the Amorites who lived there.', 'NLT'),
(4, 21, 33, 'Then they turned and marched toward Bashan, but King Og of Bashan and all his people attacked them at Edrei.', 'NLT'),
(4, 21, 34, 'The LORD said to Moses, "Do not be afraid of him, for I have given you victory over Og and his entire army, giving you all his land. You will do the same to him as you did to King Sihon of the Amorites, who ruled in Heshbon."', 'NLT'),
(4, 21, 35, 'And Israel was victorious and killed King Og, his sons, and his subjects; not a single survivor remained. Then Israel occupied their land.', 'NLT'),
(4, 22, 1, 'Then the people of Israel traveled to the plains of Moab and camped east of the Jordan River, across from Jericho.', 'NLT'),
(4, 22, 2, 'Balak son of Zippor, the Moabite king, knew what the Israelites had done to the Amorites.', 'NLT'),
(4, 22, 3, 'And when they saw how many Israelites there were, he and his people were terrified.', 'NLT'),
(4, 22, 4, 'The king of Moab said to the leaders of Midian, "This mob will devour everything in sight, like an ox devours grass!" So Balak, king of Moab,', 'NLT'),
(4, 22, 5, 'sent messengers to Balaam son of Beor, who was living in his native land of Pethor near the Euphrates River. He sent this message to request that Balaam come to help him: "A vast horde of people has arrived from Egypt. They cover the face of the earth and are threatening me.', 'NLT'),
(4, 22, 6, 'Please come and curse them for me because they are so numerous. Then perhaps I will be able to conquer them and drive them from the land. I know that blessings fall on the people you bless. I also know that the people you curse are doomed."', 'NLT'),
(4, 22, 7, 'Balak''s messengers, officials of both Moab and Midian, set out and took money with them to pay Balaam to curse Israel. They went to Balaam and urgently explained to him what Balak wanted.', 'NLT'),
(4, 22, 8, '"Stay here overnight," Balaam said. "In the morning I will tell you whatever the LORD directs me to say." So the officials from Moab stayed there with Balaam.', 'NLT'),
(4, 22, 9, 'That night God came to Balaam and asked him, "Who are these men with you?"', 'NLT'),
(4, 22, 10, 'So Balaam said to God, "Balak son of Zippor, king of Moab, has sent me this message:', 'NLT'),
(4, 22, 11, '`A vast horde of people has come from Egypt and has spread out over the whole land. Come at once to curse them. Perhaps then I will be able to conquer them and drive them from the land.''"', 'NLT'),
(4, 22, 12, '"Do not go with them," God told Balaam. "You are not to curse these people, for I have blessed them!"', 'NLT'),
(4, 22, 13, 'The next morning Balaam got up and told Balak''s officials, "Go on home! The LORD will not let me go with you."', 'NLT'),
(4, 22, 14, 'So the Moabite officials returned to King Balak and reported, "Balaam refused to come with us."', 'NLT'),
(4, 22, 15, 'Then Balak tried again. This time he sent a larger number of even more distinguished officials than those he had sent the first time.', 'NLT'),
(4, 22, 16, 'They went to Balaam and gave him this message: "This is what Balak son of Zippor says: Please don''t let anything stop you from coming.', 'NLT'),
(4, 22, 17, 'I will pay you well and do anything you ask of me. Just come and curse these people for me!"', 'NLT'),
(4, 22, 18, 'But Balaam answered them, "Even if Balak were to give me a palace filled with silver and gold, I would be powerless to do anything against the will of the LORD my God.', 'NLT'),
(4, 22, 19, 'But stay here one more night to see if the LORD has anything else to say to me."', 'NLT'),
(4, 22, 20, 'That night God came to Balaam and told him, "Since these men have come for you, get up and go with them. But be sure to do only what I tell you to do."', 'NLT'),
(4, 22, 21, 'So the next morning Balaam saddled his donkey and started off with the Moabite officials.', 'NLT'),
(4, 22, 22, 'But God was furious that Balaam was going, so he sent the angel of the LORD to stand in the road to block his way. As Balaam and two servants were riding along,', 'NLT'),
(4, 22, 23, 'Balaam''s donkey suddenly saw the angel of the LORD standing in the road with a drawn sword in his hand. The donkey bolted off the road into a field, but Balaam beat it and turned it back onto the road.', 'NLT'),
(4, 22, 24, 'Then the angel of the LORD stood at a place where the road narrowed between two vineyard walls.', 'NLT'),
(4, 22, 25, 'When the donkey saw the angel of the LORD standing there, it tried to squeeze by and crushed Balaam''s foot against the wall. So Balaam beat the donkey again.', 'NLT'),
(4, 22, 26, 'Then the angel of the LORD moved farther down the road and stood in a place so narrow that the donkey could not get by at all.', 'NLT'),
(4, 22, 27, 'This time when the donkey saw the angel, it lay down under Balaam. In a fit of rage Balaam beat it again with his staff.', 'NLT'),
(4, 22, 28, 'Then the LORD caused the donkey to speak. "What have I done to you that deserves your beating me these three times?" it asked Balaam.', 'NLT'),
(4, 22, 29, '"Because you have made me look like a fool!" Balaam shouted. "If I had a sword with me, I would kill you!"', 'NLT'),
(4, 22, 30, '"But I am the same donkey you always ride on," the donkey answered. "Have I ever done anything like this before?No," he admitted.', 'NLT'),
(4, 22, 31, 'Then the LORD opened Balaam''s eyes, and he saw the angel of the LORD standing in the roadway with a drawn sword in his hand. Balaam fell face down on the ground before him.', 'NLT'),
(4, 22, 32, '"Why did you beat your donkey those three times?" the angel of the LORD demanded. "I have come to block your way because you are stubbornly resisting me.', 'NLT'),
(4, 22, 33, 'Three times the donkey saw me and shied away; otherwise, I would certainly have killed you by now and spared the donkey."', 'NLT'),
(4, 22, 34, 'Then Balaam confessed to the angel of the LORD, "I have sinned. I did not realize you were standing in the road to block my way. I will go back home if you are against my going."', 'NLT'),
(4, 22, 35, 'But the angel of the LORD told him, "Go with these men, but you may say only what I tell you to say." So Balaam went on with Balak''s officials.', 'NLT'),
(4, 22, 36, 'When King Balak heard that Balaam was on the way, he went out to meet him at a Moabite town on the Arnon River at the border of his land.', 'NLT'),
(4, 22, 37, '"Did I not send you an urgent invitation? Why didn''t you come right away?" Balak asked Balaam. "Didn''t you believe me when I said I would reward you richly?"', 'NLT'),
(4, 22, 38, 'Balaam replied, "I have come, but I have no power to say just anything. I will speak only the messages that God gives me."', 'NLT'),
(4, 22, 39, 'Then Balaam accompanied Balak to Kiriath-huzoth,', 'NLT'),
(4, 22, 40, 'where the king sacrificed cattle and sheep. He sent portions of the meat to Balaam and the officials who were with him.', 'NLT'),
(4, 22, 41, 'The next morning Balak took Balaam up to Bamoth-baal. From there he could see the people of Israel spread out below him.', 'NLT'),
(4, 23, 1, 'Balaam said to King Balak, "Build me seven altars here, and prepare seven young bulls and seven rams for a sacrifice."', 'NLT'),
(4, 23, 2, 'Balak followed his instructions, and the two of them sacrificed a young bull and a ram on each altar.', 'NLT'),
(4, 23, 3, 'Then Balaam said to Balak, "Stand here by your burnt offerings, and I will go to see if the LORD will respond to me. Then I will tell you whatever he reveals to me." So Balaam went alone to the top of a hill,', 'NLT'),
(4, 23, 4, 'and God met him there. Balaam said to him, "I have prepared seven altars and have sacrificed a young bull and a ram on each altar."', 'NLT'),
(4, 23, 5, 'Then the LORD gave Balaam a message for King Balak and said, "Go back to Balak and tell him what I told you."', 'NLT'),
(4, 23, 6, 'When Balaam returned, the king was standing beside his burnt offerings with all the officials of Moab.', 'NLT'),
(4, 23, 7, 'This was the prophecy Balaam delivered: "Balak summoned me to come from Aram; the king of Moab brought me from the eastern hills. `Come,'' he said, `curse Jacob for me! Come and announce Israel''s doom.''', 'NLT'),
(4, 23, 8, 'But how can I curse those whom God has not cursed? How can I condemn those whom the LORD has not condemned?', 'NLT'),
(4, 23, 9, 'I see them from the cliff tops; I watch them from the hills. I see a people who live by themselves, set apart from other nations.', 'NLT'),
(4, 23, 10, 'Who can count Jacob''s descendants, as numerous as dust? Who can count even a fourth of Israel''s people? Let me die like the righteous; let my life end like theirs."', 'NLT'),
(4, 23, 11, 'Then King Balak demanded of Balaam, "What have you done to me? I brought you to curse my enemies. Instead, you have blessed them!"', 'NLT'),
(4, 23, 12, 'But Balaam replied, "Can I say anything except what the LORD tells me?"', 'NLT'),
(4, 23, 13, 'Then King Balak told him, "Come with me to another place. There you will see only a portion of the nation of Israel. Curse at least that many!"', 'NLT'),
(4, 23, 14, 'So Balak took Balaam to the plateau of Zophim on Pisgah Peak. He built seven altars there and offered a young bull and a ram on each altar.', 'NLT'),
(4, 23, 15, 'Then Balaam said to the king, "Stand here by your burnt offering while I go to meet the LORD."', 'NLT'),
(4, 23, 16, 'So the LORD met Balaam and gave him a message. Then he said, "Go back to Balak and give him this message."', 'NLT'),
(4, 23, 17, 'So Balaam returned to the place where the king and the officials of Moab were standing beside Balak''s burnt offerings. "What did the LORD say?" Balak asked eagerly.', 'NLT'),
(4, 23, 18, 'This was the prophecy Balaam delivered: "Rise up, Balak, and listen! Hear me, son of Zippor.', 'NLT'),
(4, 23, 19, 'God is not a man, that he should lie. He is not a human, that he should change his mind. Has he ever spoken and failed to act? Has he ever promised and not carried it through?', 'NLT'),
(4, 23, 20, 'I received a command to bless; he has blessed, and I cannot reverse it!', 'NLT'),
(4, 23, 21, 'No misfortune is in sight for Jacob; no trouble is in store for Israel. For the LORD their God is with them; he has been proclaimed their king.', 'NLT'),
(4, 23, 22, 'God has brought them out of Egypt; he is like a strong ox for them.', 'NLT'),
(4, 23, 23, 'No curse can touch Jacob; no sorcery has any power against Israel. For now it will be said of Jacob, `What wonders God has done for Israel!''', 'NLT'),
(4, 23, 24, 'These people rise up like a lioness; like a majestic lion they stand. They refuse to rest until they have feasted on prey, drinking the blood of the slaughtered!"', 'NLT'),
(4, 23, 25, 'Then Balak said to Balaam, "If you aren''t going to curse them, at least don''t bless them!"', 'NLT'),
(4, 23, 26, 'But Balaam replied, "Didn''t I tell you that I must do whatever the LORD tells me?"', 'NLT'),
(4, 23, 27, 'Then King Balak said to Balaam, "Come, I will take you to yet another place. Perhaps it will please God to let you curse them from there."', 'NLT'),
(4, 23, 28, 'So Balak took Balaam to the top of Mount Peor, overlooking the wasteland.', 'NLT'),
(4, 23, 29, 'Balaam again told Balak, "Build me seven altars and prepare me seven young bulls and seven rams for a sacrifice."', 'NLT'),
(4, 23, 30, 'So Balak did as Balaam ordered and offered a young bull and a ram on each altar.', 'NLT'),
(4, 24, 1, 'By now Balaam realized that the LORD intended to bless Israel, so he did not resort to divination as he often did. Instead, he turned and looked out toward the wilderness,', 'NLT'),
(4, 24, 2, 'where he saw the people of Israel camped, tribe by tribe. Then the Spirit of God came upon him,', 'NLT'),
(4, 24, 3, 'and this is the prophecy he delivered: "This is the prophecy of Balaam son of Beor, the prophecy of the man whose eyes see clearly,', 'NLT'),
(4, 24, 4, 'who hears the words of God, who sees a vision from the Almighty, who falls down with eyes wide open:', 'NLT'),
(4, 24, 5, 'How beautiful are your tents, O Jacob; how lovely are your homes, O Israel!', 'NLT'),
(4, 24, 6, 'They spread before me like groves of palms, like fruitful gardens by the riverside. They are like aloes planted by the LORD, like cedars beside the waters.', 'NLT'),
(4, 24, 7, 'Water will gush out in buckets; their offspring are supplied with all they need. Their king will be greater than Agag; their kingdom will be exalted.', 'NLT'),
(4, 24, 8, 'God brought them up from Egypt, drawing them along like a wild ox. He devours all the nations that oppose him, breaking their bones in pieces, shooting them with arrows.', 'NLT'),
(4, 24, 9, 'Like a lion, Israel crouches and lies down; like a lioness, who dares to arouse her? Blessed is everyone who blesses you, O Israel, and cursed is everyone who curses you."', 'NLT'),
(4, 24, 10, 'King Balak flew into a rage against Balaam. He angrily clapped his hands and shouted, "I called you to curse my enemies! Instead, you have blessed them three times.', 'NLT'),
(4, 24, 11, 'Now get out of here! Go back home! I had planned to reward you richly, but the LORD has kept you from your reward."', 'NLT'),
(4, 24, 12, 'Balaam told Balak, "Don''t you remember what I told your messengers? I said,', 'NLT'),
(4, 24, 13, '`Even if Balak were to give me a palace filled with silver and gold, I am powerless to do anything against the will of the LORD.'' I told you that I could say only what the LORD says!', 'NLT'),
(4, 24, 14, 'Now I am returning to my own people. But first let me tell you what the Israelites will do to your people in the future."', 'NLT'),
(4, 24, 15, 'This is the prophecy Balaam delivered: "This is the message of Balaam son of Beor, the prophecy of the man whose eyes see clearly,', 'NLT'),
(4, 24, 16, 'who hears the words of God, who has knowledge from the Most High, who sees a vision from the Almighty, who falls down with eyes wide open:', 'NLT'),
(4, 24, 17, 'I see him, but not in the present time. I perceive him, but far in the distant future. A star will rise from Jacob; a scepter will emerge from Israel. It will crush the foreheads of Moab''s people, cracking the skulls of the people of Sheth.', 'NLT'),
(4, 24, 18, 'Edom will be taken over, and Seir, its enemy, will be conquered, while Israel continues on in triumph.', 'NLT'),
(4, 24, 19, 'A ruler will rise in Jacob who will destroy the survivors of Ir."', 'NLT'),
(4, 24, 20, 'Then Balaam looked over at the people of Amalek and delivered this prophecy: "Amalek was the greatest of nations, but its destiny is destruction!"', 'NLT'),
(4, 24, 21, 'Then he looked over at the Kenites and prophesied: "You are strongly situated; your nest is set in the rocks.', 'NLT'),
(4, 24, 22, 'But the Kenites will be destroyed when Assyria takes you captive."', 'NLT'),
(4, 24, 23, 'Balaam concluded his prophecies by saying: "Alas, who can survive when God does this?', 'NLT'),
(4, 24, 24, 'Ships will come from the coasts of Cyprus; they will oppress both Assyria and Eber, but they, too, will be utterly destroyed."', 'NLT'),
(4, 24, 25, 'Then Balaam and Balak returned to their homes.', 'NLT'),
(4, 25, 1, 'While the Israelites were camped at Acacia, some of the men defiled themselves by sleeping with the local Moabite women.', 'NLT'),
(4, 25, 2, 'These women invited them to attend sacrifices to their gods, and soon the Israelites were feasting with them and worshiping the gods of Moab.', 'NLT'),
(4, 25, 3, 'Before long Israel was joining in the worship of Baal of Peor, causing the LORD''s anger to blaze against his people.', 'NLT'),
(4, 25, 4, 'The LORD issued the following command to Moses: "Seize all the ringleaders and execute them before the LORD in broad daylight, so his fierce anger will turn away from the people of Israel."', 'NLT'),
(4, 25, 5, 'So Moses ordered Israel''s judges to execute everyone who had joined in worshiping Baal of Peor.', 'NLT'),
(4, 25, 6, 'Just then one of the Israelite men brought a Midianite woman into the camp, right before the eyes of Moses and all the people, as they were weeping at the entrance of the Tabernacle.', 'NLT'),
(4, 25, 7, 'When Phinehas son of Eleazar and grandson of Aaron the priest saw this, he jumped up and left the assembly. Then he took a spear', 'NLT'),
(4, 25, 8, 'and rushed after the man into his tent. Phinehas thrust the spear all the way through the man''s body and into the woman''s stomach. So the plague against the Israelites was stopped,', 'NLT'),
(4, 25, 9, 'but not before 24,000 people had died.', 'NLT'),
(4, 25, 10, 'Then the LORD said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(4, 25, 11, '"Phinehas son of Eleazar and grandson of Aaron the priest has turned my anger away from the Israelites by displaying passionate zeal among them on my behalf. So I have stopped destroying all Israel as I had intended to do in my anger.', 'NLT'),
(4, 25, 12, 'So tell him that I am making my special covenant of peace with him.', 'NLT'),
(4, 25, 13, 'In this covenant, he and his descendants will be priests for all time, because he was zealous for his God and made atonement for the people of Israel."', 'NLT'),
(4, 25, 14, 'The Israelite man killed with the Midianite woman was named Zimri son of Salu, the leader of a family from the tribe of Simeon.', 'NLT'),
(4, 25, 15, 'The woman''s name was Cozbi; she was the daughter of Zur, the leader of a Midianite clan.', 'NLT'),
(4, 25, 16, 'Then the LORD said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(4, 25, 17, '"Attack the Midianites and destroy them,', 'NLT'),
(4, 25, 18, 'because they assaulted you with deceit by tricking you into worshiping Baal of Peor, and because of Cozbi, the daughter of a Midianite leader, who was killed on the day of the plague at Peor."', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 1, 'After the plague had ended, the LORD said to Moses and to Eleazar son of Aaron, the priest,', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 2, '"Take a census of all the men of Israel who are twenty years old or older, to find out how many of each family are of military age."', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 3, 'At that time the entire nation of Israel was camped on the plains of Moab beside the Jordan River, across from Jericho. So Moses and Eleazar the priest issued these census instructions to the leaders of Israel:', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 4, '"Count all the men of Israel twenty years old and older, just as the LORD commanded Moses." This is the census record of all the descendants of Israel who came out of Egypt.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 5, 'These were the clans descended from Reuben, Jacob''s oldest son: The Hanochite clan, named after its ancestor Hanoch. The Palluite clan, named after its ancestor Pallu.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 6, 'The Hezronite clan, named after its ancestor Hezron. The Carmite clan, named after its ancestor Carmi.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 7, 'The men from all the clans of Reuben numbered 43,730.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 8, 'Pallu was the ancestor of Eliab,', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 9, 'and Eliab was the father of Nemuel, Dathan, and Abiram. This Dathan and Abiram are the same community leaders who conspired with Korah against Moses and Aaron, defying the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 10, 'But the earth opened up and swallowed them with Korah, and 250 of their followers were destroyed that day by fire from the LORD. This served as a warning to the entire nation of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 11, 'However, the sons of Korah did not die that day.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 12, 'These were the clans descended from the sons of Simeon: The Nemuelite clan, named after its ancestor Nemuel. The Jaminite clan, named after its ancestor Jamin. The Jakinite clan, named after its ancestor Jakin.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 13, 'The Zerahite clan, named after its ancestor Zerah. The Shaulite clan, named after its ancestor Shaul.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 14, 'The men from all the clans of Simeon numbered 22,200.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 15, 'These were the clans descended from the sons of Gad: The Zephonite clan, named after its ancestor Zephon. The Haggite clan, named after its ancestor Haggi. The Shunite clan, named after its ancestor Shuni.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 16, 'The Oznite clan, named after its ancestor Ozni. The Erite clan, named after its ancestor Eri.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 17, 'The Arodite clan, named after its ancestor Arodi. The Arelite clan, named after its ancestor Areli.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 18, 'The men from all the clans of Gad numbered 40,500.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 19, 'Judah had two sons, Er and Onan, who had died in the land of Canaan.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 20, 'But the following clans descended from Judah''s surviving sons: The Shelanite clan, named after its ancestor Shelah. The Perezite clan, named after its ancestor Perez. The Zerahite clan, named after its ancestor Zerah.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 21, 'These were the subclans descended from the Perezites: The Hezronites, named after their ancestor Hezron. The Hamulites, named after their ancestor Hamul.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 22, 'The men from all the clans of Judah numbered 76,500.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 23, 'These were the clans descended from the sons of Issachar: The Tolaite clan, named after its ancestor Tola. The Puite clan, named after its ancestor Puah.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 24, 'The Jashubite clan, named after its ancestor Jashub. The Shimronite clan, named after its ancestor Shimron.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 25, 'The men from all the clans of Issachar numbered 64,300.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 26, 'These were the clans descended from the sons of Zebulun: The Seredite clan, named after its ancestor Sered. The Elonite clan, named after its ancestor Elon. The Jahleelite clan, named after its ancestor Jahleel.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 27, 'The men from all the clans of Zebulun numbered 60,500.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 28, 'Two clans were descended from Joseph through Manasseh and Ephraim.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 29, 'These were the clans descended from Manasseh: The Makirite clan, named after its ancestor Makir. The Gileadite clan, named after its ancestor Gilead, Makir''s son.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 30, 'These were the subclans descended from the Gileadites: The Iezerites, named after their ancestor Iezer. The Helekites, named after their ancestor Helek.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 31, 'The Asrielites, named after their ancestor Asriel. The Shechemites, named after their ancestor Shechem.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 32, 'The Shemidaites, named after their ancestor Shemida. The Hepherites, named after their ancestor Hepher.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 33, 'Hepher''s son, Zelophehad, had no sons, but his daughters'' names were Mahlah, Noah, Hoglah, Milcah, and Tirzah.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 34, 'The men from all the clans of Manasseh numbered 52,700.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 35, 'These were the clans descended from the sons of Ephraim: The Shuthelahite clan, named after its ancestor Shuthelah. The Bekerite clan, named after its ancestor Beker. The Tahanite clan, named after its ancestor Tahan.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 36, 'This was the subclan descended from the Shuthelahites: The Eranites, named after their ancestor Eran.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 37, 'The men from all the clans of Ephraim numbered 32,500. These clans of Manasseh and Ephraim were all descendants of Joseph.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 38, 'These were the clans descended from the sons of Benjamin: The Belaite clan, named after its ancestor Bela. The Ashbelite clan, named after its ancestor Ashbel. The Ahiramite clan, named after its ancestor Ahiram.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 39, 'The Shuphamite clan, named after its ancestor Shupham. The Huphamite clan, named after its ancestor Hupham.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 40, 'These were the subclans descended from the Belaites: The Ardites, named after their ancestor Ard. The Naamites, named after their ancestor Naaman.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 41, 'The men from all the clans of Benjamin numbered 45,600.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 42, 'These were the clans descended from the sons of Dan: The Shuhamite clan, named after its ancestor Shuham.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 43, 'All the clans of Dan were Shuhamite clans, and the men from these clans numbered 64,400.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 44, 'These were the clans descended from the sons of Asher: The Imnite clan, named after its ancestor Imnah. The Ishvite clan, named after its ancestor Ishvi. The Beriite clan, named after its ancestor Beriah.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 45, 'These were the subclans descended from the Beriites: The Heberites, named after their ancestor Heber. The Malkielites, named after their ancestor Malkiel.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 46, 'Asher also had a daughter named Serah.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 47, 'The men from all the clans of Asher numbered 53,400.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 48, 'These were the clans descended from the sons of Naphtali: The Jahzeelite clan, named after its ancestor Jahzeel. The Gunite clan, named after its ancestor Guni.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 49, 'The Jezerite clan, named after its ancestor Jezer. The Shillemite clan, named after its ancestor Shillem.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 50, 'The men from all the clans of Naphtali numbered 45,400.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 51, 'So the total number of Israelite men counted in the census numbered 601,730.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 52, 'Then the LORD said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 53, '"Divide the land among the tribes in proportion to their populations, as indicated by the census.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 54, 'Give the larger tribes more land and the smaller tribes less land, each group''s inheritance reflecting the size of its population.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 55, 'Make sure you assign the land by lot, and define the inheritance of each ancestral tribe by means of the census listings.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 56, 'Each inheritance must be assigned by lot among the larger and smaller tribal groups."', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 57, 'This is the census record for the Levites who were counted according to their clans: The Gershonite clan, named after its ancestor Gershon. The Kohathite clan, named after its ancestor Kohath. The Merarite clan, named after its ancestor Merari.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 58, 'The Libnites, the Hebronites, the Mahlites, the Mushites, and the Korahites were all subclans of the Levites. Now Kohath was the ancestor of Amram,', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 59, 'and Amram''s wife was named Jochebed. She also was a descendant of Levi, born among the Levites in the land of Egypt. Amram and Jochebed became the parents of Aaron, Moses, and their sister, Miriam.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 60, 'To Aaron were born Nadab, Abihu, Eleazar, and Ithamar.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 61, 'But Nadab and Abihu died when they burned before the LORD a different kind of fire than he had commanded.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 62, 'The men from the Levite clans who were one month old or older numbered 23,000. But the Levites were not included in the total census figure of the people of Israel because they were not given an inheritance of land when it was divided among the Israelites.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 63, 'So these are the census figures of the people of Israel as prepared by Moses and Eleazar the priest on the plains of Moab beside the Jordan River, across from Jericho.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 64, 'Not one person that was counted in this census had been among those counted in the previous census taken by Moses and Aaron in the wilderness of Sinai.', 'NLT'),
(4, 26, 65, 'For the LORD had said of them, "They will all die in the wilderness." The only exceptions were Caleb son of Jephunneh and Joshua son of Nun.', 'NLT'),
(4, 27, 1, 'One day a petition was presented by the daughters of Zelophehad--Mahlah, Noah, Hoglah, Milcah, and Tirzah. Their father, Zelophehad, was the son of Hepher, son of Gilead, son of Makir, son of Manasseh, son of Joseph.', 'NLT'),
(4, 27, 2, 'These women went and stood before Moses, Eleazar the priest, the tribal leaders, and the entire community at the entrance of the Tabernacle.', 'NLT'),
(4, 27, 3, '"Our father died in the wilderness without leaving any sons," they said. "But he was not among Korah''s followers, who rebelled against the LORD. He died because of his own sin.', 'NLT'),
(4, 27, 4, 'Why should the name of our father disappear just because he had no sons? Give us property along with the rest of our relatives."', 'NLT'),
(4, 27, 5, 'So Moses brought their case before the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(4, 27, 6, 'And the LORD replied to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(4, 27, 7, '"The daughters of Zelophehad are right. You must give them an inheritance of land along with their father''s relatives. Assign them the property that would have been given to their father.', 'NLT'),
(4, 27, 8, 'Moreover announce this to the people of Israel: `If a man dies and has no sons, then give his inheritance to his daughters.', 'NLT'),
(4, 27, 9, 'And if he has no daughters, turn his inheritance over to his brothers.', 'NLT'),
(4, 27, 10, 'If he has no brothers, give his inheritance to his father''s brothers.', 'NLT'),
(4, 27, 11, 'But if his father has no brothers, pass on his inheritance to the nearest relative in his clan. The Israelites must observe this as a general legal requirement, just as the LORD commanded Moses.''"', 'NLT'),
(4, 27, 12, 'One day the LORD said to Moses, "Climb to the top of the mountains east of the river, and look out over the land I have given the people of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(4, 27, 13, 'After you have seen it, you will die as Aaron your brother did,', 'NLT'),
(4, 27, 14, 'for you both rebelled against my instructions in the wilderness of Zin. When the people of Israel rebelled, you failed to demonstrate my holiness to them at the waters." (These are the waters of Meribah at Kadesh in the wilderness of Zin.)', 'NLT'),
(4, 27, 15, 'Then Moses said to the LORD,', 'NLT'),
(4, 27, 16, '"O LORD, the God of the spirits of all living things, please appoint a new leader for the community.', 'NLT'),
(4, 27, 17, 'Give them someone who will lead them into battle, so the people of the LORD will not be like sheep without a shepherd."', 'NLT'),
(4, 27, 18, 'The LORD replied, "Take Joshua son of Nun, who has the Spirit in him, and lay your hands on him.', 'NLT'),
(4, 27, 19, 'Present him to Eleazar the priest before the whole community, and publicly commission him with the responsibility of leading the people.', 'NLT'),
(4, 27, 20, 'Transfer your authority to him so the whole community of Israel will obey him.', 'NLT'),
(4, 27, 21, 'When direction from the LORD is needed, Joshua will stand before Eleazar the priest, who will determine the LORD''s will by means of sacred lots. This is how Joshua and the rest of the community of Israel will discover what they should do."', 'NLT'),
(4, 27, 22, 'So Moses did as the LORD commanded and presented Joshua to Eleazar the priest and the whole community.', 'NLT'),
(4, 27, 23, 'Moses laid his hands on him and commissioned him to his responsibilities, just as the LORD had commanded through Moses.', 'NLT'),
(4, 28, 1, 'The LORD said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(4, 28, 2, '"Give these instructions to the people of Israel: The offerings you present to me by fire on the altar are my food, and they are very pleasing to me. See to it that they are brought at the appointed times and offered according to my instructions.', 'NLT'),
(4, 28, 3, '"Say to them: When you present your daily whole burnt offerings to the LORD, you must offer two one-year-old male lambs with no physical defects.', 'NLT'),
(4, 28, 4, 'One lamb will be sacrificed in the morning and the other in the evening.', 'NLT'),
(4, 28, 5, 'With each lamb you must offer a grain offering of two quarts of choice flour mixed with one quart of olive oil.', 'NLT'),
(4, 28, 6, 'This is the regular burnt offering ordained at Mount Sinai, an offering made by fire, very pleasing to the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(4, 28, 7, 'Along with it you must present the proper drink offering, consisting of one quart of fermented drink with each lamb, poured out in the Holy Place as an offering to the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(4, 28, 8, 'Offer the second lamb in the evening with the same grain offering and drink offering. It, too, is an offering made by fire, very pleasing to the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(4, 28, 9, '"On the Sabbath day, sacrifice two one-year-old male lambs with no physical defects. They must be accompanied by a grain offering of three quarts of choice flour mixed with olive oil, and a drink offering.', 'NLT'),
(4, 28, 10, 'This is the whole burnt offering to be presented each Sabbath day, in addition to the regular daily burnt offering and its accompanying drink offering.', 'NLT'),
(4, 28, 11, '"On the first day of each month, present an extra burnt offering to the LORD of two young bulls, one ram, and seven one-year-old male lambs, all with no physical defects.', 'NLT'),
(4, 28, 12, 'These will be accompanied by grain offerings of choice flour mixed with olive oil--five quarts with each bull, three quarts with the ram,', 'NLT'),
(4, 28, 13, 'and two quarts with each lamb. This burnt offering must be presented by fire, and it will be very pleasing to the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(4, 28, 14, 'You must also give a drink offering with each sacrifice: two quarts of wine with each bull, two and a half pints for the ram, and one quart for each lamb. Present this monthly burnt offering on the first day of each month throughout the year.', 'NLT'),
(4, 28, 15, '"Also, on the first day of each month you must offer one male goat for a sin offering to the LORD. This is in addition to the regular daily burnt offering and its accompanying drink offering.', 'NLT'),
(4, 28, 16, '"On the appointed day in early spring, you must celebrate the LORD''s Passover.', 'NLT'),
(4, 28, 17, 'On the following day a joyous, seven-day festival will begin, but no bread made with yeast may be eaten.', 'NLT'),
(4, 28, 18, 'On the first day of the festival you must call a sacred assembly of the people. None of your regular work may be done on that day.', 'NLT'),
(4, 28, 19, 'You must present as a burnt offering to the LORD two young bulls, one ram, and seven one-year-old male lambs, all with no physical defects.', 'NLT'),
(4, 28, 20, 'These will be accompanied by grain offerings of choice flour mixed with olive oil--five quarts with each bull, three quarts with the ram,', 'NLT'),
(4, 28, 21, 'and two quarts with each of the seven lambs.', 'NLT'),
(4, 28, 22, 'You must also offer a male goat as a sin offering, to make atonement for yourselves.', 'NLT'),
(4, 28, 23, 'You will present these offerings in addition to your regular morning sacrifices.', 'NLT'),
(4, 28, 24, 'On each of the seven days of the festival, this is how you will prepare the food offerings to be presented by fire, very pleasing to the LORD. These will be offered in addition to the regular whole burnt offerings and drink offerings.', 'NLT'),
(4, 28, 25, 'On the seventh day of the festival you must call another holy assembly of the people. None of your regular work may be done on that day.', 'NLT'),
(4, 28, 26, '"On the first day of the Festival of Harvest, when you present the first of your new grain to the LORD, you must call a holy assembly of the people. None of your regular work may be done on that day.', 'NLT'),
(4, 28, 27, 'A special whole burnt offering will be offered that day, very pleasing to the LORD. It will consist of two young bulls, one ram, and seven one-year-old male lambs.', 'NLT'),
(4, 28, 28, 'These will be accompanied by grain offerings of choice flour mixed with olive oil--five quarts with each bull, three quarts with the ram,', 'NLT'),
(4, 28, 29, 'and two quarts with each of the seven lambs.', 'NLT'),
(4, 28, 30, 'Also, offer one male goat to make atonement for yourselves.', 'NLT'),
(4, 28, 31, 'These special burnt offerings, along with their drink offerings, are in addition to the regular daily burnt offering and its accompanying grain offering. Be sure that all the animals you sacrifice have no physical defects.', 'NLT'),
(4, 29, 1, '"The Festival of Trumpets will be celebrated on the appointed day in early autumn each year. You must call a solemn assembly of all the people on that day, and no regular work may be done.', 'NLT'),
(4, 29, 2, 'On that day you must present a burnt offering, very pleasing to the LORD. It will consist of one young bull, one ram, and seven one-year-old male lambs, all with no physical defects.', 'NLT'),
(4, 29, 3, 'These must be accompanied by grain offerings of choice flour mixed with olive oil--five quarts with the bull, three quarts with the ram,', 'NLT'),
(4, 29, 4, 'and two quarts with each of the seven lambs.', 'NLT'),
(4, 29, 5, 'In addition, you must sacrifice a male goat as a sin offering, to make atonement for yourselves.', 'NLT'),
(4, 29, 6, 'These special sacrifices are in addition to your regular monthly and daily burnt offerings, and they must be given with their prescribed grain offerings and drink offerings. These offerings are given to the LORD by fire and are very pleasing to him.', 'NLT'),
(4, 29, 7, '"Ten days later, you must call another holy assembly of all the people. On that day, the Day of Atonement, the people must go without food, and no regular work may be done.', 'NLT'),
(4, 29, 8, 'You must present a burnt offering, very pleasing to the LORD. It will consist of one young bull, one ram, and seven one-year-old male lambs, all with no physical defects.', 'NLT'),
(4, 29, 9, 'These offerings must be accompanied by the prescribed grain offerings of choice flour mixed with olive oil--five quarts of choice flour with the bull, three quarts of choice flour with the ram,', 'NLT'),
(4, 29, 10, 'and two quarts of choice flour with each of the seven lambs.', 'NLT'),
(4, 29, 11, 'You must also sacrifice one male goat for a sin offering. This is in addition to the sin offering of atonement and the regular daily burnt offering with its grain offering, and their accompanying drink offerings.', 'NLT'),
(4, 29, 12, '"Five days later, you must call yet another holy assembly of all the people, and on that day no regular work may be done. It is the beginning of the Festival of Shelters, a seven-day festival to the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(4, 29, 13, 'That day you must present a special whole burnt offering by fire, very pleasing to the LORD. It will consist of thirteen young bulls, two rams, and fourteen one-year-old male lambs, all with no physical defects.', 'NLT'),
(4, 29, 14, 'Each of these offerings must be accompanied by a grain offering of choice flour mixed with olive oil--five quarts for each of the thirteen bulls, three quarts for each of the two rams,', 'NLT'),
(4, 29, 15, 'and two quarts for each of the fourteen lambs.', 'NLT'),
(4, 29, 16, 'You must also sacrifice a male goat as a sin offering, in addition to the regular daily burnt offering with its accompanying grain offering and drink offering.', 'NLT'),
(4, 29, 17, '"On the second day of this seven-day festival, sacrifice twelve young bulls, two rams, and fourteen one-year-old male lambs, all with no physical defects.', 'NLT'),
(4, 29, 18, 'Each of these offerings of bulls, rams, and lambs must be accompanied by the prescribed grain offering and drink offering.', 'NLT'),
(4, 29, 19, 'You must also sacrifice a male goat as a sin offering, in addition to the regular daily burnt offering with its accompanying grain offering and drink offering.', 'NLT'),
(4, 29, 20, '"On the third day of the festival, sacrifice eleven young bulls, two rams, and fourteen one-year-old male lambs, all with no physical defects.', 'NLT'),
(4, 29, 21, 'Each of these offerings of bulls, rams, and lambs must be accompanied by the prescribed grain offering and drink offering.', 'NLT'),
(4, 29, 22, 'You must also sacrifice a male goat as a sin offering, in addition to the regular daily burnt offering with its accompanying grain offering and drink offering.', 'NLT'),
(4, 29, 23, '"On the fourth day of the festival, sacrifice ten young bulls, two rams, and fourteen one-year-old male lambs, all with no physical defects.', 'NLT'),
(4, 29, 24, 'Each of these offerings of bulls, rams, and lambs must be accompanied by the prescribed grain offering and drink offering.', 'NLT'),
(4, 29, 25, 'You must also sacrifice a male goat as a sin offering, in addition to the regular daily burnt offering with its accompanying grain offering and drink offering.', 'NLT'),
(4, 29, 26, '"On the fifth day of the festival, sacrifice nine young bulls, two rams, and fourteen one-year-old male lambs, all with no physical defects.', 'NLT'),
(4, 29, 27, 'Each of these offerings of bulls, rams, and lambs must be accompanied by the prescribed grain offering and drink offering.', 'NLT'),
(4, 29, 28, 'You must also sacrifice a male goat as a sin offering, in addition to the regular daily burnt offering with its accompanying grain offering and drink offering.', 'NLT'),
(4, 29, 29, '"On the sixth day of the festival, sacrifice eight young bulls, two rams, and fourteen one-year-old male lambs, all with no physical defects.', 'NLT'),
(4, 29, 30, 'Each of these offerings of bulls, rams, and lambs must be accompanied by the prescribed grain offering and drink offering.', 'NLT'),
(4, 29, 31, 'You must also sacrifice a male goat as a sin offering, in addition to the regular daily burnt offering with its accompanying grain offering and drink offering.', 'NLT'),
(4, 29, 32, '"On the seventh day of the festival, sacrifice seven young bulls, two rams, and fourteen one-year-old male lambs, all with no physical defects.', 'NLT'),
(4, 29, 33, 'Each of these offerings of bulls, rams, and lambs must be accompanied by the prescribed grain offering and drink offering.', 'NLT'),
(4, 29, 34, 'You must also sacrifice one male goat as a sin offering, in addition to the regular daily burnt offering with its accompanying grain offering and drink offering.', 'NLT'),
(4, 29, 35, '"On the eighth day of the festival, call all the people to another holy assembly. You must do no regular work on that day.', 'NLT'),
(4, 29, 36, 'You must present a burnt offering, very pleasing to the LORD. It will consist of one young bull, one ram, and seven one-year-old male lambs, all with no physical defects.', 'NLT'),
(4, 29, 37, 'Each of these offerings must be accompanied by the prescribed grain offering and drink offering.', 'NLT'),
(4, 29, 38, 'You must also sacrifice one male goat as a sin offering, in addition to the regular daily burnt offering with its accompanying grain offering and drink offering.', 'NLT'),
(4, 29, 39, '"You must present these offerings to the LORD at your annual festivals. These are in addition to the sacrifices and offerings you present in connection with vows, or as freewill offerings, burnt offerings, grain offerings, drink offerings, or peace offerings."', 'NLT'),
(4, 29, 40, 'So Moses gave all of these instructions to the people of Israel, just as the LORD had commanded him.', 'NLT'),
(4, 30, 1, 'Now Moses summoned the leaders of the tribes of Israel and told them, "This is what the LORD has commanded:', 'NLT'),
(4, 30, 2, 'A man who makes a vow to the LORD or makes a pledge under oath must never break it. He must do exactly what he said he would do.', 'NLT'),
(4, 30, 3, '"If a young woman makes a vow to the LORD or a pledge under oath while she is still living at her father''s home,', 'NLT'),
(4, 30, 4, 'and her father hears of the vow or pledge but says nothing, then all her vows and pledges will stand.', 'NLT'),
(4, 30, 5, 'But if her father refuses to let her fulfill the vow or pledge on the day he hears of it, then all her vows and pledges will become invalid. The LORD will forgive her because her father would not let her fulfill them.', 'NLT'),
(4, 30, 6, '"Now suppose a young woman takes a vow or makes an impulsive pledge and later marries.', 'NLT'),
(4, 30, 7, 'If her husband learns of her vow or pledge and raises no objections on the day he hears of it, her vows and pledges will stand.', 'NLT'),
(4, 30, 8, 'But if her husband refuses to accept her vow or impulsive pledge on the day he hears of it, he nullifies her commitments, and the LORD will forgive her.', 'NLT'),
(4, 30, 9, 'If, however, a woman is a widow or is divorced, she must fulfill all her vows and pledges no matter what.', 'NLT'),
(4, 30, 10, '"Suppose a woman is married and living in her husband''s home when she makes a vow or pledge.', 'NLT'),
(4, 30, 11, 'If her husband hears of it and does nothing to stop her, her vow or pledge will stand.', 'NLT'),
(4, 30, 12, 'But if her husband refuses to accept it on the day he hears of it, her vow or pledge will be nullified, and the LORD will forgive her.', 'NLT'),
(4, 30, 13, 'So her husband may either confirm or nullify any vows or pledges she makes to deny herself.', 'NLT'),
(4, 30, 14, 'But if he says nothing on the day he hears of it, then he is agreeing to it.', 'NLT'),
(4, 30, 15, 'If he waits more than a day and then tries to nullify a vow or pledge, he will suffer the consequences of her guilt."', 'NLT'),
(4, 30, 16, 'These are the regulations the LORD gave Moses concerning relationships between a man and his wife, and between a father and a young daughter who still lives at home.', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 1, 'Then the LORD said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 2, '"Take vengeance on the Midianites for leading the Israelites into idolatry. After that, you will die and join your ancestors."', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 3, 'So Moses said to the people, "Choose some men to fight the LORD''s war of vengeance against Midian.', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 4, 'From each tribe of Israel, send one thousand men into battle."', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 5, 'So they chose one thousand men from each tribe of Israel, a total of twelve thousand men armed for battle.', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 6, 'Then Moses sent them out, a thousand men from each tribe, and Phinehas son of Eleazar the priest led them into battle. They carried along the holy objects of the sanctuary and the trumpets for sounding the charge.', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 7, 'They attacked Midian just as the LORD had commanded Moses, and they killed all the men.', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 8, 'All five of the Midianite kings--Evi, Rekem, Zur, Hur, and Reba--died in the battle. They also killed Balaam son of Beor with the sword.', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 9, 'Then the Israelite army captured the Midianite women and children and seized their cattle and flocks and all their wealth as plunder.', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 10, 'They burned all the towns and villages where the Midianites had lived.', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 11, 'After they had gathered the plunder and captives, both people and animals,', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 12, 'they brought them all to Moses and Eleazar the priest, and to the whole community of Israel, which was camped on the plains of Moab beside the Jordan River, across from Jericho.', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 13, 'Moses, Eleazar the priest, and all the leaders of the people went to meet them outside the camp.', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 14, 'But Moses was furious with all the military commanders who had returned from the battle.', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 15, '"Why have you let all the women live?" he demanded.', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 16, '"These are the very ones who followed Balaam''s advice and caused the people of Israel to rebel against the LORD at Mount Peor. They are the ones who caused the plague to strike the LORD''s people.', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 17, 'Now kill all the boys and all the women who have slept with a man.', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 18, 'Only the young girls who are virgins may live; you may keep them for yourselves.', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 19, 'And all of you who have killed anyone or touched a dead body must stay outside the camp for seven days. You must purify yourselves and your captives on the third and seventh days.', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 20, 'Also, purify all your clothing and everything made of leather, goat hair, or wood."', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 21, 'Then Eleazar the priest said to the men who were in the battle, "The LORD has given Moses this requirement of the law:', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 22, 'Anything made of gold, silver, bronze, iron, tin, or lead--', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 23, 'that is, metals that do not burn--must be passed through fire in order to be made ceremonially pure. These metal objects must then be further purified with the water of purification. But everything that burns must be purified by the water alone.', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 24, 'On the seventh day you must wash your clothes and be purified. Then you may return to the camp."', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 25, 'And the LORD said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 26, '"You and Eleazar the priest and the family leaders of each tribe are to make a list of all the plunder taken in the battle, including the people and animals.', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 27, 'Then divide the plunder into two parts, and give half to the men who fought the battle and half to the rest of the people.', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 28, 'But first give the LORD his share of the captives, cattle, donkeys, sheep, and goats that belong to the army. Set apart one out of every five hundred as the LORD''s share.', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 29, 'Give this share of their half to Eleazar the priest as an offering to the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 30, 'Also take one of every fifty of the captives, cattle, donkeys, sheep, and goats in the half that belongs to the people of Israel. Give this share to the Levites in charge of maintaining the LORD''s Tabernacle."', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 31, 'So Moses and Eleazar the priest did as the LORD commanded Moses.', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 32, 'The plunder remaining from the spoils that the fighting men had taken totaled 675,000 sheep,', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 33, '72,000 cattle,', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 34, '61,000 donkeys,', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 35, 'and 32,000 young girls.', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 36, 'So the half of the plunder given to the fighting men totaled 337,500 sheep,', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 37, 'of which 675 were the LORD''s share;', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 38, '36,000 cattle, of which 72 were the LORD''s share;', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 39, '30,500 donkeys, of which 61 were the LORD''s share;', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 40, '16,000 young girls, of whom 32 were the LORD''s share.', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 41, 'Moses gave all the LORD''s share to Eleazar the priest, just as the LORD had directed him.', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 42, 'The half of the plunder belonging to the people of Israel, which Moses had separated from the half belonging to the fighting men,', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 43, 'amounted to 337,500 sheep,', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 44, '36,000 cattle,', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 45, '30,500 donkeys,', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 46, 'and 16,000 young girls.', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 47, 'From the half-share given to the people, Moses took one of every fifty prisoners and animals and gave them to the Levites who maintained the LORD''s Tabernacle. All this was done just as the LORD had commanded Moses.', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 48, 'Then all the military commanders came to Moses', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 49, 'and said, "Sir, we have accounted for all the men who went out to battle under our command; not one of us is missing!', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 50, 'So we are presenting the items of gold we captured as an offering to the LORD from our share of the plunder--armbands, bracelets, rings, earrings, and necklaces. This will make atonement for our lives before the LORD."', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 51, 'So Moses and Eleazar the priest received the gold from all the military commanders, all kinds of jewelry and crafted objects.', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 52, 'In all, the gold that the commanders presented as a gift to the LORD weighed about 420 pounds.', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 53, 'All the fighting men had taken some of the plunder for themselves.', 'NLT'),
(4, 31, 54, 'So Moses and Eleazar the priest accepted the gifts from the military commanders and brought the gold to the Tabernacle as a reminder to the LORD that the people of Israel belong to him.', 'NLT'),
(4, 32, 1, 'Now the tribes of Reuben and Gad owned vast numbers of livestock. So when they saw that the lands of Jazer and Gilead were ideally suited for their flocks and herds,', 'NLT'),
(4, 32, 2, 'they came to Moses, Eleazar the priest, and the other leaders of the people. They said,', 'NLT'),
(4, 32, 3, '"Ataroth, Dibon, Jazer, Nimrah, Heshbon, Elealeh, Sebam, Nebo, and Beon--', 'NLT'),
(4, 32, 4, 'the LORD has conquered this whole area for the people of Israel. It is ideally suited for all our flocks and herds.', 'NLT'),
(4, 32, 5, 'If we have found favor with you, please let us have this land as our property instead of giving us land across the Jordan River."', 'NLT'),
(4, 32, 6, '"Do you mean you want to stay back here while your brothers go across and do all the fighting?" Moses asked the Reubenites and Gadites.', 'NLT'),
(4, 32, 7, '"Are you trying to discourage the rest of the people of Israel from going across to the land the LORD has given them?', 'NLT'),
(4, 32, 8, 'This is what your ancestors did when I sent them from Kadesh-barnea to explore the land.', 'NLT'),
(4, 32, 9, 'After they went up to the valley of Eshcol and scouted the land, they discouraged the people of Israel from entering the land the LORD was giving them.', 'NLT'),
(4, 32, 10, 'Then the LORD was furious with them, and he vowed,', 'NLT'),
(4, 32, 11, '`Of all those I rescued from Egypt, no one who is twenty years old or older will ever see the land I solemnly promised to Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob, for they have not obeyed me completely.', 'NLT'),
(4, 32, 12, 'The only exceptions are Caleb son of Jephunneh the Kenizzite and Joshua son of Nun, for they have wholeheartedly followed the LORD.''', 'NLT'),
(4, 32, 13, '"The LORD was furious with Israel and made them wander in the wilderness for forty years until the whole generation that sinned against him had died.', 'NLT'),
(4, 32, 14, 'But here you are, a brood of sinners, doing exactly the same thing! You are making the LORD even angrier with Israel.', 'NLT'),
(4, 32, 15, 'If you turn away from him like this and he abandons them again in the wilderness, you will be responsible for destroying this entire nation!"', 'NLT'),
(4, 32, 16, 'But they responded to Moses, "We simply want to build sheepfolds for our flocks and fortified cities for our wives and children.', 'NLT'),
(4, 32, 17, 'Then we will arm ourselves and lead our fellow Israelites into battle until we have brought them safely to their inheritance. Meanwhile, our families will stay in the fortified cities we build here, so they will be safe from any attacks by the local people.', 'NLT'),
(4, 32, 18, 'We will not return to our homes until all the people of Israel have received their inheritance of land.', 'NLT'),
(4, 32, 19, 'But we do not want any of the land on the other side of the Jordan. We would rather live here on the east side where we have received our inheritance."', 'NLT'),
(4, 32, 20, 'Then Moses said, "If you keep your word and arm yourselves for the LORD''s battles,', 'NLT'),
(4, 32, 21, 'and if your troops cross the Jordan until the LORD has driven out his enemies,', 'NLT'),
(4, 32, 22, 'then you may return when the land is finally subdued before the LORD. You will have discharged your duty to the LORD and to the rest of the people of Israel. And the land on the east side of the Jordan will be your inheritance from the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(4, 32, 23, 'But if you fail to keep your word, then you will have sinned against the LORD, and you may be sure that your sin will find you out.', 'NLT'),
(4, 32, 24, 'Go ahead and build towns for your families and sheepfolds for your flocks, but do everything you have said."', 'NLT'),
(4, 32, 25, 'Then the people of Gad and Reuben replied, "We are your servants and will follow your instructions exactly.', 'NLT'),
(4, 32, 26, 'Our children, wives, flocks, and cattle will stay here in the towns of Gilead.', 'NLT'),
(4, 32, 27, 'But, sir, all who are able to bear arms will cross over to fight for the LORD, just as you have said."', 'NLT'),
(4, 32, 28, 'So Moses gave orders to Eleazar, Joshua, and the tribal leaders of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(4, 32, 29, 'He said, "If all the men of Gad and Reuben who are able to fight the LORD''s battles cross the Jordan with you, then when the land is conquered, you must give them the land of Gilead as their property.', 'NLT'),
(4, 32, 30, 'But if they refuse to cross over and march ahead of you, then they must accept land with the rest of you in the land of Canaan."', 'NLT'),
(4, 32, 31, 'The tribes of Gad and Reuben said again, "Sir, we will do as the LORD has commanded!', 'NLT'),
(4, 32, 32, 'We will cross the Jordan into Canaan fully armed to fight for the LORD, but our inheritance of land will be here on this side of the Jordan."', 'NLT'),
(4, 32, 33, 'So Moses assigned to the tribes of Gad, Reuben, and half the tribe of Manasseh son of Joseph the territory of King Sihon of the Amorites and the land of King Og of Bashan--the whole land with its towns and surrounding lands.', 'NLT'),
(4, 32, 34, 'The people of Gad built the towns of Dibon, Ataroth, Aroer,', 'NLT'),
(4, 32, 35, 'Atroth-shophan, Jazer, Jogbehah,', 'NLT'),
(4, 32, 36, 'Beth-nimrah, and Beth-haran. These were all fortified cities with sheepfolds for their flocks.', 'NLT'),
(4, 32, 37, 'The people of Reuben built the towns of Heshbon, Elealeh, Kiriathaim,', 'NLT'),
(4, 32, 38, 'Nebo, Baal-meon, and Sibmah. They changed the names of some of the towns they conquered and rebuilt.', 'NLT'),
(4, 32, 39, 'Then the descendants of Makir of the tribe of Manasseh went to Gilead and conquered it, and they drove out the Amorites, who were living there.', 'NLT'),
(4, 32, 40, 'So Moses gave Gilead to the Makirites, descendants of Manasseh, and they lived there.', 'NLT'),
(4, 32, 41, 'The people of Jair, another clan of the tribe of Manasseh, captured many of the towns in Gilead and changed the name of that region to the Towns of Jair.', 'NLT'),
(4, 32, 42, 'Meanwhile, a man named Nobah captured the town of Kenath and its surrounding villages, and he renamed that area Nobah after himself.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 1, 'This is the itinerary the Israelites followed as they marched out of Egypt under the leadership of Moses and Aaron.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 2, 'At the LORD''s direction, Moses kept a written record of their progress. These are the stages of their march, identified by the different places they stopped along the way.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 3, 'They set out from the city of Rameses on the morning after the first Passover celebration in early spring. The people of Israel left defiantly, in full view of all the Egyptians.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 4, 'Meanwhile, the Egyptians were burying all their firstborn sons, whom the LORD had killed the night before. The LORD had defeated the gods of Egypt that night with great acts of judgment!', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 5, 'After leaving Rameses, the Israelites set up camp at Succoth.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 6, 'Then they left Succoth and camped at Etham on the edge of the wilderness.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 7, 'They left Etham and turned back toward Pi-hahiroth, opposite Baal-zephon, and camped near Migdol.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 8, 'They left Pi-hahiroth and crossed the Red Sea into the wilderness beyond. Then they traveled for three days into the Etham wilderness and camped at Marah.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 9, 'They left Marah and camped at Elim, where there are twelve springs of water and seventy palm trees.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 10, 'They left Elim and camped beside the Red Sea.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 11, 'They left the Red Sea and camped in the Sin Desert.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 12, 'They left the Sin Desert and camped at Dophkah.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 13, 'They left Dophkah and camped at Alush.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 14, 'They left Alush and camped at Rephidim, where there was no water for the people to drink.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 15, 'They left Rephidim and camped in the wilderness of Sinai.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 16, 'They left the wilderness of Sinai and camped at Kibroth-hattaavah.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 17, 'They left Kibroth-hattaavah and camped at Hazeroth.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 18, 'They left Hazeroth and camped at Rithmah.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 19, 'They left Rithmah and camped at Rimmon-perez.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 20, 'They left Rimmon-perez and camped at Libnah.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 21, 'They left Libnah and camped at Rissah.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 22, 'They left Rissah and camped at Kehelathah.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 23, 'They left Kehelathah and camped at Mount Shepher.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 24, 'They left Mount Shepher and camped at Haradah.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 25, 'They left Haradah and camped at Makheloth.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 26, 'They left Makheloth and camped at Tahath.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 27, 'They left Tahath and camped at Terah.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 28, 'They left Terah and camped at Mithcah.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 29, 'They left Mithcah and camped at Hashmonah.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 30, 'They left Hashmonah and camped at Moseroth.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 31, 'They left Moseroth and camped at Bene-jaakan.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 32, 'They left Bene-jaakan and camped at Hor-haggidgad.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 33, 'They left Hor-haggidgad and camped at Jotbathah.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 34, 'They left Jotbathah and camped at Abronah.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 35, 'They left Abronah and camped at Ezion-geber.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 36, 'They left Ezion-geber and camped at Kadesh in the wilderness of Zin.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 37, 'They left Kadesh and camped at Mount Hor, at the border of Edom.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 38, 'While they were at the foot of Mount Hor, Aaron the priest was directed by the LORD to go up the mountain, and there he died. This happened on a day in midsummer, during the fortieth year after Israel''s departure from Egypt.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 39, 'Aaron was 123 years old when he died there on Mount Hor.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 40, 'It was then that the Canaanite king of Arad, who lived in the Negev in the land of Canaan, heard that the people of Israel were approaching his land.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 41, 'Meanwhile, the Israelites left Mount Hor and camped at Zalmonah.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 42, 'Then they left Zalmonah and camped at Punon.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 43, 'They left Punon and camped at Oboth.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 44, 'They left Oboth and camped at Iye-abarim on the border of Moab.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 45, 'They left Iye-abarim and camped at Dibon-gad.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 46, 'They left Dibon-gad and camped at Almon-diblathaim.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 47, 'They left Almon-diblathaim and camped in the mountains east of the river, near Mount Nebo.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 48, 'They left the mountains east of the river and camped on the plains of Moab beside the Jordan River, across from Jericho.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 49, 'Along the Jordan River they camped from Beth-jeshimoth as far as Abel-shittim on the plains of Moab.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 50, 'While they were camped near the Jordan River on the plains of Moab opposite Jericho, the LORD said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 51, '"Speak to the Israelites and tell them: `When you cross the Jordan River into the land of Canaan,', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 52, 'you must drive out all the people living there. You must destroy all their carved and molten images and demolish all their pagan shrines.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 53, 'Take possession of the land and settle in it, because I have given it to you to occupy.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 54, 'You must distribute the land among the clans by sacred lot and in proportion to their size. A larger inheritance of land will be allotted to each of the larger clans, and a smaller inheritance will be allotted to each of the smaller clans. The decision of the sacred lot is final. In this way, the land will be divided among your ancestral tribes.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 55, 'But if you fail to drive out the people who live in the land, those who remain will be like splinters in your eyes and thorns in your sides. They will harass you in the land where you live.', 'NLT'),
(4, 33, 56, 'And I will do to you what I had planned to do to them.''"', 'NLT'),
(4, 34, 1, 'Then the LORD said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(4, 34, 2, '"Give these instructions to the Israelites: When you come into the land of Canaan, which I am giving you as your special possession, these will be the boundaries.', 'NLT'),
(4, 34, 3, 'The southern portion of your country will extend from the wilderness of Zin, along the edge of Edom. The southern boundary will begin on the east at the Dead Sea.', 'NLT'),
(4, 34, 4, 'It will then run south past Scorpion Pass in the direction of Zin. Its southernmost point will be Kadesh-barnea, from which it will go to Hazar-addar, and on to Azmon.', 'NLT'),
(4, 34, 5, 'From Azmon the boundary will turn toward the brook of Egypt and end at the Mediterranean Sea.', 'NLT'),
(4, 34, 6, '"Your western boundary will be the coastline of the Mediterranean Sea.', 'NLT'),
(4, 34, 7, '"Your northern boundary will begin at the Mediterranean Sea and run eastward to Mount Hor,', 'NLT'),
(4, 34, 8, 'then to Lebo-hamath, and on through Zedad', 'NLT'),
(4, 34, 9, 'and Ziphron to Hazar-enan. This will be your northern boundary.', 'NLT'),
(4, 34, 10, '"The eastern boundary will start at Hazar-enan and run south to Shepham,', 'NLT'),
(4, 34, 11, 'then down to Riblah on the east side of Ain. From there the boundary will run down along the eastern edge of the Sea of Galilee,', 'NLT'),
(4, 34, 12, 'and then along the Jordan River to the Dead Sea. These are the boundaries of your land."', 'NLT'),
(4, 34, 13, 'Then Moses told the Israelites, "This is the territory you are to divide among yourselves by sacred lot. The LORD commands that the land be divided up among the nine and a half remaining tribes.', 'NLT'),
(4, 34, 14, 'The families of the tribes of Reuben, Gad, and half the tribe of Manasseh have already received their inheritance of land', 'NLT'),
(4, 34, 15, 'on the east side of the Jordan River, across from Jericho."', 'NLT'),
(4, 34, 16, 'And the LORD said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(4, 34, 17, '"These are the men who are to divide the land among the people: Eleazar the priest and Joshua son of Nun.', 'NLT'),
(4, 34, 18, 'Also enlist one leader from each tribe to help them with the task.', 'NLT'),
(4, 34, 19, 'These are the tribes and the names of the leaders: Judah.................... Caleb son of Jephunneh', 'NLT'),
(4, 34, 20, 'Simeon................ Shemuel son of Ammihud', 'NLT'),
(4, 34, 21, 'Benjamin................... Elidad son of Kislon', 'NLT'),
(4, 34, 22, 'Dan......................... Bukki son of Jogli', 'NLT'),
(4, 34, 23, 'Manasseh son of Joseph....... Hanniel son of Ephod', 'NLT'),
(4, 34, 24, 'Ephraim son of Joseph...... Kemuel son of Shiphtan', 'NLT'),
(4, 34, 25, 'Zebulun................ Elizaphan son of Parnach', 'NLT'),
(4, 34, 26, 'Issachar..................... Paltiel son of Azzan', 'NLT'),
(4, 34, 27, 'Asher.................... Ahihud son of Shelomi', 'NLT'),
(4, 34, 28, 'Naphtali................ Pedahel son of Ammihud', 'NLT'),
(4, 34, 29, 'These are the men the LORD has appointed to oversee the dividing of the land of Canaan among the Israelites."', 'NLT'),
(4, 35, 1, 'While Israel was camped beside the Jordan on the plains of Moab, across from Jericho, the LORD said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(4, 35, 2, '"Instruct the people of Israel to give to the Levites from their property certain towns to live in, along with the surrounding pasturelands.', 'NLT'),
(4, 35, 3, 'These towns will be their homes, and the surrounding lands will provide pasture for their cattle, flocks, and other livestock.', 'NLT'),
(4, 35, 4, 'The pastureland assigned to the Levites around these towns will extend 1,500 feet from the town walls in every direction.', 'NLT'),
(4, 35, 5, 'Measure off 3,000 feet outside the town walls in every direction--east, south, west, north--with the town at the center. This area will serve as the larger pastureland for the towns.', 'NLT'),
(4, 35, 6, '"You must give the Levites six cities of refuge, where a person who has accidentally killed someone can flee for safety. In addition, give them forty-two other towns.', 'NLT'),
(4, 35, 7, 'In all, forty-eight towns with the surrounding pastureland will be given to the Levites.', 'NLT'),
(4, 35, 8, 'These towns will come from the property of the people of Israel. The larger tribes will give more towns to the Levites, while the smaller tribes will give fewer. Each tribe will give in proportion to its inheritance."', 'NLT'),
(4, 35, 9, 'And the LORD said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(4, 35, 10, '"Say this to the people of Israel: `When you cross the Jordan into the land of Canaan,', 'NLT'),
(4, 35, 11, 'designate cities of refuge for people to flee to if they have killed someone accidentally.', 'NLT'),
(4, 35, 12, 'These cities will be places of protection from a dead person''s relatives who want to avenge the death. The slayer must not be killed before being tried by the community.', 'NLT'),
(4, 35, 13, 'Designate six cities of refuge for yourselves,', 'NLT'),
(4, 35, 14, 'three on the east side of the Jordan River and three on the west in the land of Canaan.', 'NLT'),
(4, 35, 15, 'These cities are for the protection of Israelites, resident foreigners, and traveling merchants. Anyone who accidentally kills someone may flee there for safety.', 'NLT'),
(4, 35, 16, '" `But if someone strikes and kills another person with a piece of iron, it must be presumed to be murder, and the murderer must be executed.', 'NLT'),
(4, 35, 17, 'Or if someone strikes and kills another person with a large stone, it is murder, and the murderer must be executed.', 'NLT'),
(4, 35, 18, 'The same is true if someone strikes and kills another person with a wooden weapon. It must be presumed to be murder, and the murderer must be executed.', 'NLT'),
(4, 35, 19, 'The victim''s nearest relative is responsible for putting the murderer to death. When they meet, the avenger must execute the murderer.', 'NLT'),
(4, 35, 20, 'So if in premeditated hostility someone pushes another person or throws a dangerous object and the person dies, it is murder.', 'NLT'),
(4, 35, 21, 'Or if someone angrily hits another person with a fist and the person dies, it is murder. In such cases, the victim''s nearest relative must execute the murderer when they meet.', 'NLT'),
(4, 35, 22, '" `But suppose someone pushes another person without premeditated hostility, or throws something that unintentionally hits another person,', 'NLT'),
(4, 35, 23, 'or accidentally drops a stone on someone, though they were not enemies, and the person dies.', 'NLT'),
(4, 35, 24, 'If this should happen, the assembly must follow these regulations in making a judgment between the slayer and the avenger, the victim''s nearest relative.', 'NLT'),
(4, 35, 25, 'They must protect the slayer from the avenger, and they must send the slayer back to live in a city of refuge until the death of the high priest.', 'NLT'),
(4, 35, 26, '" `But if the slayer leaves the city of refuge,', 'NLT'),
(4, 35, 27, 'and the victim''s nearest relative finds him outside the city limits and kills him, it will not be considered murder.', 'NLT'),
(4, 35, 28, 'The slayer should have stayed inside the city of refuge until the death of the high priest. But after the death of the high priest, the slayer may return to his own property.', 'NLT'),
(4, 35, 29, 'These are permanent laws for you to observe from generation to generation, wherever you may live.', 'NLT'),
(4, 35, 30, '" `All murderers must be executed, but only if there is more than one witness. No one may be put to death on the testimony of only one witness.', 'NLT'),
(4, 35, 31, 'Also, you must never accept a ransom payment for the life of someone judged guilty of murder and subject to execution; murderers must always be put to death.', 'NLT'),
(4, 35, 32, 'And never accept a ransom payment from someone who has fled to a city of refuge, allowing the slayer to return to his property before the death of the high priest.', 'NLT'),
(4, 35, 33, 'This will ensure that the land where you live will not be polluted, for murder pollutes the land. And no atonement can be made for murder except by the execution of the murderer.', 'NLT'),
(4, 35, 34, 'You must not defile the land where you are going to live, for I live there myself. I am the LORD, who lives among the people of Israel.''"', 'NLT'),
(4, 36, 1, 'Then the heads of the clan of Gilead--descendants of Makir, son of Manasseh, son of Joseph--came to Moses and the family leaders of Israel with a petition.', 'NLT'),
(4, 36, 2, 'They said, "Sir, the LORD instructed you to divide the land by sacred lot among the people of Israel. You were told by the LORD to give the inheritance of our brother Zelophehad to his daughters.', 'NLT'),
(4, 36, 3, 'But if any of them marries a man from another tribe, their inheritance of land will go with them to the tribe into which they marry. In this way, the total area of our tribal land will be reduced.', 'NLT'),
(4, 36, 4, 'Then when the Year of Jubilee comes, their inheritance of land will be added to that of the new tribe, causing it to be lost forever to our ancestral tribe."', 'NLT'),
(4, 36, 5, 'So Moses gave the Israelites this command from the LORD: "The men of the tribe of Joseph are right.', 'NLT'),
(4, 36, 6, 'This is what the LORD commands concerning the daughters of Zelophehad: Let them marry anyone they like, as long as it is within their own ancestral tribe.', 'NLT'),
(4, 36, 7, 'None of the inherited land may pass from tribe to tribe, for the inheritance of every tribe must remain fixed as it was first allotted.', 'NLT'),
(4, 36, 8, 'The daughters throughout the tribes of Israel who are in line to inherit property must marry within their tribe, so that all the Israelites will keep their ancestral property.', 'NLT'),
(4, 36, 9, 'No inheritance may pass from one tribe to another; each tribe of Israel must hold on to its allotted inheritance of land."', 'NLT'),
(4, 36, 10, 'The daughters of Zelophehad did as the LORD commanded Moses.', 'NLT'),
(4, 36, 11, 'Mahlah, Tirzah, Hoglah, Milcah, and Noah all married cousins on their father''s side.', 'NLT'),
(4, 36, 12, 'They married into the clans of Manasseh son of Joseph. Thus, their inheritance of land remained within their ancestral tribe.', 'NLT'),
(4, 36, 13, 'These are the commands and regulations that the LORD gave to the people of Israel through Moses while they were camped on the plains of Moab beside the Jordan River, across from Jericho.', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 1, 'This book records the words that Moses spoke to all the people of Israel while they were in the wilderness east of the Jordan River. They were camped in the Jordan Valley near Suph, between Paran on one side and Tophel, Laban, Hazeroth, and Di-zahab on the other.', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 2, 'Normally it takes only eleven days to travel from Mount Sinai to Kadesh-barnea, going by way of Mount Seir.', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 3, 'But forty years after the Israelites left Mount Sinai, on a day in midwinter, Moses gave these speeches to the Israelites, telling them everything the LORD had commanded him to say.', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 4, 'This was after he had defeated King Sihon of the Amorites, who had ruled in Heshbon, and King Og of Bashan, who had ruled in Ashtaroth and Edrei.', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 5, 'So Moses addressed the people of Israel while they were in the land of Moab east of the Jordan River. He began to explain the law as follows:', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 6, '"When we were at Mount Sinai, the LORD our God said to us, `You have stayed at this mountain long enough.', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 7, 'It is time to break camp and move on. Go to the hill country of the Amorites and to all the neighboring regions--the Jordan Valley, the hill country, the western foothills, the Negev, and the coastal plain. Go to the land of the Canaanites and to Lebanon, and all the way to the great Euphrates River.', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 8, 'I am giving all this land to you! Go in and occupy it, for it is the land the LORD swore to give to your ancestors Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob, and to all their descendants.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 9, '"At that time I told you, `You are too great a burden for me to carry all by myself.', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 10, 'The LORD your God has made you as numerous as the stars!', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 11, 'And may the LORD, the God of your ancestors, multiply you a thousand times more and bless you as he promised!', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 12, 'But how can I settle all your quarrels and problems by myself?', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 13, 'Choose some men from each tribe who have wisdom, understanding, and a good reputation, and I will appoint them as your leaders.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 14, '"You agreed that my plan was a good one.', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 15, 'So I took the wise and respected men you had selected from your tribes and appointed them to serve as judges and officials over you. Some were responsible for a thousand people, some for a hundred, some for fifty, and some for ten.', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 16, 'I instructed the judges, `You must be perfectly fair at all times, not only to fellow Israelites, but also to the foreigners living among you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 17, 'When you make decisions, never favor those who are rich; be fair to lowly and great alike. Don''t be afraid of how they will react, for you are judging in the place of God. Bring me any cases that are too difficult for you, and I will handle them.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 18, 'And at that time I gave you instructions about everything you were to do.', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 19, '"Then, just as the LORD our God directed us, we left Mount Sinai and traveled through the great and terrifying wilderness, which you yourselves saw, and headed toward the hill country of the Amorites. When we arrived at Kadesh-barnea,', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 20, 'I said to you, `You have now reached the land that the LORD our God is giving us.', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 21, 'Look! He has placed it in front of you. Go and occupy it as the LORD, the God of your ancestors, has promised you. Don''t be afraid! Don''t be discouraged!''', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 22, '"But you responded, `First, let''s send out scouts to explore the land for us. They will advise us on the best route to take and decide which towns we should capture.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 23, 'This seemed like a good idea to me, so I chose twelve scouts, one from each of your tribes.', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 24, 'They crossed into the hills and came to the valley of Eshcol and explored it.', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 25, 'They picked some of its fruit and brought it back to us. And they reported that the land the LORD our God had given us was indeed a good land.', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 26, '"But you rebelled against the command of the LORD your God and refused to go in.', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 27, 'You murmured and complained in your tents and said, `The LORD must hate us, bringing us here from Egypt to be slaughtered by these Amorites.', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 28, 'How can we go on? Our scouts have demoralized us with their report. They say that the people of the land are taller and more powerful than we are, and that the walls of their towns rise high into the sky! They have even seen giants there--the descendants of Anak!''', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 29, '"But I said to you, `Don''t be afraid!', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 30, 'The LORD your God is going before you. He will fight for you, just as you saw him do in Egypt.', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 31, 'And you saw how the LORD your God cared for you again and again here in the wilderness, just as a father cares for his child. Now he has brought you to this place.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 32, 'But even after all he did, you refused to trust the LORD your God,', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 33, 'who goes before you looking for the best places to camp, guiding you by a pillar of fire at night and a pillar of cloud by day.', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 34, '"When the LORD heard your complaining, he became very angry. So he solemnly swore,', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 35, '`Not one of you from this entire wicked generation will live to see the good land I swore to give your ancestors,', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 36, 'except Caleb son of Jephunneh. He will see this land because he has followed the LORD completely. I will give to him and his descendants some of the land he walked over during his scouting mission.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 37, '"And the LORD was also angry with me because of you. He said to me, `You will never enter the Promised Land!', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 38, 'Instead, your assistant, Joshua son of Nun, will lead the people into the land. Encourage him as he prepares to enter it.', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 39, 'I will give the land to your innocent children. You were afraid they would be captured, but they will be the ones who occupy it.', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 40, 'As for you, turn around now and go on back through the wilderness toward the Red Sea. ''', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 41, '"Then you confessed, `We have sinned against the LORD! We will go into the land and fight for it, as the LORD our God has told us.'' So your men strapped on their weapons, thinking it would be easy to conquer the hill country.', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 42, '"But the LORD said to me, `Tell them not to attack, for I will not go with them. If they do, they will be crushed by their enemies.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 43, 'This is what I told you, but you would not listen. Instead, you again rebelled against the LORD''s command and arrogantly went into the hill country to fight.', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 44, 'But the Amorites who lived there came out against you like a swarm of bees. They chased and battered you all the way from Seir to Hormah.', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 45, 'Then you returned and wept before the LORD, but he refused to listen.', 'NLT'),
(5, 1, 46, 'So you stayed there at Kadesh for a long time.', 'NLT'),
(5, 2, 1, '"Then we turned around and set out across the wilderness toward the Red Sea, just as the LORD had instructed me, and we wandered around Mount Seir for a long time.', 'NLT'),
(5, 2, 2, 'Then at last the LORD said to me,', 'NLT'),
(5, 2, 3, '`You have been wandering around in this hill country long enough; turn northward.', 'NLT'),
(5, 2, 4, 'Give these orders to the people: "You will be passing through the country belonging to your relatives the Edomites, the descendants of Esau, who live in Seir. The Edomites will feel threatened, so be careful.', 'NLT'),
(5, 2, 5, 'Don''t bother them, for I have given them all the hill country around Mount Seir as their property, and I will not give you any of their land.', 'NLT'),
(5, 2, 6, 'Pay them for whatever food or water you use.', 'NLT'),
(5, 2, 7, 'The LORD your God has blessed everything you have done and has watched your every step through this great wilderness. During these forty years, the LORD your God has been with you and provided for your every need so that you lacked nothing."''', 'NLT'),
(5, 2, 8, 'So we went past our relatives, the descendants of Esau, who live in Seir, and avoided the road through the Arabah Valley that comes up from Elath and Ezion-geber. "Then as we traveled northward along the desert route through Moab,', 'NLT'),
(5, 2, 9, 'the LORD warned us, `Do not bother the Moabites, the descendants of Lot, or start a war with them. I have given them Ar as their property, and I will not give you any of their land.''"', 'NLT'),
(5, 2, 10, '(A numerous and powerful race of giants called the Emites had once lived in the area of Ar. They were as tall as the Anakites, another race of giants.', 'NLT'),
(5, 2, 11, 'Both the Emites and the Anakites are often referred to as the Rephaites, but the Moabites called them Emites.', 'NLT'),
(5, 2, 12, 'In earlier times the Horites had lived at Mount Seir, but they were driven out and displaced by the descendants of Esau. In a similar way the peoples in Canaan were driven from the land that the LORD had assigned to Israel.)', 'NLT'),
(5, 2, 13, 'Moses continued, "Then the LORD told us to cross Zered Brook, and we did.', 'NLT'),
(5, 2, 14, 'So thirty-eight years passed from the time we first arrived at Kadesh-barnea until we finally crossed Zered Brook! For the LORD had vowed that this could not happen until all the men old enough to fight in battle had died in the wilderness.', 'NLT'),
(5, 2, 15, 'The LORD had lifted his hand against them until all of them had finally died.', 'NLT'),
(5, 2, 16, '"When all the men of fighting age had died,', 'NLT'),
(5, 2, 17, 'the LORD said to me,', 'NLT'),
(5, 2, 18, '`Today you will cross the border of Moab at Ar', 'NLT'),
(5, 2, 19, 'and enter the land of Ammon. But do not bother the Ammonites, the descendants of Lot, or start a war with them. I have given the land of Ammon to them as their property, and I will not give you any of their land.''"', 'NLT'),
(5, 2, 20, '(That area, too, was once considered the land of the Rephaites, though the Ammonites referred to them as Zamzummites.', 'NLT'),
(5, 2, 21, 'They were a numerous and powerful race, as tall as the Anakites. But the LORD destroyed them so the Ammonites could occupy their land.', 'NLT'),
(5, 2, 22, 'He had similarly helped the descendants of Esau at Mount Seir, for he destroyed the Horites so they could settle there in their place. The descendants of Esau live there to this day.', 'NLT'),
(5, 2, 23, 'A similar thing happened when the Caphtorites from Crete invaded and destroyed the Avvites, who had lived in villages in the area of Gaza.)', 'NLT'),
(5, 2, 24, 'Moses continued, "Then the LORD said, `Now cross the Arnon Gorge! Look, I will help you defeat Sihon the Amorite, king of Heshbon, and I will give you his land. Attack him and begin to occupy the land.', 'NLT'),
(5, 2, 25, 'Beginning today I will make all people throughout the earth terrified of you. When they hear reports about you, they will tremble with dread and fear.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 2, 26, '"Then from the wilderness of Kedemoth I sent ambassadors to King Sihon of Heshbon with this proposal of peace:', 'NLT'),
(5, 2, 27, '`Let us pass through your land. We will stay on the main road and won''t turn off into the fields on either side.', 'NLT'),
(5, 2, 28, 'We will pay for every bite of food we eat and all the water we drink. All we want is permission to pass through your land.', 'NLT'),
(5, 2, 29, 'The descendants of Esau at Mount Seir allowed us to go through their country, and so did the Moabites, who live in Ar. Let us pass through until we cross the Jordan into the land the LORD our God has given us.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 2, 30, 'But King Sihon refused to allow you to pass through, because the LORD your God made Sihon stubborn and defiant so he could help you defeat them, as he has now done.', 'NLT'),
(5, 2, 31, '"Then the LORD said to me, `Look, I have begun to hand King Sihon and his land over to you. Begin now to conquer and occupy his land.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 2, 32, 'Then King Sihon declared war on us and mobilized his forces at Jahaz.', 'NLT'),
(5, 2, 33, 'But the LORD our God handed him over to us, and we crushed him, his sons, and all his people.', 'NLT'),
(5, 2, 34, 'We conquered all his towns and completely destroyed everyone--men, women, and children. Not a single person was spared.', 'NLT'),
(5, 2, 35, 'We took all the livestock as plunder for ourselves, along with anything of value from the towns we ransacked.', 'NLT'),
(5, 2, 36, '"The LORD our God helped us conquer Aroer on the edge of the Arnon Gorge, the town in the gorge, and the whole area as far as Gilead. No town had walls too strong for us.', 'NLT'),
(5, 2, 37, 'However, we stayed away from the Ammonites along the Jabbok River and the towns in the hill country--all the places the LORD our God had commanded us to leave alone.', 'NLT'),
(5, 3, 1, '"Next we headed for the land of Bashan, where King Og and his army attacked us at Edrei.', 'NLT'),
(5, 3, 2, 'But the LORD told me, `Do not be afraid of him, for I have given you victory over Og and his army, giving you his entire land. Treat him just as you treated King Sihon of the Amorites, who ruled in Heshbon.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 3, 3, 'So the LORD our God handed King Og and all his people over to us, and we killed them all.', 'NLT'),
(5, 3, 4, 'We conquered all sixty of his towns, the entire Argob region in his kingdom of Bashan.', 'NLT'),
(5, 3, 5, 'These were all fortified cities with high walls and barred gates. We also took many unwalled villages at the same time.', 'NLT'),
(5, 3, 6, 'We completely destroyed the kingdom of Bashan, just as we had destroyed King Sihon of Heshbon. We destroyed all the people in every town we conquered--men, women, and children alike.', 'NLT'),
(5, 3, 7, 'But we kept all the livestock for ourselves and took plunder from all the towns.', 'NLT'),
(5, 3, 8, '"We now possessed all the land of the two Amorite kings east of the Jordan River--from the Arnon Gorge to Mount Hermon.', 'NLT'),
(5, 3, 9, '(Mount Hermon is called Sirion by the Sidonians; the Amorites call it Senir.)', 'NLT'),
(5, 3, 10, 'We had now conquered all the cities on the plateau, and all Gilead and Bashan as far as the towns of Salecah and Edrei, which were part of Og''s kingdom in Bashan.', 'NLT'),
(5, 3, 11, '(Incidentally, King Og of Bashan was the last of the giant Rephaites. His iron bed was more than thirteen feet long and six feet wide. It can still be seen in the Ammonite city of Rabbah.)', 'NLT'),
(5, 3, 12, '"When we took possession of this land, I gave the territory beyond Aroer along the Arnon Gorge, plus half of the hill country of Gilead with its towns, to the tribes of Reuben and Gad.', 'NLT'),
(5, 3, 13, 'Then I gave the rest of Gilead and all of Bashan--Og''s former kingdom--to the half-tribe of Manasseh. (The Argob region of Bashan used to be known as the land of the Rephaites.', 'NLT'),
(5, 3, 14, 'Jair, a leader from the tribe of Manasseh, acquired the whole Argob region in Bashan all the way to the borders of the Geshurites and Maacathites. Jair renamed this region after himself, calling it the Towns of Jair, as it is still known today.)', 'NLT'),
(5, 3, 15, 'I gave Gilead to the clan of Makir.', 'NLT'),
(5, 3, 16, 'And to the tribes of Reuben and Gad I gave the area extending from Gilead to the middle of the Arnon Gorge, all the way to the Jabbok River on the Ammonite frontier.', 'NLT'),
(5, 3, 17, 'They also received the Jordan Valley, including the Jordan River and its eastern banks, all the way from the Sea of Galilee down to the Dead Sea, with the slopes of Pisgah on the east.', 'NLT'),
(5, 3, 18, '"At that time I gave this command to the tribes that will live east of the Jordan: `Although the LORD your God has given you this land as your property, all your fighting men must cross the Jordan, armed and ready to protect your Israelite relatives.', 'NLT'),
(5, 3, 19, 'Your wives, children, and numerous livestock, however, may stay behind in the towns I have given you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 3, 20, 'When the LORD has given security to the rest of the Israelites, as he has to you, and when they occupy the land the LORD your God is giving them across the Jordan River, then you may return here to the land I have given you.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 3, 21, '"At that time I said to Joshua, `You have seen all that the LORD your God has done to these two kings. He will do the same to all the kingdoms on the west side of the Jordan.', 'NLT'),
(5, 3, 22, 'Do not be afraid of the nations there, for the LORD your God will fight for you.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 3, 23, '"At that time I pleaded with the LORD and said,', 'NLT'),
(5, 3, 24, '`O Sovereign LORD, I am your servant. You have only begun to show me your greatness and power. Is there any god in heaven or on earth who can perform such great deeds as yours?', 'NLT'),
(5, 3, 25, 'Please let me cross the Jordan to see the wonderful land on the other side, the beautiful hill country and the Lebanon mountains.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 3, 26, '"But the LORD was angry with me because of you, and he would not listen to me. `That''s enough!'' he ordered. `Speak of it no more.', 'NLT'),
(5, 3, 27, 'You can go to Pisgah Peak and view the land in every direction, but you may not cross the Jordan River.', 'NLT'),
(5, 3, 28, 'But commission Joshua and encourage him, for he will lead the people across the Jordan. He will give them the land you now see before you.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 3, 29, 'So we stayed in the valley near Beth-peor.', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 1, '"And now, Israel, listen carefully to these laws and regulations that I am about to teach you. Obey them so that you may live, so you may enter and occupy the land the LORD, the God of your ancestors, is giving you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 2, 'Do not add to or subtract from these commands I am giving you from the LORD your God. Just obey them.', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 3, 'You saw what the LORD did to you at Baal-peor, where the LORD your God destroyed everyone who had worshiped the god Baal of Peor.', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 4, 'But all of you who were faithful to the LORD your God are still alive today.', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 5, '"You must obey these laws and regulations when you arrive in the land you are about to enter and occupy. The LORD my God gave them to me and commanded me to pass them on to you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 6, 'If you obey them carefully, you will display your wisdom and intelligence to the surrounding nations. When they hear about these laws, they will exclaim, `What other nation is as wise and prudent as this!''', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 7, 'For what great nation has a god as near to them as the LORD our God is near to us whenever we call on him?', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 8, 'And what great nation has laws and regulations as fair as this body of laws that I am giving you today?', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 9, '"But watch out! Be very careful never to forget what you have seen the LORD do for you. Do not let these things escape from your mind as long as you live! And be sure to pass them on to your children and grandchildren.', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 10, 'Tell them especially about the day when you stood before the LORD your God at Mount Sinai, where he told me, `Summon the people before me, and I will instruct them. That way, they will learn to fear me as long as they live, and they will be able to teach my laws to their children.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 11, 'You came near and stood at the foot of the mountain, while the mountain was burning with fire. Flames shot into the sky, shrouded in black clouds and deep darkness.', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 12, 'And the LORD spoke to you from the fire. You heard his words but didn''t see his form; there was only a voice.', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 13, 'He proclaimed his covenant, which he commanded you to keep--the Ten Commandments--and wrote them on two stone tablets.', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 14, 'It was at that time that the LORD commanded me to issue the laws and regulations you must obey in the land you are about to enter and occupy.', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 15, '"But be careful! You did not see the LORD''s form on the day he spoke to you from the fire at Mount Sinai.', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 16, 'So do not corrupt yourselves by making a physical image in any form--whether of a man or a woman,', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 17, 'an animal or a bird,', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 18, 'a creeping creature or a fish.', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 19, 'And when you look up into the sky and see the sun, moon, and stars--all the forces of heaven--don''t be seduced by them and worship them. The LORD your God designated these heavenly bodies for all the peoples of the earth.', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 20, 'Remember that the LORD rescued you from the burning furnace of Egypt to become his own people and special possession; that is what you are today.', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 21, '"But the LORD was very angry with me because of you. He vowed that I would never cross the Jordan River into the good land the LORD your God is giving you as your special possession.', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 22, 'Though you will cross the Jordan to occupy the land, I will die here on this side of the river.', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 23, 'So be careful not to break the covenant the LORD your God has made with you. You will break it if you make idols of any shape or form, for the LORD your God has absolutely forbidden this.', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 24, 'The LORD your God is a devouring fire, a jealous God.', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 25, '"In the future, when you have children and grandchildren and have lived in the land a long time, do not corrupt yourselves by making idols of any kind. This is evil in the sight of the LORD your God and will arouse his anger.', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 26, '"Today I call heaven and earth as witnesses against you. If you disobey me, you will quickly disappear from the land you are crossing the Jordan to occupy. You will live there only a short time; then you will be utterly destroyed.', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 27, 'For the LORD will scatter you among the nations, where only a few of you will survive.', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 28, 'There, in a foreign land, you will worship idols made from wood and stone, gods that neither see nor hear nor eat nor smell.', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 29, 'From there you will search again for the LORD your God. And if you search for him with all your heart and soul, you will find him.', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 30, '"When those bitter days have come upon you far in the future, you will finally return to the LORD your God and listen to what he tells you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 31, 'For the LORD your God is merciful--he will not abandon you or destroy you or forget the solemn covenant he made with your ancestors.', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 32, '"Search all of history, from the time God created people on the earth until now. Then search from one end of the heavens to the other. See if anything as great as this has ever happened before.', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 33, 'Has any nation ever heard the voice of God speaking from fire--as you did--and survived?', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 34, 'Has any other god taken one nation for himself by rescuing it from another by means of trials, miraculous signs, wonders, war, awesome power, and terrifying acts? Yet that is what the LORD your God did for you in Egypt, right before your very eyes.', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 35, '"He showed you these things so you would realize that the LORD is God and that there is no other god.', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 36, 'He let you hear his voice from heaven so he could instruct you. He let you see his great fire here on earth so he could speak to you from it.', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 37, 'Because he loved your ancestors, he chose to bless their descendants and personally brought you out of Egypt with a great display of power.', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 38, 'He drove out nations far greater than you, so he could bring you in and give you their land as a special possession, as it is today.', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 39, 'So remember this and keep it firmly in mind: The LORD is God both in heaven and on earth, and there is no other god!', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 40, 'If you obey all the laws and commands that I will give you today, all will be well with you and your children. Then you will enjoy a long life in the land the LORD your God is giving you for all time."', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 41, 'Then Moses set apart three cities of refuge east of the Jordan River,', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 42, 'where anyone who had accidentally killed someone without having any previous hostility could flee for safety.', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 43, 'These were the cities: Bezer on the wilderness plateau for the tribe of Reuben; Ramoth in Gilead for the tribe of Gad; Golan in Bashan for the tribe of Manasseh.', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 44, 'This is the law that Moses handed down to the Israelites.', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 45, 'These are the stipulations, laws, and regulations that Moses gave to the people of Israel when they left Egypt,', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 46, 'and as they camped in the valley near Beth-peor east of the Jordan River. (This land was formerly occupied by the Amorites under King Sihon of Heshbon. He and his people had been destroyed by Moses and the Israelites as they came up from Egypt.', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 47, 'Israel conquered his land and that of King Og of Bashan--the two Amorite kings east of the Jordan.', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 48, 'So Israel conquered all the area from Aroer at the edge of the Arnon Gorge to Mount Sirion, also called Mount Hermon.', 'NLT'),
(5, 4, 49, 'And they took the eastern bank of the Jordan Valley as far south as the Dead Sea, below the slopes of Pisgah.)', 'NLT'),
(5, 5, 1, 'Moses called all the people of Israel together and said, "Listen carefully to all the laws and regulations I am giving you today. Learn them and be sure to obey them!', 'NLT'),
(5, 5, 2, '"While we were at Mount Sinai, the LORD our God made a covenant with us.', 'NLT'),
(5, 5, 3, 'The LORD did not make this covenant long ago with our ancestors, but with all of us who are alive today.', 'NLT'),
(5, 5, 4, 'The LORD spoke to you face to face from the heart of the fire on the mountain.', 'NLT'),
(5, 5, 5, 'I stood as an intermediary between you and the LORD, for you were afraid of the fire and did not climb the mountain. He spoke to me, and I passed his words on to you. This is what he said:', 'NLT'),
(5, 5, 6, '" `I am the LORD your God, who rescued you from slavery in Egypt.', 'NLT'),
(5, 5, 7, '" `Do not worship any other gods besides me.', 'NLT'),
(5, 5, 8, '" `Do not make idols of any kind, whether in the shape of birds or animals or fish.', 'NLT'),
(5, 5, 9, 'You must never worship or bow down to them, for I, the LORD your God, am a jealous God who will not share your affection with any other god! I do not leave unpunished the sins of those who hate me, but I punish the children for the sins of their parents to the third and fourth generations.', 'NLT'),
(5, 5, 10, 'But I lavish my love on those who love me and obey my commands, even for a thousand generations.', 'NLT'),
(5, 5, 11, '" `Do not misuse the name of the LORD your God. The LORD will not let you go unpunished if you misuse his name.', 'NLT'),
(5, 5, 12, '" `Observe the Sabbath day by keeping it holy, as the LORD your God has commanded you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 5, 13, 'Six days a week are set apart for your daily duties and regular work,', 'NLT'),
(5, 5, 14, 'but the seventh day is a day of rest dedicated to the LORD your God. On that day no one in your household may do any kind of work. This includes you, your sons and daughters, your male and female servants, your oxen and donkeys and other livestock, and any foreigners living among you. All your male and female servants must rest as you do.', 'NLT'),
(5, 5, 15, 'Remember that you were once slaves in Egypt and that the LORD your God brought you out with amazing power and mighty deeds. That is why the LORD your God has commanded you to observe the Sabbath day.', 'NLT'),
(5, 5, 16, '" `Honor your father and mother, as the LORD your God commanded you. Then you will live a long, full life in the land the LORD your God will give you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 5, 17, '" `Do not murder.', 'NLT'),
(5, 5, 18, '" `Do not commit adultery.', 'NLT'),
(5, 5, 19, '" `Do not steal.', 'NLT'),
(5, 5, 20, '" `Do not testify falsely against your neighbor.', 'NLT'),
(5, 5, 21, '" `Do not covet your neighbor''s wife. Do not covet your neighbor''s house or land, male or female servant, ox or donkey, or anything else your neighbor owns.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 5, 22, '"The LORD spoke these words with a loud voice to all of you from the heart of the fire, surrounded by clouds and deep darkness. This was all he said at that time, and he wrote his words on two stone tablets and gave them to me.', 'NLT'),
(5, 5, 23, 'But when you heard the voice from the darkness, while the mountain was blazing with fire, all your tribal leaders came to me.', 'NLT'),
(5, 5, 24, 'They said, `The LORD our God has shown us his glory and greatness, and we have heard his voice from the heart of the fire. Today we have seen God speaking to humans, and yet we live!', 'NLT'),
(5, 5, 25, 'But now, why should we die? If the LORD our God speaks to us again, we will certainly die and be consumed by this awesome fire.', 'NLT'),
(5, 5, 26, 'Can any living thing hear the voice of the living God from the heart of the fire and yet survive?', 'NLT'),
(5, 5, 27, 'You go and listen to what the LORD our God says. Then come and tell us everything he tells you, and we will listen and obey.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 5, 28, '"The LORD heard your request and said to me, `I have heard what the people have said to you, and they are right.', 'NLT'),
(5, 5, 29, 'Oh, that they would always have hearts like this, that they might fear me and obey all my commands! If they did, they and their descendants would prosper forever.', 'NLT'),
(5, 5, 30, 'Go and tell them to return to their tents.', 'NLT'),
(5, 5, 31, 'But you stay here with me so I can give you all my commands, laws, and regulations. You will teach them to the people so they can obey them in the land I am giving to them as their inheritance.''"', 'NLT'),
(5, 5, 32, 'So Moses told the people, "You must obey all the commands of the LORD your God, following his instructions in every detail.', 'NLT'),
(5, 5, 33, 'Stay on the path that the LORD your God has commanded you to follow. Then you will live long and prosperous lives in the land you are about to enter and occupy.', 'NLT'),
(5, 6, 1, '"These are all the commands, laws, and regulations that the LORD your God told me to teach you so you may obey them in the land you are about to enter and occupy,', 'NLT'),
(5, 6, 2, 'and so you and your children and grandchildren might fear the LORD your God as long as you live. If you obey all his laws and commands, you will enjoy a long life.', 'NLT'),
(5, 6, 3, 'Listen closely, Israel, to everything I say. Be careful to obey. Then all will go well with you, and you will have many children in the land flowing with milk and honey, just as the LORD, the God of your ancestors, promised you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 6, 4, '"Hear, O Israel! The LORD is our God, the LORD alone.', 'NLT'),
(5, 6, 5, 'And you must love the LORD your God with all your heart, all your soul, and all your strength.', 'NLT'),
(5, 6, 6, 'And you must commit yourselves wholeheartedly to these commands I am giving you today.', 'NLT'),
(5, 6, 7, 'Repeat them again and again to your children. Talk about them when you are at home and when you are away on a journey, when you are lying down and when you are getting up again.', 'NLT'),
(5, 6, 8, 'Tie them to your hands as a reminder, and wear them on your forehead.', 'NLT'),
(5, 6, 9, 'Write them on the doorposts of your house and on your gates.', 'NLT'),
(5, 6, 10, '"The LORD your God will soon bring you into the land he swore to give your ancestors Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob. It is a land filled with large, prosperous cities that you did not build.', 'NLT'),
(5, 6, 11, 'The houses will be richly stocked with goods you did not produce. You will draw water from cisterns you did not dig, and you will eat from vineyards and olive trees you did not plant. When you have eaten your fill in this land,', 'NLT'),
(5, 6, 12, 'be careful not to forget the LORD, who rescued you from slavery in the land of Egypt.', 'NLT'),
(5, 6, 13, 'You must fear the LORD your God and serve him. When you take an oath, you must use only his name.', 'NLT'),
(5, 6, 14, '"You must not worship any of the gods of neighboring nations,', 'NLT'),
(5, 6, 15, 'for the LORD your God, who lives among you, is a jealous God. His anger will flare up against you and wipe you from the face of the earth.', 'NLT'),
(5, 6, 16, 'Do not test the LORD your God as you did when you complained at Massah.', 'NLT'),
(5, 6, 17, 'You must diligently obey the commands of the LORD your God--all the stipulations and laws he has given you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 6, 18, 'Do what is right and good in the LORD''s sight, so all will go well with you. Then you will enter and occupy the good land that the LORD solemnly promised to give your ancestors.', 'NLT'),
(5, 6, 19, 'You will drive out all the enemies living in your land, just as the LORD said you would.', 'NLT'),
(5, 6, 20, '"In the future your children will ask you, `What is the meaning of these stipulations, laws, and regulations that the LORD our God has given us?''', 'NLT'),
(5, 6, 21, 'Then you must tell them, `We were Pharaoh''s slaves in Egypt, but the LORD brought us out of Egypt with amazing power.', 'NLT'),
(5, 6, 22, 'Before our eyes the LORD did miraculous signs and wonders, dealing terrifying blows against Egypt and Pharaoh and all his people.', 'NLT'),
(5, 6, 23, 'He brought us out of Egypt so he could give us this land he had solemnly promised to give our ancestors.', 'NLT'),
(5, 6, 24, 'And the LORD our God commanded us to obey all these laws and to fear him for our own prosperity and well-being, as is now the case.', 'NLT'),
(5, 6, 25, 'For we are righteous when we obey all the commands the LORD our God has given us.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 7, 1, '"When the LORD your God brings you into the land you are about to enter and occupy, he will clear away many nations ahead of you: the Hittites, Girgashites, Amorites, Canaanites, Perizzites, Hivites, and Jebusites. These seven nations are all more powerful than you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 7, 2, 'When the LORD your God hands these nations over to you and you conquer them, you must completely destroy them. Make no treaties with them and show them no mercy.', 'NLT'),
(5, 7, 3, 'Do not intermarry with them, and don''t let your daughters and sons marry their sons and daughters.', 'NLT'),
(5, 7, 4, 'They will lead your young people away from me to worship other gods. Then the anger of the LORD will burn against you, and he will destroy you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 7, 5, 'Instead, you must break down their pagan altars and shatter their sacred pillars. Cut down their Asherah poles and burn their idols.', 'NLT'),
(5, 7, 6, 'For you are a holy people, who belong to the LORD your God. Of all the people on earth, the LORD your God has chosen you to be his own special treasure.', 'NLT'),
(5, 7, 7, '"The LORD did not choose you and lavish his love on you because you were larger or greater than other nations, for you were the smallest of all nations!', 'NLT'),
(5, 7, 8, 'It was simply because the LORD loves you, and because he was keeping the oath he had sworn to your ancestors. That is why the LORD rescued you with such amazing power from your slavery under Pharaoh in Egypt.', 'NLT'),
(5, 7, 9, 'Understand, therefore, that the LORD your God is indeed God. He is the faithful God who keeps his covenant for a thousand generations and constantly loves those who love him and obey his commands.', 'NLT'),
(5, 7, 10, 'But he does not hesitate to punish and destroy those who hate him.', 'NLT'),
(5, 7, 11, 'Therefore, obey all these commands, laws, and regulations I am giving you today.', 'NLT'),
(5, 7, 12, '"If you listen to these regulations and obey them faithfully, the LORD your God will keep his covenant of unfailing love with you, as he solemnly promised your ancestors.', 'NLT'),
(5, 7, 13, 'He will love you and bless you and make you into a great nation. He will give you many children and give fertility to your land and your animals. When you arrive in the land he swore to give your ancestors, you will have large crops of grain, grapes, and olives, and great herds of cattle, sheep, and goats.', 'NLT'),
(5, 7, 14, 'You will be blessed above all the nations of the earth. None of your men or women will be childless, and all your livestock will bear young.', 'NLT'),
(5, 7, 15, 'And the LORD will protect you from all sickness. He will not let you suffer from the terrible diseases you knew in Egypt, but he will bring them all on your enemies!', 'NLT'),
(5, 7, 16, '"You must destroy all the nations the LORD your God hands over to you. Show them no mercy and do not worship their gods. If you do, they will trap you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 7, 17, 'Perhaps you will think to yourselves, `How can we ever conquer these nations that are so much more powerful than we are?''', 'NLT'),
(5, 7, 18, 'But don''t be afraid of them! Just remember what the LORD your God did to Pharaoh and to all the land of Egypt.', 'NLT'),
(5, 7, 19, 'Remember the great terrors the LORD your God sent against them. You saw it all with your own eyes! And remember the miraculous signs and wonders, and the amazing power he used when he brought you out of Egypt. The LORD your God will use this same power against the people you fear.', 'NLT'),
(5, 7, 20, 'And then the LORD your God will send hornets to drive out the few survivors still hiding from you!', 'NLT'),
(5, 7, 21, '"No, do not be afraid of those nations, for the LORD your God is among you, and he is a great and awesome God.', 'NLT'),
(5, 7, 22, 'The LORD your God will drive those nations out ahead of you little by little. You will not clear them away all at once, for if you did, the wild animals would multiply too quickly for you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 7, 23, 'But the LORD your God will hand them over to you. He will throw them into complete confusion until they are destroyed.', 'NLT'),
(5, 7, 24, 'He will put their kings in your power, and you will erase their names from the face of the earth. No one will be able to stand against you, and you will destroy them all.', 'NLT'),
(5, 7, 25, '"You must burn their idols in fire, and do not desire the silver or gold with which they are made. Do not take it or it will become a snare to you, for it is detestable to the LORD your God.', 'NLT'),
(5, 7, 26, 'Do not bring any detestable objects into your home, for then you will be set apart for destruction just like them. You must utterly detest such things, for they are set apart for destruction.', 'NLT'),
(5, 8, 1, '"Be careful to obey all the commands I am giving you today. Then you will live and multiply, and you will enter and occupy the land the LORD swore to give your ancestors.', 'NLT'),
(5, 8, 2, 'Remember how the LORD your God led you through the wilderness for forty years, humbling you and testing you to prove your character, and to find out whether or not you would really obey his commands.', 'NLT'),
(5, 8, 3, 'Yes, he humbled you by letting you go hungry and then feeding you with manna, a food previously unknown to you and your ancestors. He did it to teach you that people need more than bread for their life; real life comes by feeding on every word of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(5, 8, 4, 'For all these forty years your clothes didn''t wear out, and your feet didn''t blister or swell.', 'NLT'),
(5, 8, 5, 'So you should realize that just as a parent disciplines a child, the LORD your God disciplines you to help you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 8, 6, '"So obey the commands of the LORD your God by walking in his ways and fearing him.', 'NLT'),
(5, 8, 7, 'For the LORD your God is bringing you into a good land of flowing streams and pools of water, with springs that gush forth in the valleys and hills.', 'NLT'),
(5, 8, 8, 'It is a land of wheat and barley, of grapevines, fig trees, pomegranates, olives, and honey.', 'NLT'),
(5, 8, 9, 'It is a land where food is plentiful and nothing is lacking. It is a land where iron is as common as stone, and copper is abundant in the hills.', 'NLT'),
(5, 8, 10, 'When you have eaten your fill, praise the LORD your God for the good land he has given you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 8, 11, '"But that is the time to be careful! Beware that in your plenty you do not forget the LORD your God and disobey his commands, regulations, and laws.', 'NLT'),
(5, 8, 12, 'For when you have become full and prosperous and have built fine homes to live in,', 'NLT'),
(5, 8, 13, 'and when your flocks and herds have become very large and your silver and gold have multiplied along with everything else,', 'NLT'),
(5, 8, 14, 'that is the time to be careful. Do not become proud at that time and forget the LORD your God, who rescued you from slavery in the land of Egypt.', 'NLT'),
(5, 8, 15, 'Do not forget that he led you through the great and terrifying wilderness with poisonous snakes and scorpions, where it was so hot and dry. He gave you water from the rock!', 'NLT'),
(5, 8, 16, 'He fed you with manna in the wilderness, a food unknown to your ancestors. He did this to humble you and test you for your own good.', 'NLT'),
(5, 8, 17, 'He did it so you would never think that it was your own strength and energy that made you wealthy.', 'NLT'),
(5, 8, 18, 'Always remember that it is the LORD your God who gives you power to become rich, and he does it to fulfill the covenant he made with your ancestors.', 'NLT'),
(5, 8, 19, '"But I assure you of this: If you ever forget the LORD your God and follow other gods, worshiping and bowing down to them, you will certainly be destroyed.', 'NLT'),
(5, 8, 20, 'Just as the LORD has destroyed other nations in your path, you also will be destroyed for not obeying the LORD your God.', 'NLT'),
(5, 9, 1, '"Hear, O Israel! Today you are about to cross the Jordan River to occupy the land belonging to nations much greater and more powerful than you. They live in cities with walls that reach to the sky!', 'NLT'),
(5, 9, 2, 'They are strong and tall--descendants of the famous Anakite giants. You''ve heard the saying, `Who can stand up to the Anakites?''', 'NLT'),
(5, 9, 3, 'But the LORD your God will cross over ahead of you like a devouring fire to destroy them. He will subdue them so that you will quickly conquer them and drive them out, just as the LORD has promised.', 'NLT'),
(5, 9, 4, '"After the LORD your God has done this for you, don''t say to yourselves, `The LORD has given us this land because we are so righteous!'' No, it is because of the wickedness of the other nations that he is doing it.', 'NLT'),
(5, 9, 5, 'It is not at all because you are such righteous, upright people that you are about to occupy their land. The LORD your God will drive these nations out ahead of you only because of their wickedness, and to fulfill the oath he had sworn to your ancestors Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob.', 'NLT'),
(5, 9, 6, 'I will say it again: The LORD your God is not giving you this good land because you are righteous, for you are not--you are a stubborn people.', 'NLT'),
(5, 9, 7, '"Remember how angry you made the LORD your God out in the wilderness. From the day you left Egypt until now, you have constantly rebelled against him.', 'NLT'),
(5, 9, 8, 'Remember how angry you made the LORD at Mount Sinai, where he was ready to destroy you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 9, 9, 'That was when I was on the mountain receiving the tablets of stone inscribed with the covenant that the LORD had made with you. I was there for forty days and forty nights, and all that time I ate nothing and drank no water.', 'NLT'),
(5, 9, 10, 'The LORD gave me the covenant, the tablets on which God himself had written all the words he had spoken to you from the fire on the mountain.', 'NLT'),
(5, 9, 11, '"At the end of the forty days and nights, the LORD handed me the two stone tablets with the covenant inscribed on them.', 'NLT'),
(5, 9, 12, 'Then the LORD said to me, `Go down immediately because the people you led out of Egypt have become corrupt. They have already turned from the way I commanded them to live and have cast an idol for themselves from gold.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 9, 13, '"The LORD said to me, `I have been watching this people, and they are extremely stubborn.', 'NLT'),
(5, 9, 14, 'Leave me alone so I may destroy them and erase their name from under heaven. Then I will make a mighty nation of your descendants, a nation larger and more powerful than they are.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 9, 15, '"So I came down from the fiery mountain, holding in my hands the two stone tablets of the covenant.', 'NLT'),
(5, 9, 16, 'There below me I could see the gold calf you had made in your terrible sin against the LORD your God. How quickly you had turned from the path the LORD had commanded you to follow!', 'NLT'),
(5, 9, 17, 'So I raised the stone tablets and dashed them to the ground. I smashed them before your very eyes.', 'NLT'),
(5, 9, 18, 'Then for forty days and nights I lay prostrate before the LORD, neither eating bread nor drinking water. I did this because you had sinned by doing what the LORD hated, thus making him very angry.', 'NLT'),
(5, 9, 19, 'How I feared for you, for the LORD was ready to destroy you. But again he listened to me.', 'NLT'),
(5, 9, 20, 'The LORD was so angry with Aaron that he wanted to destroy him. But I prayed for Aaron, and the LORD spared him.', 'NLT'),
(5, 9, 21, 'I took your sin--the calf you had made--and I melted it in the fire and ground it into fine dust. I threw the dust into the stream that cascades down the mountain.', 'NLT'),
(5, 9, 22, '"You also made the LORD angry at Taberah, Massah, and Kibroth-hattaavah.', 'NLT'),
(5, 9, 23, 'And at Kadesh-barnea the LORD sent you out with this command: `Go up and take the land I have given you.'' But you rebelled against the command of the LORD your God and refused to trust him or obey him.', 'NLT'),
(5, 9, 24, 'Yes, you have been rebelling against the LORD as long as I have known you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 9, 25, '"That is why I fell down and lay before the LORD for forty days and nights when he was ready to destroy you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 9, 26, 'I prayed to the LORD and said, `O Sovereign LORD, do not destroy your own people. They are your special possession, redeemed from Egypt by your mighty power and glorious strength.', 'NLT'),
(5, 9, 27, 'Overlook the stubbornness and sin of these people, but remember instead your servants Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob.', 'NLT'),
(5, 9, 28, 'If you destroy these people, the Egyptians will say, "The LORD destroyed them because he wasn''t able to bring them to the land he had sworn to give them." Or they might say, "He destroyed them because he hated them; he brought them into the wilderness to slaughter them."', 'NLT'),
(5, 9, 29, 'But they are your people and your special possession, whom you brought from Egypt by your mighty power and glorious strength.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 10, 1, '"At that time the LORD said to me, `Prepare two stone tablets like the first ones, and make a sacred chest of wood to keep them in. Return to me on the mountain,', 'NLT'),
(5, 10, 2, 'and I will write on the tablets the same words that were on the ones you smashed. Then place the tablets in the sacred chest--the Ark of the Covenant.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 10, 3, '"So I made a chest of acacia wood and cut two stone tablets like the first two, and I took the tablets up the mountain.', 'NLT'),
(5, 10, 4, 'The LORD again wrote the terms of the covenant--the Ten Commandments--on them and gave them to me. They were the same words the LORD had spoken to you from the heart of the fire on the mountain as you were assembled below.', 'NLT'),
(5, 10, 5, 'Then I came down and placed the tablets in the Ark of the Covenant, which I had made, just as the LORD commanded me. And the tablets are still there in the Ark.', 'NLT'),
(5, 10, 6, '"The people of Israel set out from the wells of the people of Jaakan and traveled to Moserah, where Aaron died and was buried. His son Eleazar became the high priest in his place.', 'NLT'),
(5, 10, 7, 'Then they journeyed to Gudgodah, and from there to Jotbathah, a land with brooks of water.', 'NLT'),
(5, 10, 8, 'At that time the LORD set apart the tribe of Levi to carry the Ark of the LORD''s covenant, to minister before the LORD, and to pronounce blessings in his name. These are still their duties.', 'NLT'),
(5, 10, 9, 'That is why the Levites have no share or inheritance reserved for them among the other Israelite tribes. The LORD himself is their inheritance, as the LORD your God told them.', 'NLT'),
(5, 10, 10, '"As I said before, I stayed on the mountain in the LORD''s presence for forty days and nights, as I had done the first time. And once again the LORD yielded to my pleas and didn''t destroy you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 10, 11, 'But the LORD said to me, `Get up and lead the people into the land I swore to give their ancestors, so they may take possession of it.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 10, 12, '"And now, Israel, what does the LORD your God require of you? He requires you to fear him, to live according to his will, to love and worship him with all your heart and soul,', 'NLT'),
(5, 10, 13, 'and to obey the LORD''s commands and laws that I am giving you today for your own good.', 'NLT'),
(5, 10, 14, 'The highest heavens and the earth and everything in it all belong to the LORD your God.', 'NLT'),
(5, 10, 15, 'Yet the LORD chose your ancestors as the objects of his love. And he chose you, their descendants, above every other nation, as is evident today.', 'NLT'),
(5, 10, 16, 'Therefore, cleanse your sinful hearts and stop being stubborn.', 'NLT'),
(5, 10, 17, '"The LORD your God is the God of gods and Lord of lords. He is the great God, mighty and awesome, who shows no partiality and takes no bribes.', 'NLT'),
(5, 10, 18, 'He gives justice to orphans and widows. He shows love to the foreigners living among you and gives them food and clothing.', 'NLT'),
(5, 10, 19, 'You, too, must show love to foreigners, for you yourselves were once foreigners in the land of Egypt.', 'NLT'),
(5, 10, 20, 'You must fear the LORD your God and worship him and cling to him. Your oaths must be in his name alone.', 'NLT'),
(5, 10, 21, 'He is your God, the one who is worthy of your praise, the one who has done mighty miracles that you yourselves have seen.', 'NLT'),
(5, 10, 22, 'When your ancestors went down into Egypt, there were only seventy of them. But now the LORD your God has made you as numerous as the stars in the sky!', 'NLT'),
(5, 11, 1, '"You must love the LORD your God and obey all his requirements, laws, regulations, and commands.', 'NLT'),
(5, 11, 2, 'Listen! I am not talking now to your children, who have never experienced the discipline of the LORD your God or seen his greatness and awesome power.', 'NLT'),
(5, 11, 3, 'They weren''t there to see the miraculous signs and wonders he performed in Egypt against Pharaoh and all his land.', 'NLT'),
(5, 11, 4, 'They didn''t see what the LORD did to the armies of Egypt and to their horses and chariots--how he drowned them in the Red Sea as they were chasing you, and how he has kept them devastated to this very day!', 'NLT'),
(5, 11, 5, 'They didn''t see how the LORD cared for you in the wilderness until you arrived here.', 'NLT'),
(5, 11, 6, 'They weren''t there to see what he did to Dathan and Abiram (the sons of Eliab, a descendant of Reuben) when the earth opened up and swallowed them, along with their households and tents and every living thing that belonged to them.', 'NLT'),
(5, 11, 7, 'But you have seen all the LORD''s mighty deeds with your own eyes!', 'NLT'),
(5, 11, 8, '"Therefore, be careful to obey every command I am giving you today, so you may have strength to go in and occupy the land you are about to enter.', 'NLT'),
(5, 11, 9, 'If you obey, you will enjoy a long life in the land the LORD swore to give to your ancestors and to you, their descendants--a land flowing with milk and honey!', 'NLT'),
(5, 11, 10, 'For the land you are about to enter and occupy is not like the land of Egypt from which you came, where you planted your seed and dug out irrigation ditches with your foot as in a vegetable garden.', 'NLT'),
(5, 11, 11, 'It is a land of hills and valleys with plenty of rain--', 'NLT'),
(5, 11, 12, 'a land that the LORD your God cares for. He watches over it day after day throughout the year!', 'NLT'),
(5, 11, 13, '"If you carefully obey all the commands I am giving you today, and if you love the LORD your God with all your heart and soul, and if you worship him,', 'NLT'),
(5, 11, 14, 'then he will send the rains in their proper seasons so you can harvest crops of grain, grapes for wine, and olives for oil.', 'NLT'),
(5, 11, 15, 'He will give you lush pastureland for your cattle to graze in, and you yourselves will have plenty to eat.', 'NLT'),
(5, 11, 16, '"But do not let your heart turn away from the LORD to worship other gods.', 'NLT'),
(5, 11, 17, 'If you do, the LORD''s anger will burn against you. He will shut up the sky and hold back the rain, and your harvests will fail. Then you will quickly die in that good land the LORD is now giving you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 11, 18, 'So commit yourselves completely to these words of mine. Tie them to your hands as a reminder, and wear them on your forehead.', 'NLT'),
(5, 11, 19, 'Teach them to your children. Talk about them when you are at home and when you are away on a journey, when you are lying down and when you are getting up again.', 'NLT'),
(5, 11, 20, 'Write them on the doorposts of your house and on your gates,', 'NLT'),
(5, 11, 21, 'so that as long as the sky remains above the earth, you and your children may flourish in the land the LORD swore to give your ancestors.', 'NLT'),
(5, 11, 22, '"Be careful to obey all the commands I give you; show love to the LORD your God by walking in his ways and clinging to him.', 'NLT'),
(5, 11, 23, 'Then the LORD will drive out all the nations in your land, though they are much greater and stronger than you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 11, 24, 'Wherever you set your feet, the land will be yours. Your frontiers will stretch from the wilderness in the south to Lebanon in the north, and from the Euphrates River in the east to the Mediterranean Sea in the west.', 'NLT'),
(5, 11, 25, 'No one will be able to stand against you, for the LORD your God will send fear and dread ahead of you, as he promised you, wherever you go in the whole land.', 'NLT'),
(5, 11, 26, '"Today I am giving you the choice between a blessing and a curse!', 'NLT'),
(5, 11, 27, 'You will be blessed if you obey the commands of the LORD your God that I am giving you today.', 'NLT'),
(5, 11, 28, 'You will receive a curse if you reject the commands of the LORD your God and turn from his way by worshiping foreign gods.', 'NLT'),
(5, 11, 29, '"When the LORD your God brings you into the land to possess it, you must pronounce a blessing from Mount Gerizim and a curse from Mount Ebal.', 'NLT'),
(5, 11, 30, '(These two mountains are west of the Jordan River in the land of the Canaanites who live in the Jordan Valley, near the town of Gilgal. They are located toward the west, not far from the oaks of Moreh.)', 'NLT'),
(5, 11, 31, 'For you are about to cross the Jordan to occupy the land the LORD your God is giving you. When you are living in that land,', 'NLT'),
(5, 11, 32, 'you must be careful to obey all the laws and regulations I am giving you today.', 'NLT'),
(5, 12, 1, '"These are the laws and regulations you must obey as long as you live in the land the LORD, the God of your ancestors, is giving you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 12, 2, '"When you drive out the nations that live there, you must destroy all the places where they worship their gods--high on the mountains, up on the hills, and under every green tree.', 'NLT'),
(5, 12, 3, 'Break down their altars and smash their sacred pillars. Burn their Asherah poles and cut down their carved idols. Erase the names of their gods from those places!', 'NLT'),
(5, 12, 4, '"Do not worship the LORD your God in the way these pagan peoples worship their gods.', 'NLT'),
(5, 12, 5, 'Rather, you must seek the LORD your God at the place he himself will choose from among all the tribes for his name to be honored.', 'NLT'),
(5, 12, 6, 'There you will bring to the LORD your burnt offerings, your sacrifices, your tithes, your special gifts, your offerings to fulfill a vow, your freewill offerings, and your offerings of the firstborn animals of your flocks and herds.', 'NLT'),
(5, 12, 7, 'There you and your families will feast in the presence of the LORD your God, and you will rejoice in all you have accomplished because the LORD your God has blessed you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 12, 8, '"Today you are doing whatever you please, but that is not how it will be', 'NLT'),
(5, 12, 9, 'when you arrive in the place of rest the LORD your God is giving you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 12, 10, 'You will soon cross the Jordan River and live in the land the LORD your God is giving you as a special possession. When he gives you rest and security from all your enemies,', 'NLT'),
(5, 12, 11, 'you must bring everything I command you--your burnt offerings, your sacrifices, your tithes, your special gifts, and your offerings to fulfill a vow--to the place the LORD your God will choose for his name to be honored.', 'NLT'),
(5, 12, 12, 'You must celebrate there with your sons and daughters and all your servants in the presence of the LORD your God. And remember the Levites who live in your towns, for they will have no inheritance of land as their own.', 'NLT'),
(5, 12, 13, 'Be careful not to sacrifice your burnt offerings just anywhere.', 'NLT'),
(5, 12, 14, 'You may do so only at the place the LORD will choose within one of your tribal territories. There you must offer your burnt offerings and do everything I command you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 12, 15, '"But you may butcher animals for meat in any town, wherever you want, just as you do now with gazelle and deer. You may eat as many animals as the LORD your God gives you. All of you, whether ceremonially clean or unclean, may eat that meat.', 'NLT'),
(5, 12, 16, 'The only restriction is that you are not to eat the blood. You must pour it out on the ground like water.', 'NLT'),
(5, 12, 17, '"But your offerings must not be eaten at home--neither the tithe of your grain and new wine and olive oil, nor the firstborn of your flocks and herds, nor an offering to fulfill a vow, nor your freewill offerings, nor your special gifts.', 'NLT'),
(5, 12, 18, 'You must eat these in the presence of the LORD your God at the place he will choose. Eat them there with your children, your servants, and the Levites who live in your towns, celebrating in the presence of the LORD your God in all you do.', 'NLT'),
(5, 12, 19, 'Be very careful never to forget the Levites as long as you live in your land.', 'NLT'),
(5, 12, 20, '"When the LORD your God enlarges your territory as he has promised, you may eat meat whenever you want.', 'NLT'),
(5, 12, 21, 'It might happen that the place the LORD your God chooses for his name to be honored is a long way from your home. If so, you may butcher any of the cattle or sheep the LORD has given you, and you may eat the meat at your home as I have commanded you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 12, 22, 'Anyone, whether ceremonially clean or unclean, may eat that meat, just as you do now with gazelle and deer.', 'NLT'),
(5, 12, 23, 'The only restriction is never to eat the blood, for the blood is the life, and you must not eat the life with the meat.', 'NLT'),
(5, 12, 24, 'Instead, pour out the blood on the ground like water.', 'NLT'),
(5, 12, 25, 'Do not eat the blood; then all will go well with you and your children, because you will be doing what pleases the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(5, 12, 26, 'Take your sacred gifts and your offerings given to fulfill a vow to the place the LORD chooses to dwell.', 'NLT'),
(5, 12, 27, 'You must offer the meat and blood of your burnt offerings on the altar of the LORD your God. The blood of your other sacrifices must be poured out beside the altar of the LORD your God, but you may eat the meat.', 'NLT'),
(5, 12, 28, 'Be careful to obey all my commands so that all will go well with you and your children, because you will be doing what pleases the LORD your God.', 'NLT'),
(5, 12, 29, '"When the LORD your God destroys the nations and you drive them out and occupy their land,', 'NLT'),
(5, 12, 30, 'do not be trapped into following their example in worshiping their gods. Do not say, `How do these nations worship their gods? I want to follow their example.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 12, 31, 'You must not do this to the LORD your God. These nations have committed many detestable acts that the LORD hates, all in the name of their gods. They have even burned their sons and daughters as sacrifices to their gods.', 'NLT'),
(5, 12, 32, 'Carefully obey all the commands I give you. Do not add to them or subtract from them.', 'NLT'),
(5, 13, 1, '"Suppose there are prophets among you, or those who have dreams about the future, and they promise you signs or miracles,', 'NLT'),
(5, 13, 2, 'and the predicted signs or miracles take place. If the prophets then say, `Come, let us worship the gods of foreign nations,''', 'NLT'),
(5, 13, 3, 'do not listen to them. The LORD your God is testing you to see if you love him with all your heart and soul.', 'NLT'),
(5, 13, 4, 'Serve only the LORD your God and fear him alone. Obey his commands, listen to his voice, and cling to him.', 'NLT'),
(5, 13, 5, 'The false prophets or dreamers who try to lead you astray must be put to death, for they encourage rebellion against the LORD your God, who brought you out of slavery in the land of Egypt. Since they try to keep you from following the LORD your God, you must execute them to remove the evil from among you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 13, 6, '"Suppose your brother, son, daughter, beloved wife, or closest friend comes to you secretly and says, `Let us go worship other gods''--gods that neither you nor your ancestors have known.', 'NLT'),
(5, 13, 7, 'They might suggest that you worship the gods of peoples who live nearby or who come from the ends of the earth.', 'NLT'),
(5, 13, 8, 'If they do this, do not give in or listen, and have no pity. Do not spare or protect them.', 'NLT'),
(5, 13, 9, 'You must put them to death! You must be the one to initiate the execution; then all the people must join in.', 'NLT'),
(5, 13, 10, 'Stone the guilty ones to death because they have tried to draw you away from the LORD your God, who rescued you from the land of Egypt, the place of slavery.', 'NLT'),
(5, 13, 11, 'Then all Israel will hear about it and be afraid, and such wickedness will never again be done among you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 13, 12, '"Suppose you hear in one of the towns the LORD your God is giving you', 'NLT'),
(5, 13, 13, 'that some worthless rabble among you have led their fellow citizens astray by encouraging them to worship foreign gods.', 'NLT'),
(5, 13, 14, 'In such cases, you must examine the facts carefully. If you find it is true and can prove that such a detestable act has occurred among you,', 'NLT'),
(5, 13, 15, 'you must attack that town and completely destroy all its inhabitants, as well as all the livestock.', 'NLT'),
(5, 13, 16, 'Then you must pile all the plunder in the middle of the street and burn it. Put the entire town to the torch as a burnt offering to the LORD your God. That town must remain a ruin forever; it may never be rebuilt.', 'NLT'),
(5, 13, 17, 'Keep none of the plunder that has been set apart for destruction. Then the LORD will turn from his fierce anger and be merciful to you. He will have compassion on you and make you a great nation, just as he solemnly promised your ancestors.', 'NLT'),
(5, 13, 18, '"The LORD your God will be merciful only if you obey him and keep all the commands I am giving you today, doing what is pleasing to him.', 'NLT'),
(5, 14, 1, '"Since you are the people of the LORD your God, never cut yourselves or shave the hair above your foreheads for the sake of the dead.', 'NLT'),
(5, 14, 2, 'You have been set apart as holy to the LORD your God, and he has chosen you to be his own special treasure from all the nations of the earth.', 'NLT'),
(5, 14, 3, '"You must not eat animals that are ceremonially unclean.', 'NLT'),
(5, 14, 4, 'These are the animals you may eat: the ox, the sheep, the goat,', 'NLT'),
(5, 14, 5, 'the deer, the gazelle, the roebuck, the wild goat, the ibex, the antelope, and the mountain sheep.', 'NLT'),
(5, 14, 6, '"Any animal that has split hooves and chews the cud may be eaten,', 'NLT'),
(5, 14, 7, 'but if the animal doesn''t have both, it may not be eaten. So you may not eat the camel, the hare, or the rock badger. They chew the cud but do not have split hooves.', 'NLT'),
(5, 14, 8, 'And the pig may not be eaten, for though it has split hooves, it does not chew the cud. All these animals are ceremonially unclean for you. You may not eat or even touch the dead bodies of such animals.', 'NLT'),
(5, 14, 9, '"As for marine animals, you may eat whatever has both fins and scales.', 'NLT'),
(5, 14, 10, 'You may not, however, eat marine animals that do not have both fins and scales. They are ceremonially unclean for you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 14, 11, '"You may eat any bird that is ceremonially clean.', 'NLT'),
(5, 14, 12, 'These are the birds you may not eat: the eagle, the vulture, the osprey,', 'NLT'),
(5, 14, 13, 'the buzzard, kites of all kinds,', 'NLT'),
(5, 14, 14, 'ravens of all kinds,', 'NLT'),
(5, 14, 15, 'the ostrich, the nighthawk, the seagull, hawks of all kinds,', 'NLT'),
(5, 14, 16, 'the little owl, the great owl, the white owl,', 'NLT'),
(5, 14, 17, 'the pelican, the carrion vulture, the cormorant,', 'NLT'),
(5, 14, 18, 'the stork, herons of all kinds, the hoopoe, and the bat.', 'NLT'),
(5, 14, 19, '"All flying insects are ceremonially unclean for you and may not be eaten.', 'NLT'),
(5, 14, 20, 'But you may eat any winged creature that is ceremonially clean.', 'NLT'),
(5, 14, 21, '"Do not eat anything that has died a natural death. You may give it to a foreigner living among you, or you may sell it to a foreigner. But do not eat it yourselves, for you are set apart as holy to the LORD your God. "Do not boil a young goat in its mother''s milk.', 'NLT'),
(5, 14, 22, '"You must set aside a tithe of your crops--one-tenth of all the crops you harvest each year.', 'NLT'),
(5, 14, 23, 'Bring this tithe to the place the LORD your God chooses for his name to be honored, and eat it there in his presence. This applies to your tithes of grain, new wine, olive oil, and the firstborn males of your flocks and herds. The purpose of tithing is to teach you always to fear the LORD your God.', 'NLT'),
(5, 14, 24, 'Now the place the LORD your God chooses for his name to be honored might be a long way from your home.', 'NLT'),
(5, 14, 25, 'If so, you may sell the tithe portion of your crops and herds and take the money to the place the LORD your God chooses.', 'NLT'),
(5, 14, 26, 'When you arrive, use the money to buy anything you want--an ox, a sheep, some wine, or beer. Then feast there in the presence of the LORD your God and celebrate with your household.', 'NLT'),
(5, 14, 27, 'And do not forget the Levites in your community, for they have no inheritance as you do.', 'NLT'),
(5, 14, 28, '"At the end of every third year bring the tithe of all your crops and store it in the nearest town.', 'NLT'),
(5, 14, 29, 'Give it to the Levites, who have no inheritance among you, as well as to the foreigners living among you, the orphans, and the widows in your towns, so they can eat and be satisfied. Then the LORD your God will bless you in all your work.', 'NLT'),
(5, 15, 1, '"At the end of every seventh year you must cancel your debts.', 'NLT'),
(5, 15, 2, 'This is how it must be done. Creditors must cancel the loans they have made to their fellow Israelites. They must not demand payment from their neighbors or relatives, for the LORD''s time of release has arrived.', 'NLT'),
(5, 15, 3, 'This release from debt, however, applies only to your fellow Israelites--not to the foreigners living among you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 15, 4, 'There should be no poor among you, for the LORD your God will greatly bless you in the land he is giving you as a special possession.', 'NLT'),
(5, 15, 5, 'You will receive this blessing if you carefully obey the commands of the LORD your God that I am giving you today.', 'NLT'),
(5, 15, 6, 'The LORD your God will bless you as he has promised. You will lend money to many nations but will never need to borrow! You will rule many nations, but they will not rule over you!', 'NLT'),
(5, 15, 7, '"But if there are any poor people in your towns when you arrive in the land the LORD your God is giving you, do not be hard-hearted or tightfisted toward them.', 'NLT'),
(5, 15, 8, 'Instead, be generous and lend them whatever they need.', 'NLT'),
(5, 15, 9, 'Do not be mean-spirited and refuse someone a loan because the year of release is close at hand. If you refuse to make the loan and the needy person cries out to the LORD, you will be considered guilty of sin.', 'NLT'),
(5, 15, 10, 'Give freely without begrudging it, and the LORD your God will bless you in everything you do.', 'NLT'),
(5, 15, 11, 'There will always be some among you who are poor. That is why I am commanding you to share your resources freely with the poor and with other Israelites in need.', 'NLT'),
(5, 15, 12, '"If an Israelite man or woman voluntarily becomes your servant and serves you for six years, in the seventh year you must set that servant free.', 'NLT'),
(5, 15, 13, '"When you release a male servant, do not send him away empty-handed.', 'NLT'),
(5, 15, 14, 'Give him a generous farewell gift from your flock, your threshing floor, and your winepress. Share with him some of the bounty with which the LORD your God has blessed you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 15, 15, 'Remember that you were slaves in the land of Egypt and the LORD your God redeemed you! That is why I am giving you this command.', 'NLT'),
(5, 15, 16, 'But suppose your servant says, `I will not leave you,'' because he loves you and your family, and he is well off with you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 15, 17, 'In that case, take an awl and push it through his earlobe into the door. After that, he will be your servant for life. "You must do the same for your female servants.', 'NLT'),
(5, 15, 18, '"Do not consider it a hardship when you release your servants. Remember that for six years they have given you the services worth double the wages of hired workers, and the LORD your God will bless you in all you do.', 'NLT'),
(5, 15, 19, '"You must set aside for the LORD your God all the firstborn males from your flocks and herds. Do not use the firstborn of your herds to work your fields, and do not shear the firstborn of your flocks.', 'NLT'),
(5, 15, 20, 'Instead, you and your family must eat these animals in the presence of the LORD your God each year at the place he chooses.', 'NLT'),
(5, 15, 21, 'But if this firstborn animal has any defect, such as being lame or blind, or if anything else is wrong with it, you must not sacrifice it to the LORD your God.', 'NLT'),
(5, 15, 22, 'Instead, use it for food for your family at home. Anyone may eat it, whether ceremonially clean or unclean, just as anyone may eat a gazelle or deer.', 'NLT'),
(5, 15, 23, 'But do not eat the blood. You must pour it out on the ground like water.', 'NLT'),
(5, 16, 1, '"In honor of the LORD your God, always celebrate the Passover at the proper time in early spring, for that was when the LORD your God brought you out of Egypt by night.', 'NLT'),
(5, 16, 2, 'Your Passover sacrifice may be from either the flock or the herd, and it must be sacrificed to the LORD your God at the place he chooses for his name to be honored.', 'NLT'),
(5, 16, 3, 'Eat it with bread made without yeast. For seven days eat only bread made without yeast, as you did when you escaped from Egypt in such a hurry. Eat this bread--the bread of suffering--so that you will remember the day you departed from Egypt as long as you live.', 'NLT'),
(5, 16, 4, 'Let no yeast be found in any house throughout your land for seven days. And do not let any of the meat of the Passover lamb remain until the next morning.', 'NLT'),
(5, 16, 5, '"The Passover must not be eaten in the towns that the LORD your God is giving you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 16, 6, 'It must be offered at the place the LORD your God will choose for his name to be honored. Sacrifice it there as the sun goes down on the anniversary of your exodus from Egypt.', 'NLT'),
(5, 16, 7, 'Roast the lamb and eat it in the place the LORD your God chooses. Then go back to your tents the next morning.', 'NLT'),
(5, 16, 8, 'For the next six days you may not eat bread made with yeast. On the seventh day the people must assemble before the LORD your God, and no work may be done on that day.', 'NLT'),
(5, 16, 9, '"Count off seven weeks from the beginning of your grain harvest.', 'NLT'),
(5, 16, 10, 'Then you must celebrate the Festival of Harvest to honor the LORD your God. Bring him a freewill offering in proportion to the blessings you have received from him.', 'NLT'),
(5, 16, 11, 'It is a time to celebrate before the LORD your God at the place he chooses for his name to be honored. Celebrate with your whole family, all your servants, the Levites from your towns, and the foreigners, orphans, and widows who live among you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 16, 12, 'Remember that you were slaves in Egypt, so be careful to obey all these laws.', 'NLT'),
(5, 16, 13, '"Another celebration, the Festival of Shelters, must be observed for seven days at the end of the harvest season, after the grain has been threshed and the grapes have been pressed.', 'NLT'),
(5, 16, 14, 'This festival will be a happy time of rejoicing with your family, your servants, and with the Levites, foreigners, orphans, and widows from your towns.', 'NLT'),
(5, 16, 15, 'For seven days celebrate this festival to honor the LORD your God at the place he chooses, for it is the LORD your God who gives you bountiful harvests and blesses all your work. This festival will be a time of great joy for all.', 'NLT'),
(5, 16, 16, '"Each year every man in Israel must celebrate these three festivals: the Festival of Unleavened Bread, the Festival of Harvest, and the Festival of Shelters. They must appear before the LORD your God at the place he chooses on each of these occasions, and they must bring a gift to the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(5, 16, 17, 'All must give as they are able, according to the blessings given to them by the LORD your God.', 'NLT'),
(5, 16, 18, '"Appoint judges and officials for each of your tribes in all the towns the LORD your God is giving you. They will judge the people fairly throughout the land.', 'NLT'),
(5, 16, 19, 'You must never twist justice or show partiality. Never accept a bribe, for bribes blind the eyes of the wise and corrupt the decisions of the godly.', 'NLT'),
(5, 16, 20, 'Let true justice prevail, so you may live and occupy the land that the LORD your God is giving you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 16, 21, '"You must never set up an Asherah pole beside the altar of the LORD your God.', 'NLT'),
(5, 16, 22, 'And never set up sacred pillars for worship, for the LORD your God hates them.', 'NLT'),
(5, 17, 1, '"Never sacrifice a sick or defective ox or sheep to the LORD your God, for he detests such gifts.', 'NLT'),
(5, 17, 2, '"Suppose a man or woman among you, in one of your towns that the LORD your God is giving you, has done evil in the sight of the LORD your God and has violated the covenant', 'NLT'),
(5, 17, 3, 'by serving other gods or by worshiping the sun, the moon, or any of the forces of heaven, which I have strictly forbidden.', 'NLT'),
(5, 17, 4, 'When you hear about it, investigate the matter thoroughly. If it is true that this detestable thing has been done in Israel,', 'NLT'),
(5, 17, 5, 'then that man or woman must be taken to the gates of the town and stoned to death.', 'NLT'),
(5, 17, 6, 'But never put a person to death on the testimony of only one witness. There must always be at least two or three witnesses.', 'NLT'),
(5, 17, 7, 'The witnesses must throw the first stones, and then all the people will join in. In this way, you will purge all evil from among you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 17, 8, '"Suppose a case arises in a local court that is too hard for you to decide--for instance, whether someone is guilty of murder or only of manslaughter, or a difficult lawsuit, or a case involving different kinds of assault. Take such cases to the place the LORD your God will choose,', 'NLT'),
(5, 17, 9, 'where the Levitical priests and the judge on duty will hear the case and decide what to do.', 'NLT'),
(5, 17, 10, 'The decision they make at the place the LORD chooses will always stand. You must do exactly what they say.', 'NLT'),
(5, 17, 11, 'After they have interpreted the law and reached a verdict, the sentence they impose must be fully executed; do not modify it in any way.', 'NLT'),
(5, 17, 12, 'Anyone arrogant enough to reject the verdict of the judge or of the priest who represents the LORD your God must be put to death. Such evil must be purged from Israel.', 'NLT'),
(5, 17, 13, 'Then everyone will hear about it and be afraid to act so arrogantly.', 'NLT'),
(5, 17, 14, '"You will soon arrive in the land the LORD your God is giving you, and you will conquer it and settle there. Then you may begin to think, `We ought to have a king like the other nations around us.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 17, 15, 'If this happens, be sure that you select as king the man the LORD your God chooses. You must appoint a fellow Israelite, not a foreigner.', 'NLT'),
(5, 17, 16, 'The king must not build up a large stable of horses for himself, and he must never send his people to Egypt to buy horses there, for the LORD has told you, `You must never return to Egypt.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 17, 17, 'The king must not take many wives for himself, because they will lead him away from the LORD. And he must not accumulate vast amounts of wealth in silver and gold for himself.', 'NLT'),
(5, 17, 18, '"When he sits on the throne as king, he must copy these laws on a scroll for himself in the presence of the Levitical priests.', 'NLT'),
(5, 17, 19, 'He must always keep this copy of the law with him and read it daily as long as he lives. That way he will learn to fear the LORD his God by obeying all the terms of this law.', 'NLT'),
(5, 17, 20, 'This regular reading will prevent him from becoming proud and acting as if he is above his fellow citizens. It will also prevent him from turning away from these commands in the smallest way. This will ensure that he and his descendants will reign for many generations in Israel.', 'NLT'),
(5, 18, 1, '"Remember that the Levitical priests and the rest of the tribe of Levi will not be given an inheritance of land like the other tribes in Israel. Instead, the priests and Levites will eat from the offerings given to the LORD by fire, for that is their inheritance.', 'NLT'),
(5, 18, 2, 'They will have no inheritance of their own among the Israelites. The LORD himself is their inheritance, just as he promised them.', 'NLT'),
(5, 18, 3, '"These are the parts the priests may claim as their share from the oxen and sheep that the people bring as offerings: the shoulder, the cheeks, and the stomach.', 'NLT'),
(5, 18, 4, 'You must also give to the priests the first share of the grain, the new wine, the olive oil, and the wool at shearing time.', 'NLT'),
(5, 18, 5, 'For the LORD your God chose the tribe of Levi out of all your tribes to minister in the LORD''s name forever.', 'NLT'),
(5, 18, 6, '"Any Levite who so desires may come from any town in Israel, from wherever he is living, to the place the LORD chooses.', 'NLT'),
(5, 18, 7, 'He may minister there in the name of the LORD his God, just like his fellow Levites who are serving the LORD there.', 'NLT'),
(5, 18, 8, 'He may eat his share of the sacrifices and offerings, even if he has a private source of income.', 'NLT'),
(5, 18, 9, '"When you arrive in the land the LORD your God is giving you, be very careful not to imitate the detestable customs of the nations living there.', 'NLT'),
(5, 18, 10, 'For example, never sacrifice your son or daughter as a burnt offering. And do not let your people practice fortune-telling or sorcery, or allow them to interpret omens, or engage in witchcraft,', 'NLT'),
(5, 18, 11, 'or cast spells, or function as mediums or psychics, or call forth the spirits of the dead.', 'NLT'),
(5, 18, 12, 'Anyone who does these things is an object of horror and disgust to the LORD. It is because the other nations have done these things that the LORD your God will drive them out ahead of you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 18, 13, 'You must be blameless before the LORD your God.', 'NLT'),
(5, 18, 14, 'The people you are about to displace consult with sorcerers and fortune-tellers, but the LORD your God forbids you to do such things.', 'NLT'),
(5, 18, 15, '"The LORD your God will raise up for you a prophet like me from among your fellow Israelites, and you must listen to that prophet.', 'NLT'),
(5, 18, 16, 'For this is what you yourselves requested of the LORD your God when you were assembled at Mount Sinai. You begged that you might never again have to listen to the voice of the LORD your God or see this blazing fire for fear you would die.', 'NLT'),
(5, 18, 17, '"Then the LORD said to me, `Fine, I will do as they have requested.', 'NLT'),
(5, 18, 18, 'I will raise up a prophet like you from among their fellow Israelites. I will tell that prophet what to say, and he will tell the people everything I command him.', 'NLT'),
(5, 18, 19, 'I will personally deal with anyone who will not listen to the messages the prophet proclaims on my behalf.', 'NLT'),
(5, 18, 20, 'But any prophet who claims to give a message from another god or who falsely claims to speak for me must die.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 18, 21, 'You may wonder, `How will we know whether the prophecy is from the LORD or not?''', 'NLT'),
(5, 18, 22, 'If the prophet predicts something in the LORD''s name and it does not happen, the LORD did not give the message. That prophet has spoken on his own and need not be feared.', 'NLT'),
(5, 19, 1, '"The LORD your God will soon destroy the nations whose land he is giving you, and you will displace them and settle in their towns and homes.', 'NLT'),
(5, 19, 2, 'Then you must set apart three cities of refuge in the land the LORD your God is giving you to occupy.', 'NLT'),
(5, 19, 3, 'Divide the land the LORD your God is giving you into three districts, with one of these cities in each district. Keep the roads to these cities in good repair so that anyone who has killed someone can flee there for safety.', 'NLT'),
(5, 19, 4, '"If someone accidentally kills a neighbor without harboring any previous hatred, the slayer may flee to any of these cities and be safe.', 'NLT'),
(5, 19, 5, 'For example, suppose someone goes into the forest with a neighbor to cut wood. And suppose one of them swings an ax and the ax head flies off the handle, killing the other person. In such cases, the slayer could flee to one of the cities of refuge and be safe.', 'NLT'),
(5, 19, 6, 'If the distance to the nearest city of refuge was too far, an enraged avenger might be able to chase down and kill the person who caused the death. The slayer would die, even though there was no death sentence and the first death had been an accident.', 'NLT'),
(5, 19, 7, 'That is why I am commanding you to set aside three cities of refuge.', 'NLT'),
(5, 19, 8, '"If the LORD your God enlarges your territory, as he solemnly promised your ancestors, and gives you all the land he promised them,', 'NLT'),
(5, 19, 9, 'you must designate three additional cities of refuge. (He will give you this land if you obey all the commands I have given you--if you always love the LORD your God and walk in his ways.)', 'NLT'),
(5, 19, 10, 'That way you will prevent the death of innocent people in the land the LORD your God is giving you as a special possession, and you will not be held responsible for murder.', 'NLT'),
(5, 19, 11, '"But suppose someone hates a neighbor and deliberately ambushes and murders that neighbor and then escapes to one of the cities of refuge.', 'NLT'),
(5, 19, 12, 'In that case, the leaders of the murderer''s hometown must have the murderer brought back from the city of refuge and handed over to the dead person''s avenger to be killed.', 'NLT'),
(5, 19, 13, 'Do not feel sorry for that murderer! Purge the guilt of murder from Israel so all may go well with you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 19, 14, '"When you arrive in the land the LORD your God is giving you as a special possession, never steal someone''s land by moving the boundary markers your ancestors set up to mark their property.', 'NLT'),
(5, 19, 15, '"Never convict anyone of a crime on the testimony of just one witness. The facts of the case must be established by the testimony of two or three witnesses.', 'NLT'),
(5, 19, 16, 'If a malicious witness comes forward and accuses someone of a crime,', 'NLT'),
(5, 19, 17, 'then both the accuser and accused must appear before the priests and judges who are on duty before the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(5, 19, 18, 'They must be closely questioned, and if the accuser is found to be lying,', 'NLT'),
(5, 19, 19, 'the accuser will receive the punishment intended for the accused. In this way, you will cleanse such evil from among you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 19, 20, 'Those who hear about it will be afraid to do such an evil thing again.', 'NLT'),
(5, 19, 21, 'You must never show pity! Your rule should be life for life, eye for eye, tooth for tooth, hand for hand, foot for foot.', 'NLT'),
(5, 20, 1, '"When you go out to fight your enemies and you face horses and chariots and an army greater than your own, do not be afraid. The LORD your God, who brought you safely out of Egypt, is with you!', 'NLT'),
(5, 20, 2, 'Before you go into battle, the priest will come forward to speak with the troops.', 'NLT'),
(5, 20, 3, 'He will say, `Listen to me, all you men of Israel! Do not be afraid as you go out to fight today! Do not lose heart or panic.', 'NLT'),
(5, 20, 4, 'For the LORD your God is going with you! He will fight for you against your enemies, and he will give you victory!''', 'NLT'),
(5, 20, 5, '"Then the officers of the army will address the troops and say, `Has anyone just built a new house but not yet dedicated it? If so, go home! You might be killed in the battle, and someone else would dedicate your house!', 'NLT'),
(5, 20, 6, 'Has anyone just planted a vineyard but not yet eaten any of its fruit? If so, go home! You might die in battle, and someone else would eat from it!', 'NLT'),
(5, 20, 7, 'Has anyone just become engaged? Well, go home and get married! You might die in the battle, and someone else would marry your fiance.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 20, 8, 'Then the officers will also say, `Is anyone terrified? If you are, go home before you frighten anyone else.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 20, 9, 'When the officers have finished saying this to their troops, they will announce the names of the unit commanders.', 'NLT'),
(5, 20, 10, '"As you approach a town to attack it, first offer its people terms for peace.', 'NLT'),
(5, 20, 11, 'If they accept your terms and open the gates to you, then all the people inside will serve you in forced labor.', 'NLT'),
(5, 20, 12, 'But if they refuse to make peace and prepare to fight, you must attack the town.', 'NLT'),
(5, 20, 13, 'When the LORD your God hands it over to you, kill every man in the town.', 'NLT'),
(5, 20, 14, 'But you may keep for yourselves all the women, children, livestock, and other plunder. You may enjoy the spoils of your enemies that the LORD your God has given you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 20, 15, 'But these instructions apply only to distant towns, not to the towns of nations nearby.', 'NLT'),
(5, 20, 16, '"As for the towns of the nations the LORD your God is giving you as a special possession, destroy every living thing in them.', 'NLT'),
(5, 20, 17, 'You must completely destroy the Hittites, Amorites, Canaanites, Perizzites, Hivites, and Jebusites, just as the LORD your God has commanded you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 20, 18, 'This will keep the people of the land from teaching you their detestable customs in the worship of their gods, which would cause you to sin deeply against the LORD your God.', 'NLT'),
(5, 20, 19, '"When you are besieging a town and the war drags on, do not destroy the trees. Eat the fruit, but do not cut down the trees. They are not enemies that need to be attacked!', 'NLT'),
(5, 20, 20, 'But you may cut down trees that you know are not valuable for food. Use them to make the equipment you need to besiege the town until it falls.', 'NLT'),
(5, 21, 1, '"Suppose someone is found murdered in a field in the land the LORD your God is giving you, and you don''t know who committed the murder.', 'NLT'),
(5, 21, 2, 'In such cases, your leaders and judges must determine which town is nearest the body.', 'NLT'),
(5, 21, 3, 'Then the leaders of that town must select a young cow that has never been trained or yoked to a plow.', 'NLT'),
(5, 21, 4, 'They must lead it to a valley that is neither plowed nor planted with a stream running through it. There they must break the cow''s neck.', 'NLT'),
(5, 21, 5, 'The Levitical priests must go there also, for the LORD your God has chosen them to minister before him and to pronounce blessings in the LORD''s name. And they are to decide all lawsuits and punishments.', 'NLT'),
(5, 21, 6, '"The leaders of the town nearest the body must wash their hands over the young cow whose neck was broken.', 'NLT'),
(5, 21, 7, 'Then they must say, `Our hands did not shed this blood, nor did we see it happen.', 'NLT'),
(5, 21, 8, 'O LORD, forgive your people Israel whom you have redeemed. Do not charge your people Israel with the guilt of murdering an innocent person.'' Then they will be absolved of the guilt of this person''s blood.', 'NLT'),
(5, 21, 9, 'By following these instructions and doing what is right in the LORD''s sight, you will cleanse the guilt of murder from your community.', 'NLT'),
(5, 21, 10, '"Suppose you go to war against your enemies and the LORD your God hands them over to you and you take captives.', 'NLT'),
(5, 21, 11, 'And suppose you see among the captives a beautiful woman, and you are attracted to her and want to marry her.', 'NLT'),
(5, 21, 12, 'If this happens, you may take her to your home, where she must shave her head, cut her fingernails,', 'NLT'),
(5, 21, 13, 'and change all her clothes. Then she must remain in your home for a full month, mourning for her father and mother. After that you may marry her.', 'NLT'),
(5, 21, 14, 'But if you marry her and then decide you do not like her, you must let her go free. You may not sell her or treat her as a slave, for you have humiliated her.', 'NLT'),
(5, 21, 15, '"Suppose a man has two wives, but he loves one and not the other, and both have given him sons. And suppose the firstborn son is the son of the wife he does not love.', 'NLT'),
(5, 21, 16, 'When the man divides the inheritance, he may not give the larger inheritance to his younger son, the son of the wife he loves.', 'NLT'),
(5, 21, 17, 'He must give the customary double portion to his oldest son, who represents the strength of his father''s manhood and who owns the rights of the firstborn son, even though he is the son of the wife his father does not love.', 'NLT'),
(5, 21, 18, '"Suppose a man has a stubborn, rebellious son who will not obey his father or mother, even though they discipline him.', 'NLT'),
(5, 21, 19, 'In such cases, the father and mother must take the son before the leaders of the town.', 'NLT'),
(5, 21, 20, 'They must declare: `This son of ours is stubborn and rebellious and refuses to obey. He is a worthless drunkard.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 21, 21, 'Then all the men of the town must stone him to death. In this way, you will cleanse this evil from among you, and all Israel will hear about it and be afraid.', 'NLT'),
(5, 21, 22, '"If someone has committed a crime worthy of death and is executed and then hanged on a tree,', 'NLT'),
(5, 21, 23, 'the body must never remain on the tree overnight. You must bury the body that same day, for anyone hanging on a tree is cursed of God. Do not defile the land the LORD your God is giving you as a special possession.', 'NLT'),
(5, 22, 1, '"If you see your neighbor''s ox or sheep wandering away, don''t pretend not to see it. Take it back to its owner.', 'NLT'),
(5, 22, 2, 'If it does not belong to someone nearby or you don''t know who the owner is, keep it until the owner comes looking for it; then return it.', 'NLT'),
(5, 22, 3, 'Do the same if you find your neighbor''s donkey, clothing, or anything else your neighbor loses. Don''t pretend you did not see it.', 'NLT'),
(5, 22, 4, '"If you see your neighbor''s ox or donkey lying on the road, do not look the other way. Go and help your neighbor get it to its feet!', 'NLT'),
(5, 22, 5, '"A woman must not wear men''s clothing, and a man must not wear women''s clothing. The LORD your God detests people who do this.', 'NLT'),
(5, 22, 6, '"If you find a bird''s nest on the ground or in a tree and there are young ones or eggs in it with the mother sitting in the nest, do not take the mother with the young.', 'NLT'),
(5, 22, 7, 'You may take the young, but let the mother go, so you may prosper and enjoy a long life.', 'NLT'),
(5, 22, 8, '"Every new house you build must have a barrier around the edge of its flat rooftop. That way you will not bring the guilt of bloodshed on your household if someone falls from the roof.', 'NLT'),
(5, 22, 9, '"Do not plant any other crop between the rows of your vineyard. If you do, you are forbidden to use either the grapes from the vineyard or the produce of the other crop.', 'NLT'),
(5, 22, 10, '"Do not plow with an ox and a donkey harnessed together.', 'NLT'),
(5, 22, 11, '"Do not wear clothing made of wool and linen woven together.', 'NLT'),
(5, 22, 12, '"You must put tassels on the four corners of your cloaks.', 'NLT'),
(5, 22, 13, '"Suppose a man marries a woman and, after sleeping with her, changes his mind about her', 'NLT'),
(5, 22, 14, 'and falsely accuses her of having slept with another man. He might say, `I discovered she was not a virgin when I married her.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 22, 15, 'If the man does this, the woman''s father and mother must bring the proof of her virginity to the leaders of the town.', 'NLT'),
(5, 22, 16, 'Her father must tell them, `I gave my daughter to this man to be his wife, and now he has turned against her.', 'NLT'),
(5, 22, 17, 'He has accused her of shameful things, claiming that she was not a virgin when he married her. But here is the proof of my daughter''s virginity.'' Then they must spread the cloth before the judges.', 'NLT'),
(5, 22, 18, 'The judges must then punish the man.', 'NLT'),
(5, 22, 19, 'They will fine him one hundred pieces of silver, for he falsely accused a virgin of Israel. The payment will be made to the woman''s father. The woman will then remain the man''s wife, and he may never divorce her.', 'NLT'),
(5, 22, 20, '"But suppose the man''s accusations are true, and her virginity could not be proved.', 'NLT'),
(5, 22, 21, 'In such cases, the judges must take the girl to the door of her father''s home, and the men of the town will stone her to death. She has committed a disgraceful crime in Israel by being promiscuous while living in her parents'' home. Such evil must be cleansed from among you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 22, 22, '"If a man is discovered committing adultery, both he and the other man''s wife must be killed. In this way, the evil will be cleansed from Israel.', 'NLT'),
(5, 22, 23, '"Suppose a man meets a young woman, a virgin who is engaged to be married, and he has sexual intercourse with her. If this happens within a town,', 'NLT'),
(5, 22, 24, 'you must take both of them to the gates of the town and stone them to death. The woman is guilty because she did not scream for help. The man must die because he violated another man''s wife. In this way, you will cleanse the land of evil.', 'NLT'),
(5, 22, 25, '"But if the man meets the engaged woman out in the country, and he rapes her, then only the man should die.', 'NLT'),
(5, 22, 26, 'Do nothing to the young woman; she has committed no crime worthy of death. This case is similar to that of someone who attacks and murders a neighbor.', 'NLT'),
(5, 22, 27, 'Since the man raped her out in the country, it must be assumed that she screamed, but there was no one to rescue her.', 'NLT'),
(5, 22, 28, '"If a man is caught in the act of raping a young woman who is not engaged,', 'NLT'),
(5, 22, 29, 'he must pay fifty pieces of silver to her father. Then he must marry the young woman because he violated her, and he will never be allowed to divorce her.', 'NLT'),
(5, 22, 30, '"A man must not have intercourse with his father''s wife, for this would violate his father.', 'NLT'),
(5, 23, 1, '"If a man''s testicles are crushed or his penis is cut off, he may not be included in the assembly of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(5, 23, 2, '"Those of illegitimate birth and their descendants for ten generations may not be included in the assembly of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(5, 23, 3, '"No Ammonites or Moabites, or any of their descendants for ten generations, may be included in the assembly of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(5, 23, 4, 'These nations did not welcome you with food and water when you came out of Egypt. Instead, they tried to hire Balaam son of Beor from Pethor in Aram-naharaim to curse you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 23, 5, '(But the LORD your God would not listen to Balaam. He turned the intended curse into a blessing because the LORD your God loves you.)', 'NLT'),
(5, 23, 6, 'You must never, as long as you live, try to help the Ammonites or the Moabites in any way.', 'NLT'),
(5, 23, 7, '"Do not detest the Edomites or the Egyptians, because the Edomites are your relatives, and you lived as foreigners among the Egyptians.', 'NLT'),
(5, 23, 8, 'The third generation of Egyptians who came with you from Egypt may enter the assembly of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(5, 23, 9, '"When you go to war against your enemies, stay away from everything impure.', 'NLT'),
(5, 23, 10, '"Any man who becomes ceremonially defiled because of a nocturnal emission must leave the camp and stay away all day.', 'NLT'),
(5, 23, 11, 'Toward evening he must bathe himself, and at sunset he may return to the camp.', 'NLT'),
(5, 23, 12, '"Mark off an area outside the camp for a latrine.', 'NLT'),
(5, 23, 13, 'Each of you must have a spade as part of your equipment. Whenever you relieve yourself, you must dig a hole with the spade and cover the excrement.', 'NLT'),
(5, 23, 14, 'The camp must be holy, for the LORD your God moves around in your camp to protect you and to defeat your enemies. He must not see any shameful thing among you, or he might turn away from you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 23, 15, '"If slaves should escape from their masters and take refuge with you, do not force them to return.', 'NLT'),
(5, 23, 16, 'Let them live among you in whatever town they choose, and do not oppress them.', 'NLT'),
(5, 23, 17, '"No Israelite man or woman may ever become a temple prostitute.', 'NLT'),
(5, 23, 18, 'Do not bring to the house of the LORD your God any offering from the earnings of a prostitute, whether a man or a woman, for both are detestable to the LORD your God.', 'NLT'),
(5, 23, 19, '"Do not charge interest on the loans you make to a fellow Israelite, whether it is money, food, or anything else that may be loaned with interest.', 'NLT'),
(5, 23, 20, 'You may charge interest to foreigners, but not to Israelites, so the LORD your God may bless you in everything you do in the land you are about to enter and occupy.', 'NLT'),
(5, 23, 21, '"When you make a vow to the LORD your God, be prompt in doing whatever you promised him. For the LORD your God demands that you promptly fulfill all your vows. If you don''t, you will be guilty of sin.', 'NLT'),
(5, 23, 22, 'However, it is not a sin to refrain from making a vow.', 'NLT'),
(5, 23, 23, 'But once you have voluntarily made a vow, be careful to do as you have said, for you have made a vow to the LORD your God.', 'NLT'),
(5, 23, 24, '"You may eat your fill of grapes from your neighbor''s vineyard, but do not take any away in a basket.', 'NLT'),
(5, 23, 25, 'And you may pluck a few heads of your neighbor''s grain by hand, but you may not harvest it with a sickle.', 'NLT'),
(5, 24, 1, '"Suppose a man marries a woman but later discovers something about her that is shameful. So he writes her a letter of divorce, gives it to her, and sends her away.', 'NLT'),
(5, 24, 2, 'If she then leaves and marries another man', 'NLT'),
(5, 24, 3, 'and the second husband also divorces her or dies,', 'NLT'),
(5, 24, 4, 'the former husband may not marry her again, for she has been defiled. That would be detestable to the LORD. You must not bring guilt upon the land the LORD your God is giving you as a special possession.', 'NLT'),
(5, 24, 5, '"A newly married man must not be drafted into the army or given any other special responsibilities. He must be free to be at home for one year, bringing happiness to the wife he has married.', 'NLT'),
(5, 24, 6, '"It is wrong to take a pair of millstones, or even just the upper millstone, as a pledge, for the owner uses it to make a living.', 'NLT'),
(5, 24, 7, '"If anyone kidnaps a fellow Israelite and treats him as a slave or sells him, the kidnapper must die. You must cleanse the evil from among you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 24, 8, '"Watch all contagious skin diseases carefully and follow the instructions of the Levitical priests; obey the commands I have given them.', 'NLT'),
(5, 24, 9, 'Remember what the LORD your God did to Miriam as you were coming from Egypt.', 'NLT'),
(5, 24, 10, '"If you lend anything to your neighbor, do not enter your neighbor''s house to claim the security.', 'NLT'),
(5, 24, 11, 'Stand outside and the owner will bring it out to you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 24, 12, 'If your neighbor is poor and has only a cloak to give as security, do not keep the cloak overnight.', 'NLT'),
(5, 24, 13, 'Return the cloak to its owner by sunset so your neighbor can sleep in it and bless you. And the LORD your God will count it as a righteous act.', 'NLT'),
(5, 24, 14, '"Never take advantage of poor laborers, whether fellow Israelites or foreigners living in your towns.', 'NLT'),
(5, 24, 15, 'Pay them their wages each day before sunset because they are poor and are counting on it. Otherwise they might cry out to the LORD against you, and it would be counted against you as sin.', 'NLT'),
(5, 24, 16, '"Parents must not be put to death for the sins of their children, nor the children for the sins of their parents. Those worthy of death must be executed for their own crimes.', 'NLT'),
(5, 24, 17, '"True justice must be given to foreigners living among you and to orphans, and you must never accept a widow''s garment in pledge of her debt.', 'NLT'),
(5, 24, 18, 'Always remember that you were slaves in Egypt and that the LORD your God redeemed you. That is why I have given you this command.', 'NLT'),
(5, 24, 19, '"When you are harvesting your crops and forget to bring in a bundle of grain from your field, don''t go back to get it. Leave it for the foreigners, orphans, and widows. Then the LORD your God will bless you in all you do.', 'NLT'),
(5, 24, 20, 'When you beat the olives from your olive trees, don''t go over the boughs twice. Leave some of the olives for the foreigners, orphans, and widows.', 'NLT'),
(5, 24, 21, 'This also applies to the grapes in your vineyard. Do not glean the vines after they are picked, but leave any remaining grapes for the foreigners, orphans, and widows.', 'NLT'),
(5, 24, 22, 'Remember that you were slaves in the land of Egypt. That is why I am giving you this command.', 'NLT'),
(5, 25, 1, '"Suppose two people take a dispute to court, and the judges declare that one is right and the other is wrong.', 'NLT'),
(5, 25, 2, 'If the person in the wrong is sentenced to be flogged, the judge will command him to lie down and be beaten in his presence with the number of lashes appropriate to the crime.', 'NLT'),
(5, 25, 3, 'No more than forty lashes may ever be given; more than forty lashes would publicly humiliate your neighbor.', 'NLT'),
(5, 25, 4, '"Do not keep an ox from eating as it treads out the grain.', 'NLT'),
(5, 25, 5, '"If two brothers are living together on the same property and one of them dies without a son, his widow must not marry outside the family. Instead, her husband''s brother must marry her and fulfill the duties of a brother-in-law.', 'NLT'),
(5, 25, 6, 'The first son she bears to him will be counted as the son of the dead brother, so that his name will not be forgotten in Israel.', 'NLT'),
(5, 25, 7, 'But if the dead man''s brother refuses to marry the widow, she must go to the town gate and say to the leaders there, `My husband''s brother refuses to preserve his brother''s name in Israel--he refuses to marry me.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 25, 8, 'The leaders of the town will then summon him and try to reason with him. If he still insists that he doesn''t want to marry her,', 'NLT'),
(5, 25, 9, 'the widow must walk over to him in the presence of the leaders, pull his sandal from his foot, and spit in his face. She will then say, `This is what happens to a man who refuses to raise up a son for his brother.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 25, 10, 'Ever afterward his family will be referred to as `the family of the man whose sandal was pulled off''!', 'NLT'),
(5, 25, 11, '"If two Israelite men are fighting and the wife of one tries to rescue her husband by grabbing the testicles of the other man,', 'NLT'),
(5, 25, 12, 'her hand must be cut off without pity.', 'NLT'),
(5, 25, 13, '"You must use accurate scales when you weigh out merchandise,', 'NLT'),
(5, 25, 14, 'and you must use full and honest measures.', 'NLT'),
(5, 25, 15, 'Yes, use honest weights and measures, so that you will enjoy a long life in the land the LORD your God is giving you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 25, 16, 'Those who cheat with dishonest weights and measures are detestable to the LORD your God.', 'NLT'),
(5, 25, 17, '"Never forget what the Amalekites did to you as you came from Egypt.', 'NLT'),
(5, 25, 18, 'They attacked you when you were exhausted and weary, and they struck down those who were lagging behind. They had no fear of God.', 'NLT'),
(5, 25, 19, 'Therefore, when the LORD your God has given you rest from all your enemies in the land he is giving you as a special possession, you are to destroy the Amalekites and erase their memory from under heaven. Never forget this!', 'NLT'),
(5, 26, 1, '"When you arrive in the land the LORD your God is giving you as a special possession and you have conquered it and settled there,', 'NLT'),
(5, 26, 2, 'put some of the first produce from each harvest into a basket and bring it to the place the LORD your God chooses for his name to be honored.', 'NLT'),
(5, 26, 3, 'Go to the priest in charge at that time and say to him, `With this gift I acknowledge that the LORD your God has brought me into the land he swore to give our ancestors.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 26, 4, 'The priest will then take the basket from your hand and set it before the altar of the LORD your God.', 'NLT'),
(5, 26, 5, 'You must then say in the presence of the LORD your God, `My ancestor Jacob was a wandering Aramean who went to live in Egypt. His family was few in number, but in Egypt they became a mighty and numerous nation.', 'NLT'),
(5, 26, 6, 'When the Egyptians mistreated and humiliated us by making us their slaves,', 'NLT'),
(5, 26, 7, 'we cried out to the LORD, the God of our ancestors. He heard us and saw our hardship, toil, and oppression.', 'NLT'),
(5, 26, 8, 'So the LORD brought us out of Egypt with amazing power, overwhelming terror, and miraculous signs and wonders.', 'NLT'),
(5, 26, 9, 'He brought us to this place and gave us this land flowing with milk and honey!', 'NLT'),
(5, 26, 10, 'And now, O LORD, I have brought you a token of the first crops you have given me from the ground.'' Then place the produce before the LORD your God and worship him.', 'NLT'),
(5, 26, 11, 'Afterward go and celebrate because of all the good things the LORD your God has given to you and your household. Remember to include the Levites and the foreigners living among you in the celebration.', 'NLT'),
(5, 26, 12, '"Every third year you must offer a special tithe of your crops. You must give these tithes to the Levites, foreigners, orphans, and widows so that they will have enough to eat in your towns.', 'NLT'),
(5, 26, 13, 'Then you must declare in the presence of the LORD your God, `I have taken the sacred gift from my house and have given it to the Levites, foreigners, orphans, and widows, just as you commanded me. I have not violated or forgotten any of your commands.', 'NLT'),
(5, 26, 14, 'I have not eaten any of it while in mourning; I have not touched it while I was ceremonially unclean; and I have not offered any of it to the dead. I have obeyed the LORD my God and have done everything you commanded me.', 'NLT'),
(5, 26, 15, 'Look down from your holy dwelling place in heaven and bless your people Israel and the land you have given us--a land flowing with milk and honey--just as you solemnly promised our ancestors.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 26, 16, '"Today the LORD your God has commanded you to obey all these laws and regulations. You must commit yourself to them without reservation.', 'NLT'),
(5, 26, 17, 'You have declared today that the LORD is your God. You have promised to obey his laws, commands, and regulations by walking in his ways and doing everything he tells you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 26, 18, 'The LORD has declared today that you are his people, his own special treasure, just as he promised, and that you must obey all his commands.', 'NLT'),
(5, 26, 19, 'And if you do, he will make you greater than any other nation. Then you will receive praise, honor, and renown. You will be a nation that is holy to the LORD your God, just as he promised."', 'NLT'),
(5, 27, 1, 'Then Moses and the leaders of Israel charged the people as follows: "Keep all these commands that I am giving you today.', 'NLT'),
(5, 27, 2, 'When you cross the Jordan River and enter the land the LORD your God is giving you, set up some large stones and coat them with plaster.', 'NLT'),
(5, 27, 3, 'Then write all the terms of this law on them. I repeat, you will soon cross the river to enter the land the LORD your God is giving you, a land flowing with milk and honey, just as the LORD, the God of your ancestors, promised you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 27, 4, 'When you cross the Jordan, set up these stones at Mount Ebal and coat them with plaster, as I am commanding you today.', 'NLT'),
(5, 27, 5, 'Then build an altar there to the LORD your God, using natural stones.', 'NLT'),
(5, 27, 6, 'Do not shape the stones with an iron tool. On the altar you must offer burnt offerings to the LORD your God.', 'NLT'),
(5, 27, 7, 'Sacrifice peace offerings on it also, and feast there with great joy before the LORD your God.', 'NLT'),
(5, 27, 8, 'On the stones coated with plaster, you must clearly write all the terms of this law."', 'NLT'),
(5, 27, 9, 'Then Moses and the Levitical priests addressed all Israel as follows: "O Israel, be quiet and listen! Today you have become the people of the LORD your God.', 'NLT'),
(5, 27, 10, 'So obey the LORD your God by keeping all these commands and laws that I am giving you today."', 'NLT'),
(5, 27, 11, 'That same day Moses gave this charge to the people:', 'NLT'),
(5, 27, 12, '"When you cross the Jordan River, the tribes of Simeon, Levi, Judah, Issachar, Joseph, and Benjamin must stand on Mount Gerizim to proclaim a blessing over the people.', 'NLT'),
(5, 27, 13, 'And the tribes of Reuben, Gad, Asher, Zebulun, Dan, and Naphtali must stand on Mount Ebal to proclaim a curse.', 'NLT'),
(5, 27, 14, 'Then the Levites must shout to all the people of Israel:', 'NLT'),
(5, 27, 15, '`Cursed is anyone who carves or casts idols and secretly sets them up. These idols, the work of craftsmen, are detestable to the LORD.'' And all the people will reply, `Amen.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 27, 16, '`Cursed is anyone who despises father or mother.'' And all the people will reply, `Amen.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 27, 17, '`Cursed is anyone who steals property from a neighbor by moving a boundary marker.'' And all the people will reply, `Amen.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 27, 18, '`Cursed is anyone who leads a blind person astray on the road.'' And all the people will reply, `Amen.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 27, 19, '`Cursed is anyone who is unjust to foreigners, orphans, and widows.'' And all the people will reply, `Amen.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 27, 20, '`Cursed is anyone who has sexual intercourse with his father''s wife, for he has violated his father.'' And all the people will reply, `Amen.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 27, 21, '`Cursed is anyone who has sexual intercourse with an animal.'' And all the people will reply, `Amen.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 27, 22, '`Cursed is anyone who has sexual intercourse with his sister, whether she is the daughter of his father or his mother.'' And all the people will reply, `Amen.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 27, 23, '`Cursed is anyone who has sexual intercourse with his mother-in-law.'' And all the people will reply, `Amen.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 27, 24, '`Cursed is anyone who kills another person in secret.'' And all the people will reply, `Amen.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 27, 25, '`Cursed is anyone who accepts payment to kill an innocent person.'' And all the people will reply, `Amen.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 27, 26, '`Cursed is anyone who does not affirm the terms of this law by obeying them.'' And all the people will reply, `Amen.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 1, '"If you fully obey the LORD your God by keeping all the commands I am giving you today, the LORD your God will exalt you above all the nations of the world.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 2, 'You will experience all these blessings if you obey the LORD your God:', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 3, 'You will be blessed in your towns and in the country.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 4, 'You will be blessed with many children and productive fields. You will be blessed with fertile herds and flocks.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 5, 'You will be blessed with baskets overflowing with fruit, and with kneading bowls filled with bread.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 6, 'You will be blessed wherever you go, both in coming and in going.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 7, '"The LORD will conquer your enemies when they attack you. They will attack you from one direction, but they will scatter from you in seven!', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 8, '"The LORD will bless everything you do and will fill your storehouses with grain. The LORD your God will bless you in the land he is giving you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 9, '"If you obey the commands of the LORD your God and walk in his ways, the LORD will establish you as his holy people as he solemnly promised to do.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 10, 'Then all the nations of the world will see that you are a people claimed by the LORD, and they will stand in awe of you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 11, '"The LORD will give you an abundance of good things in the land he swore to give your ancestors--many children, numerous livestock, and abundant crops.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 12, 'The LORD will send rain at the proper time from his rich treasury in the heavens to bless all the work you do. You will lend to many nations, but you will never need to borrow from them.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 13, 'If you listen to these commands of the LORD your God and carefully obey them, the LORD will make you the head and not the tail, and you will always have the upper hand.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 14, 'You must not turn away from any of the commands I am giving you today to follow after other gods and worship them.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 15, '"But if you refuse to listen to the LORD your God and do not obey all the commands and laws I am giving you today, all these curses will come and overwhelm you:', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 16, 'You will be cursed in your towns and in the country.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 17, 'You will be cursed with baskets empty of fruit, and with kneading bowls empty of bread.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 18, 'You will be cursed with few children and barren fields. You will be cursed with infertile herds and flocks.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 19, 'You will be cursed wherever you go, both in coming and in going.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 20, '"The LORD himself will send against you curses, confusion, and disillusionment in everything you do, until at last you are completely destroyed for doing evil and forsaking me.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 21, 'The LORD will send diseases among you until none of you are left in the land you are about to enter and occupy.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 22, 'The LORD will strike you with wasting disease, fever, and inflammation, with scorching heat and drought, and with blight and mildew. These devastations will pursue you until you die.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 23, 'The skies above will be as unyielding as bronze, and the earth beneath will be as hard as iron.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 24, 'The LORD will turn your rain into sand and dust, and it will pour down from the sky until you are destroyed.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 25, '"The LORD will cause you to be defeated by your enemies. You will attack your enemies from one direction, but you will scatter from them in seven! You will be an object of horror to all the kingdoms of the earth.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 26, 'Your dead bodies will be food for the birds and wild animals, and no one will be there to chase them away.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 27, '"The LORD will afflict you with the boils of Egypt and with tumors, scurvy, and the itch, from which you cannot be cured.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 28, 'The LORD will strike you with madness, blindness, and panic.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 29, 'You will grope around in broad daylight, just like a blind person groping in the darkness, and you will not succeed at anything you do. You will be oppressed and robbed continually, and no one will come to save you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 30, '"You will be engaged to a woman, but another man will ravish her. You will build a house, but someone else will live in it. You will plant a vineyard, but you will never enjoy its fruit.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 31, 'Your ox will be butchered before your eyes, but you won''t get a single bite of the meat. Your donkey will be driven away, never to be returned. Your sheep will be given to your enemies, and no one will be there to help you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 32, 'You will watch as your sons and daughters are taken away as slaves. Your heart will break as you long for them, but nothing you do will help.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 33, 'A foreign nation you have never heard about will eat the crops you worked so hard to grow. You will suffer under constant oppression and harsh treatment.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 34, 'You will go mad because of all the tragedy around you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 35, 'The LORD will cover you from head to foot with incurable boils.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 36, '"The LORD will exile you and the king you crowned to a nation unknown to you and your ancestors. Then in exile you will worship gods of wood and stone!', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 37, 'You will become an object of horror, a proverb and a mockery among all the nations to which the LORD sends you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 38, '"You will plant much but harvest little, for locusts will eat your crops.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 39, 'You will plant vineyards and care for them, but you will not drink the wine or eat the grapes, for worms will destroy the vines.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 40, 'You will grow olive trees throughout your land, but you will never use the olive oil, for the trees will drop the fruit before it is ripe.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 41, 'You will have sons and daughters, but you will not keep them, for they will be led away into captivity.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 42, 'Swarms of insects will destroy your trees and crops.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 43, 'The foreigners living among you will become stronger and stronger, while you become weaker and weaker.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 44, 'They will lend money to you, not you to them. They will be the head, and you will be the tail!', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 45, '"If you refuse to listen to the LORD your God and to obey the commands and laws he has given you, all these curses will pursue and overtake you until you are destroyed.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 46, 'These horrors will serve as a sign and warning among you and your descendants forever.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 47, 'Because you have not served the LORD your God with joy and enthusiasm for the abundant benefits you have received,', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 48, 'you will serve your enemies whom the LORD will send against you. You will be left hungry, thirsty, naked, and lacking in everything. They will oppress you harshly until you are destroyed.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 49, '"The LORD will bring a distant nation against you from the end of the earth, and it will swoop down on you like an eagle. It is a nation whose language you do not understand,', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 50, 'a fierce and heartless nation that shows no respect for the old and no pity for the young.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 51, 'Its armies will devour your livestock and crops, and you will starve to death. They will leave you no grain, new wine, olive oil, calves, or lambs, bringing about your destruction.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 52, 'They will lay siege to your cities until all the fortified walls in your land--the walls you trusted to protect you--are knocked down. They will attack all the towns in the land the LORD your God has given you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 53, 'The siege will be so severe that you will eat the flesh of your own sons and daughters, whom the LORD your God has given you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 54, 'The most tenderhearted man among you will have no compassion for his own brother, his beloved wife, and his surviving children.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 55, 'He will refuse to give them a share of the flesh he is devouring--the flesh of one of his own children--because he has nothing else to eat during the siege that your enemy will inflict on all your towns.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 56, 'The most tender and delicate woman among you--so delicate she would not so much as touch her feet to the ground--will be cruel to the husband she loves and to her own son or daughter.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 57, 'She will hide from them the afterbirth and the new baby she has borne, so that she herself can secretly eat them. She will have nothing else to eat during the siege and terrible distress that your enemy will inflict on all your towns.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 58, '"If you refuse to obey all the terms of this law that are written in this book, and if you do not fear the glorious and awesome name of the LORD your God,', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 59, 'then the LORD will overwhelm both you and your children with indescribable plagues. These plagues will be intense and without relief, making you miserable and unbearably sick.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 60, 'He will bring against you all the diseases of Egypt that you feared so much, and they will claim you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 61, 'The LORD will bring against you every sickness and plague there is, even those not mentioned in this Book of the Law, until you are destroyed.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 62, 'Though you are as numerous as the stars in the sky, few of you will be left because you would not listen to the LORD your God.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 63, '"Just as the LORD has found great pleasure in helping you to prosper and multiply, the LORD will find pleasure in destroying you, until you disappear from the land you are about to enter and occupy.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 64, 'For the LORD will scatter you among all the nations from one end of the earth to the other. There you will worship foreign gods that neither you nor your ancestors have known, gods made of wood and stone!', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 65, 'There among those nations you will find no place of security and rest. And the LORD will cause your heart to tremble, your eyesight to fail, and your soul to despair.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 66, 'Your lives will hang in doubt. You will live night and day in fear, with no reason to believe that you will see the morning light.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 67, 'In the morning you will say, `If only it were night!'' And in the evening you will say, `If only it were morning!'' You will say this because of your terror at the awesome horrors you see around you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 28, 68, 'Then the LORD will send you back to Egypt in ships, a journey I promised you would never again make. There you will offer to sell yourselves to your enemies as slaves, but no one will want to buy you."', 'NLT'),
(5, 29, 1, 'These are the terms of the covenant the LORD commanded Moses to make with the Israelites while they were in the land of Moab, in addition to the covenant he had made with them at Mount Sinai.', 'NLT'),
(5, 29, 2, 'Moses summoned all the Israelites and said to them, "You have seen with your own eyes everything the LORD did in Egypt to Pharaoh and all his servants and his whole country--', 'NLT'),
(5, 29, 3, 'all the great tests of strength, the miraculous signs, and the amazing wonders.', 'NLT'),
(5, 29, 4, 'But to this day the LORD has not given you minds that understand, nor eyes that see, nor ears that hear!', 'NLT'),
(5, 29, 5, 'For forty years I led you through the wilderness, yet your clothes and sandals did not wear out.', 'NLT'),
(5, 29, 6, 'You had no bread or wine or other strong drink, but he gave you food so you would know that he is the LORD your God.', 'NLT'),
(5, 29, 7, 'When we came here, King Sihon of Heshbon and King Og of Bashan came out to fight against us, but we defeated them.', 'NLT'),
(5, 29, 8, 'We took their land and gave it to the tribes of Reuben and Gad and to the half-tribe of Manasseh as their inheritance.', 'NLT'),
(5, 29, 9, '"Therefore, obey the terms of this covenant so that you will prosper in everything you do.', 'NLT'),
(5, 29, 10, 'All of you--your tribal leaders, your judges, your officers, all the men of Israel--are standing today before the LORD your God.', 'NLT'),
(5, 29, 11, 'With you are your little ones, your wives, and the foreigners living among you who chop your wood and carry your water.', 'NLT'),
(5, 29, 12, 'You are standing here today to enter into a covenant with the LORD your God. The LORD is making this covenant with you today, and he has sealed it with an oath.', 'NLT'),
(5, 29, 13, 'He wants to confirm you today as his people and to confirm that he is your God, just as he promised you, and as he swore to your ancestors Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob.', 'NLT'),
(5, 29, 14, 'But you are not the only ones with whom the LORD is making this covenant with its obligations.', 'NLT'),
(5, 29, 15, 'The LORD your God is making this covenant with you who stand in his presence today and also with all future generations of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(5, 29, 16, '"Surely you remember how we lived in the land of Egypt and how we traveled through the lands of enemy nations as we left.', 'NLT'),
(5, 29, 17, 'You have seen their detestable idols made of wood, stone, silver, and gold.', 'NLT'),
(5, 29, 18, 'The LORD made this covenant with you so that no man, woman, family, or tribe among you would turn away from the LORD our God to worship these gods of other nations, and so that no root among you would bear bitter and poisonous fruit.', 'NLT'),
(5, 29, 19, 'Let none of those who hear the warnings of this curse consider themselves immune, thinking, `I am safe, even though I am walking in my own stubborn way.'' This would lead to utter ruin!', 'NLT'),
(5, 29, 20, 'The LORD will not pardon such people. His anger and jealousy will burn against them. All the curses written in this book will come down on them, and the LORD will erase their names from under heaven.', 'NLT'),
(5, 29, 21, 'The LORD will separate them from all the tribes of Israel, to pour out on them all the covenant curses recorded in this Book of the Law.', 'NLT'),
(5, 29, 22, '"Then the generations to come, both your own descendants and the foreigners who come from distant lands, will see the devastation of the land and the diseases the LORD will send against it.', 'NLT'),
(5, 29, 23, 'They will find its soil turned into sulfur and salt, with nothing planted and nothing growing, not even a blade of grass. It will be just like Sodom and Gomorrah, Admah and Zeboiim, which the LORD destroyed in his anger.', 'NLT'),
(5, 29, 24, 'The surrounding nations will ask, `Why has the LORD done this to his land? Why was he so angry?''', 'NLT'),
(5, 29, 25, '"And they will be told, `This happened because the people of the land broke the covenant they made with the LORD, the God of their ancestors, when he brought them out of the land of Egypt.', 'NLT'),
(5, 29, 26, 'They turned to serve and worship other gods that were foreign to them, gods that the LORD had not designated for them.', 'NLT'),
(5, 29, 27, 'That is why the LORD''s anger burned against this land, bringing down on it all the curses recorded in this book.', 'NLT'),
(5, 29, 28, 'In great anger and fury the LORD uprooted his people from their land and exiled them to another land, where they still live today!''', 'NLT'),
(5, 29, 29, '"There are secret things that belong to the LORD our God, but the revealed things belong to us and our descendants forever, so that we may obey these words of the law.', 'NLT'),
(5, 30, 1, '"Suppose all these things happen to you--the blessings and the curses I have listed--and you meditate on them as you are living among the nations to which the LORD your God has exiled you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 30, 2, 'If at that time you return to the LORD your God, and you and your children begin wholeheartedly to obey all the commands I have given you today,', 'NLT'),
(5, 30, 3, 'then the LORD your God will restore your fortunes. He will have mercy on you and gather you back from all the nations where he has scattered you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 30, 4, 'Though you are at the ends of the earth, the LORD your God will go and find you and bring you back again.', 'NLT'),
(5, 30, 5, 'He will return you to the land that belonged to your ancestors, and you will possess that land again. He will make you even more prosperous and numerous than your ancestors!', 'NLT'),
(5, 30, 6, '"The LORD your God will cleanse your heart and the hearts of all your descendants so that you will love him with all your heart and soul, and so you may live!', 'NLT'),
(5, 30, 7, 'The LORD your God will inflict all these curses on your enemies and persecutors.', 'NLT'),
(5, 30, 8, 'Then you will again obey the LORD and keep all the commands I am giving you today.', 'NLT'),
(5, 30, 9, 'The LORD your God will make you successful in everything you do. He will give you many children and numerous livestock, and your fields will produce abundant harvests, for the LORD will delight in being good to you as he was to your ancestors.', 'NLT'),
(5, 30, 10, 'The LORD your God will delight in you if you obey his voice and keep the commands and laws written in this Book of the Law, and if you turn to the LORD your God with all your heart and soul.', 'NLT'),
(5, 30, 11, '"This command I am giving you today is not too difficult for you to understand or perform.', 'NLT'),
(5, 30, 12, 'It is not up in heaven, so distant that you must ask, `Who will go to heaven and bring it down so we can hear and obey it?''', 'NLT'),
(5, 30, 13, 'It is not beyond the sea, so far away that you must ask, `Who will cross the sea to bring it to us so we can hear and obey it?''', 'NLT'),
(5, 30, 14, 'The message is very close at hand; it is on your lips and in your heart so that you can obey it.', 'NLT'),
(5, 30, 15, '"Now listen! Today I am giving you a choice between prosperity and disaster, between life and death.', 'NLT'),
(5, 30, 16, 'I have commanded you today to love the LORD your God and to keep his commands, laws, and regulations by walking in his ways. If you do this, you will live and become a great nation, and the LORD your God will bless you and the land you are about to enter and occupy.', 'NLT'),
(5, 30, 17, 'But if your heart turns away and you refuse to listen, and if you are drawn away to serve and worship other gods,', 'NLT'),
(5, 30, 18, 'then I warn you now that you will certainly be destroyed. You will not live a long, good life in the land you are crossing the Jordan to occupy.', 'NLT'),
(5, 30, 19, '"Today I have given you the choice between life and death, between blessings and curses. I call on heaven and earth to witness the choice you make. Oh, that you would choose life, that you and your descendants might live!', 'NLT'),
(5, 30, 20, 'Choose to love the LORD your God and to obey him and commit yourself to him, for he is your life. Then you will live long in the land the LORD swore to give your ancestors Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob."', 'NLT'),
(5, 31, 1, 'When Moses had finished saying these things to all the people of Israel,', 'NLT'),
(5, 31, 2, 'he said, "I am now 120 years old and am no longer able to lead you. The LORD has told me that I will not cross the Jordan River.', 'NLT'),
(5, 31, 3, 'But the LORD your God himself will cross over ahead of you. He will destroy the nations living there, and you will take possession of their land. Joshua is your new leader, and he will go with you, just as the LORD promised.', 'NLT'),
(5, 31, 4, 'The LORD will destroy the nations living in the land, just as he destroyed Sihon and Og, the kings of the Amorites.', 'NLT'),
(5, 31, 5, 'The LORD will hand over to you the people who live there, and you will deal with them as I have commanded you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 31, 6, 'Be strong and courageous! Do not be afraid of them! The LORD your God will go ahead of you. He will neither fail you nor forsake you."', 'NLT'),
(5, 31, 7, 'Then Moses called for Joshua, and as all Israel watched he said to him, "Be strong and courageous! For you will lead these people into the land that the LORD swore to give their ancestors. You are the one who will deliver it to them as their inheritance.', 'NLT'),
(5, 31, 8, 'Do not be afraid or discouraged, for the LORD is the one who goes before you. He will be with you; he will neither fail you nor forsake you."', 'NLT'),
(5, 31, 9, 'So Moses wrote down this law and gave it to the priests, who carried the Ark of the LORD''s covenant, and to the leaders of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(5, 31, 10, 'Then Moses gave them this command: "At the end of every seventh year, the Year of Release, during the Festival of Shelters,', 'NLT'),
(5, 31, 11, 'you must read this law to all the people of Israel when they assemble before the LORD your God at the place he chooses.', 'NLT'),
(5, 31, 12, 'Call them all together--men, women, children, and the foreigners living in your towns--so they may listen and learn to fear the LORD your God and carefully obey all the terms of this law.', 'NLT'),
(5, 31, 13, 'Do this so that your children who have not known these laws will hear them and will learn to fear the LORD your God. Do this as long as you live in the land you are crossing the Jordan to occupy."', 'NLT'),
(5, 31, 14, 'Then the LORD said to Moses, "The time has come for you to die. Call Joshua and take him with you to the Tabernacle, and I will commission him there." So Moses and Joshua went and presented themselves at the Tabernacle.', 'NLT'),
(5, 31, 15, 'And the LORD appeared to them in a pillar of cloud at the entrance to the sacred tent.', 'NLT'),
(5, 31, 16, 'The LORD said to Moses, "You are about to die and join your ancestors. After you are gone, these people will begin worshiping foreign gods, the gods of the land where they are going. They will abandon me and break the covenant I have made with them.', 'NLT'),
(5, 31, 17, 'Then my anger will blaze forth against them. I will abandon them, hiding my face from them, and they will be destroyed. Terrible trouble will come down on them, so that they will say, `These disasters have come because God is no longer among us!''', 'NLT'),
(5, 31, 18, 'At that time I will hide my face from them on account of all the sins they have committed by worshiping other gods.', 'NLT'),
(5, 31, 19, '"Now write down the words of this song, and teach it to the people of Israel. Teach them to sing it, so it may serve as a witness against them.', 'NLT'),
(5, 31, 20, 'For I will bring them into the land I swore to give their ancestors--a land flowing with milk and honey. There they will become prosperous; they will eat all the food they want and become well nourished. Then they will begin to worship other gods; they will despise me and break my covenant.', 'NLT'),
(5, 31, 21, 'Then great disasters will come down on them, and this song will stand as evidence against them, for it will never be forgotten by their descendants. I know what these people are like, even before they have entered the land I swore to give them."', 'NLT'),
(5, 31, 22, 'So that very day Moses wrote down the words of the song and taught it to the Israelites.', 'NLT'),
(5, 31, 23, 'Then the LORD commissioned Joshua son of Nun with these words: "Be strong and courageous! You must bring the people of Israel into the land I swore to give them. I will be with you."', 'NLT'),
(5, 31, 24, 'When Moses had finished writing down this entire body of law in a book,', 'NLT'),
(5, 31, 25, 'he gave these instructions to the Levites who carried the Ark of the LORD''s covenant:', 'NLT'),
(5, 31, 26, '"Take this Book of the Law and place it beside the Ark of the Covenant of the LORD your God, so it may serve as a witness against the people of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(5, 31, 27, 'For I know how rebellious and stubborn you are. Even now, while I am still with you, you have rebelled against the LORD. How much more rebellious will you be after my death!', 'NLT'),
(5, 31, 28, 'Now summon all the leaders and officials of your tribes so that I can speak to them and call heaven and earth to witness against them.', 'NLT'),
(5, 31, 29, 'I know that after my death you will become utterly corrupt and will turn from the path I have commanded you to follow. In the days to come, disaster will come down on you, for you will make the LORD very angry by doing what is evil in his sight."', 'NLT'),
(5, 31, 30, 'So Moses recited this entire song to the assembly of Israel:', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 1, '1 "Listen, O heavens, and I will speak! Hear, O earth, the words that I say!', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 2, 'My teaching will fall on you like rain; my speech will settle like dew. My words will fall like rain on tender grass, like gentle showers on young plants.', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 3, 'I will proclaim the name of the LORD; how glorious is our God!', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 4, 'He is the Rock; his work is perfect. Everything he does is just and fair. He is a faithful God who does no wrong; how just and upright he is!', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 5, '"But they have acted corruptly toward him; when they act like that, are they really his children? They are a deceitful and twisted generation.', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 6, 'Is this the way you repay the LORD, you foolish and senseless people? Isn''t he your Father who created you? Has he not made you and established you?', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 7, 'Remember the days of long ago; think about the generations past. Ask your father and he will inform you. Inquire of your elders, and they will tell you.', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 8, 'When the Most High assigned lands to the nations, when he divided up the human race, he established the boundaries of the peoples according to the number of angelic beings.', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 9, 'For the people of Israel belong to the LORD; Jacob is his special possession.', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 10, '"He found them in a desert land, in an empty, howling wasteland. He surrounded them and watched over them; he guarded them as his most precious possession.', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 11, 'Like an eagle that rouses her chicks and hovers over her young, so he spread his wings to take them in and carried them aloft on his pinions.', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 12, 'The LORD alone guided them; they lived without any foreign gods.', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 13, 'He made them ride over the highlands; he let them feast on the crops of the fields. He nourished them with honey from the cliffs, with olive oil from the hard rock.', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 14, 'He fed them curds from the herd and milk from the flock, together with the fat of lambs and goats. He gave them choice rams and goats from Bashan, together with the choicest wheat. You drank the finest wine, made from the juice of grapes.', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 15, 'But Israel soon became fat and unruly; the people grew heavy, plump, and stuffed! Then they abandoned the God who had made them; they made light of the Rock of their salvation.', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 16, 'They stirred up his jealousy by worshiping foreign gods; they provoked his fury with detestable acts.', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 17, 'They offered sacrifices to demons, non-gods, to gods they had not known before, to gods only recently arrived, to gods their ancestors had never feared.', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 18, 'You neglected the Rock who had fathered you; you forgot the God who had given you birth.', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 19, '"The LORD saw this and was filled with loathing. He was provoked to anger by his own sons and daughters.', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 20, 'He said, `I will abandon them; I will see to their end! For they are a twisted generation, children without integrity.', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 21, 'They have roused my jealousy by worshiping non-gods; they have provoked my fury with useless idols. Now I will rouse their jealousy by blessing other nations; I will provoke their fury by blessing the foolish Gentiles.', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 22, 'For my anger blazes forth like fire and burns to the depths of the grave. It devours the earth and all its crops and ignites the foundations of the mountains.', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 23, 'I will heap disasters upon them and shoot them down with my arrows.', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 24, 'I will send against them wasting famine, burning fever, and deadly disease. They will be troubled by the fangs of wild beasts, by poisonous snakes that glide in the dust.', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 25, 'Outside, the sword will bring death, and inside, terror will strike both young men and young women, both infants and the aged.', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 26, 'I decided to scatter them, so even the memory of them would disappear.', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 27, 'But I feared the taunt of the enemy, that their adversaries might misunderstand and say, "Our power has triumphed! It was not the LORD who did this!"''', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 28, '"Israel is a nation that lacks sense; the people are foolish, without understanding.', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 29, 'Oh, that they were wise and could understand this! Oh, that they might know their fate!', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 30, 'How could one person chase a thousand of them, and two people put ten thousand to flight, unless their Rock had sold them, unless the LORD had given them up?', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 31, 'But the rock of our enemies is not like our Rock, as even they recognize.', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 32, 'Their vine grows from the vine of Sodom, from the vineyards of Gomorrah. Their grapes are poison, and their clusters are bitter.', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 33, 'Their wine is the venom of snakes, the deadly poison of vipers.', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 34, '"`I am storing up these things, sealing them away within my treasury.', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 35, 'I will take vengeance; I will repay those who deserve it. In due time their feet will slip. Their day of disaster will arrive, and their destiny will overtake them.''', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 36, '"Indeed, the LORD will judge his people, and he will change his mind about his servants, when he sees their strength is gone and no one is left, slave or free.', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 37, 'Then he will ask, `Where are their gods, the rocks they fled to for refuge?', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 38, 'Where now are those gods, who ate the fat of their sacrifices and drank the wine of their offerings? Let those gods arise and help you! Let them provide you with shelter!', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 39, 'Look now; I myself am he! There is no god other than me! I am the one who kills and gives life; I am the one who wounds and heals; no one delivers from my power!', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 40, 'Now I raise my hand to heaven and declare, "As surely as I live,', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 41, 'when I sharpen my flashing sword and begin to carry out justice, I will bring vengeance on my enemies and repay those who hate me.', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 42, 'I will make my arrows drunk with blood, and my sword will devour flesh--the blood of the slaughtered and the captives, and the heads of the enemy leaders."''', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 43, '"Rejoice with him, O heavens, and let all the angels of God worship him, for he will avenge the blood of his servants. He will take vengeance on his enemies and cleanse his land and his people."', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 44, 'So Moses came with Joshua son of Nun and recited all the words of this song to the people.', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 45, 'When Moses had finished reciting these words to Israel,', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 46, 'he added: "Take to heart all the words I have given you today. Pass them on as a command to your children so they will obey every word of this law.', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 47, 'These instructions are not mere words--they are your life! By obeying them you will enjoy a long life in the land you are crossing the Jordan River to occupy."', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 48, 'That same day the LORD said to Moses,', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 49, '"Go to Moab, to the mountains east of the river, and climb Mount Nebo, which is across from Jericho. Look out across the land of Canaan, the land I am giving to the people of Israel as their own possession.', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 50, 'Then you must die there on the mountain and join your ancestors, just as Aaron, your brother, died on Mount Hor and joined his ancestors.', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 51, 'For both of you broke faith with me among the Israelites at the waters of Meribah at Kadesh in the wilderness of Zin. You failed to demonstrate my holiness to the people of Israel there.', 'NLT'),
(5, 32, 52, 'So you will see the land from a distance, but you may not enter the land I am giving to the people of Israel."', 'NLT'),
(5, 33, 1, 'This is the blessing that Moses, the man of God, gave to the people of Israel before his death:', 'NLT'),
(5, 33, 2, '"The LORD came from Mount Sinai and dawned upon us from Mount Seir; he shone forth from Mount Paran and came from Meribah-kadesh with flaming fire at his right hand.', 'NLT'),
(5, 33, 3, 'Indeed, you love the people; all your holy ones are in your hands. They follow in your steps and accept your instruction.', 'NLT'),
(5, 33, 4, 'Moses charged us with the law, the special possession of the assembly of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(5, 33, 5, 'The LORD became king in Israel--when the leaders of the people assembled, when the tribes of Israel gathered."', 'NLT'),
(5, 33, 6, 'Moses said this about the tribe of Reuben: "Let the tribe of Reuben live and not die out, even though their tribe is small."', 'NLT'),
(5, 33, 7, 'Moses said this about the tribe of Judah: "O LORD, hear the cry of Judah and bring them again to their people. Give them strength to defend their cause; help them against their enemies!"', 'NLT'),
(5, 33, 8, 'Moses said this about the tribe of Levi: "O LORD, you have given the sacred lots to your faithful servants the Levites. You put them to the test at Massah and contended with them at the waters of Meribah.', 'NLT'),
(5, 33, 9, 'The Levites obeyed your word and guarded your covenant. They were more loyal to you than to their parents, relatives, and children.', 'NLT'),
(5, 33, 10, 'Now let them teach your regulations to Jacob; let them give your instructions to Israel. They will present incense before you and offer whole burnt offerings on the altar.', 'NLT'),
(5, 33, 11, 'Bless the Levites, O LORD, and accept all their work. Crush the loins of their enemies; strike down their foes so they never rise again."', 'NLT'),
(5, 33, 12, 'Moses said this about the tribe of Benjamin: "The people of Benjamin are loved by the LORD and live in safety beside him. He surrounds them continuously and preserves them from every harm."', 'NLT'),
(5, 33, 13, 'Moses said this about the tribes of Joseph: "May their land be blessed by the LORD with the choice gift of rain from the heavens, and water from beneath the earth;', 'NLT'),
(5, 33, 14, 'with the riches that grow in the sun, and the bounty produced each month;', 'NLT'),
(5, 33, 15, 'with the finest crops of the ancient mountains, and the abundance from the everlasting hills;', 'NLT'),
(5, 33, 16, 'with the best gifts of the earth and its fullness, and the favor of the one who appeared in the burning bush. May these blessings rest on Joseph''s head, crowning the brow of the prince among his brothers.', 'NLT'),
(5, 33, 17, 'Joseph has the strength and majesty of a young bull; his power is like the horns of a wild ox. He will gore distant nations, driving them to the ends of the earth. This is my blessing for the multitudes of Ephraim and the thousands of Manasseh."', 'NLT'),
(5, 33, 18, 'Moses said this about the tribes of Zebulun and Issachar: "May the people of Zebulun prosper in their expeditions abroad. May the people of Issachar prosper at home in their tents.', 'NLT'),
(5, 33, 19, 'They summon the people to the mountain to offer proper sacrifices there. They benefit from the riches of the sea and the hidden treasures of the sand."', 'NLT'),
(5, 33, 20, 'Moses said this about the tribe of Gad: "Blessed is the one who enlarges Gad''s territory! Gad is poised there like a lion to tear off an arm or a head.', 'NLT'),
(5, 33, 21, 'The people of Gad took the best land for themselves; a leader''s share was assigned to them. When the leaders of the people were assembled, they carried out the LORD''s justice and obeyed his regulations for Israel."', 'NLT'),
(5, 33, 22, 'Moses said this about the tribe of Dan: "Dan is a lion''s cub, leaping out from Bashan."', 'NLT'),
(5, 33, 23, 'Moses said this about the tribe of Naphtali: "O Naphtali, you are rich in favor and full of the LORD''s blessings; may you possess the west and the south."', 'NLT'),
(5, 33, 24, 'Moses said this about the tribe of Asher: "May Asher be blessed above other sons; may he be esteemed by his brothers; may he bathe his feet in olive oil.', 'NLT'),
(5, 33, 25, 'May the bolts of your gates be of iron and bronze; may your strength match the length of your days!"', 'NLT'),
(5, 33, 26, '"There is no one like the God of Israel. He rides across the heavens to help you, across the skies in majestic splendor.', 'NLT'),
(5, 33, 27, 'The eternal God is your refuge, and his everlasting arms are under you. He thrusts out the enemy before you; it is he who cries, `Destroy them!''', 'NLT'),
(5, 33, 28, 'So Israel will live in safety, prosperous Jacob in security, in a land of grain and wine, while the heavens drop down dew.', 'NLT'),
(5, 33, 29, 'How blessed you are, O Israel! Who else is like you, a people saved by the LORD? He is your protecting shield and your triumphant sword! Your enemies will bow low before you, and you will trample on their backs!"', 'NLT'),
(5, 34, 1, 'Then Moses went to Mount Nebo from the plains of Moab and climbed Pisgah Peak, which is across from Jericho. And the LORD showed him the whole land, from Gilead as far as Dan;', 'NLT'),
(5, 34, 2, 'all the land of Naphtali; the land of Ephraim and Manasseh; all the land of Judah, extending to the Mediterranean Sea;', 'NLT'),
(5, 34, 3, 'the Negev; the Jordan Valley with Jericho--the city of palms--as far as Zoar.', 'NLT'),
(5, 34, 4, 'Then the LORD said to Moses, "This is the land I promised on oath to Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob, and I told them I would give it to their descendants. I have now allowed you to see it, but you will not enter the land."', 'NLT'),
(5, 34, 5, 'So Moses, the servant of the LORD, died there in the land of Moab, just as the LORD had said.', 'NLT'),
(5, 34, 6, 'He was buried in a valley near Beth-peor in Moab, but to this day no one knows the exact place.', 'NLT'),
(5, 34, 7, 'Moses was 120 years old when he died, yet his eyesight was clear, and he was as strong as ever.', 'NLT'),
(5, 34, 8, 'The people of Israel mourned thirty days for Moses on the plains of Moab, until the customary period of mourning was over.', 'NLT'),
(5, 34, 9, 'Now Joshua son of Nun was full of the spirit of wisdom, for Moses had laid his hands on him. So the people of Israel obeyed him and did everything just as the LORD had commanded Moses.', 'NLT'),
(5, 34, 10, 'There has never been another prophet like Moses, whom the LORD knew face to face.', 'NLT'),
(5, 34, 11, 'The LORD sent Moses to perform all the miraculous signs and wonders in the land of Egypt against Pharaoh, all his servants, and his entire land.', 'NLT'),
(5, 34, 12, 'And it was through Moses that the LORD demonstrated his mighty power and terrifying acts in the sight of all Israel.', 'NLT'),
(10, 1, 1, 'After the death of Moses the LORD''s servant, the LORD spoke to Joshua son of Nun, Moses'' assistant. He said,', 'NLT'),
(10, 1, 2, '"Now that my servant Moses is dead, you must lead my people across the Jordan River into the land I am giving them.', 'NLT'),
(10, 1, 3, 'I promise you what I promised Moses: `Everywhere you go, you will be on land I have given you--', 'NLT'),
(10, 1, 4, 'from the Negev Desert in the south to the Lebanon mountains in the north, from the Euphrates River on the east to the Mediterranean Sea on the west, and all the land of the Hittites.''', 'NLT'),
(10, 1, 5, 'No one will be able to stand their ground against you as long as you live. For I will be with you as I was with Moses. I will not fail you or abandon you.', 'NLT'),
(10, 1, 6, '"Be strong and courageous, for you will lead my people to possess all the land I swore to give their ancestors.', 'NLT'),
(10, 1, 7, 'Be strong and very courageous. Obey all the laws Moses gave you. Do not turn away from them, and you will be successful in everything you do.', 'NLT'),
(10, 1, 8, 'Study this Book of the Law continually. Meditate on it day and night so you may be sure to obey all that is written in it. Only then will you succeed.', 'NLT'),
(10, 1, 9, 'I command you--be strong and courageous! Do not be afraid or discouraged. For the LORD your God is with you wherever you go."', 'NLT'),
(10, 1, 10, 'Joshua then commanded the leaders of Israel,', 'NLT'),
(10, 1, 11, '"Go through the camp and tell the people to get their provisions ready. In three days you will cross the Jordan River and take possession of the land the LORD your God has given you."', 'NLT'),
(10, 1, 12, 'Then Joshua called together the tribes of Reuben, Gad, and the half-tribe of Manasseh. He told them,', 'NLT'),
(10, 1, 13, '"Remember what Moses, the servant of the LORD, commanded you: `The LORD your God is giving you rest and has given you this land.''', 'NLT'),
(10, 1, 14, 'Your wives, children, and cattle may remain here on the east side of the Jordan River, but your warriors, fully armed, must lead the other tribes across the Jordan to help them conquer their territory. Stay with them', 'NLT'),
(10, 1, 15, 'until the LORD gives rest to them as he has given rest to you, and until they, too, possess the land the LORD your God is giving them. Only then may you settle here on the east side of the Jordan River in the land that Moses, the servant of the LORD, gave you."', 'NLT'),
(10, 1, 16, 'They answered Joshua, "We will do whatever you command us, and we will go wherever you send us.', 'NLT'),
(10, 1, 17, 'We will obey you just as we obeyed Moses. And may the LORD your God be with you as he was with Moses.', 'NLT'),
(10, 1, 18, 'Anyone who rebels against your word and does not obey your every command will be put to death. So be strong and courageous!"', 'NLT'),
(10, 2, 1, 'Then Joshua secretly sent out two spies from the Israelite camp at Acacia. He instructed them, "Spy out the land on the other side of the Jordan River, especially around Jericho." So the two men set out and came to the house of a prostitute named Rahab and stayed there that night.', 'NLT'),
(10, 2, 2, 'But someone told the king of Jericho, "Some Israelites have come here tonight to spy out the land."', 'NLT'),
(10, 2, 3, 'So the king of Jericho sent orders to Rahab: "Bring out the men who have come into your house. They are spies sent here to discover the best way to attack us."', 'NLT'),
(10, 2, 4, 'Rahab, who had hidden the two men, replied, "The men were here earlier, but I didn''t know where they were from.', 'NLT'),
(10, 2, 5, 'They left the city at dusk, as the city gates were about to close, and I don''t know where they went. If you hurry, you can probably catch up with them."', 'NLT'),
(10, 2, 6, '(But she had taken them up to the roof and hidden them beneath piles of flax.)', 'NLT'),
(10, 2, 7, 'So the king''s men went looking for the spies along the road leading to the shallow crossing places of the Jordan River. And as soon as the king''s men had left, the city gate was shut.', 'NLT'),
(10, 2, 8, 'Before the spies went to sleep that night, Rahab went up on the roof to talk with them.', 'NLT'),
(10, 2, 9, '"I know the LORD has given you this land," she told them. "We are all afraid of you. Everyone is living in terror.', 'NLT'),
(10, 2, 10, 'For we have heard how the LORD made a dry path for you through the Red Sea when you left Egypt. And we know what you did to Sihon and Og, the two Amorite kings east of the Jordan River, whose people you completely destroyed.', 'NLT'),
(10, 2, 11, 'No wonder our hearts have melted in fear! No one has the courage to fight after hearing such things. For the LORD your God is the supreme God of the heavens above and the earth below.', 'NLT'),
(10, 2, 12, 'Now swear to me by the LORD that you will be kind to me and my family since I have helped you. Give me some guarantee that', 'NLT'),
(10, 2, 13, 'when Jericho is conquered, you will let me live, along with my father and mother, my brothers and sisters, and all their families."', 'NLT'),
(10, 2, 14, '"We offer our own lives as a guarantee for your safety," the men agreed. "If you don''t betray us, we will keep our promise when the LORD gives us the land."', 'NLT'),
(10, 2, 15, 'Then, since Rahab''s house was built into the city wall, she let them down by a rope through the window.', 'NLT'),
(10, 2, 16, '"Escape to the hill country," she told them. "Hide there for three days until the men who are searching for you have returned; then go on your way."', 'NLT'),
(10, 2, 17, 'Before they left, the men told her, "We can guarantee your safety', 'NLT'),
(10, 2, 18, 'only if you leave this scarlet rope hanging from the window. And all your family members--your father, mother, brothers, and all your relatives--must be here inside the house.', 'NLT'),
(10, 2, 19, 'If they go out into the street, they will be killed, and we cannot be held to our oath. But we swear that no one inside this house will be killed--not a hand will be laid on any of them.', 'NLT'),
(10, 2, 20, 'If you betray us, however, we are not bound by this oath in any way."', 'NLT'),
(10, 2, 21, '"I accept your terms," she replied. And she sent them on their way, leaving the scarlet rope hanging from the window.', 'NLT'),
(10, 2, 22, 'The spies went up into the hill country and stayed there three days. The men who were chasing them had searched everywhere along the road, but they finally returned to the city without success.', 'NLT'),
(10, 2, 23, 'Then the two spies came down from the hill country, crossed the Jordan River, and reported to Joshua all that had happened to them.', 'NLT'),
(10, 2, 24, '"The LORD will certainly give us the whole land," they said, "for all the people in the land are terrified of us."', 'NLT'),
(10, 3, 1, 'Early the next morning Joshua and all the Israelites left Acacia and arrived at the banks of the Jordan River, where they camped before crossing.', 'NLT'),
(10, 3, 2, 'Three days later, the Israelite leaders went through the camp', 'NLT'),
(10, 3, 3, 'giving these instructions to the people: "When you see the Levitical priests carrying the Ark of the Covenant of the LORD your God, follow them.', 'NLT'),
(10, 3, 4, 'Since you have never traveled this way before, they will guide you. Stay about a half mile behind them, keeping a clear distance between you and the Ark. Make sure you don''t come any closer."', 'NLT'),
(10, 3, 5, 'Then Joshua told the people, "Purify yourselves, for tomorrow the LORD will do great wonders among you."', 'NLT'),
(10, 3, 6, 'In the morning Joshua said to the priests, "Lift up the Ark of the Covenant and lead the people across the river." And so they started out.', 'NLT'),
(10, 3, 7, 'The LORD told Joshua, "Today I will begin to make you great in the eyes of all the Israelites. Now they will know that I am with you, just as I was with Moses.', 'NLT'),
(10, 3, 8, 'Give these instructions to the priests who are carrying the Ark of the Covenant: `When you reach the banks of the Jordan River, take a few steps into the river and stop.''"', 'NLT'),
(10, 3, 9, 'So Joshua told the Israelites, "Come and listen to what the LORD your God says.', 'NLT'),
(10, 3, 10, 'Today you will know that the living God is among you. He will surely drive out the Canaanites, Hittites, Hivites, Perizzites, Girgashites, Amorites, and Jebusites.', 'NLT'),
(10, 3, 11, 'Think of it! The Ark of the Covenant, which belongs to the Lord of the whole earth, will lead you across the Jordan River!', 'NLT'),
(10, 3, 12, 'Now choose twelve men, one from each tribe.', 'NLT'),
(10, 3, 13, 'The priests will be carrying the Ark of the LORD, the Lord of all the earth. When their feet touch the water, the flow of water will be cut off upstream, and the river will pile up there in one heap."', 'NLT'),
(10, 3, 14, 'When the people set out to cross the Jordan, the priests who were carrying the Ark of the Covenant went ahead of them.', 'NLT'),
(10, 3, 15, 'Now it was the harvest season, and the Jordan was overflowing its banks. But as soon as the feet of the priests who were carrying the Ark touched the water at the river''s edge,', 'NLT'),
(10, 3, 16, 'the water began piling up at a town upstream called Adam, which is near Zarethan. And the water below that point flowed on to the Dead Sea until the riverbed was dry. Then all the people crossed over near the city of Jericho.', 'NLT'),
(10, 3, 17, 'Meanwhile, the priests who were carrying the Ark of the LORD''s covenant stood on dry ground in the middle of the riverbed as the people passed by them. They waited there until everyone had crossed the Jordan on dry ground.', 'NLT'),
(10, 4, 1, 'When all the people were safely across the river, the LORD said to Joshua,', 'NLT'),
(10, 4, 2, '"Now choose twelve men, one from each tribe.', 'NLT'),
(10, 4, 3, 'Tell the men to take twelve stones from where the priests are standing in the middle of the Jordan and pile them up at the place where you camp tonight."', 'NLT'),
(10, 4, 4, 'So Joshua called together the twelve men', 'NLT'),
(10, 4, 5, 'and told them, "Go into the middle of the Jordan, in front of the Ark of the LORD your God. Each of you must pick up one stone and carry it out on your shoulder--twelve stones in all, one for each of the twelve tribes.', 'NLT'),
(10, 4, 6, 'We will use these stones to build a memorial. In the future, your children will ask, `What do these stones mean to you?''', 'NLT'),
(10, 4, 7, 'Then you can tell them, `They remind us that the Jordan River stopped flowing when the Ark of the LORD''s covenant went across.'' These stones will stand as a permanent memorial among the people of Israel."', 'NLT'),
(10, 4, 8, 'So the men did as Joshua told them. They took twelve stones from the middle of the Jordan River, one for each tribe, just as the LORD had commanded Joshua. They carried them to the place where they camped for the night and constructed the memorial there.', 'NLT'),
(10, 4, 9, 'Joshua also built another memorial of twelve stones in the middle of the Jordan, at the place where the priests who carried the Ark of the Covenant were standing. The memorial remains there to this day.', 'NLT'),
(10, 4, 10, 'The priests who were carrying the Ark stood in the middle of the river until all of the LORD''s instructions, which Moses had given to Joshua, were carried out. Meanwhile, the people hurried across the riverbed.', 'NLT'),
(10, 4, 11, 'And when everyone was on the other side, the priests crossed over with the Ark of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(10, 4, 12, 'The armed warriors from the tribes of Reuben, Gad, and the half-tribe of Manasseh led the Israelites across the Jordan, just as Moses had directed.', 'NLT'),
(10, 4, 13, 'These warriors--about forty thousand strong--were ready for battle, and they crossed over to the plains of Jericho in the LORD''s presence.', 'NLT'),
(10, 4, 14, 'That day the LORD made Joshua great in the eyes of all the Israelites, and for the rest of his life they revered him as much as they had revered Moses.', 'NLT'),
(10, 4, 15, 'The LORD had said to Joshua,', 'NLT'),
(10, 4, 16, '"Command the priests carrying the Ark of the Covenant to come up out of the riverbed."', 'NLT'),
(10, 4, 17, 'So Joshua gave the command.', 'NLT'),
(10, 4, 18, 'And as soon as the priests carrying the Ark of the LORD''s covenant came up out of the riverbed, the Jordan River flooded its banks as before.', 'NLT'),
(10, 4, 19, 'The people crossed the Jordan on the tenth day of the first month--the month that marked their exodus from Egypt. They camped at Gilgal, east of Jericho.', 'NLT'),
(10, 4, 20, 'It was there at Gilgal that Joshua piled up the twelve stones taken from the Jordan River.', 'NLT'),
(10, 4, 21, 'Then Joshua said to the Israelites, "In the future, your children will ask, `What do these stones mean?''', 'NLT'),
(10, 4, 22, 'Then you can tell them, `This is where the Israelites crossed the Jordan on dry ground.''', 'NLT'),
(10, 4, 23, 'For the LORD your God dried up the river right before your eyes, and he kept it dry until you were all across, just as he did at the Red Sea when he dried it up until we had all crossed over.', 'NLT'),
(10, 4, 24, 'He did this so that all the nations of the earth might know the power of the LORD, and that you might fear the LORD your God forever."', 'NLT'),
(10, 5, 1, 'When all the Amorite kings west of the Jordan and all the Canaanite kings who lived along the Mediterranean coast heard how the LORD had dried up the Jordan River so the people of Israel could cross, they lost heart and were paralyzed with fear.', 'NLT'),
(10, 5, 2, 'At that time the LORD told Joshua, "Use knives of flint to make the Israelites a circumcised people again."', 'NLT'),
(10, 5, 3, 'So Joshua made flint knives and circumcised the entire male population of Israel at Gibeath-haaraloth.', 'NLT'),
(10, 5, 4, 'Joshua had to circumcise them because all the men who were old enough to bear arms when they left Egypt had died in the wilderness.', 'NLT'),
(10, 5, 5, 'Those who left Egypt had all been circumcised, but none of those born after the Exodus, during the years in the wilderness, had been circumcised.', 'NLT'),
(10, 5, 6, 'The Israelites wandered in the wilderness for forty years until all the men who were old enough to bear arms when they left Egypt had died. For they had disobeyed the LORD, and the LORD vowed he would not let them enter the land he had sworn to give us--a land flowing with milk and honey.', 'NLT'),
(10, 5, 7, 'So Joshua circumcised their sons who had not been circumcised on the way to the Promised Land--those who had grown up to take their fathers'' places.', 'NLT'),
(10, 5, 8, 'After all the males had been circumcised, they rested in the camp until they were healed.', 'NLT'),
(10, 5, 9, 'Then the LORD said to Joshua, "Today I have rolled away the shame of your slavery in Egypt." So that place has been called Gilgal to this day.', 'NLT'),
(10, 5, 10, 'While the Israelites were camped at Gilgal on the plains of Jericho, they celebrated Passover on the evening of the fourteenth day of the first month--the month that marked their exodus from Egypt.', 'NLT'),
(10, 5, 11, 'The very next day they began to eat unleavened bread and roasted grain harvested from the land.', 'NLT'),
(10, 5, 12, 'No manna appeared that day, and it was never seen again. So from that time on the Israelites ate from the crops of Canaan.', 'NLT'),
(10, 5, 13, 'As Joshua approached the city of Jericho, he looked up and saw a man facing him with sword in hand. Joshua went up to him and asked, "Are you friend or foe?"', 'NLT'),
(10, 5, 14, '"Neither one," he replied. "I am commander of the LORD''s army." At this, Joshua fell with his face to the ground in reverence. "I am at your command," Joshua said. "What do you want your servant to do?"', 'NLT'),
(10, 5, 15, 'The commander of the LORD''s army replied, "Take off your sandals, for this is holy ground." And Joshua did as he was told.', 'NLT'),
(10, 6, 1, 'Now the gates of Jericho were tightly shut because the people were afraid of the Israelites. No one was allowed to go in or out.', 'NLT'),
(10, 6, 2, 'But the LORD said to Joshua, "I have given you Jericho, its king, and all its mighty warriors.', 'NLT'),
(10, 6, 3, 'Your entire army is to march around the city once a day for six days.', 'NLT'),
(10, 6, 4, 'Seven priests will walk ahead of the Ark, each carrying a ram''s horn. On the seventh day you are to march around the city seven times, with the priests blowing the horns.', 'NLT'),
(10, 6, 5, 'When you hear the priests give one long blast on the horns, have all the people give a mighty shout. Then the walls of the city will collapse, and the people can charge straight into the city."', 'NLT'),
(10, 6, 6, 'So Joshua called together the priests and said, "Take up the Ark of the Covenant, and assign seven priests to walk in front of it, each carrying a ram''s horn."', 'NLT'),
(10, 6, 7, 'Then he gave orders to the people: "March around the city, and the armed men will lead the way in front of the Ark of the LORD."', 'NLT'),
(10, 6, 8, 'After Joshua spoke to the people, the seven priests with the rams'' horns started marching in the presence of the LORD, blowing the horns as they marched. And the priests carrying the Ark of the LORD''s covenant followed behind them.', 'NLT'),
(10, 6, 9, 'Armed guards marched both in front of the priests and behind the Ark, with the priests continually blowing the horns.', 'NLT'),
(10, 6, 10, '"Do not shout; do not even talk," Joshua commanded. "Not a single word from any of you until I tell you to shout. Then shout!"', 'NLT'),
(10, 6, 11, 'So the Ark of the LORD was carried around the city once that day, and then everyone returned to spend the night in the camp.', 'NLT'),
(10, 6, 12, 'Joshua got up early the next morning, and the priests again carried the Ark of the LORD.', 'NLT'),
(10, 6, 13, 'The seven priests with the rams'' horns marched in front of the Ark of the LORD, blowing their horns. Armed guards marched both in front of the priests with the horns and behind the Ark of the LORD. All this time the priests were sounding their horns.', 'NLT'),
(10, 6, 14, 'On the second day they marched around the city once and returned to the camp. They followed this pattern for six days.', 'NLT'),
(10, 6, 15, 'On the seventh day the Israelites got up at dawn and marched around the city as they had done before. But this time they went around the city seven times.', 'NLT'),
(10, 6, 16, 'The seventh time around, as the priests sounded the long blast on their horns, Joshua commanded the people, "Shout! For the LORD has given you the city!', 'NLT'),
(10, 6, 17, 'The city and everything in it must be completely destroyed as an offering to the LORD. Only Rahab the prostitute and the others in her house will be spared, for she protected our spies.', 'NLT'),
(10, 6, 18, 'Do not take any of the things set apart for destruction, or you yourselves will be completely destroyed, and you will bring trouble on all Israel.', 'NLT'),
(10, 6, 19, 'Everything made from silver, gold, bronze, or iron is sacred to the LORD and must be brought into his treasury."', 'NLT'),
(10, 6, 20, 'When the people heard the sound of the horns, they shouted as loud as they could. Suddenly, the walls of Jericho collapsed, and the Israelites charged straight into the city from every side and captured it.', 'NLT'),
(10, 6, 21, 'They completely destroyed everything in it--men and women, young and old, cattle, sheep, donkeys--everything.', 'NLT'),
(10, 6, 22, 'Then Joshua said to the two spies, "Keep your promise. Go to the prostitute''s house and bring her out, along with all her family."', 'NLT'),
(10, 6, 23, 'The young men went in and brought out Rahab, her father, mother, brothers, and all the other relatives who were with her. They moved her whole family to a safe place near the camp of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(10, 6, 24, 'Then the Israelites burned the city and everything in it. Only the things made from silver, gold, bronze, or iron were kept for the treasury of the LORD''s house.', 'NLT'),
(10, 6, 25, 'So Joshua spared Rahab the prostitute and her relatives who were with her in the house, because she had hidden the spies Joshua sent to Jericho. And she lives among the Israelites to this day.', 'NLT'),
(10, 6, 26, 'At that time Joshua invoked this curse: "May the curse of the LORD fall on anyone who tries to rebuild the city of Jericho. At the cost of his firstborn son, he will lay its foundation. At the cost of his youngest son, he will set up its gates."', 'NLT'),
(10, 6, 27, 'So the LORD was with Joshua, and his name became famous throughout the land.', 'NLT'),
(10, 7, 1, 'But Israel was unfaithful concerning the things set apart for the LORD. A man named Achan had stolen some of these things, so the LORD was very angry with the Israelites. Achan was the son of Carmi, of the family of Zimri, of the clan of Zerah, and of the tribe of Judah.', 'NLT'),
(10, 7, 2, 'Joshua sent some of his men from Jericho to spy out the city of Ai, east of Bethel, near Beth-aven.', 'NLT'),
(10, 7, 3, 'When they returned, they told Joshua, "It''s a small town, and it won''t take more than two or three thousand of us to destroy it. There''s no need for all of us to go there."', 'NLT'),
(10, 7, 4, 'So approximately three thousand warriors were sent, but they were soundly defeated. The men of Ai', 'NLT'),
(10, 7, 5, 'chased the Israelites from the city gate as far as the quarries, and they killed about thirty-six who were retreating down the slope. The Israelites were paralyzed with fear at this turn of events, and their courage melted away.', 'NLT'),
(10, 7, 6, 'Joshua and the leaders of Israel tore their clothing in dismay, threw dust on their heads, and bowed down facing the Ark of the LORD until evening.', 'NLT'),
(10, 7, 7, 'Then Joshua cried out, "Sovereign LORD, why did you bring us across the Jordan River if you are going to let the Amorites kill us? If only we had been content to stay on the other side!', 'NLT'),
(10, 7, 8, 'Lord, what am I to say, now that Israel has fled from its enemies?', 'NLT'),
(10, 7, 9, 'For when the Canaanites and all the other people living in the land hear about it, they will surround us and wipe us off the face of the earth. And then what will happen to the honor of your great name?"', 'NLT'),
(10, 7, 10, 'But the LORD said to Joshua, "Get up! Why are you lying on your face like this?', 'NLT'),
(10, 7, 11, 'Israel has sinned and broken my covenant! They have stolen the things that I commanded to be set apart for me. And they have not only stolen them; they have also lied about it and hidden the things among their belongings.', 'NLT'),
(10, 7, 12, 'That is why the Israelites are running from their enemies in defeat. For now Israel has been set apart for destruction. I will not remain with you any longer unless you destroy the things among you that were set apart for destruction.', 'NLT'),
(10, 7, 13, '"Get up! Command the people to purify themselves in preparation for tomorrow. For this is what the LORD, the God of Israel, says: Hidden among you, O Israel, are things set apart for the LORD. You will never defeat your enemies until you remove these things.', 'NLT'),
(10, 7, 14, 'In the morning you must present yourselves by tribes, and the LORD will point out the tribe to which the guilty man belongs. That tribe must come forward with its clans, and the LORD will point out the guilty clan. That clan will then come forward, and the LORD will point out the guilty family. Finally, each member of the guilty family must come one by one.', 'NLT'),
(10, 7, 15, 'The one who has stolen what was set apart for destruction will himself be burned with fire, along with everything he has, for he has broken the covenant of the LORD and has done a horrible thing in Israel."', 'NLT'),
(10, 7, 16, 'Early the next morning Joshua brought the tribes of Israel before the LORD, and the tribe of Judah was singled out.', 'NLT'),
(10, 7, 17, 'Then the clans of Judah came forward, and the clan of Zerah was singled out. Then the families of Zerah came before the LORD, and the family of Zimri was singled out.', 'NLT'),
(10, 7, 18, 'Every member of Zimri''s family was brought forward person by person, and Achan was singled out.', 'NLT'),
(10, 7, 19, 'Then Joshua said to Achan, "My son, give glory to the LORD, the God of Israel, by telling the truth. Make your confession and tell me what you have done. Don''t hide it from me."', 'NLT'),
(10, 7, 20, 'Achan replied, "I have sinned against the LORD, the God of Israel.', 'NLT'),
(10, 7, 21, 'For I saw a beautiful robe imported from Babylon, two hundred silver coins, and a bar of gold weighing more than a pound. I wanted them so much that I took them. They are hidden in the ground beneath my tent, with the silver buried deeper than the rest."', 'NLT'),
(10, 7, 22, 'So Joshua sent some men to make a search. They ran to the tent and found the stolen goods hidden there, just as Achan had said, with the silver buried beneath the rest.', 'NLT'),
(10, 7, 23, 'They took the things from the tent and brought them to Joshua and all the Israelites. Then they laid them on the ground in the presence of the LORD.', 'NLT');
